{"title_page": "Pierino Favalli", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Pierino Favalli\n| image          = Pierino Favalli.jpg\n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|1914|5|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = Zanengo di Grumello, [[Cremona]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1986|5|16|1914|5|1|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = Cremona, Italy\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = \n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = 1934\u201336\n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = 1936\u201343\n| proteam1       = Legnano\n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry| {{ITA}} }}\n{{MedalSport| Men's [[road bicycle racing]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Road World Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalBronze |[[1936 UCI Road World Championships|1936 Bern]]|Amateur's road race}}\n| show-medals = yes\n}}\n\n'''Pierino Favalli''' (1 May 1914 \u2013 16 May 1986) was an Italian road cyclist. As an amateur he won the road race at the 1934 national championships and finished third at the 1936 World Championships. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1936 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|individual]] and [[Cycling at the 1936 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team road race|team road race]] events at the [[1936 Summer Olympics]] and placed seventh and fourth, respectively.<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/fa/pierino-favalli-1.html |title=Pierino Favalli  |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref> After the Olympics he turned professional and won the [[Milano\u2013Torino]] race in 1938\u201340 and [[Milan\u2013San Remo]] race in 1941, finishing second in 1937\u201338 and 1942. He also won one stage in the [[1940 Giro d'Italia]].<ref>[http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=3828 Pierino Favalli]. cyclingarchives.com</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Milan\u2013San Remo winners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Favalli, Pierino}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1936 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Italian Giro d'Italia stage winners]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Cremona]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lombardy]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Italy]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1910s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Pierino Favalli\n| image          = Pierino Favalli.jpg\n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|1914|5|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = Zanengo di Grumello, [[Cremona]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1986|5|16|1914|5|1|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = Cremona, Italy\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = \n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = 1934\u201336\n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = 1936\u201343\n| proteam1       = Legnano\n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry| {{ITA}} }}\n{{MedalSport| Men's [[road bicycle racing]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Road World Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalBronze |[[1936 UCI Road World Championships|1936 Bern]]|Amateur's road race}}\n| show-medals = yes\n}}\n\n'''Pierino Favalli''' (1 May 1914 \u2013 16 May 1986) was an Italian road cyclist. As an amateur he won the road race at the 1934 national championships and finished third at the 1936 World Championships. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1936 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|individual]] and [[Cycling at the 1936 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team road race|team road race]] events at the [[1936 Summer Olympics]] and placed seventh and fourth, respectively.<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/fa/pierino-favalli-1.html |title=Pierino Favalli  |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref> After the Olympics he turned professional and won the [[Milano\u2013Torino]] race in 1938\u201340 and [[Milan\u2013San Remo]] race in 1941, finishing second in 1937\u201338 and 1942. He also won one stage in the [[1940 Giro d'Italia]].<ref>[http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=3828 Pierino Favalli]. cyclingarchives.com</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Milan\u2013San Remo winners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Favalli, Pierino}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1936 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Italian Giro d'Italia stage winners]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Cremona]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lombardy]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Italy]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1910s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierino_Favalli"}
{"title_page": "Robert Syms", "text_new": "{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Sir Robert Syms\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Sir Robert Syms MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption =  \n| office = [[Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| primeminister = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start = 17 July 2016\n| term_end = 15 June 2017\n| predecessor = [[Charlie Elphicke]]\n| successor = [[Mark Spencer (British politician)|Mark Spencer]]\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Poole (UK Parliament constituency)|Poole]]\n| parliament1 = \n| term_start1 = 1 May 1997\n| term_end1 = \n| majority1 = 19,116 (38.0%)\n| predecessor1 = [[John Devereux Ward]]\n| successor1 = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1956|08|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Chippenham, Wiltshire|Chippenham]], [[Wiltshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Nicola Guy<br />|1991|1999|end=div}}<br />{{marriage|Fiona Mellersh<br />|2000|2016|end=div}} \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| relations = \n| children = 2\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| footnotes = \n| website = \n}}\n'''Sir Robert Andrew Raymond Syms''' (born 15 August 1956) is a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician in the [[United Kingdom]].  He has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Poole (UK Parliament constituency)|Poole]] in [[Dorset]] since [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]. He was granted a [[Knight bachelor|knighthood]] on 12 October 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Knighthoods: Michael Penning and Robert Syms|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/knighthoods-michael-penning-and-robert-syms|accessdate=12 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSyms was born in [[Chippenham]] in 1956 and educated at [[Colston's School]].<ref name=\"politics\">{{cite web|title=Robert Syms|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/robert-andrew-raymond-syms|website=Politics.co.uk|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"conservativebio\" /> He was leader of [[North Wiltshire|North Wiltshire District Council]] from 1984-7 and a [[Wiltshire County Council]]lor from 1985\u201397.<ref name=\"politics\" /> He was managing director of his family's plant hire firm in Bristol Road in Chippenham and is a Fellow of the Chartered Institute of Building.<ref name=\"politics\" /><ref name=\"conservativebio\" />\n\n==Business interests==\nHe retains a directorship and shareholding in Marden Holdings Ltd headquartered in Bristol Road, Chippenham.<ref name=\"UK Parliament website\">{{cite web|title=House of Commons - The Register of Members' Financial Interests 5 Mar 2012|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmregmem/120305/syms_robert.htm|work=UK Parliament website|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=21 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nHe contested [[Walsall North (UK Parliament constituency)|Walsall North]] in [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]], but was first elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] as MP for [[Poole (UK Parliament constituency)|Poole]] in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]].<ref name=\"ParliamentUK\">{{cite web|title=Robert Syms|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/mr-robert-syms/245|website=UK Parliament|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nSyms served on opposition front bench from 1998 to 2007.<ref name=\"ParliamentUK\" /> He was shadow spokesman for environment, transport and the regions between 1999 and 2001, an opposition whip for a few months in 2003, and shadow minister in the office of the deputy Prime Minister and for communities and local government between 2003 and 2007.<ref name=\"conservativebio\" /><ref name=\"ParliamentUK\" /> He was also vice-Chairman of the Conservative Party between 2001 and 2002.<ref name=\"conservativebio\" />\n\nSyms was an Assistant Whip for the Coalition government between 2012 and 2013.<ref name=\"ParliamentUK\" /> He has served on a variety of Select Committees, acting as Chair of the Regulatory Reform select committee from July 2010 to September 2012 and the High Speed Rail select committee from April 2014 to February 2016.<ref name=\"ParliamentUK\" />\n\nSyms organised a letter signed by more than 80 fellow [[Euroscepticism in the United Kingdom|Eurosceptic]] Conservative MPs urging [[David Cameron]] to continue as Prime Minister regardless of the result of the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|EU referendum in 2016]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/23/eurosceptic-tory-mps-and-ministers-sign-letter-urging-david-came/ |title=Eurosceptic Tory MPs and ministers sign letter urging David Cameron to continue as Prime Minister |first1=Peter |last1=Dominiczak |first2=Steven |last2=Swinford |work=The Telegraph |date=24 June 2016}}</ref> He backed [[Theresa May]]'s leadership bid following Cameron's resignation,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36704241 |title=Conservative Party leadership: Who's backing who? |work=BBC News |date=8 July 2016}}</ref> and was appointed as a Government Whip and [[Lords Commissioners of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of HM Treasury]] upon May's succession.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/robert-syms |title=Robert Syms |website=GOV.UK |accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Syms was at the centre of an expenses scandal after he claimed more than \u00a32,000 for furniture to be moved to his parents' address in Wiltshire.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5339776/Robert-Syms-had-furniture-delivered-to-wrong-home-MPs-expenses.html|title=Robert Syms had furniture delivered to 'wrong home': MPs' expenses|last=Gammell|first=Caroline|work=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=3 May 2017|language=en}}</ref> He was also forced to defend using his expense account to employ his wife and ex-wife.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/4463126.MP_defends_hiring_of_his_wife_and_ex_wife/|title=MP defends hiring of his wife and ex-wife|last=Morton|first=James|work=Bournemouth Echo|access-date=12 June 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Syms was criticised by the local press and other candidates for failing to attend hustings for the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] and spending more time campaigning in [[Mid Dorset and North Poole (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Dorset and North Poole]] with [[Michael Tomlinson]] than Poole due to Poole's status as a [[safe seat]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/vote2015/12893756.Robert_Syms__too_busy__to_attend_hustings_in_Poole/|title=Robert Syms \"too busy\" to attend hustings in Poole|work=Bournemouth Echo|language=en|access-date=3 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Syms was criticised for name calling on [[Twitter]]. Four years earlier, his wife announced on Twitter that he had been dismissed from his job as a whip over the phone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/15341219.___It___s_not_a_coalition__you_d__k_____Poole_MP_Robert_Syms_criticised_for_response_to_Corbyn_supporter/|title=\"It's not a coalition, you d**k\": Poole MP Robert Syms criticised for response to Corbyn supporter|last=Grassby|first=Jade|website=Bournemouth Echo|language=en|access-date=3 May 2017}}</ref> He replied to a tweet calling the Conservative-DUP deal after the 2017 general election a \"coalition\", by calling him a \"dick\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nagesh|first1=Ashitha|title=Tory MP calls member of public a 'd*ck' for mistakenly calling DUP deal a coalition|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/06/11/tory-mp-calls-member-of-public-a-dck-for-mistakenly-calling-dup-deal-a-coalition-6701979/|website=Metro|accessdate=11 June 2017|date=11 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is divorced and has two teenage children.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tory MP's ex-wife rages at David Cameron over whip's sacking|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/07/reshuffle-tory-whip-twitter-fury|accessdate=10 August 2016|work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=\"conservativebio\">{{cite web|title=Robert Syms bio|url=https://www.conservatives.com/OurTeam/Members-of-Parliament/Syms-Robert|website=Conservatives|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[1989 Wiltshire County Council election]]\n*[[1993 Wiltshire County Council election]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{UK MP links |parliament=mr-robert-syms/245 |hansard=mr-robert-syms/ |hansardcurr=4197 |publicwhip=Robert_Syms |theywork=10582/robert_syms/poole}}\n* [http://www.pooleconservatives.org Poole Conservatives]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Devereux Ward|John Ward]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Poole (UK Parliament constituency)|Poole]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{South West Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Syms, Robert}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of Wiltshire County Council]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Politics of Dorset]]\n[[Category:Councillors in South West England]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:People from Chippenham]]\n[[Category:People educated at Colston's School]]\n[[Category:Leaders of local authorities of England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Sir Robert Syms\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Sir Robert Syms MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption =  \n| office = [[Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| primeminister = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start = 17 July 2016\n| term_end = 15 June 2017\n| predecessor = [[Charlie Elphicke]]\n| successor = [[Mark Spencer (British politician)|Mark Spencer]]\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Poole (UK Parliament constituency)|Poole]]\n| parliament1 = \n| term_start1 = 1 May 1997\n| term_end1 = \n| majority1 = 19,116 (38.0%)\n| predecessor1 = [[John Devereux Ward]]\n| successor1 = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1956|08|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Chippenham, Wiltshire|Chippenham]], [[Wiltshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Nicola Guy<br />|1991|1999|end=div}}<br />{{marriage|Fiona Mellersh<br />|2000|2016|end=div}} \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| relations = \n| children = 2\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| footnotes = \n| website = \n}}\n'''Sir Robert Andrew Raymond Syms''' (born 15 August 1956) is a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician in the [[United Kingdom]].  He has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Poole (UK Parliament constituency)|Poole]] in [[Dorset]] since [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]. He was granted a [[Knight bachelor|knighthood]] on 12 October 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Knighthoods: Michael Penning and Robert Syms|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/knighthoods-michael-penning-and-robert-syms|accessdate=12 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSyms was born in [[Chippenham]] in 1956 and educated at [[Colston's School]].<ref name=\"politics\">{{cite web|title=Robert Syms|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/robert-andrew-raymond-syms|website=Politics.co.uk|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"conservativebio\" /> He was leader of [[North Wiltshire|North Wiltshire District Council]] from 1984-7 and a [[Wiltshire County Council]]lor from 1985-97.<ref name=\"politics\" /> He was managing director of his family's plant hire firm in Bristol Road in Chippenham and is a Fellow of the Chartered Institute of Building.<ref name=\"politics\" /><ref name=\"conservativebio\" />\n\n==Business interests==\nHe retains a directorship and shareholding in Marden Holdings Ltd headquartered in Bristol Road, Chippenham.<ref name=\"UK Parliament website\">{{cite web|title=House of Commons - The Register of Members' Financial Interests 5 Mar 2012|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmregmem/120305/syms_robert.htm|work=UK Parliament website|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=21 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nHe contested [[Walsall North (UK Parliament constituency)|Walsall North]] in [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]], but was first elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] as MP for [[Poole (UK Parliament constituency)|Poole]] in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]].<ref name=\"ParliamentUK\">{{cite web|title=Robert Syms|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/mr-robert-syms/245|website=UK Parliament|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nSyms served on opposition front bench from 1998 to 2007.<ref name=\"ParliamentUK\" /> He was shadow spokesman for environment, transport and the regions between 1999 and 2001, an opposition whip for a few months in 2003, and shadow minister in the office of the deputy Prime Minister and for communities and local government between 2003 and 2007.<ref name=\"conservativebio\" /><ref name=\"ParliamentUK\" /> He was also vice-Chairman of the Conservative Party between 2001 and 2002.<ref name=\"conservativebio\" />\n\nSyms was an Assistant Whip for the Coalition government between 2012 and 2013.<ref name=\"ParliamentUK\" /> He has served on a variety of Select Committees, acting as Chair of the Regulatory Reform select committee from July 2010 to September 2012 and the High Speed Rail select committee from April 2014 to February 2016.<ref name=\"ParliamentUK\" />\n\nSyms organised a letter signed by more than 80 fellow [[Euroscepticism in the United Kingdom|Eurosceptic]] Conservative MPs urging [[David Cameron]] to continue as Prime Minister regardless of the result of the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|EU referendum in 2016]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/23/eurosceptic-tory-mps-and-ministers-sign-letter-urging-david-came/ |title=Eurosceptic Tory MPs and ministers sign letter urging David Cameron to continue as Prime Minister |first1=Peter |last1=Dominiczak |first2=Steven |last2=Swinford |work=The Telegraph |date=24 June 2016}}</ref> He backed [[Theresa May]]'s leadership bid following Cameron's resignation,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36704241 |title=Conservative Party leadership: Who's backing who? |work=BBC News |date=8 July 2016}}</ref> and was appointed as a Government Whip and [[Lords Commissioners of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of HM Treasury]] upon May's succession.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/robert-syms |title=Robert Syms |website=GOV.UK |accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Syms was at the centre of an expenses scandal after he claimed more than \u00a32,000 for furniture to be moved to his parents' address in Wiltshire.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5339776/Robert-Syms-had-furniture-delivered-to-wrong-home-MPs-expenses.html|title=Robert Syms had furniture delivered to 'wrong home': MPs' expenses|last=Gammell|first=Caroline|work=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=3 May 2017|language=en}}</ref> He was also forced to defend using his expense account to employ his wife and ex-wife.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/4463126.MP_defends_hiring_of_his_wife_and_ex_wife/|title=MP defends hiring of his wife and ex-wife|last=Morton|first=James|work=Bournemouth Echo|access-date=12 June 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Syms was criticised by the local press and other candidates for failing to attend hustings for the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] and spending more time campaigning in [[Mid Dorset and North Poole (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Dorset and North Poole]] with [[Michael Tomlinson]] than Poole due to Poole's status as a [[safe seat]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/vote2015/12893756.Robert_Syms__too_busy__to_attend_hustings_in_Poole/|title=Robert Syms \"too busy\" to attend hustings in Poole|work=Bournemouth Echo|language=en|access-date=3 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Syms was criticised for name calling on [[Twitter]]. Four years earlier, his wife announced on Twitter that he had been dismissed from his job as a whip over the phone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/15341219.___It___s_not_a_coalition__you_d__k_____Poole_MP_Robert_Syms_criticised_for_response_to_Corbyn_supporter/|title=\"It's not a coalition, you d**k\": Poole MP Robert Syms criticised for response to Corbyn supporter|last=Grassby|first=Jade|website=Bournemouth Echo|language=en|access-date=3 May 2017}}</ref> He replied to a tweet calling the Conservative-DUP deal after the 2017 general election a \"coalition\", by calling him a \"dick\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nagesh|first1=Ashitha|title=Tory MP calls member of public a 'd*ck' for mistakenly calling DUP deal a coalition|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/06/11/tory-mp-calls-member-of-public-a-dck-for-mistakenly-calling-dup-deal-a-coalition-6701979/|website=Metro|accessdate=11 June 2017|date=11 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is divorced and has two teenage children.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tory MP's ex-wife rages at David Cameron over whip's sacking|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/oct/07/reshuffle-tory-whip-twitter-fury|accessdate=10 August 2016|work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=\"conservativebio\">{{cite web|title=Robert Syms bio|url=https://www.conservatives.com/OurTeam/Members-of-Parliament/Syms-Robert|website=Conservatives|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[1989 Wiltshire County Council election]]\n*[[1993 Wiltshire County Council election]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{UK MP links |parliament=mr-robert-syms/245 |hansard=mr-robert-syms/ |hansardcurr=4197 |publicwhip=Robert_Syms |theywork=10582/robert_syms/poole}}\n* [http://www.pooleconservatives.org Poole Conservatives]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Devereux Ward|John Ward]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Poole (UK Parliament constituency)|Poole]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{South West Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Syms, Robert}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of Wiltshire County Council]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Politics of Dorset]]\n[[Category:Councillors in South West England]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:People from Chippenham]]\n[[Category:People educated at Colston's School]]\n[[Category:Leaders of local authorities of England]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1985-97 \u2192 1985\u201397", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Syms"}
{"title_page": "Western African Ebola virus epidemic", "text_new": "{{about|the Ebola virus epidemic in West Africa in 2013\u20132016|the ongoing Ebola virus epidemic in the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Uganda|Kivu Ebola epidemic}}\n{{short description|2013\u20132016 major outbreak of Ebola virus disease mainly in Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2014}}<!--Sierra Leone & Nigerian English are based on British English -->\n{{Infobox event\n|image = 2014 ebola virus epidemic in West Africa simplified.svg\n|image_size = 300px\n|caption = Simplified Ebola virus epidemic situation map\n|date = December 2013&nbsp;\u2013 June 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/dg/speeches/2016/executive-board-138/en/|title=WHO Director-General addresses the Executive Board|author=|date=|accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"tru\" />\n<!-- One case of uncontained or locally transmitted Ebola constitutes an outbreak by definition. See: http://www.who.int/topics/disease_outbreaks/en-->\n|casualties1= <!-- Please do not add a mortality percentage here because it is misleading and cannot reflect real mortality until the outbreak has ceased (see [[Talk:2014 West Africa Ebola outbreak#Total mortality]]) -->\n<!-- Please ensure this Casualty list ONLY includes data as reported in the WHO, OCHA or governments reports. Also note a DRN has concluded that WHO reports are erroneous hence it may not tie up with reports, but are correlated with government reports.-->\n<!-- Please update the WHO numbers and As-Of date consistently in 5 parts of this article: (1) Infobox (here), (2) lead section, (3) Subsequent Spread section, (4) Timeline table, (5) Timeline graph(s). -->\n* ''Note: current estimates suggest that between 17 per cent and 70 per cent of Ebola cases were unreported.''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/16/science/fewer-ebola-cases-go-unreported-than-thought-study-finds-.html|title=Fewer Ebola cases go unreported than thought, study finds |author=Donald G. McNeil Jr.|date=16 December 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=23 July 2015}}</ref>\n{{aligned table|class=wikitable|fullwidth=y|cols=4\n| row1header = yes|col2style=text-align:right|col3style=text-align:right\n| Country | Cases | Deaths | Last update <br /><small>On 9 June 2016 by WHO</small>\n| <!--Liberia-->[[Ebola virus epidemic in Liberia|Liberia]]\n| 10,675\n| 4,809 |<small>Outbreak ended 9 June 2016</small><ref name=\"tru\">{{cite web|last1=Brice|first1=Makini|title=WHO declares Liberia free of active Ebola virus transmission|url=http://news.trust.org/item/20160609104923-cft2c| publisher=Thomson Reuters Foundation|accessdate=16 October 2016|date=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n| <!--Sierra Leone-->[[Ebola virus epidemic in Sierra Leone|Sierra Leone]]\n| 14,124\n| 3,956 |<small>Outbreak ended 17 March 2016</small><ref\nname=\"16who16\">{{cite web|title=Ebola Situation Report \u2013 16 March 2016 {{!}} Ebola|url=http://apps.who.int/ebola/current-situation/ebola-situation-report-16-march-2016|publisher=World Health Organization|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n| <!--Guinea-->[[Ebola virus epidemic in Guinea|Guinea]]\n| 3,811\n| 2,543 |<small>Outbreak ended 1 June 2016</small><ref name=\"guinn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.afro.who.int/en/media-centre/pressreleases/item/8676-end-of-ebola-transmission-in-guinea.html|title=End of Ebola transmission in Guinea|author=|date=2015|publisher=WHO Regional Office for Africa|accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n| <!--Nigeria-->[[Ebola virus disease in Nigeria|Nigeria]]\n| 20\n| 8 |<small>Outbreak ended 19 October 2014</small><ref name=WHO20141022 />\n\n| <!--Mali-->[[Ebola virus disease in Mali|Mali]]\n| 8\n| 6 |<small>Outbreak ended 18 January 2015</small><ref name=\"WHO2015_01_21\">{{cite web |url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/149314/1/roadmapsitrep_21Jan2015_eng.pdf?ua=1 |format= PDF |title=Ebola situation report |publisher=World Health Organization |date=21 January 2015 |accessdate =22 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Please do not edit the USA total to add the 5 medivac cases, these are included in the totals of the respective area of infection country-->\n| <!--United States-->[[Ebola virus cases in the United States|United States]]\n| 4\n| 1 |<small>Outbreak ended 21 December 2014</small><ref name=\"WHO2014_12_23\">{{cite web |url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/situation-reports/en/?m=20141224 |title=Ebola response roadmap \u2013 Situation report 24 December 2014 |publisher=World Health Organization|date=26 December 2014|accessdate =29 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n| <!--Italy-->[[Italy]]\n| 1\n| 0 |<small>Outbreak ended 20 July 2015</small><ref>{{cite web| url=http://apps.who.int/ebola/current-situation/ebola-situation-report-22-july-2015 |title=Ebola situation report |publisher=World Health Organization |date=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n| <!--United Kingdom-->[[Ebola virus disease in the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]]\n| 1\n| 0 |<small>Outbreak ended 10 March 2015</small><ref name=Uk_10_March />\n\n| <!--Senegal-->[[Senegal]]\n| 1\n| 0 |<small>Outbreak ended 17 October 2014</small><ref name=WHO20141022 />\n\n| <!--Spain-->[[Ebola virus disease cases in Spain|Spain]]\n| 1\n| 0 |<small>Outbreak ended 2 December 2014</small><ref name=\"WHO2014_12_05\">{{cite web |url=http://apps.who.int/gho/data/view.ebola-sitrep.ebola-summary-20141205?lang=en |title=Situation summary |publisher=World Health Organization |date=5 December 2014 |accessdate =6 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n| row12style=font-weight:bold; background-color:#f0f0f0\n| Total | 28,646 | 11,323 | {{As of |2016|5|08|lc=yes}}\n}}<!-- DO NOT ADD NORWAY OR ANY OTHER STATE WITHOUT USING THE TALKPAGE FIRST -->\n}}\n<!-- Per MOS:BOLDTITLE and WP:SBE, neither the article's title nor related text appears in bold. -->\n\nThe '''Western African Ebola virus epidemic''' (2013\u20132016) was the most widespread outbreak of [[Ebola virus disease]] (EVD) [[List of Ebola outbreaks|in history]]\u2014causing major loss of life and socioeconomic disruption in the region, mainly in [[Ebola virus epidemic in Guinea|Guinea]], [[Ebola virus epidemic in Liberia|Liberia]] and [[Ebola virus epidemic in Sierra Leone|Sierra Leone]]. The first cases were recorded in Guinea in December 2013; later, the disease spread to neighbouring Liberia and Sierra Leone,<ref name=\":1\" /> with minor outbreaks occurring elsewhere. It caused significant mortality, with the [[case fatality rate]] reported which was initially considerable,<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa1411100 |title=Ebola virus disease in West Africa \u2013 the first 9 months of the epidemic and forward projections |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |date=23 September 2014 |author=WHO Ebola Response Team|quote=...&nbsp;we estimate that the case fatality rate is 70.8% (95% confidence interval [CI], 69 to 73) among persons with known clinical outcome of infection. |volume=371 |issue=16 |pages=1481\u20131495 |pmid=25244186 |pmc=4235004}}</ref><ref name=\"cfrebolavirus\">{{cite web|url=http://epidemic.bio.ed.ac.uk/ebolavirus_fatality_rate|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140829075833/http://epidemic.bio.ed.ac.uk/ebolavirus_fatality_rate|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 August 2014|title=Case Fatality Rate for ebolavirus|date=2015|publisher= University of Edinburgh|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"WHO2014_12_28\">{{cite report |url=http://apps.who.int/ebolaweb/sitreps/20141231/20141231.pdf |format= PDF |title=Ebola response roadmap situation report  |publisher=WHO|date=31 December 2014|accessdate =1 January 2015|quote=The reported case fatality rate in the three intense-transmission countries among all cases for whom a definitive outcome is known is 71%.}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|name=cfr|The mortality (number of dead per number of healthy per time frame) recorded in Liberia up to 26 August 2014 was 70%.<ref name=\"cfrebolavirus\" /> However, due to the estimation method used, the estimated case fatality rate (70.8%) for this particular epidemic differs from the actual ratio between the number of deaths and the number of cases.}} while the rate among hospitalised patients was 57\u201359%,<ref name=\"WHOreport\">{{cite report |url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/situation-reports/en/ |title=Ebola Situation report |publisher=WHO |date=12 January 2015 |accessdate =28 January 2015}}</ref> the final numbers 28,616 people, including 11,310 deaths, for a case-fatality rate of 40%.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wappes |first1=Jim |title=US health worker monitored as DRC Ebola nears 600 cases |url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2018/12/us-health-worker-monitored-drc-ebola-nears-600-cases |publisher=CIDRAP |accessdate=23 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Small outbreaks occurred in [[Ebola virus disease in Nigeria|Nigeria]] and [[Ebola virus disease in Mali|Mali]],<ref name=\"WHO2015_01_211\" >{{cite report |title=End of Ebola transmission in Guinea |url=https://afro.who.int/news/end-ebola-transmission-guinea |publisher=WHO Regional Office for Africa |accessdate=30 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"health-ebola-mali-idINL6N0T15CN20141112\">{{cite news |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2014/11/12/health-ebola-mali-idINL6N0T15CN20141112|title=Update: Mali confirms new case of Ebola, locks down Bamako clinic |accessdate=15 November 2014|work=Reuters |date=12 November 2014}}</ref> and imported cases led to secondary infection of medical workers in the [[Ebola virus cases in the United States|United States]] and [[Ebola virus disease in Spain|Spain]].<ref name=El_Mundo>{{cite news |title=Una enfermera que atendi\u00f3 al misionero fallecido Garc\u00eda Viejo, contagiada de \u00e9bola |url=http://www.elmundo.es/madrid/2014/10/06/5432bb62e2704e347a8b4577.html?a=a733fe5654cd56f5e1d50d769a9b4204&t=1412616936|accessdate=6 October 2014 |date=6 October 2014 |newspaper=El Mundo |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=\"Ebola_Outbreak_total_WHO_8_Oct\">{{cite report |url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/136020/1/roadmapsitrep_8Oct2014_eng.pdf?ua=1 |format= PDF|title= Ebola outbreak situation report|publisher=WHO | accessdate=15 October 2014| date=8 October 2014}}</ref> In addition, isolated cases were recorded in [[Senegal]],<ref name=\"sitrep_7Nov2014\">{{cite report |url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/137592/1/roadmapsitrep_7Nov2014_eng.pdf?ua=1 |format= PDF |title=Ebola response roadmap situation report update |publisher=WHO|date=7 November 2014 |accessdate =7 November 2014}}</ref> the [[Ebola virus disease in the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]] and Italy.<ref name=\"WHO2014_12_28\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Ebola virus disease \u2013 Italy|url=http://www.who.int/csr/don/13-may-2015-ebola/en/|publisher=WHO |accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref> The number of cases peaked in October 2014 and then began to decline gradually, following the commitment of substantial international resources. <section begin=casesasof />{{As of|2016|5|08}}<section end=casesasof />, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) and respective governments reported a total of <section begin=cases />28,646<section end=cases /> suspected cases and <section begin=deaths />11,323<section end=deaths /> deaths<section begin=caserefs /><ref name=\"08who2016\">{{cite report|url=https://www.who.int/en/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/ebola-virus-disease|title=Ebola virus disease|author=|date=|publisher=World Health Organization|accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref><section end=caserefs /> (39.5%), though the WHO believes that this substantially understates the magnitude of the outbreak.<ref name=\"CDC Estimating future number of cases\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/su63e0923a1.htm | title=Estimating the future number of cases in the Ebola epidemic \u2013 Liberia and Sierra Leone, 2014\u20132015 | journal=Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report |date=26 September 2014 | author=Meltzer, Martin I. | author2=Atkins, Charisma Y. | author3=Santibanez, Scott | author4=Knust, Barbara | author5=Petersen, Brett W. | author6=Ervin, Elizabeth D. | author7=Nichol, Stuart T. | author8=Damon, Inger K. | author9=Washington, Michael L. | volume=63 | issue=3 | pages=1\u201314 | pmid=25254986 | display-authors=3}}</ref><ref name=\"HP New cases 10,000 per week\">{{cite magazine|last1=Worl|first1=Justin|title=New Ebola Cases Could Hit 10,000 Per Week|url=http://time.com/3505982/ebola-new-cases-world-health-organization/|accessdate=28 October 2016|magazine=Time|date=2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August 2014, a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]] was declared<ref>{{cite report|title= Statement on the 1st meeting of the IHR Emergency Committee on the 2014 Ebola outbreak in West Africa |url=https://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2014/ebola-20140808/en/ |publisher=WHO |accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref> and on 29 March 2016, the WHO terminated the Public Health Emergency of International Concern status of the outbreak.<ref name=EmergencyEnd/><ref>{{cite report|title=Interim advice on the sexual transmission of the Ebola virus disease|url=http://www.who.int/reproductivehealth/topics/rtis/ebola-virus-semen/en/|publisher=WHO|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"who.int1\">{{cite report|url=http://www.who.int/dg/speeches/2016/executive-board-138/en/|title=WHO Director-General addresses the Executive Board|publisher=WHO|accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref> Subsequent flare-ups occurred; the last was declared over on 9 June 2016, 42 days after the last case tested negative on 28 April 2016 in Monrovia.<ref>{{cite report|last1=WHO|title=Situation Report Ebola|date=10 June 2016|url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/208883/1/ebolasitrep_10Jun2016_eng.pdf|publisher=WHO|accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe outbreak left about 17,000 survivors of the disease, many of whom report post-recovery symptoms termed [[post-Ebola syndrome]], often severe enough to require medical care for months or even years. An additional cause for concern is the apparent ability of the virus to \"hide\" in a recovered survivor's body for an extended period of time and then become active months or years later, either in the same individual or in a sexual partner.<ref name=\"Scientific American\">{{cite magazine| url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/why-ebola-survivors-struggle-with-new-symptoms/ | title=Why Ebola Survivors Struggle with New Symptoms | magazine=Scientific American | date=29 February 2016 | accessdate=9 September 2016 | author=Yasmin, Seema}}</ref> In December 2016, the WHO announced that a two-year trial of the [[rVSV-ZEBOV vaccine]] appeared to offer protection from the variant of EBOV responsible for the Western Africa outbreak. The vaccine is considered to be effective and is the only prophylactic which offers protection; hence, 300,000 doses have been stockpiled.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal|last1=Geisbert|first1=Thomas W.|title=First Ebola virus vaccine to protect human beings?|journal=The Lancet|volume=389|issue=10068|pages=479\u2013480|date=December 2016|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(16)32618-6|pmid=28017402}}</ref><ref name=\"PBS NewsHour\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/ebola-vaccine-results-encouraging-preliminary/ |title=Ebola vaccine results are encouraging \u2013 but preliminary |date=December 23, 2016 |publisher=PBS}}</ref> rVSV-ZEBOV received regulatory approval in 2019.<ref name=EMA_ZEBOV>{{cite web |url=https://www.ema.europa.eu/en/medicines/human/EPAR/ervebo |title=Ervebo |publisher=EMA |date=12 December 2019 |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=FDA_ZEBOV>{{cite web |url=https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/first-fda-approved-vaccine-prevention-ebola-virus-disease-marking-critical-milestone-public-health |title=First FDA-approved vaccine for the prevention of Ebola virus disease, marking a critical milestone in public health preparedness and response |publisher=FDA |date=19 December 2019 |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\n\nEbola virus disease (commonly known as \"Ebola\")  was first described in 1976 in two simultaneous outbreaks in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] and what is now [[South Sudan]].<ref>{{cite journal | pmc = 2395567 | pmid=307456 | volume=56 | issue=2 | title=Ebola haemorrhagic fever in Zaire, 1976 | year=1978 | journal=Bulletin of the World Health Organization | pages=271\u2013293}}</ref> The 2013\u20132016 outbreak, caused by Ebola virus (EBOV)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Becker |first1=Stephan |last2=Matrosovich |first2=Mikhail |last3=Kr\u00e4hling |first3=Verena |last4=Schudt |first4=Gordian |last5=Dietzel |first5=Erik |title=Functional Characterization of Adaptive Mutations during the West African Ebola Virus Outbreak |journal=Journal of Virology |date=15 January 2017 |volume=91 |issue=2 |pages=e01913\u2013e01916 |doi=10.1128/JVI.01913-16 |pmid=27847361 |pmc=5215343 }}</ref> was the first anywhere in the world to reach epidemic proportions. Previous outbreaks had been brought under control in a much shorter period of time. [[Extreme poverty]], dysfunctional healthcare systems, distrust of government after years of armed conflict, and the delay in responding for several months, all contributed to the failure to control the epidemic. Other factors, per media reports, included local burial customs of washing the body and the unprecedented spread of Ebola to densely populated cities.<ref name=sitrep_24Sept2014>{{cite report|title=Ebola response roadmap situation report |url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/134771/1/roadmapsitrep_24Sept2014_eng.pdf?ua=1 |format=PDF |publisher=WHO|accessdate=25 September 2014|page=6}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Runaway doctors and missing supplies cripple care in Ebola-hit Liberia |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ebola-virus-outbreak/runaway-doctors-missing-supplies-cripple-care-ebola-hit-liberia-n220686 |publisher=NBC News|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"WHO 2014-07-03\">{{cite report|url=http://www.afro.who.int/en/clusters-a-programmes/dpc/epidemic-a-pandemic-alert-and-response/outbreak-news/4216-ebola-virus-disease-west-africa-3-july-2014.html|title=Ebola virus disease, West Africa|date=3 July 2014|publisher=WHO|accessdate=18 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728210024/http://www.afro.who.int/en/clusters-a-programmes/dpc/epidemic-a-pandemic-alert-and-response/outbreak-news/4216-ebola-virus-disease-west-africa-3-july-2014.html|archivedate=28 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Global Post\">{{cite news |url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/xinhua-news-agency/140527/8-ebola-suspects-freed-relatives-sierra-leone |title=8 Ebola suspects freed by relatives in Sierra Leone |publisher=Global Post |agency=Xinhua |date=28 May 2014 |accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Today Health\">{{cite news |url=http://www.today.com/health/growing-ebola-outbreak-threatens-overwhelm-volunteers-2D79775266 |title=Growing Ebola outbreak threatens to overwhelm volunteers |publisher=Today Health |date=8 June 2014 |accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:2014 ebola virus epidemic in West Africa.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|Map showing death statistics as of 2014]]\nAs the outbreak progressed, the media reports, many hospitals, short on both staff and supplies, were overwhelmed and closed down, leading some health experts to state that the inability to treat other medical needs may have been causing \"an additional death toll [that is] likely to exceed that of the outbreak itself\".<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/ebola-outbreak-deaths-from-malaria-and-other-diseases-could-soar-while-africas-overstretched-healthcare-systems-fight-the-virus-expert-warns-9667362.html|title=Ebola outbreak: Deaths from malaria and other diseases could soar while Africa's over-stretched healthcare systems fight the virus, expert warns|newspaper=The Independent| date=27 October 2014|accessdate=28 October 2014|author=Cooper, Charlie|location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"Diary\">{{cite magazine|last1=Farmer|first1=Paul|title=Diary|url=http://www.lrb.co.uk/v36/n20/paul-farmer/diary|accessdate=25 October 2014|magazine=London Review of Books|date=23 October 2014}}</ref> Hospital workers, who worked closely with the highly contagious body fluids of the victims, were especially vulnerable to contracting the virus; in August 2014, the WHO reported that ten per cent of the dead had been healthcare workers.<ref name=\"As Ebola outbreak surges, health officials slam international 'Coalition of Inaction'\">{{cite web|url=http://www.commondreams.org/news/2014/09/03/ebola-outbreak-surges-health-officials-slam-international-coalition-inaction|title=As Ebola outbreak surges, health officials slam international 'Coalition of Inaction'|publisher=Common Dreams |date=3 September 2014 |accessdate=7 September 2014 |author=McCauley, Lauren}}</ref> In September 2014, it was estimated that the affected countries' capacity for treating Ebola patients was insufficient by the equivalent of 2,122 beds; however, by December 2014 there were enough beds to treat and isolate all reported cases, although the uneven distribution of cases was resulting in serious shortfalls in some areas.<ref name=\"WHO2014_12_10\">{{cite report |url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/145198/1/roadmapsitrep_10Dec2014_eng.pdf?ua=1|format= PDF|title=Ebola response roadmap situation report|publisher=WHO|date=10 December 2014|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe WHO has been widely criticised for its delay in taking action to address the epidemic.<ref name=\"AP News\">{{cite news | url=https://apnews.com/2489c78bff86463589b41f3faaea5ab2/emails-un-health-agency-resisted-declaring-ebola-emergency | title=Emails: UN health agency resisted declaring Ebola emergency | publisher=Associated Press | date=20 March 2015 | accessdate=21 March 2015 |author1=Cheng, Maria |author2=Satter, Raphael }}</ref> On 8 August 2014, it declared the outbreak a [[public health emergency of international concern]].<ref name=WHO_PHEIC_8Aug2014>{{cite report |url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2014/ebola-20140808/en/ |title=WHO Statement on the Meeting of the International Health Regulations Emergency Committee Regarding the 2014 Ebola Outbreak in West Africa |publisher=WHO |date=8 August 2014 |accessdate=8 August 2014}}</ref> By September 2014, [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res/Doctors Without Borders]] (MSF), the [[non-governmental organisation]] with the largest working presence in the affected countries, had grown increasingly critical of the international response. Speaking on 3 September, the International President of MSF spoke out concerning the lack of assistance from [[United Nations]] (UN) member countries: \"Six months into the worst Ebola epidemic in history, the world is losing the battle to contain it.\"<ref name=\"Ebola: the failures of the international outbreak response\">{{cite news|title=Ebola: the failures of the international outbreak response |url=https://www.msf.org/ebola-failures-international-outbreak-response |publisher=M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|accessdate=5 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref>  In a 26 September statement, the WHO stated that \"[t]he Ebola epidemic ravaging parts of Western Africa is the most severe acute public health emergency seen in modern times\" and its Director-General called the outbreak \"the largest, most complex and most severe we've ever seen\".<ref name=\"UN senior leaders outline needs for global Ebola response\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2014/ebola-response-needs/en/ |title=UN senior leaders outline needs for global Ebola response |publisher=WHO |date=3 September 2014 |accessdate=7 September 2014}}</ref> In March 2015, the [[United Nations Development Group]] reported that due to a decrease in trade, closing of borders, flight cancellations, and drop in foreign investment and tourism activity fuelled by stigma, the epidemic had resulted in vast economic consequences in both the affected areas in Western Africa and even in other African nations with no cases of Ebola.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.undp.org/content/undp/en/home/presscenter/pressreleases/2015/03/12/west-african-economies-feeling-ripple-effects-of-ebola-says-un.html|title=West African economies feeling ripple effects of Ebola, says UN |publisher=United Nations Development Programme |date=12 March 2015|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 January 2015, the WHO reported that for the first time since the week ending 29 June 2014, there had been fewer than 100 new confirmed cases reported in a week in the three most-affected countries. The response to the epidemic then moved to a second phase, as the focus shifted from slowing transmission to ending the epidemic.<ref name=\"WHO5feb\">{{cite report|url=http://apps.who.int/ebola/en/ebola-situation-report/situation-reports/ebola-situation-report-28-january-2015|title=Ebola situation report |date=28 January 2015|publisher=WHO|accessdate=5 February 2015}}</ref> On 8 April 2015, the WHO reported a total of only 30 confirmed cases,<ref name=\"WHO8apil\">{{cite report|url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/161244/1/roadmapsitrep_8Apr2015_eng.pdf?ua=1&ua=1|title=Ebola situation report|date=8 April 2015|publisher=WHO|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref> and the weekly update for 29 July reported only seven new cases.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2015/07/ebola-numbers-drop-sharply-guinea-sierra-leone|title=Ebola numbers drop sharply in Guinea, Sierra Leone|publisher=CIDRAP|accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref>  Cases continued to gradually dwindle and on 7 October 2015, all three of the most seriously affected countries, per media reports, recorded their first joint week without any new cases.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-34471234|title=Ebola countries record first week with no new cases|work=BBC News|accessdate=8 October 2015|date=2015-10-07}}</ref> However, as of late 2015, while the large-scale epidemic had ended, according to media reports, sporadic new cases were still being recorded, frustrating hopes that the epidemic could be declared over.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/20/ebola-case-in-liberia-confirmed-by-who|title=Liberian official urges calm as three new Ebola cases confirmed|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 July 2015, the WHO announced \"an extremely promising development\" in the search for an effective vaccine for Ebola virus disease. While the vaccine had shown high efficacy in individuals, more conclusive evidence was needed regarding its capacity to protect populations through [[herd immunity]].<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite journal |last1=Henao-Restrepo |first1=Ana Maria |last2=Longini |first2=Ira M |last3=Egger |first3=Matthias |last4=Dean |first4=Natalie E |last5=Edmunds |first5=W John |last6=Camacho |first6=Anton |last7=Carroll |first7=Miles W |last8=Doumbia |first8=Moussa |last9=Draguez |first9=Bertrand |last10=Duraffour |first10=Sophie |last11=Enwere |first11=Godwin |last12=Grais |first12=Rebecca |last13=Gunther |first13=Stephan |last14=Hossmann |first14=Stefanie |last15=Kond\u00e9 |first15=Mandy Kader |last16=Kone |first16=Souleymane |last17=Kuisma |first17=Eeva |last18=Levine |first18=Myron M |last19=Mandal |first19=Sema |last20=Norheim |first20=Gunnstein |last21=Riveros |first21=Ximena |last22=Soumah |first22=Aboubacar |last23=Trelle |first23=Sven |last24=Vicari |first24=Andrea S |last25=Watson |first25=Conall H |last26=K\u00e9\u00efta |first26=Sakoba |last27=Kieny |first27=Marie Paule |last28=R\u00f8ttingen |first28=John-Arne |title=Efficacy and effectiveness of an rVSV-vectored vaccine expressing Ebola surface glycoprotein: interim results from the Guinea ring vaccination cluster-randomised trial |journal=The Lancet |date=August 2015 |volume=386 |issue=9996 |pages=857\u2013866 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(15)61117-5|pmid=26248676|hdl=10144/575218 }}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite press release |title=World on the verge of an effective Ebola vaccine |url=http://who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2015/effective-ebola-vaccine/en/ |publisher=WHO |accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref>  In August 2015, after substantial progress in reducing the scale of the epidemic, the WHO held a meeting to work out a \"Comprehensive care plan for Ebola survivors\" and identify research needed to optimise clinical care and social well-being.  Stating that \"the Ebola outbreak has decimated families, health systems, economies, and social structures\", the WHO called the aftermath of the epidemic \"an emergency within an emergency.\"  Of special concern is recent research that shows some Ebola survivors experience a so-called \"post-Ebola Syndrome\", with symptoms so severe that survivors may require medical care for months and even years.<ref name=\"WHO20150807\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.afro.who.int/en/sierra-leone/press-materials/item/7908-an-emergency-within-an-emergency-caring-for-ebola-survivors.html | title=An emergency within an emergency: caring for Ebola survivors | publisher=WHO | date=7 August 2015 | accessdate=19 August 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150813163313/http://www.afro.who.int/en/sierra-leone/press-materials/item/7908-an-emergency-within-an-emergency-caring-for-ebola-survivors.html | archivedate=13 August 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"post\">{{cite journal |last1=Burki |first1=Talha Khan |title=Post-Ebola syndrome |journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases |date=1 July 2016 |volume=16 |issue=7 |pages=780\u2013781 |doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(15)00259-5 |pmid=27352759 |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(15)00259-5/fulltext |accessdate=6 March 2019  }}</ref>  As the main epidemic was coming to an end in December 2015, the UN announced that 22,000 children had lost one or both parents to Ebola.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=52913 |title=UN declares end to Ebola virus transmission in Guinea; first time all three host countries free <!--|author=no by-line.--> |date= |publisher=UN News Center |access-date=30 December 2015}}</ref>  On 29 March 2016, the Director-General of WHO terminated the Public Health Emergency of International Concern status of the Western African Ebola virus epidemic.<ref name=EmergencyEnd/>\n\n== Epidemiology ==\n\n=== Outbreak ===\n{{See also|Ebola virus epidemic in West Africa timeline}}\n[[File:Ebola Outbreak Map (ongoing).png|thumb|upright=1.5|Ebola outbreak worldwide{{legend|#eb1c23|Widespread outbreak}}{{legend|#ff7e29|Limited outbreak}}{{legend|#ffee00|Isolated cases}}{{legend|#00a1e6|Medically evacuated cases}}]]\nIt is generally believed that a one-year-old boy,<ref name=\"NYT122914\">{{cite news|author1=Kevin Sack |author2=Sheri Fink |author3=Pam Belluck |author4=Adam Nossiter|title=How Ebola Roared Back|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/30/health/how-ebola-roared-back.html|accessdate=30 December 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=29 December 2014|quote=The messages about don't touch the dead, wash your hands, if somebody is sick, leave them\u2014these were all strange things, completely contrary to our tradition and culture.<!--Anchor cite of important article, do not remove-->}}</ref> later identified as [[Emile Ouamouno]], who died in December 2013 in the village of [[Meliandou|M\u00e9liandou]], [[Gu\u00e9ck\u00e9dou Prefecture]], [[Guinea]], was the [[index case]] of the Western African epidemic.<ref name=\"Baize-2014\" /> Scientists have deduced that bats are involved in the spread of the virus,<ref>{{cite news|title=Scientists Discover Ebola Virus in West African Bat |url=https://www.mailman.columbia.edu/public-health-now/news/scientists-discover-ebola-virus-west-african-bat |work=www.mailman.columbia.edu |publisher=Columbia University Mailman School of Public Health|accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref> and, incidentally, the boy's home was in the vicinity of a large colony of [[Angolan free-tailed bat]]s, according to media reports.<ref name=mg>{{cite news |agency=AFP |date=30 December 2014 | title=Hollow tree in Guinea was Ebola's Ground Zero, scientists say |url=http://mgafrica.com/article/2014-12-30-hollow-tree-in-guinea-was-ebolas-ground-zero-scientists-say |publisher=Mail & Guardian Africa |accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref> His mother, sister, and grandmother, per media reports later became ill with similar symptoms and also died; people infected by these initial cases spread the disease to other villages.<ref name=\"tracingebola\">{{cite news | author=Grady, Denise | author2=Fink, Sheri | title=Tracing Ebola's Breakout to an African 2-Year-Old | newspaper=The New York Times | date=9 August 2014  |accessdate= 11 April 2015| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/10/world/africa/tracing-ebolas-breakout-to-an-african-2-year-old.html }}</ref><ref name=BBC-world-africa-30199004>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-30199004|title=How world's worst Ebola outbreak began with one boy's death|author=Nassos Stylianou |date=27 November 2014 |accessdate= 11 April 2015|work=BBC News}}</ref> There was knowledge of ''Tai Forest virus'' in C\u00f4te d'Ivoire, which had resulted in one human transmission in 1994. Thus, these early cases were diagnosed as other conditions more common to the area and the disease had several months to spread before it became recognised as Ebola.<ref name=\"Baize-2014\">{{cite journal|title= Emergence of Zaire Ebola Virus Disease in Guinea&nbsp;\u2013 Preliminary Report|date= 16 April 2014 |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa1404505 |last= Baize |first= Sylvain |last2= Pannetier |first2= Delphine |last3= Oestereich|first3= Lisa|last4= Rieger|first4= Toni|journal= New England Journal of Medicine |pmid= 24738640 |volume= 371 |issue= 15 |pages= 1418\u20131425|url= https://semanticscholar.org/paper/29bafbdb9b461edc7f705777a6672000570b896c }}</ref><ref name=\"tracingebola\" />\n[[File:ebola cases.gif|thumb|upright=1.5|Monthly aggregate Ebola cases in the Western Africa epidemic 2014\u201315]]\n[[File:ebola deaths.gif|thumb|upright=1.5|Monthly aggregate Ebola deaths in the Western Africa epidemic 2014\u201315]]\nOn 25 March 2014, the WHO indicated that [[Ministry of Health (Guinea)|Guinea's Ministry of Health]] had reported an outbreak of Ebola virus disease in four southeastern districts, and that suspected cases in the neighbouring countries of [[Liberia]] and [[Sierra Leone]] were being investigated. In Guinea, a total of 86 suspected cases, including 59 deaths, had been reported as of 24 March.<ref name=Previous_Updates_2014_West_Africa_Outbreak>{{cite report|url=https://www.cdc.gov/vhf/ebola/outbreaks/guinea/recent_updates.html |title=Previous Updates: 2014 West Africa Outbreak |publisher=CDC|accessdate= 11 April 2015}}</ref> By late May, the outbreak had spread to [[Conakry]], Guinea's capital\u2014a city of about two million people.<ref name=Previous_Updates_2014_West_Africa_Outbreak /> On 28 May, the total number of reported cases had reached 281, with 186 deaths.<ref name=Previous_Updates_2014_West_Africa_Outbreak />\n\nIn Liberia, the disease was reported in four counties by mid-April 2014 and cases in Liberia's capital [[Monrovia]] were reported in mid-June.<ref name=\"DON 16APR14\">{{cite report|url= http://www.afro.who.int/en/clusters-a-programmes/dpc/epidemic-a-pandemic-alert-and-response/outbreak-news/4100-ebola-virus-disease-west-africa-16-april-2014.html|title= Ebola virus disease, West Africa (Situation as of 16 April 2014)|publisher= WHO|accessdate= 18 September 2014|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141006171623/http://www.afro.who.int/en/clusters-a-programmes/dpc/epidemic-a-pandemic-alert-and-response/outbreak-news/4100-ebola-virus-disease-west-africa-16-april-2014.html|archivedate= 6 October 2014|df= dmy-all}}</ref> The outbreak then spread to Sierra Leone and progressed rapidly. By 17 July, the total number of suspected cases in the country stood at 442, surpassing those in Guinea and Liberia.<ref name=\"WHO 2014-07-18\">{{cite report|url=http://www.afro.who.int/en/clusters-a-programmes/dpc/epidemic-a-pandemic-alert-and-response/outbreak-news/4225-ebola-virus-disease-west-africa-18-july-2014.html|title=Ebola virus disease, West Africa|date=18 July 2014|publisher=WHO|accessdate=18 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140725195212/http://www.afro.who.int/en/clusters-a-programmes/dpc/epidemic-a-pandemic-alert-and-response/outbreak-news/4225-ebola-virus-disease-west-africa-18-july-2014.html|archivedate=25 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> By 20 July, additional cases of the disease had been reported by the media in the [[Bo District]], while the first case in [[Freetown]], Sierra Leone's capital, was reported in late July.<ref name=\"BBC_Freetown\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-28485041 |title=Sierra Leone hunts Ebola patient kidnapped in Freetown |work=BBC News |date=25 July 2014 |accessdate=27 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-28505061 |title=Ebola outbreak: Sierra Leone escaped patient dies |work=BBC News |date=27 July 2014 |accessdate=27 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs the epidemic progressed, a small outbreak occurred in Nigeria that resulted in 20 cases and another in Mali with 7&nbsp;cases. Four other countries (Senegal, Spain, the United Kingdom and the United States of America) also reported cases imported from Western Africa, with widespread and intense transmission.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite report | url= http://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/situation-reports/en/?m=20141112&file=sitreps/20141112/20141112.html | title= Ebola response roadmap situation report | publisher= WHO | date= 12 November 2014 | accessdate= 16 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"WHO2014_11_23\">{{cite report |url= http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/144498/1/roadmapsitrep_26Nov2014_eng.pdf?ua=1 |title= Ebola response roadmap situation report |publisher= WHO|date=26 November 2014 |accessdate = 27 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"WHO2014_11_30\">{{cite report |url= http://apps.who.int/gho/data/view.ebola-sitrep.ebola-summary-20141202?lang=en |title= Situation summary Data published on 2 December 2014|publisher= WHO|date= 2 December 2014|accessdate = 2 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March 2015, one year after the first report of the outbreak, the total number of cases was in excess of 25,000\u2014with over 10,000&nbsp;deaths.<ref name=\"WHO2015_03_31\">{{cite report|title=Ebola data and statistics|url=http://apps.who.int/gho/data/view.ebola-sitrep.ebola-summary-20150331?lang=en |publisher=WHO|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs the epidemic waned, following international control efforts, the edition of 8 April 2015 of the WHO's ''Ebola Situation Reports'' stated that a total of 30 cases were reported<ref>{{cite report|title=Ebola Situation Report |date=8 April 2015 |url=http://apps.who.int/ebola/current-situation/ebola-situation-report-8-april-2015|publisher=WHO|accessdate=29 October 2016}}</ref> and in 29 July 2015, the WHO weekly update reported only 7 cases\u2014the lowest in more than a year.<ref name=\":4\" />  In October 2015, the WHO recorded its first week without any new cases,<ref name=\":9\" /> and while the large-scale epidemic appeared to have ended by late 2015, sporadic new cases continued to be reported.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{cite report|url= http://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/flare-up-liberia/en/|title= Flare up of Ebola in Liberia|publisher= WHO|accessdate= 26 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 January 2016, after all the previously infected countries had been declared Ebola-free, the WHO reported that \"all known chains of transmission have been stopped in Western Africa\", but cautioned that further small outbreaks of the disease could occur in the future.<ref>{{cite news|title=West Africa declared free of Ebola transmission, but UN health agency warns new flare-ups possible |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2016/01/519932-west-africa-declared-free-ebola-transmission-un-health-agency-warns-new-flare |work=UN News |publisher=United Nations |accessdate=6 March 2019 |language=en |date=14 January 2016}}</ref> The following day, Sierra Leone confirmed its first new case since September 2015.<ref name=\"who.int1\"/>\n\n=== Countries that experienced widespread transmission ===\n[[File:2014 West Africa Ebola virus outbreak situation map.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Outbreak distribution map affected part of Western Africa (17 December 2014)]]\n\n==== Guinea ====\n{{Further|Ebola virus epidemic in Guinea}}\nOn 25 March 2014, the WHO reported an outbreak of Ebola virus disease in four southeastern districts of Guinea with a total of 86 suspected cases, including 59 deaths, and MSF assisted the Ministry of Health by establishing Ebola treatment centres in the epicentre of the outbreak.<ref name=Previous_Updates_2014_West_Africa_Outbreak /> On 31 March, the [[U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) sent a five-person team to assist in the response to the outbreak.<ref name=Previous_Updates_2014_West_Africa_Outbreak /> Thinking that spread of the virus had been contained, MSF closed its treatment centres in May, leaving only a skeleton staff to handle the [[Macenta]] region. However, in late August, according to media reports, large numbers of new cases reappeared in the region.<ref name=Guinea_Ebola_Sep_Update>{{cite news |url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/health/ebola-virus-is-surging-in-places-where-it-was-beaten-back-experts-1.1996179 |title=Ebola virus is surging in places where it was beaten back: experts |publisher=CTV News |date=8 September 2014 |accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, media reported that Guinea recorded a rise in cases for the second week in a row,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/ebola-cases-double-guinea-second-week-says-who-1487620|title=Ebola cases double in Guinea in second week, says WHO|publisher=International Business Times UK|accessdate=12 February 2015|date=2015-02-12}}</ref>  health authorities stated that this was related to the fact that they \"were only now gaining access to faraway villages\", where violence had previously prevented them from entering.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voanews.com/content/guinea-ebola-infections-double-as-hidden-cases-discovered/2631698.html|title=In Guinea, Ebola Infections Double as Hidden Cases Discovered|publisher=VOA|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref> On 14 February, violence erupted and an Ebola treatment centre near the centre of the country was destroyed.   Guinean [[Red Cross]] teams said they had suffered an average of 10 attacks a month over the previous year;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/02/14/us-health-ebola-guinea-idUSKBN0LI0G920150214|title=Crowds attack Ebola facility, health workers in Guinea|work=Reuters|accessdate=19 February 2015|date=14 February 2015}}</ref> MSF reported that acceptance of Ebola education remained low and that further violence against their workers might force them to leave.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-32103625|title=Guinea declares Ebola 'health emergency' in five regions|work=BBC News|accessdate=29 March 2015|date=2015-03-29}}</ref>\n\nResistance to interventions by health officials among the Guinean population remained greater than in Sierra Leone and Liberia, per media reports, raising concerns over its impact on ongoing efforts to halt the epidemic;  in mid-March, there were 95 new cases and on 28 March, and a 45-day \"health emergency\" was declared in 5 regions of the country.<ref name=\"auto3\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ebola-virus-outbreak/ebola-epidemic-slows-even-more-n358376|title=Ebola Epidemic Slows Even More, WHO Says|publisher=NBC News|date=13 May 2015|author=Fox, Maggie}}</ref>  On 22 May, the WHO reported another rise in cases, per media reports,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/guinea-reports-27-ebola-cases-previous-lull-31228633|title=Guinea Families Transport Bodies in Public Taxis|author=|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=23 May 2015}}</ref> which was believed to have been due to funeral transmissions;<ref>{{cite news |title=Guinea Ebola cases climb due to transmissions at funerals {{!}} Fox News |url=http://www.foxnews.com/health/2015/05/15/guinea-ebola-cases-climb-due-to-transmissions-at-funerals/ |accessdate=27 March 2019 |work=web.archive.org |date=29 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529232101/http://www.foxnews.com/health/2015/05/15/guinea-ebola-cases-climb-due-to-transmissions-at-funerals/ |archive-date=29 May 2015 }}</ref>  on 25 May, six persons were placed in prison isolation after they were found travelling with the corpse of an individual who had died of the disease,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-32877392|title=Ebola crisis: Guineans jailed for putting corpse in taxi|work=BBC News|accessdate=27 May 2015|date=2015-05-25}}</ref> on 1 June, it was reported that violent protests in a north Guinean town at the border with [[Guinea-Bissau]] had caused the Red Cross to withdraw its workers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/ebola-threat-guinea-bissau-rises-border-zone-heats-063714122.html|title=Ebola threat to Guinea Bissau rises as border zone heats up|date=2 June 2015|publisher=Yahoo! News|accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn late June 2015, the WHO reported that \"weekly case incidence has stalled at between 20 and 27 cases since the end of May, whilst cases continue to arise from unknown sources of infection, and to be detected only after [[post-mortem]] testing of community deaths\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=51245#.VYvszzfbJpg|title=United Nations News Centre|date=24 June 2015|publisher=UN News Service Section|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> On 29 July, a sharp decline in cases was reported,<ref name=\":4\" /> with only a single case, per media reports left by the end of the week,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ebola-virus-outbreak/ebola-rates-plummet-who-says-more-come-n404696|title=Ebola Rates Plummet, But WHO Says More to Come|author=Maggie Fox|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=7 August 2015}}</ref> the number of cases eventually plateaued at 1 or 2 cases per week after the beginning of August.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://apps.who.int/ebola/ebola-situation-reports-archive|date=17 September 2015|title=Ebola situation reports Archive |publisher=WHO |accessdate=20 September 2015}}</ref> On 28 October, an additional 3 cases were reported in the [[For\u00e9cariah Prefecture]] by the WHO.<ref name=\"WHO2015_10_28a\">{{cite report|url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/191299/1/ebolasitrep_28Oct2015_eng.pdf?ua=1|title=Ebola Situation Report |publisher=WHO |date=28 October 2015}}</ref> On 6 November, a media report indicated [[Tana, Guinea|Tana]] village to be the last known place with Ebola in the country,<ref>{{cite news|title = The Last Place on Earth With Ebola: Getting Guinea to Zero|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/07/world/africa/the-last-place-on-earth-with-ebola-guineas-fight-to-get-to-zero.html|newspaper= The New York Times|date = 6 November 2015|access-date = 8 November 2015|issn = 0362-4331|first = Dionne|last = Searcey}}</ref> and on 11 November, WHO indicated that no Ebola cases were reported in Guinea; this was the first time since the epidemic began, that no cases had been reported in any country.<ref>{{cite report |title=Ebola Situation Report|date=11 November 2015|url=http://apps.who.int/ebola/current-situation/ebola-situation-report-11-november-2015 |publisher=WHO |accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> On 15 November, the last quarantined individuals were released, per media reports<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/guinea-releases-last-68-people-ebola-quarantine-143241412.html|title=Guinea releases last 68 people from Ebola quarantine|date=14 November 2015|publisher=Yahoo! News}}</ref> and on 17 November, the last Ebola patient in Guinea\u2014a 3-week-old baby\u2014had recovered; the 42-day countdown toward the country being declared Ebola-free started on 17 November, the day after the patient yielded a second consecutive negative blood test.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/11/28/health-ebola-guinea-idUSL8N13N0FV20151128#uBtDZJMYH0TtKLqF.97|title=Guinea's last Ebola case, a baby girl, leaves hospital|author=Reuters Editorial|date=28 November 2015|work=Reuters|accessdate=29 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|title=Ebola Situation Report|date= 2 December 2015 |url=http://apps.who.int/ebola/current-situation/ebola-situation-report-2-december-2015|publisher=WHO}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/declaration-ebola-end/en/|title=Criteria for declaring the end of the Ebola outbreak in Guinea, Liberia or Sierra Leone|publisher=WHO|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref> The patient was discharged from the hospital on 28 November, per media reports<ref name=zoroya2015-11-17>{{cite news|title = Last known Ebola patient in West Africa recovers|url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2015/11/17/last-known-ebola-patient-baby-girl-recovers/75916410/|newspaper= USA Today|accessdate = 20 November 2015|last = Zoroya|first = Greg|date = 17 November 2015}}</ref>  on 29 December 2015, upon expiration of the 42-day waiting period, the WHO declared Guinea Ebola-free.<ref name=\"WHOend\">{{cite news|title=End of Ebola transmission in Guinea |url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/29-12-2015-end-of-ebola-transmission-in-guinea |publisher= WHO  |accessdate=6 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2016, the government of Guinea reported, per the media, that 2 people had again tested positive for Ebola virus in [[Korokpara]],<ref name=\"Reuters2016\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-guinea-idUSKCN0WJ2UQ|title=Guinea says two people tested positive for Ebola|work=Reuters|date=17 March 2016}}</ref> it was also reported that they were from the village where members of one family had recently died from vomiting (and diarrhea).<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/4263806/two-people-test-positive-ebola-guinea/|title=2 Test Positive for Ebola in Guinea|last=Reilly|first=Katie|magazine=Time |access-date=2 April 2016}}</ref> On 19 March, it was also reported by the media that another individual had died due to the virus at the treatment centre in [[Nzerekore]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-03-20/ebola-fourth-person-dies-in-guinea/7261234|title=Fourth person dies of Ebola in Guinea|publisher=ABC News Australia|language=en-AU|access-date=2 April 2016|date=2016-03-19}}</ref> consequently, the country's government quarantined an area around the home where the cases took place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/ebola-clinic-reopens-guinea-virus-resurfaces-140557643.html|title=Ebola clinic reopens in Guinea after virus resurfaces|publisher=Yahoo! news|access-date=2 April 2016}}</ref> On 22 March, the media reported that medical authorities in Guinea had quarantined 816 suspected contacts of the prior cases (more than 100 individuals were considered high-risk);<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/guinea-flareup-update/en/|title=Hundreds of contacts identified and monitored in new Ebola flare-up in Guinea|publisher=WHO|language=en-GB|access-date=2 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/live/world-africa-35783318|title=Africa highlights: Tuesday 22 March 2016 as it happened |work=BBC News |access-date=2 April 2016}}</ref> the same day, Liberia ordered its border with Guinea closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voanews.com/content/liberia-closes-boerder-with-guinea-after-ebola-flareup/3249034.html|title=Liberia Closes Border With Guinea After Ebola Flare-up |publisher=Voice of America|access-date=2 April 2016}}</ref> [[Macenta Prefecture]], {{convert|200|km}} from Korokpara, registered Guinea's fifth fatality due to Ebola virus disease within the same period.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-guinea-idUSKCN0WO2T1|title=Fifth person dies in Guinea Ebola flare-up|date=22 March 2016|work=Reuters|access-date=2 April 2016}}</ref> On 29 March, it was reported that about 1,000 contacts had been identified (142 of them high-risk),<ref name=EmergencyEnd>{{cite report|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2016/ihr-emergency-committee-ebola/en/|title=WHO Director-General briefs media on outcome of Ebola Emergency Committee|publisher=WHO|language=en-GB|access-date=2 April 2016}}</ref> and on 30 March 3 more confirmed cases were reported from the sub-prefecture of Koropara.<ref name=\"30who2016\">{{cite report|url=http://apps.who.int/ebola/current-situation/ebola-situation-report-30-march-2016|title=Ebola Situation Report |author=|date=30 March 2016|publisher=WHO|accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref> On 1 April, it was reported by the media, that possible contacts, which numbered in the hundreds, had been vaccinated with an experimental vaccine using a [[ring vaccination]] approach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/health/2016/04/01/hundreds-in-guinea-get-ebola-vaccine-in-fight-against-flare-up.html|title=Hundreds in Guinea get Ebola vaccine in fight against flare-up|date=1 April 2016|publisher=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=2 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kucharski |first1=Adam J. |last2=Eggo |first2=Rosalind M. |last3=Watson |first3=Conall H. |last4=Camacho |first4=Anton |last5=Funk |first5=Sebastian |last6=Edmunds |first6=W. John |title=Effectiveness of Ring Vaccination as Control Strategy for Ebola Virus Disease |journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases |date=2016 |volume=22 |issue=1 |pages=105\u2013108 |doi=10.3201/eid2201.151410 |pmid=26691346 |pmc=4696719 }}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 2016, it was reported via the media, that there had been 9 new cases of Ebola since the virus resurfaced, out of which 8 were fatal;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/ebola-claims-another-victim-guinea-vaccinations-ramped-192323781.html|title=Ebola claims another victim in Guinea as vaccinations ramped up|date=5 April 2016|publisher=Yahoo! News|language=en-US|access-date=6 April 2016}}</ref> on 1 June, after the stipulated waiting period, the WHO again declared Guinea Ebola-free,<ref name=\"guin\">{{cite magazine|title=2 Test Positive for Ebola in Guinea |url=http://time.com/4263806/two-people-test-positive-ebola-guinea/ |magazine=Time |accessdate=31 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> after which the country entered a 90-day period of heightened surveillance that was concluded on 30 August 2016.\n\nIn September 2016, findings were published suggesting that the resurgence in Guinea was caused by an Ebola survivor who, after eight months of abstinence, had sexual relations with several partners, including the first victim in the new outbreak.<ref name=\"lurked\">{{Cite journal|last=Duraffour|first=Sophie|last2=Rambaut|first2=Andrew|last3=G\u00fcnther|first3=Stephan|last4=Ke\u00efta|first4=Sakoba|last5=Formenty|first5=Pierre|last6=Diarra|first6=Abdoulaye|last7=Djingarey|first7=Mamoudou Harouna|last8=Aylward|first8=Raymond Bruce|last9=Carroll|first9=Miles W.|date=15 November 2016|title=Resurgence of Ebola Virus Disease in Guinea Linked to a Survivor With Virus Persistence in Seminal Fluid for More Than 500 Days|journal=Clinical Infectious Diseases|volume=63|issue=10|pages=1353\u20131356|doi=10.1093/cid/ciw601|pmc=5091350|pmid=27585800}}</ref><ref name=BDiallo>{{cite journal |last1=Diallo |first1=Boubacar |last2=Sissoko |first2=Daouda |last3=Loman |first3=Nicholas J. |last4=Bah |first4=Hadja A\u00efssatou |last5=Bah |first5=Hawa |last6=Worrell |first6=Mary Claire |last7=Conde |first7=lya Saidou |last8=Sacko |first8=Ramata |last9=Mesfin |first9=Samuel |last10=Loua |first10=Angelo |last11=Kalonda |first11=Jacques Katomba |last12=Erondu |first12=Ngozi A. |last13=Dahl |first13=Benjamin A. |last14=Handrick |first14=Susann |last15=Goodfellow |first15=Ian |last16=Meredith |first16=Luke W. |last17=Cotten |first17=Matthew |last18=Jah |first18=Umaru |last19=Guetiya Wadoum |first19=Raoul Emeric |last20=Rollin |first20=Pierre |last21=Magassouba |first21=N'Faly |last22=Malvy |first22=Denis |last23=Anglaret |first23=Xavier |last24=Carroll |first24=Miles W. |last25=Aylward |first25=Raymond Bruce |last26=Djingarey |first26=Mamoudou Harouna |last27=Diarra |first27=Abdoulaye |last28=Formenty |first28=Pierre |last29=Ke\u00efta |first29=Sakoba |last30=G\u00fcnther |first30=Stephan |last31=Rambaut |first31=Andrew |last32=Duraffour |first32=Sophie |title=Resurgence of Ebola Virus Disease in Guinea Linked to a Survivor With Virus Persistence in Seminal Fluid for More Than 500 Days |journal=Clinical Infectious Diseases |date=15 November 2016 |volume=63 |issue=10 |pages=1353\u20131356 |doi=10.1093/cid/ciw601|pmid=27585800|pmc=5091350}}</ref> The disease was also spread to Liberia by a woman who went there after her husband had died of Ebola.<ref name=discharge/>\n\n==== Sierra Leone ====\n{{Further|Ebola virus epidemic in Sierra Leone}}\n[[File:Kenema Hospital Sierra Leone Ebola.JPG|thumb|Kenema Hospital, Sierra Leone]]\nThe first person reported infected in Sierra Leone, according to media reports, was a [[Traditional medicine|tribal healer]] who had been treating Ebola patients from across the nearby border with Guinea and who died on 26 May 2014; according to tribal tradition, her body was washed for burial, and this appears to have led to infections in women from neighbouring towns.<ref name=\"Fox News\">{{cite news |url= http://www.foxnews.com/health/2014/08/25/sierra-leone-hero-doctor-death-exposes-slow-ebola-response/ |title= Sierra Leone 'hero' doctor's death exposes slow Ebola response |publisher= Fox News |date= 25 August 2014 |accessdate= 25 August 2014}}</ref> On 11 June Sierra Leone shut its borders for trade with Guinea and Liberia and closed some schools in an attempt to slow the spread of the virus;<ref>{{cite news |url= http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/06/11/us-health-ebola-leone-idUKKBN0EM2CG20140611|title= Sierra Leone shuts borders, closes schools to fight Ebola |work= Reuters |date= 11 June 2014 | accessdate= 11 April 2015}}</ref> on 30 July the government began to deploy troops to enforce quarantines,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.news24.com/Africa/News/Sierra-Leone-Liberia-deploy-troops-for-Ebola-20140804 |title= Sierra Leone, Liberia deploy troops for Ebola|publisher= News 24 |date= 4 August 2014 | accessdate= 11 April 2015}}</ref> and by 15 October the last district in Sierra Leone previously untouched by the disease had declared Ebola cases.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.foxnews.com/world/2014/10/16/ebola-cases-appear-in-last-untouched-district-in-sierra-leone|title= Ebola cases appear in last untouched district in Sierra Leone|publisher= Fox News|date= 16 October 2014|accessdate= 16 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring the first week of November reports told of a worsening situation due to intense transmission in Freetown. According to the Disaster Emergency Committee, food shortages resulting from aggressive quarantines were making the situation worse,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://news.vice.com/article/the-ebola-outbreak-is-getting-worse-in-sierra-leone|title= The Ebola Outbreak Is Getting Worse in Sierra Leone|publisher= VICE News|accessdate= 10 November 2014|date= 2014-11-06}}</ref> and on 4 November media reported that thousands had violated quarantine in search of food in the town of [[Kenema]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/world/2014/11/04/ebola-west-africa/18463943/|title= Thousands in Sierra Leone break Ebola quarantine|first1= Sarah |last1= DiLorenzo|date= 4 November 2014|publisher= Associated Press|accessdate= 5 November 2014}}</ref> With the number of cases continuing to increase, an MSF coordinator described the situation in Sierra Leone as \"catastrophic\", saying, \"there are several villages and communities that have been basically wiped out&nbsp;... Whole communities have disappeared but many of them are not in the statistics.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= http://rt.com/news/201567-ebola-sierra-leone-toll-underreported/|title= 'Entire villages disappeared': Ebola deaths in Sierra Leone 'underreported'|publisher= Russia Today |accessdate= 7 November 2014}}</ref> In mid-November the WHO reported that, while there was some evidence that the number of cases were no longer rising in Guinea and Liberia, steep increases persisted in Sierra Leone.<ref name=\":5\" />\n[[File:Ebola crisis- More UK aid arrives in Sierra Leone (15327635047).jpg|thumb|Ebola crisis: More UK aid arrives in Sierra Leone]]\nOn 9 December 2014 news reports described the discovery of \"a grim scene\"\u2014piles of bodies, overwhelmed medical personnel and exhausted burial teams\u2014in the remote eastern [[Kono District]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-12-11/sierra-leone-hit-by-largely-hidden-ebola-outbreak/5959596|title= Ebola crisis: Sierra Leone hit by largely hidden outbreak; WHO says scores of bodies piled up|publisher= ABC News|accessdate= 11 December 2014|date= 2014-12-10}}</ref>  On 15 December the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] indicated that their main concern was Sierra Leone, where the epidemic had shown no signs of abating as cases continued to rise exponentially; by the second week of December, Sierra Leone had reported nearly 400&nbsp;cases\u2014more than three times the number reported by Guinea and Liberia combined. According to the CDC, \"the risk we face now [is] that Ebola will simmer along, become native and be a problem for Africa and the world, for years to come\".<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.npr.org/blogs/goatsandsoda/2014/12/15/370446566/endless-ebola-endemic-thats-the-risk-we-face-now-cdc-says|title= Endless Ebola Epidemic? That's The 'Risk We Face Now,' CDC Says|date= 15 December 2014|publisher= NPR |accessdate= 18 December 2014}}</ref>  On 17 December [[Ernest Bai Koroma|President Koroma]] of Sierra Leone launched \"Operation Western Area Surge\" and workers went door-to-door in the capital city looking for possible cases.<ref name=\"Ebola_Outbreak_total_sl_14_Dec\">{{cite report|publisher= Sierra Leone Ministry of Health and Sanitation| url= http://health.gov.sl/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Ebola-Situation-Report_Vol-201.pdf| format= PDF| title= Sierra Leone: Ebola Virus Disease \u2013 Situation Report| accessdate= 15 December 2014| date= 15 December 2014| url-status= dead| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141220203935/http://health.gov.sl/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Ebola-Situation-Report_Vol-201.pdf| archivedate= 20 December 2014| df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-30511208|title= Ebola: Sierra Leone begins house-to-house searches|work= BBC News|accessdate= 18 December 2014|date= 2014-12-17}}</ref>  The operation led to a surge in reports of cases, with 403&nbsp;new ones reported between 14&nbsp;and&nbsp;17 December.<ref name=Ebola_Outbreak_total_sl_14_Dec /><ref name=\"Ebola_Outbreak_total_sl_18_Dec\">{{cite report|publisher= Sierra Leone Ministry of Health and Sanitation| url= http://health.gov.sl/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Ebola-Situation-Report_Vol-204.pdf| format= PDF| title= Ebola Virus Disease \u2013 Situation Report| accessdate= 19 December 2014| date= 18 December 2014| url-status= dead| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141219161011/http://health.gov.sl/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Ebola-Situation-Report_Vol-204.pdf| archivedate= 19 December 2014| df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 21 January 2015 WHO Situation Report, the case [[Incidence (epidemiology)|incidence]] was rapidly decreasing in Sierra Leone.<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Ebola Could be 'Levelling Off' in Sierra Leone: WHO|url= http://www.newsweek.com/ebola-could-be-levelling-sierra-leone-who-297831|magazine= Newsweek|date= 8 January 2015|accessdate= 11 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Latest-News-Wires/2015/0114/Sierra-Leone-predicts-no-new-Ebola-cases-by-March-end-video|title= Sierra Leone predicts no new Ebola cases by March end (+video)|work= Christian Science Monitor|publisher= The Christian Science Monitor|accessdate= 15 January 2015|date= 2015-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite report |title= Ebola Situation Report | date= 21 January 2015 |url= http://apps.who.int/ebola/en/status-outbreak/situation-reports/ebola-situation-report-21-january-2015 |publisher= WHO|accessdate= 27 January 2019}}</ref> However, in February and March reports indicated a rise again in the number of cases.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2015/02/05/ebola-liberia-sierra-leone-guinea-infections-increase/22935171/|title= Downward Ebola trend suddenly reverses itself|author= Gregg Zoroya|date= 5 February 2015|newspaper= USA Today|accessdate= 6 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.voanews.com/content/ebola-hit-sierra-leone-to-reopen-schools-march-3oth/2629854.html|title= Ebola-hit Sierra Leone to Reopen Schools March 30|publisher= VOA|accessdate= 7 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.philstar.com/world/2015/02/21/1426253/decline-ebola-cases-flattens-raising-un-concern|title= Decline in Ebola cases flattens, raising UN concern|publisher= Philadelphia Star |accessdate= 22 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.gnnliberia.com/articles/2015/03/05/more-ebola-guinea-sierra-leone-last-week-no-liberia-cases-says-who|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150402093450/http://www.gnnliberia.com/articles/2015/03/05/more-ebola-guinea-sierra-leone-last-week-no-liberia-cases-says-who|archivedate= 2 April 2015|title= More Ebola in Guinea, Sierra Leone last week, no Liberia cases says WHO|publisher= gnnliberia.com|accessdate= 7 March 2015}}</ref>  The following month, the 5 April WHO report again disclosed a downward trend<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.voanews.com/content/lowest-weekly-figure-of-ebola-cases-reported-in-nearly-a-year/2711801.html|title= Lowest Weekly Figure of Ebola Cases Reported in Nearly a Year|publisher= VOA|accessdate= 10 April 2015}}</ref> and the WHO weekly update for 29 July reported a total of only 3 new cases, the lowest in more than a year.<ref name=\":4\" /> On 17 August the country marked its first week with no new cases,<ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://time.com/4000158/sierra-leone-no-new-ebola/|title= Sierra Leone Has First Week of No New Ebola Cases|author= Alexandra Sifferlin|magazine= Time |accessdate= 19 August 2015|date= 17 August 2015}}</ref> and one week later the last patients were released.<ref>[https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=51732#.Vd7mcTZRFpg Sierra Leone begins 42-day countdown to be declared free of Ebola virus transmission]. ''UN News Centre''. 26 August 2015.</ref>  However, a new case emerged on 1 September, when a patient from Sella Kafta village in [[Kambia District]] tested positive for the disease after her death;<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.news24.com/Africa/News/New-Ebola-death-in-Sierra-Leone-sets-back-efforts-to-beat-epidemic-20150831|title= New Ebola death in Sierra Leone sets back efforts to beat epidemic|publisher= News 24|accessdate= 1 September 2015|date= 1 September 2015 }}</ref> her case eventually resulted in 3 other infections among her contacts.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2015/09/08/sierra-leone-officials-confirm-3-new-cases-of-ebola |title= Sierra Leone officials confirm 3 new cases of Ebola among high risk contacts with fatal case |agency= Associated Press |accessdate= 9 September 2015 |date= 8 September 2015 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151121075747/http://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2015/09/08/sierra-leone-officials-confirm-3-new-cases-of-ebola |archivedate= 21 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn 14 September 2015 Sierra Leone's National Ebola Response Centre confirmed the death of a 16-year-old in a village in the [[Bombali District]].<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite news|url= http://www.ctvnews.ca/health/new-ebola-death-reported-in-northern-sierra-leone-1.2562302|title= New Ebola death reported in northern Sierra Leone|publisher= CTV News|accessdate= 14 September 2015|date= 14 September 2015 }}</ref> It is suspected that she contracted the disease from the semen of an Ebola survivor who had been discharged in March 2015.<ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite news|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/09/14/us-health-ebola-leone-idUSKCN0RE1P620150914|title= Hundreds quarantined as Ebola returns to north Sierra Leone district|work= Reuters|accessdate= 14 September 2015|date= 14 September 2015 }}</ref> On 27 September a new 42-day countdown began to declare the country Ebola-free,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.voanews.com/content/sierra-leone-begins-new-ebola-42-day-countdown/2982177.html|title= Sierra Leone Begins New Ebola 42-day Countdown|publisher= VOA|accessdate= 30 September 2015}}</ref> which eventually occurred on 7 November 2015; thereafter, the country increased its vigilance on the Guinean border.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.voanews.com/content/anticipation-grows-as-sierra-leone-readies-to-be-declared-ebola-free/3041603.html|title= Anticipation Grows as Sierra Leone Readies to be Declared Ebola-free|publisher= VOA|accessdate= 8 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url= http://apps.who.int/ebola/current-situation/ebola-situation-report-11-november-2015|title= Ebola Situation Report | date= 11 November 2015|publisher= WHO|accessdate= 27 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nSierra Leone had entered a 90-day period of enhanced surveillance that was scheduled to end on 5 February 2016, when, on 14 January, a new Ebola death was reported in the [[Tonkolili District]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://apps.who.int/ebola/current-situation/ebola-situation-report-9-december-2015|title= Ebola Situation Report | date= 9 December 2015|accessdate= 17 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-35320363|title= Ebola virus: New case emerges in Sierra Leone|work= BBC News|date= 2016-01-15}}</ref> Prior to this case, the WHO had advised that \"we still anticipate more flare-ups and must be prepared for them. A massive effort is underway to ensure robust prevention, surveillance and response capacity across all three countries by the end of March.\"<ref>{{cite report|url= http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2016/ebola-zero-liberia/en/|title= Latest Ebola outbreak over in Liberia; West Africa is at zero, but new flare-ups are likely to occur|publisher= WHO}}</ref> On 16 January aid workers reported that a woman had died of the virus and that she may have exposed several individuals; the government later announced that 100 people had been quarantined.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jan/15/ebola-victim-in-sierra-leone-feared-to-have-exposed-27-others-to-virus|title= Sierra Leone puts more than 100 people in quarantine after new Ebola death|newspaper= The Guardian|date= 2016-01-17}}</ref> Investigations indicated that the deceased was a female student from [[Lunsar]], in [[Port Loko District]], who had gone to [[Kambia District]] on 28 December 2015 before returning symptomatic. She had also visited Bombali District to consult a herbalist, and had later gone to a government hospital in [[Magburaka]]. The WHO indicated that there were 109&nbsp;contacts (28 of them high-risk), that there were another 3&nbsp;missing contacts, and that the source or route of transmission that caused the fatality was unknown.<ref>{{cite report |url= http://www.afro.who.int/en/sierra-leone/press-materials/item/8281-government-press-statement-confirmation-of-evd-death-in-sierra-leone-\u2013-16-january-2016.html |title= Government Press Statement: Confirmation of EVD Death in Sierra Leone |publisher= WHO |date= 16 January 2016 |accessdate= 21 January 2016 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160122004724/http://www.afro.who.int/en/sierra-leone/press-materials/item/8281-government-press-statement-confirmation-of-evd-death-in-sierra-leone-%E2%80%93-16-january-2016.html |archivedate= 22 January 2016 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> A second new case\u2014confirmed by WHO spokesman Tarik Jasarevic to involve a 38-year-old relative and caregiver of the aforementioned Ebola victim\u2014had become symptomatic on 20 Jan while under observation at a quarantine centre.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.itv.com/news/update/2016-01-20/sierra-leone-confirms-second-case-of-ebola-in-a-week/ |title= Sierra Leone confirms second case of Ebola in a week |publisher= Yahoo! News |date= 20 January 2016 |accessdate= 21 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url= http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/01/fear-sierra-leone-ebola-case-confirmed-160121055559943.html|title= Ebola in Sierra Leone: New case spreads community fear|publisher= WHO|accessdate= 22 January 2016}}</ref> On 22 January it was reported that this patient was responding to treatment.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://news.yahoo.com/sierra-leone-ebola-case-responding-treatment-222558577.html|title= New Sierra Leone Ebola case responding to treatment|date= 22 January 2016|publisher= Yahoo! News|accessdate= 27 January 2016}}</ref> On 26 January WHO Director-General, Dr&nbsp;Margaret Chan officially confirmed that the outbreak was not yet over;<ref name=\"who.int1\"/> that same day, it was also reported that Ebola restrictions had halted market activity in Kambia District amid protests.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/sierra-leone-youth-protest-ebola-restrictions-36530631|title= Health Index|publisher= ABC News|date= |accessdate= 9 June 2016}}</ref> On 7 February 70&nbsp;individuals were released from quarantine,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://learningenglish.voanews.com/content/sierra-leone-releases-ebola-quarantine/3178930.html|title= Sierra Leone Releases 70 from Ebola Quarantine|author= |date= |publisher= VOA |accessdate= 9 June 2016}}</ref> and on 8 February the last Ebola patient was also released.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-leone-idUSKCN0VH1ZD|title= Sierra Leone discharges last known Ebola patient|date= 8 February 2016|work= Reuters |accessdate= 9 June 2016}}</ref> On 17 February the WHO indicated that 2,600 Ebola survivors had accessed health assessments and eye examinations.<ref name=\"16who161\">{{cite report |title= Latest Ebola outbreak over in Liberia; West Africa is at zero, but new flare-ups are likely to occur |url= http://www.who.int/en/news-room/detail/14-01-2016-latest-ebola-outbreak-over-in-liberia-west-africa-is-at-zero-but-new-flare-ups-are-likely-to-occur |publisher= WHO |accessdate= 30 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 February 2016 the last known case tested negative for a second consecutive time and Sierra Leone commenced another 42-day countdown towards being declared Ebola-free.<ref>{{cite report|url= http://apps.who.int/ebola/current-situation/ebola-situation-report-17-february-2016|title= Ebola Situation Report |author= |date= 17 February 2016|publisher= WHO |accessdate= 9 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url= http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2016/end-flare-ebola-sierra-leone/en/|title= WHO statement on end of Ebola flare-up in Sierra Leone|author= |date= |publisher= WHO |accessdate= 9 June 2016}}</ref> On 17 March 2016 the WHO announced that the Sierra Leone flare-up was over, and that no other chains of transmission were known to be active at that time.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://news.yahoo.com/sierra-leone-ebola-flare-over-virus-no-longer-093953051.html|title= Sierra Leone Ebola flare-up over, virus no longer spreading: WHO|publisher= Yahoo! News|access-date= 17 March 2016}}</ref> The media reported that Sierra Leone then entered a 90-day period of heightened surveillance, which concluded on 15 June 2016, and it was reported that by 15 July the country had discontinued testing corpses for the virus.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title= Sierra Leone Stops Mandatory Testing Of Corpses For Ebola\n|url= http://www.ndtv.com/world-news/sierra-leone-stops-mandatory-testing-of-corpses-for-ebola-1431971\n|publisher= Agence France Presse|accessdate= 1 August 2016\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==== Liberia ====\n{{Further|Ebola virus epidemic in Liberia}}\n[[File:Ebola Treatment Unit.jpg|thumb|An Ebola treatment unit in Liberia]]\nIn Liberia, the disease was reported in both [[Lofa County|Lofa]] and [[Nimba County|Nimba]] counties in late March 2014.<ref name=\"liberianobserver.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.liberianobserver.com/security-health/2-5-test-positive-ebola-liberia |title=2 of 5 Test Positive for Ebola in Liberia |publisher=Liberian Observer |date=31 March 2014 |accessdate=6 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140709004219/http://www.liberianobserver.com/security-health/2-5-test-positive-ebola-liberia |archivedate= 9 July 2014 }}</ref>  On 27 July, [[Ellen Johnson Sirleaf|President Ellen Johnson Sirleaf]] announced that Liberia would close its borders, with the exception of a few crossing points such as the airport, where screening centres would be established.<ref name=BBC_28_July_2014>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-28522824 |title=Ebola outbreak: Liberia shuts most border points |work=BBC News |date=28 July 2014 |accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref> Schools and universities were closed,<ref>{{cite news|last=Kwanue|first=C.Y.|url=http://www.liberianobserver.com/security/compliance-sirleaf%E2%80%99s-mandate-ul-closed|title=In Compliance with Sirleaf's Mandate, UL Closed|publisher=Liberian Observer|date=1 August 2014|accessdate=2 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808051313/http://www.liberianobserver.com/security/compliance-sirleaf%E2%80%99s-mandate-ul-closed|archivedate=8 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/30/health-ebola-africa-idUSL6N0Q56DX20140730|title=Liberia shuts schools, quarantines communities in bid to halt Ebola|work=Reuters|date=30 July 2014|accessdate=30 July 2014}}</ref> and the worst-affected areas in the country were placed under quarantine.<ref name=\"BBC_28_July_20142\">{{cite news |url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-28522824|title = Ebola outbreak: Liberia shuts most border points|work= BBC News|date = 28 July 2014|accessdate = 28 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nWith only 50 physicians in the entire country\u2014one for every 70,000&nbsp;citizens\u2014Liberia was already in a healthcare crisis.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-29516663 | title=Ebola outbreak: Liberia 'close to collapse' \u2013 ambassador | publisher=BBC News Africa | author=Katty, Kay | date=7 October 2014 | accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>  In September, the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] reported that some hospitals had been abandoned, while those still functioning lacked basic facilities and supplies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Runaway Doctors and Missing Supplies Cripple Care in Ebola-Hit Liberia|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ebola-virus-outbreak/runaway-doctors-missing-supplies-cripple-care-ebola-hit-liberia-n220686|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>  In October, the Liberian ambassador in Washington was reported as saying that he feared that his country may be \"close to collapse\";<ref name=\":6\" />  by 24 October, all [[counties of Liberia|15 counties]] had reported Ebola cases.<ref name=\"WHO20141022\">{{cite report|url = http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/137091/1/roadmapsitrep22Oct2014_eng.pdf|format = PDF|accessdate = 22 October 2014|title = Ebola Response Roadmap Situation Report|date = 22 October 2014|publisher= WHO}}</ref><ref name=\"Ebola_Outbreak_total_lr_24_Oct\">{{cite report |publisher= Liberia Ministry of Health and Social Welfare|url=http://www.mohsw.gov.lr/documents/SITREP%20162%20Oct%2024th%202014_1.pdf |title=Liberia Ebola SitRep no. 157 |accessdate=24 October 2014 |date=24 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20141204105311/http://www.mohsw.gov.lr/documents/SITREP%20162%20Oct%2024th%202014_1.pdf |archivedate=4 December 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBy November 2014, the rate of new infections in Liberia appeared to be declining and the state of emergency was lifted.  The drop in cases was believed to be related to an integrated strategy combining isolation and treatment with community behaviour change, including safe burial practices, case finding and [[contact tracing]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Cumming-Bruce |first=Nick |date=29 October 2014 |title=Ebola Slowing in Liberia, WHO Says, but International Support Is Still Necessary |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/30/world/africa/ebola-liberia-who.html |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=3 November 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ebola state of emergency lifted in Liberia|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/ebola-vaccine-trials-to-begin-in-west-africa-amid-threat-of-mali-outbreak/|publisher=CBS News|date=14 November 2014|accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, the MSF field coordinator reported that Liberia was down to only 5&nbsp;confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-01-29/worlds-largest-ebola-unit-dismantled-as-outbreak-retreats/6053498|title=Ebola outbreak eases as world's largest treatment centre dismantled|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=29 January 2015|date=2015-01-29}}</ref>  In March, after two weeks of not reporting any new cases, 3&nbsp;new cases were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.healthmap.org/site/diseasedaily/article/three-new-ebola-cases-liberia-32715|title=Three New Ebola Cases in Liberia|publisher=The Disease Daily|date=27 March 2015|accessdate=28 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330072625/http://www.healthmap.org/site/diseasedaily/article/three-new-ebola-cases-liberia-32715|archive-date=30 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>  On 8 April, a new health minister was named in an effort to end Ebola in the country and on 26 April, MSF handed the Ebola treatment facility, ELWA-3, over to the government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201504271412.html|title=allAfrica.com: Liberia: MSF Hands Over ELWA \u2013 3 to Liberian Ministry of Health|publisher=allAfrica.com|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>  On 30 April, the US shut down a special Ebola treatment unit in Liberia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/us-shuts-ebola-treatment-center-liberia-30703643|title=US Shuts Down Ebola Treatment Center in Liberia|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=2 May 2015}}</ref>  The last known case of Ebola died on 27 March,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/liberia-names-health-minister-seeks-beat-ebola-144957753.html|title=Liberia names new health minister as it seeks to beat Ebola|date=8 April 2015|publisher=Yahoo! News|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref> and the country was officially declared Ebola-free on 9 May 2015, after 42&nbsp;days without any further cases being recorded.  The WHO congratulated Liberia saying, \"reaching this milestone is a testament to the strong leadership and coordination of Liberian President Ellen Johnson Sirleaf and the Liberian Government, the determination and vigilance of Liberian communities, the extensive support of global partners, and the tireless and heroic work of local and international health teams.\"<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite report|url= http://www.who.int/features/2015/liberia-ends-ebola/en/|title= How Liberia got to zero cases of Ebola|date= 9 May 2015|publisher= WHO|accessdate= 10 May 2015}}</ref>  As at May 2015, the country remained on high alert against recurrence of the disease.<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/10/world/africa/liberia-is-free-of-ebola-world-health-organization-declares.html|title = Liberia Is Declared Free of Ebola, but Officials Sound Note of Caution|date = 9 May 2015|newspaper= The New York Times|last = Fink|first = Sheri}}</ref><ref>{{cite report |url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/161244/1/roadmapsitrep_8Apr2015_eng.pdf?ua=1 |title=Ebola situation report |publisher=WHO |date=8 April 2015 |format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/164523/1/roadmapsitrep_6May15_eng.pdf?ua=1|title=Ebola situation report |publisher=WHO |date=6 May 2015 |format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nAfter three months with no new reports of cases, on 29 June Liberia reported that the body of a 17-year-old boy, who had been treated for malaria, tested positive for Ebola.  The WHO said the boy had been in close contact with at least 200 people,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/04/world/africa/liberia-200-reportedly-had-contact-with-ebola-victim.html?_r=0 |title=Liberia: 200 Reportedly Had Contact With Ebola Victim |newspaper=The New York Times |author=Gladstone, Rick |date=3 July 2015}}</ref> who they were following up, and that \"the case reportedly had no recent history of travel, contact with visitors from affected areas, or funeral attendance.\"  A second case was confirmed on 1 July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2015/06/30/418913144/ebola-returns-to-liberia-with-a-mysterious-case-near-monrovia|title=Ebola Returns To Liberia With A Mysterious Case Near Monrovia|date=30 June 2015|publisher=NPR |accessdate=1 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/liberia-reports-second-case-ebola-n385116|title=Liberia Reports Second Case of Ebola|date=1 July 2015|publisher=NBC News}}</ref>  After a third new case was confirmed on 2 July, and it was discovered that all 3 new cases had shared a meal of [[dog meat]], researchers looked at the possibility that the meat may have been involved in the transfer of the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/07/02/us-health-ebola-liberia-idUSKCN0PC0WJ20150702|title=Liberia investigating animal link after Ebola re-emerges|date=2 July 2015|work=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pulse.com.gh/news/in-liberia-dog-meat-identified-as-possible-source-of-ebola-id3931731.html|title=In Liberia: Dog meat identified as possible source of Ebola|author=Sena Quashie|date=2 July 2015|publisher=pulse.com.gh|accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref>  Testing of the dog's remains, however, was negative for the Ebola virus.<ref>Reuters. (7 July 2015).[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/08/world/africa/liberia-dog-suspected-in-new-ebola-case-tests-negative-for-the-virus.html?_r=0 \"Liberia: Dog Suspected in New Ebola Case Tests Negative for the Virus\"]. ''The New York Times''.</ref>  By 9 July 3 more cases were discovered, bringing the total number of new cases to 5, all from the same area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/liberia-confirms-ebola-cases-32340305|title=Liberia Confirms 2 New Ebola Cases|date=9 July 2015|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref>  On 14 July, a woman died of the disease in the county of [[Montserrado]], bringing the total to 6.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/3957212/ebola-liberia-reemerge/|title=Ebola|author=Tanya Basu|magazine=Time |date=14 July 2015}}</ref>  On 20 July, the last patients were discharged,<ref>Reuters. (20 July 2015).[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/21/world/africa/liberia-ebola-patients-discharged-last-of-the-countrys-latest-wave.html?_r=0 \"Liberia: Ebola Patients Discharged, Last of the Country's Latest Wave\"]. ''The New York Times''.</ref> and on 3 September 2015, Liberia was declared Ebola-free again.<ref name=\"Lib_free_3_9\">{{cite report|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2015/ebola-transmission-over-liberia/en/ |title=Ebola transmission in Liberia over: Nation enters 90-day intensive surveillance period |publisher=WHO |date=3 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter two months of being Ebola-free, a new case was confirmed on 20 November 2015, when a 15-year-old boy was diagnosed with the virus<ref name=\"Liberia New Case 20/11/2015 LA Times\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/world/africa/la-fg-ebola-case-in-liberia-20151120-story.html |title=New Ebola case confirmed in Liberia |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=2015-11-20 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201511200980.html|title=Liberia: Fears of Deadly Ebola Virus Reportedly Resurface in Liberia|publisher=allAfrica.com|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> and two family members subsequently tested positive as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ebola-virus-outbreak/ebola-returns-liberia-again-n467146|title=Ebola Returns to Liberia, Again|author=Maggie Fox|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/22/liberian-health-officials-ebola-outbreak-monrovia|title=Liberian health officials move to control Ebola outbreak in Monrovia|newspaper=The Guardian|date=22 November 2015|accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref>  Health officials were concerned because the child had not recently travelled or been exposed to someone with Ebola and the WHO stated that \"we believe that this is probably again, somehow, someone who has come in contact with a virus that had been persisting in an individual, who had suffered the disease months ago.\" Two staff of the CDC were sent to the country to help ascertain the cause of the new cases.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/11/23/world/africa/ap-af-liberia-ebola.html|title=Liberia Seeks US Help to Determine Cause of New Ebola Cases|date=23 November 2015|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref>  The infected boy died on 24 November,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/liberia-records-1st-ebola-death-july-35386693|title=Liberia Records 1st Ebola Death Since July|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=26 November 2015}}</ref> and on 3 December 2 remaining cases were released after recovering from the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/liberias-last-two-ebola-patients-recover-leave-hospital-193116450.html|title=Liberia's last two Ebola patients recover, leave hospital|date=3 December 2015|publisher=Yahoo! News|accessdate=4 December 2015}}</ref> The 42-day countdown toward Liberia being declared Ebola-free, for the third time, started on 4 December 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-liberia-idUSKBN0TU2Q820151211#hJsbSReZzDZ7Ih4S.97|title=Liberia's last Ebola contacts finish quarantine|author=Reuters Editorial|date=11 December 2015|work=Reuters|accessdate=12 December 2015}}</ref> On 16 December, the WHO reaffirmed that the cases in Liberia were the result of re-emergence of the virus in a previously infected person,<ref>{{cite report|url=http://apps.who.int/ebola/current-situation/ebola-situation-report-16-december-2015|title=Ebola Situation Report |date= 16 December 2015|publisher=WHO |accessdate=25 December 2015}}</ref> and there was speculation that the boy may have been infected by an individual who became infectious once more due to pregnancy, which may have weakened her immune system.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-liberia-idUSKBN0U02EJ20151217|title=Female survivor may be cause of Ebola flare-up in Liberia|author1=Emma Farge |author2=James Harding Giahyue |date=17 December 2015|work=Reuters|accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref> On 18 December, the WHO indicated that it still considered Ebola in Western Africa a public health emergency, though progress had been made.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2015/ihr-ebola-8th-meeting/en/|title=Statement on the 8th meeting of the IHR Emergency Committee regarding the Ebola outbreak in West Africa|publisher=WHO|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter having completed the 42-day time period, Liberia was declared free from the virus on 14 January 2016, effectively ending the outbreak that had started in neighbouring Guinea 2 years earlier. Liberia began a 90-day period of heightened surveillance, scheduled to conclude on 13 April 2016,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/4179412/ebola-outbreak-over/|title=West Africa to Be Declared Ebola-Free, Health Officials Say|author=Alexandra Sifferlin|magazine=Time|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref> but on 1 April, it was reported that a new Ebola fatality had occurred,<ref name=\"reu2016\">{{cite news|url=http://news.trust.org/item/20160401113911-cthc6|title=Liberia records new Ebola death, months after end of its outbreak|first=Thomson Reuters|last=Foundation|work=Reuters |accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref> and on 3 April, a second case was reported in [[Monrovia]].<ref name=\"abc\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/ebola-free-liberia-confirms-2nd-case-38116197 |title=International News &#124; World News |publisher=ABC News |date= |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> On 4 April, it was reported that 84 individuals were under observation due to contact with the 2 confirmed Ebola cases.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/liberia-flareups-update/en/|title=Emergency response to Ebola flare underway in Liberia. Case investigation widens to Guinea|author=|date=|publisher=WHO |accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref> By 7 April, Liberia had confirmed 3 new cases since the virus resurfaced and a total of 97&nbsp;contacts, including 15&nbsp;healthcare workers, were being monitored.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenewdawnliberia.com/news/10041-liberia-records-97-ebola-contacts|title=Liberia records 97 Ebola contacts|publisher=The New Dawn Liberia|accessdate=7 April 2016|date=7 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409014448/http://www.thenewdawnliberia.com/news/10041-liberia-records-97-ebola-contacts|archivedate=9 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The index case of the new flareup was reported to be the wife of a patient who died from Ebola in Guinea; she had travelled to Monrovia after the funeral but succumbed to the disease.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/liberia-guinea-flareups-update/en/|title=Liberia and Guinea step up coordination to stem new cases of Ebola|publisher=WHO|accessdate=7 April 2016|date=8 April 2016}}</ref> The outbreak in Guinea, in turn, had begun when a man, who had survived Ebola, had sexual intercourse with a woman and passed the virus to her, even though he had recovered more than a year earlier.<ref name=lurked/><ref name=BDiallo/>\n\nOn 29 April, WHO reported that Liberia had discharged the last patient and had begun the 42-day countdown to be declared Ebola-free once more. According to the WHO, tests indicated that the flare-up was likely due to contact with a prior Ebola survivor's infected body fluids.<ref name=discharge>{{cite report|url=http://www.who.int/features/2016/ebola-patients-discharge/en/|title=Liberia and Guinea discharge final Ebola patients in latest flare-up and begin 42 days of heightened surveillance|author=|date=|publisher=WHO |accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref> On 9 June, the flare-up was declared over, and the country Ebola-free, due to the passage of the 42-day period;<ref name=\"true\">{{cite news|last1=Farge |first1=Emma |title=Female survivor may be cause of Ebola flare-up in Liberia |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-liberia-idUSKBN0U02EJ20151217 |work=Reuters|accessdate=30 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.afro.who.int/en/media-centre/pressreleases/item/8699-who-declares-the-end-of-the-most-recent-ebola-virus-disease-outbreak-in-liberia.html|title=WHO declares the end of the most recent Ebola virus disease outbreak in Liberia|publisher=WHO |access-date=9 June 2016}}</ref> Liberia then entered a 90-day period of heightened surveillance, which ended on 7 September 2016. In early July 2016, a trial for males with detectable Ebola [[Ribonucleic acid|RNA]] in semen, started.<ref>{{cite report|title=PREVAIL treatment trial for men with persistent Ebola viral RNA in semen opens in Liberia|url=https://www.nih.gov/news-events/news-releases/prevail-treatment-trial-men-persistent-ebola-viral-rna-semen-opens-liberia|publisher=NIH|accessdate=1 August 2016|date=5 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Western African countries with limited local cases ===\n\n==== Senegal ====\nIn March 2014, the [[Senegal]] Ministry of Interior closed its southern border with Guinea,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-03-29/ebola-virus-death-toll-in-guinea-outbreak-rises-to-70-people.html|title=Ebola Death Toll in Guinea Rises to 70 as Senegal Closes Border |publisher=Bloomberg News|date=29 March 2014 |accessdate=31 March 2014 |first=Ougna |last=Camara}}</ref> but on 29 August, the health minister announced the country's first case \u2013 a university student from Guinea who was being treated in a [[Dakar]] hospital.<ref name=\"Ebola virus disease \u2013 Senegal\">{{cite report|url=http://www.afro.who.int/en/clusters-a-programmes/dpc/epidemic-a-pandemic-alert-and-response/outbreak-news/4265-ebola-virus-disease-senegal.html|title=Ebola virus disease \u2013 Senegal|publisher=WHO|date=29 March 2014|accessdate=1 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905001908/http://www.afro.who.int/en/clusters-a-programmes/dpc/epidemic-a-pandemic-alert-and-response/outbreak-news/4265-ebola-virus-disease-senegal.html|archivedate=5 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The patient was a native of Guinea who had travelled to Dakar, arriving on 20 August. On 23 August, he sought medical care for symptoms including diarrhoea, and vomiting plus signs of fever. He received treatment for malaria but did not improve and left the facility. Still experiencing the same symptoms, on 26 August he was referred to a specialised facility for infectious diseases, and subsequently hospitalised.<ref name=\"Ebola virus disease \u2013 Senegal\" />\n\nOn 28 August 2014, authorities in Guinea issued an alert informing their medical services and neighbouring countries that a person who had been in close contact with an Ebola-infected patient had escaped their surveillance system. The alert prompted testing for Ebola at the Dakar laboratory, and the positive result launched an investigation, triggering urgent contact tracing.<ref name=\"Ebola virus disease \u2013 Senegal\" /> On 10 September, it was reported that the student had recovered but health officials continued to monitor his contacts for 21 days.<ref>{{cite web|title=Guinean Who Brought Ebola To Senegal Recovers From Virus|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/r-guinean-who-brought-ebola-to-senegal-recovers-from-virus-2014-9|website=Business Insider|accessdate=20 September 2014}}</ref> No further cases were reported,<ref name=\"Ebola_Outbreak_total_20_Sept\">{{cite report|url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/134449/1/roadmapupdate22sept14_eng.pdf?ua=1 |format= PDF|title=Ebola Response Roadmap Update, 22 September 2014 |publisher=WHO|date=22 September 2014|accessdate=22 September 2014}}</ref> and on 17 October 2014, the WHO officially declared that the outbreak in Senegal had ended.<ref name=WHO20141022 />\n\nThe WHO officially commended the Senegalese government, and in particular the [[Macky Sall|President Macky Sall]] and the Minister of Health, [[Awa Coll-Seck|Dr Awa Coll-Seck]], for their response in quickly isolating the patient and tracing and following up 74 contacts, as well as for their public awareness campaign.  This acknowledgement was also extended to MSF and the CDC for their assistance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2014/senegal-ends-ebola/en/|title=WHO congratulates Senegal on ending Ebola transmission|date=17 October 2014|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==== Nigeria ====\n{{Further|Ebola virus disease in Nigeria}}\nThe first case in Nigeria was a Liberian-American, who flew from Liberia to Nigeria's most populated city of [[Lagos]] on 20 July 2014.  On 6 August 2014, the Nigerian health minister told reporters that one of the nurses that attended to the Liberian had died from the disease. 5 newly confirmed cases were being treated at an isolation ward.<ref name=\"theguardian1\">{{cite news |last=Mark|first=Monica |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/06/ebola-outbreak-nurse-nigeria-dies|title=Ebola Outbreak: Nurse who Treated First Victim in Nigeria Dies|publisher=The Guardian (Nigeria)|date=6 August 2014|accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 September 2014, the Nigerian health ministry announced, \"As of today, there is no case of Ebola in Nigeria.\" According to the WHO, 20&nbsp;cases and 8&nbsp;deaths were confirmed, including the imported case, who also died. 4 of the dead were health workers who had cared for the index case.<ref name=\"Nigeria in first step towards all-clear on Ebola\">{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/nigeria-first-step-towards-clear-ebola-203222268.html |title=Nigeria in first step towards all-clear on Ebola |publisher=Yahoo News |date=23 September 2014 |accessdate=26 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe WHO's representative in Nigeria officially declared the country Ebola-free on 20 October 2014, after no new active cases were reported in the follow up contacts, stating it was a \"spectacular success story\".<ref>{{cite report |url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/ebola/20-october-2014/en/ |title=Nigeria is now free of Ebola virus transmission |publisher=WHO|date=20 October 2014 |accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> Nigeria was the first African country to be declared Ebola free.<ref>{{cite report|title=WHO Declares Nigeria Ebola-Free|url=http://www.afro.who.int/en/media-centre/pressreleases/item/7108-who-declares-nigeria-ebola-free.html|publisher=WHO |accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> This was largely due to the early quarantine efforts of Dr. Ameyo Stella Adadevoh at First Consultants Medical Centre in Lagos.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Green|first=Andrew|date=2014|title=Remembering health workers who died from Ebola in 2014|journal=The Lancet|language=en|volume=384|issue=9961|pages=2201\u20132206|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(14)62417-X|pmid=25625389}}</ref>\n\n==== Mali ====\n[[File:Mali- Ebola districts.png|thumb|upright=1.5|Malian regions with Ebola cases (Kayes/Bamako), November 2014]]\n{{Further|Ebola virus disease in Mali}}\nOn 23 October 2014, the first case of Ebola virus disease in [[Mali]] was confirmed in the city of [[Kayes]]\u2014a two-year-old girl who had arrived with a family group from Guinea, and died the next day.<ref name=\"WHO_sitrep_Mali_10_nov\">{{cite report|title=Mali case, Ebola imported from Guinea Ebola situation assessment \u2013 10 November 2014|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/ebola/10-november-2014-mali/en/|publisher=WHO|accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ebola Outbreak 2014|url=http://www.breakingnews.com/item/2014/10/24/2-year-old-girl-who-was-malis-1st-ebola-case-has/|publisher=NBC News |accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref> Her father had worked for the Red Cross in Guinea and also in a private health clinic; he had died earlier in the month, likely from an Ebola infection contracted in the private clinic. It was later established that a number of family members had also died of Ebola. The family had returned to Mali after the father's funeral via public bus and taxi\u2014a journey of more than {{convert|1200|km}}. All contacts were followed for 21&nbsp;days, with no further spread of the disease reported.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mali : Situation de la lutte contre la maladie \u00e0 virus Ebola au Mali \u00e0 la date du mercredi 19 novembre 2014|url=http://maliactu.net/mali-situation-de-la-lutte-contre-la-maladie-a-virus-ebola-au-mali-a-la-date-du-mercredi-19-novembre-2014|date=19 November 2014|publisher=maliactu|accessdate=26 November 2014|language=French}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 November 2014, Mali reported deaths from Ebola in an outbreak unconnected with the first case in Kayes. The first probable case was an [[imam]] who had fallen ill on 17 October in Guinea and was transferred to the Pasteur Clinic in Mali's capital city, [[Bamako]], for treatment. He was treated for kidney failure but was not tested for Ebola; he died on 27 October and his body returned to Guinea for burial.<ref>{{cite report|title=Mali confirms its second fatal case of Ebola virus disease|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/ebola/12-november-2014-mali/en/|publisher=WHO|accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref>  A nurse and a doctor who had treated the imam subsequently fell ill with Ebola and died.<ref>{{cite news|title=Update 2 \u2013 Doctor who treated source of second Mali Ebola outbreak dies|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/20/health-ebola-mali-idUSL6N0TA62R20141120|work=Reuters|accessdate=21 November 2014|date=21 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Ebola_case_mali_12_nov\">{{cite news|title=Ebola crisis: Third death confirmed in Mali|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-30019895|work=BBC News|date=12 November 2014 |accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref>  The next 3&nbsp;cases were related to the imam as well: a man who had visited the imam while he was in hospital, his wife and his son. On 22 November, the final case related to the imam was reported\u2014a friend of the Pasteur Clinic nurse who had died from the Ebola virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/22/us-health-ebola-mali-idUSKCN0J60EI20141122|title=Mali records new Ebola case, linked to dead nurse|work=Reuters|accessdate=22 November 2014|date=22 November 2014}}</ref> On 12 December, the last case in treatment recovered and was discharged, \"so there are no more people sick with Ebola in Mali\", according to a Ministry of Health source.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20141212-mali-nears-ebola-free-status-last-patient/|title=Africa \u2013 Mali nears Ebola-free status as last patient leaves hospital|publisher=France 24|accessdate=12 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227162708/http://www.france24.com/en/20141212-mali-nears-ebola-free-status-last-patient/|archive-date=27 December 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 16 December,  Mali released the final 13&nbsp;individuals who were being quarantined<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/Africa/News/Mali-ends-quarantines-could-be-Ebola-free-soon-20141216|title=Mali ends quarantines, could be Ebola-free soon|publisher=News24|accessdate=17 December 2014|date=2014-12-16}}</ref> and 24&nbsp;days later (18 January 2015) without new cases, the country was declared Ebola-free.<ref name=WHO2015_01_211 />\n\n=== Other countries with limited local cases ===\n\n==== United Kingdom ====\n{{Further|Ebola virus disease in the United Kingdom}}\nOn 29 December 2014, [[Pauline Cafferkey]], a British aid worker who had just returned to [[Glasgow]] from Sierra Leone, was diagnosed with Ebola.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/ebola-in-britain-infected-nurse-pauline-cafferkey-treated-with-survivors-blood-and-experimental-drugs-9951992.html|title=Ebola in the UK: Infected nurse Pauline Cafferkey treated with survivors' blood plasma and experimental drugs|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=1 January 2015|location=London|first=Charlie|last=Cooper|date=31 December 2014}}</ref> She was treated and declared to be free of infection and released from hospital on 24 January 2015.<ref name=\"Uk_10_March\">{{cite report|url=http://www.euro.who.int/en/health-topics/emergencies/pages/news/news/2015/03/united-kingdom-is-declared-free-of-ebola-virus-disease|title=United Kingdom is declared free of Ebola virus disease|publisher=WHO Europe|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-30967337|title=Ebola nurse: Pauline Cafferkey 'happy to be alive'|work=BBC News|date=24 January 2015 |accessdate= 11 April 2015}}</ref> On 8 October, she was readmitted for complications caused by the virus<ref>{{cite news|title = Ebola nurse Pauline Cafferkey 'in serious condition'|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-34483584|work= BBC News|accessdate = 9 October 2015|date = 2015-10-09}}</ref> and was in \"serious\" condition, according to a hospital report.  On 14 October, her condition was listed as \"critical\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/10/14/europe/uk-ebola-nurse/|title=UK's first Ebola patient 'critically ill,' in isolation|first1=Greg|last1=Botelho|date=14 October 2015|publisher=CNN|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref> and 58&nbsp;individuals were being monitored and 25 received an experimental vaccination, being close contacts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-34509572|title=Ebola nurse's close contacts identified|work=BBC News|accessdate=16 October 2015|date=2015-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.news.yahoo.com/ebola-nurse-58-monitored-deadly-virus-191740171.html#1B1gP9Z|title=Ebola Nurse: 58 Monitored For Deadly Virus|date=13 October 2015|publisher=Yahoo! News UK|accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref>  On 21 October, it was reported that she had been diagnosed with [[meningitis]] caused by the virus persisting in her brain.<ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/health/ebola-nurse-uk-1.3281635|title=U.K. Ebola nurse has meningitis caused by persisting Ebola, doctors say|date=21 October 2015|publisher=CBC |accessdate=27 October 2015}}</ref> On 12 November, she was released from hospital after making a full recovery.<ref name=\"davidwilcock\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/ebola-nurse-pauline-cafferkey-released-from-london-hospital-after-full-recovery-a6731111.html|title=Ebola nurse Pauline Cafferkey released from London hospital after 'full recovery'|first1=David|last1=Wilcock|date=12 November 2015|newspaper=The Independent}}</ref> However, on 23 February, Ms. Cafferkey was admitted for a third time, \"under routine monitoring by the Infectious Diseases Unit&nbsp;... for further investigations\", according to a spokesperson.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ebola nurse Pauline Cafferkey flying back to Royal Free Hospital amid ongoing tests|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/ebola/12169799/Ebola-nurse-Pauline-Cafferkey-flying-back-to-Royal-Free-Hospital-amid-ongoing-tests.html |publisher=The Telegragh|accessdate=28 October 2016|date=2016-02-23 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ebola nurse Pauline Cafferkey 'stable' after night in London hospital|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-35639748|work=BBC News |accessdate=28 October 2016|date=24 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Italy ====\nOn 12 May 2015, it was reported that a nurse, who had been working in Sierra Leone, had been diagnosed with Ebola after returning home to the Italian island of [[Sardinia]]. He was treated at [[Spallanzani Hospital]], the national reference centre for Ebola patients.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2015/may/12/nurse-in-italy-tests-positive-for-ebola-was-in/|title=Nurse in Italy tests positive for Ebola; was in Sierra Leone|newspaper=The San Diego Union-Tribune |accessdate=13 May 2015|date=2015-05-12}}</ref>  On 10 June, it was reported that he had recovered and was disease-free and he was released from hospital.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/italian-nurse-cured-ebola-130902382.html Italian nurse cured of Ebola], AFP, 10 June 2015</ref>\n\n==== Spain ====\n{{Further|Ebola virus disease cases in Spain}}\nOn 5 August 2014, the [[Brothers Hospitallers of Saint John of God]] confirmed that Brother Miguel Pajares, who had been volunteering in Liberia, had become infected. He was evacuated to Spain and died on 12 August.<ref>{{cite news|title=Muere el religioso espa\u00f1ol Miguel Pajares a causa del \u00e9bola |url=http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20140812/muere-religioso-espanol-miguel-pajares-causa-del-ebola/991420.shtml |publisher=RTVE |date=12 August 2014 |accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> On 21 September it was announced that Brother Manuel Garc\u00eda Viejo, another Spanish citizen who was medical director at the [[San Juan de Dios Hospital]] in [[Lunsar]], had been evacuated to Spain from Sierra Leone after being infected with the virus. His death was announced on 25 September.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/ebola-outbreak-spanish-missionary-manuel-garcia-viejo-dies-deadly-virus-madrid-1467233|title=Ebola Outbreak: Spanish Missionary Manuel Garcia Viejo Dies of Deadly Virus in Madrid|date=25 September 2014|accessdate=25 September 2014|newspaper=International Business Times}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, a nursing assistant, Teresa Romero, who had cared for these patients became unwell and on 6 October tested positive for Ebola,<ref>{{cite news|title=Nurse 'infected with Ebola' in Spain|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-29514920|accessdate=6 October 2014|work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cadenaser.com/sociedad/articulo/enfermera-ingresada-alcorcon-da-positivo-ebola/csrcsrpor/20141006csrcsrsoc_5/Tes|title=La enfermera ingresada en Alcorc\u00f3n da positivo por \u00e9bola \u2013 La segunda prueba ha dado positivo y confirma el diagn\u00f3stico |publisher=Cadena Ser|date=6 October 2014 |accessdate= 11 April 2015}}</ref> making this the first confirmed case of Ebola transmission outside of Africa. On 19 October, it was reported that Romero had recovered, and on 2 December the WHO declared Spain Ebola-free following the passage of 42 days since Teresa Romero was found to be cured.<ref name=\"Spain_Ebola_outbreak_2_Dec\">{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/spain-ebola-free-nurse-recovery-27300284|title=WHO Says Spain Ebola-Free Following Nurse Recovery|date=2 December 2014|accessdate=2 December 2014|publisher=ABC News}}</ref>\n\n==== United States ====\n{{Further|Ebola virus cases in the United States}}\n\nOn 30 September 2014, the CDC declared its first case of Ebola virus disease.  It disclosed that [[Thomas Eric Duncan]] became infected in Liberia and travelled to [[Dallas]], [[Texas]] on 20 September.  On 26 September, he fell ill and sought medical treatment, but was sent home with antibiotics. He returned to the hospital by ambulance on 28 September and was placed in isolation and tested for Ebola.<ref name=\"First_Us_case\">{{cite report|url=https://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2014/s930-ebola-confirmed-case.html|title= CDC and Texas Health Department Confirm First Ebola Case Diagnosed in the U.S.|publisher=CDC |date=1 October 2014| accessdate=1 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/ebola/11132475/First-Ebola-victim-in-America-was-sent-home-with-antibiotics.html| author=Nick Allen| title=First Ebola victim in America was sent home with antibiotics|newspaper=The Telegraph| date=1 October 2014 |accessdate= 11 April 2015| location=London}}</ref>  He died on 8 October.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/10/08/health/thomas-eric-duncan-ebola/|title=Thomas Eric Duncan: First Ebola death in U.S.|date=8 October 2014|publisher=CNN|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>  Two cases stemmed from Duncan, when two nurses that had treated him tested positive for the virus on 10 and 14 October<ref name=\"NYT-20141012-MF\">{{cite news|last=Fernandez|first=Manny|title=Texas Health Worker Tests Positive for Ebola|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/13/us/texas-health-worker-tests-positive-for-ebola.html|date=12 October 2014 |newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/health/2014/10/15/family-identifies-2nd-health-care-worker-infected-with-ebola/|title=Second Ebola-infected nurse ID'd; flew domestic flight day before diagnosis|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=15 October 2014|date=15 October 2014}}</ref>  and ended when they were declared Ebola-free on 24 and 22 October, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ebola-virus-outbreak/virus-free-ebola-infected-nurse-nina-pham-go-home-n233171|title=Virus Free: Ebola-Infected Nurse Nina Pham to Go Home|date=24 October 2014 |accessdate= 11 April 2015|publisher=NBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/nurse-amber-vinson-free-of-ebola-virus-family-says-001502702.html|title=Nurse Amber Vinson free of Ebola virus, family says|date=23 October 2014|publisher=Yahoo! News|accessdate=23 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nA fourth case was identified on 23 October 2014, when [[Ebola virus cases in the United States#Craig Spencer|Craig Spencer]], an American physician who had returned to the United States after treating Ebola patients in Western Africa, tested positive for the virus.<ref name=\"nbc-spencer 20141023\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ebola-virus-outbreak/new-york-doctor-just-back-africa-has-ebola-n232561|title=New York Doctor Just Back From Africa Has Ebola|publisher=NBC News|date=23 October 2014|accessdate=23 October 2014}}</ref>  This case, however, had no relation to those originating from Duncan.  Spencer recovered and was released from hospital on 11 November.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/11/nyregion/craig-spencer-new-york-doctor-with-ebola-will-leave-bellevue-hospital.html?_r=0|newspaper=The New York Times|date=10 November 2014 |accessdate= 11 April 2015|title=Craig Spencer, New York Doctor With Ebola, Will Leave Bellevue Hospital|first=Anemona|last=Hartocollis}}</ref>\n\n=== Countries with medically evacuated cases ===\nA number of people who had become infected with Ebola were [[medical evacuation|medically evacuated]] for treatment in [[isolation ward]]s in Europe or the US. They were mostly health workers with one of the NGOs in Western Africa. With the exception of a single isolated case in [[Ebola virus disease in Spain|Spain]], no secondary infections occurred as a result of the medical evacuations.  The [[Ebola virus cases in the United States|US accepted]] four evacuees and three were flown to Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zeit.de/gesellschaft/2014-10/ebola-patient-in-leipzig-gestorben|title=Infektion: Ebola-Patient in Leipziger Klinik gestorben|date=14 October 2014|publisher=De Zeit|accessdate=14 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://uk.news.yahoo.com/ugandan-doctor-cured-ebola-german-hospital-181422896.html#AWJipQ5 |title=Ugandan doctor cured of Ebola in German hospital |publisher=Yahoo! News |date=4 December 2014 |accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hamburg clinic dismisses Ebola patient|url=http://www.berliner-zeitung.de/panorama/universitaetsklinikum-eppendorf-klinik-entlaesst-hamburger-ebola-patient,10808334,28645204.html|accessdate=4 October 2014|language=German|date=2014-10-04}}</ref>\nFrance,<ref>{{cite web|title=French MSF nurse cured of Ebola|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20141004-french-nurse-cured-ebola-health-minister-msf-touraine/|accessdate=4 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004174917/http://www.france24.com/en/20141004-french-nurse-cured-ebola-health-minister-msf-touraine/|archive-date=4 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ebola: l'agent de l'Unicef soign\u00e9 \u00e0 l'h\u00f4pital B\u00e9gin a quitt\u00e9 la France \"gu\u00e9ri\"|url=http://www.bfmtv.com/societe/l-agent-de-l-unicef-atteint-d-ebola-a-quitte-la-france-gueri-848374.html|accessdate=24 November 2014|language=French}}</ref> Italy,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/150102/world-europe/article/italy-doctor-ebola-has-recovered-reports|title=Italy doctor with Ebola has recovered: reports|newspaper=Deccan Chronicle |date=2 January 2015|accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref> the Netherlands,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2014/dec/23/un-nigerian-peacekeeper-recovers-from-ebola/|title=UN: Nigerian peacekeeper recovers from Ebola|newspaper=The San Diego Union-Tribune|accessdate=28 December 2014|date=2014-12-23}}</ref> Norway,<ref>{{cite web|title=\u2013 Jeg er utrolig takknemlig|url=http://www.nrk.no/norge/_-jeg-er-utrolig-takknemlig-1.11996836|accessdate=20 October 2014|language=Norwegian|date=2014-10-20}}</ref><ref name=\"Yahoo News\">{{cite news| url=https://news.yahoo.com/norwegian-ebola-patient-cured-aid-group-150617578.html | title=Norwegian Ebola Patient Cured | publisher=Yahoo! News | date=20 October 2014 | accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref>  Switzerland,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/health/felix-baez-cuban-doctor-with-ebola-recovers-in-geneva-1.2862976|title=Felix Baez, Cuban doctor with Ebola, recovers in Geneva|publisher=CBC News|date=6 December 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> and the United Kingdom [[Ebola virus disease in the United Kingdom|received]] two patients (and five who were exposed).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-31908301|title=BBC News \u2013 Ebola: Seventh British health worker sent home|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 March 2015|date=2015-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-32088310|title=British medic declared free of Ebola|work=BBC News|date=27 March 2015|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Unrelated outbreak in the Democratic Republic of the Congo ===\n{{Further|2014 Democratic Republic of the Congo Ebola virus outbreak}}\nIn August 2014, the WHO reported an outbreak of Ebola virus in the [[Boende]] District, part of the northern [[\u00c9quateur (former province)|\u00c9quateur]] province of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), where 13 people were reported to have died of Ebola-like symptoms.<ref name=DRC_Ebola_case>{{cite report|title=Ebola virus disease \u2013 Democratic Republic of Congo E-mail Print Epidemiology and surveillance|url=http://www.afro.who.int/en/clusters-a-programmes/dpc/epidemic-a-pandemic-alert-and-response/outbreak-news/4263-ebola-virus-disease-drc.html|publisher=WHO (WHO)|accessdate= 11 April 2015}}</ref> Genetic [[sequencing]] revealed that this outbreak was caused by the Zaire Ebola species, which is native to the DRC; there have been seven previous Ebola outbreaks in the country since 1976. The virology results and epidemiological findings indicated no connection to the epidemic in Western Africa.<ref name=DRC_Ebola_case /><ref name=\"who.int\">{{cite report |url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/ebola/2-september-2014/en/ |title=Virological analysis: no link between Ebola outbreaks in west Africa and Democratic Republic of Congo |publisher=WHO |date=2 September 2014 |accessdate=7 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe index case was initially reported to have been a woman from Ikanamongo Village, who became ill with symptoms of Ebola after she had butchered a bush animal.<ref name=DRC_Ebola_case /><ref>{{cite report|url=https://www.cdc.gov/vhf/ebola/outbreaks/history/chronology.html|title=Outbreaks Chronology: Ebola Virus Disease|publisher=CDC |accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref> However, later findings suggested that there may have been several previous cases, and it was reported that pigs in the village may have been infected with Ebola some time before the first human case occurred.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/ebola-sleuths-scour-dr-congo-jungle-source-outbreak-060715032.html|title=Ebola sleuths scour DR Congo jungle for source of outbreak|date=23 October 2014|publisher=Yahoo! News|accessdate=23 October 2014}}</ref> The WHO declared the outbreak over on 21 November 2014, after a total of 66 cases and 49 deaths.<ref>{{cite report|title=WHO declares end of Ebola outbreak in the Democratic Republic of Congo|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2014/drc-ends-ebola/en/|publisher=WHO|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=WHO20141029>{{cite report |url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/137376/1/roadmapsitrep_29Oct2014_eng.pdf?ua=1  |format= PDF|title=Ebola response roadmap situation report update |publisher=WHO|date=29 October 2014 |accessdate =3 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Virology ==\n{{See also|Ebola virus disease#Virology|Ebola virus}}\n[[File:Ebola virus particles.jpg|thumb|Ebola virus particles using electron micrograph]]\nEbola virus disease is caused by four of five viruses classified in the genus ''[[Ebolavirus]]''. Of the four disease-causing viruses, [[Ebola virus]] (formerly and often still called the Zaire Ebola virus) is dangerous and is the virus responsible for the epidemic in Western Africa.<ref name=\"Gire 2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Gire|first1=S. K.|last2=Goba|first2=A.|last3=Andersen|first3=K. G.|last4=Sealfon|first4=R. S. G.|last5=Park|first5=D. J.|last6=Kanneh|first6=L.|last7=Jalloh|first7=S.|last8=Momoh|first8=M.|last9=Fullah|first9=M.|last10=Dudas|first10=G.|last11=Wohl|first11=S.|last12=Moses|first12=L. M.|last13=Yozwiak|first13=N. L.|last14=Winnicki|first14=S.|last15=Matranga|first15=C. B.|last16=Malboeuf|first16=C. M.|last17=Qu|first17=J.|last18=Gladden|first18=A. D.|last19=Schaffner|first19=S. F.|last20=Yang|first20=X.|last21=Jiang|first21=P.-P.|last22=Nekoui|first22=M.|last23=Colubri|first23=A.|last24=Coomber|first24=M. R.|last25=Fonnie|first25=M.|last26=Moigboi|first26=A.|last27=Gbakie|first27=M.|last28=Kamara|first28=F. K.|last29=Tucker|first29=V.|last30=Konuwa|first30=E.|last31=Saffa|first31=S.|last32=Sellu|first32=J.|last33=Jalloh|first33=A. A.|last34=Kovoma|first34=A.|last35=Koninga|first35=J.|last36=Mustapha|first36=I.|last37=Kargbo|first37=K.|last38=Foday|first38=M.|last39=Yillah|first39=M.|last40=Kanneh|first40=F.|last41=Robert|first41=W.|last42=Massally|first42=J. L. B.|last43=Chapman|first43=S. B.|last44=Bochicchio|first44=J.|last45=Murphy|first45=C.|last46=Nusbaum|first46=C.|last47=Young|first47=S.|last48=Birren|first48=B. W.|last49=Grant|first49=D. S.|last50=Scheiffelin|first50=J. S.|last51=Lander|first51=E. S.|last52=Happi|first52=C.|last53=Gevao|first53=S. M.|last54=Gnirke|first54=A.|last55=Rambaut|first55=A.|last56=Garry|first56=R. F.|last57=Khan|first57=S. H.|last58=Sabeti|first58=P. C.|title=Genomic surveillance elucidates Ebola virus origin and transmission during the 2014 outbreak|journal=Science|date=28 August 2014|volume=345|issue=6202|pages=1369\u20131372|doi=10.1126/science.1259657|pmid=25214632|pmc=4431643|bibcode=2014Sci...345.1369G}}</ref><ref name=KuhnArch>{{cite journal|last1=Kuhn|first1=Jens H.|last2=Becker|first2=Stephan|last3=Ebihara|first3=Hideki|last4=Geisbert|first4=Thomas W.|last5=Johnson|first5=Karl M.|last6=Kawaoka|first6=Yoshihiro|last7=Lipkin|first7=W. Ian|last8=Negredo|first8=Ana I.|last9=Netesov|first9=Sergey V.|last10=Nichol|first10=Stuart T.|last11=Palacios|first11=Gustavo|last12=Peters|first12=Clarence J.|last13=Tenorio|first13=Antonio|last14=Volchkov|first14=Viktor E.|last15=Jahrling|first15=Peter B.|title=Proposal for a revised taxonomy of the family Filoviridae: classification, names of taxa and viruses, and virus abbreviations|journal=Archives of Virology|date=30 October 2010|volume=155|issue=12|pages=2083\u20132103|doi=10.1007/s00705-010-0814-x|pmid=21046175|pmc=3074192}}</ref>\nSince the discovery of the viruses in 1976, when outbreaks occurred in South Sudan (then Sudan) and Democratic Republic of the Congo (then Zaire), Ebola virus disease had been confined to areas in Middle Africa, where it is native. With the current outbreak, it was initially thought that a new species native to Guinea might be the cause, rather than being imported from Middle to Western Africa.<ref name=\"Baize-2014\" /> However, further studies have shown that the outbreak was likely caused by an Ebola virus lineage that spread from Middle Africa via an animal host within the last decade, with the first viral transfer to humans in Guinea.<ref name=\"Gire 2014\" /><ref name=\"EurekAlert!\">{{cite journal|last1=Schoepp|first1=Randal J.|last2=Rossi|first2=Cynthia A.|last3=Khan|first3=Sheik H.|last4=Goba|first4=Augustine|last5=Fair|first5=Joseph N.|title=Undiagnosed Acute Viral Febrile Illnesses, Sierra Leone|journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases|volume=20|issue=7|pages=1176\u20131182|doi=10.3201/eid2007.131265|pmid=24959946|pmc=4073864|year=2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a study done by [[Tulane University]], the [[Broad Institute]] and [[Harvard University]], in partnership with the [[Sierra Leone Ministry of Health and Sanitation]], researchers provided information about the origin and transmission of the Ebola virus that set the Western African outbreak apart from previous ones, including 341 genetic changes in the [[virion]].<ref name=\"Gire 2014\" /> Five members of the research team became ill and died from Ebola before the study was published in August 2014.<ref name=\"Gire 2014\" />\n[[File:Ebola Virus Particles (8).jpg|thumb|Ebola virus particles]]\nIn a report released in August 2014,  researchers tracked the spread of Ebola in Sierra Leone from the group first infected\u201413 women who had attended the funeral of the traditional healer, where they contracted the disease\u2014giving them a unique opportunity to track how the virus had changed.  This provided \"the first time that the real evolution of the Ebola virus [could] be observed in humans.\" The research showed that the outbreak in Sierra Leone was sparked by at least two distinct lineages introduced from Guinea at about the same time. It is not clear whether the traditional healer was infected with both variants, or if perhaps one of the women attending the funeral was independently infected. As the Sierra Leone epidemic progressed, one virus lineage disappeared from patient samples, while a third one appeared.<ref>{{Cite journal | title=Genomes reveal start of Ebola outbreak | journal=Science | volume=345 | issue=6200 | pages=989\u2013990 | date=29 August 2014 | last1=Vogel|first1= Gretchen| bibcode=2014Sci...345..989V | pmid=25170128 | doi=10.1126/science.345.6200.989 }}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/phe-study-finds-ebola-virus-mutated-slower-than-first-thought|title=PHE study finds Ebola virus mutated slower than first thought|author=Public Health England|publisher=Public Health England|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dddmag.com/news/2015/06/scientists-release-ebola-sequencing-data-global-research-community-online|title=Scientists Release Ebola Sequencing Data to Global Research Community Online|publisher=Drug Discovery & Development|accessdate=7 June 2015|date=2015-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Simon-Loriere|first1=Etienne|last2=Faye|first2=Ousmane|last3=Faye|first3=Oumar|last4=Koivogui|first4=Lamine|last5=Magassouba|first5=Nfaly|last6=Keita|first6=Sakoba|last7=Thiberge|first7=Jean-Michel|last8=Diancourt|first8=Laure|last9=Bouchier|first9=Christiane|last10=Vandenbogaert|first10=Matthias|last11=Caro|first11=Val\u00e9rie|last12=Fall|first12=Gamou|last13=Buchmann|first13=Jan P.|last14=Matranga|first14=Christan B.|last15=Sabeti|first15=Pardis C.|last16=Manuguerra|first16=Jean-Claude|last17=Holmes|first17=Edward C.|last18=Sall|first18=Amadou A.|title=Distinct lineages of Ebola virus in Guinea during the 2014 West African epidemic|journal=Nature|date=6 August 2015|volume=524|issue=7563|pages=102\u2013104|doi=10.1038/nature14612|pmid=26106863|bibcode=2015Natur.524..102S}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, the media stated researchers in Guinea had reported mutations in the virus samples that they were looking at.  According to them, \"we've now seen several cases that don't have any symptoms at all, asymptomatic cases. These people may be the people who can spread the virus better, but we still don't know that yet. A virus can change itself to [become] less deadly, but more contagious and that's something we are afraid of.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/3687240/ebola-disease-health-vaccine-guinea/|title=Ebola Virus has Mutated, Scientists Say|author=Kevin McSpadden|magazine=Time|accessdate=31 January 2015|date=29 January 2015}}</ref> A 2015 study suggested that accelerating the rate of mutation of the Ebola virus could make the virus less capable of infecting humans. In this animal study, the virus became practically non-viable, consequently increasing survival.<ref>{{cite journal |date=16 December 2015 |title=Determination of the Spontaneous Mutation Frequency of Ebola virus and Exploitation of this Therapeutically|journal=Journal of Virology |volume=90 |issue=5 |pages=2345\u20132355 |doi=10.1128/JVI.02701-15|pmid=26676781 |pmc=4810732|last1=Alfson |first1=K. J. |last2=Worwa |first2=G. |last3=Carrion Jr |first3=R. |last4=Griffiths |first4=A. }}</ref>\n\n== Transmission ==\n{{See also|Ebola virus disease#Transmission}}\n\n=== Animal to human transmission ===\n[[File:EbolaCycle.png|thumb|upright=1.5|The life cycles of the Ebolavirus]]\nThe initial infection is believed to occur after an Ebola virus is transmitted to a human by contact with an infected animal's body fluids. Evidence strongly implicates bats as the reservoir hosts for ebolaviruses (however, despite considerable research, infectious ebolaviruses have never been recovered from bats).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Griensven |first1=Johan van |last2=G\u00fcnther |first2=Stephan |last3=Clerck |first3=Hilde de |last4=McElroy |first4=Anita K. |last5=Malvy |first5=Denis |title=Ebola virus disease |journal=The Lancet |date=2 March 2019 |volume=393 |issue=10174 |pages=936\u2013948 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(18)33132-5 |pmid=30777297 |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(18)33132-5/fulltext  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ng|first=Melinda|last2=Ndungo|first2=Esther|last3=Kaczmarek|first3=Maria E|last4=Herbert|first4=Andrew S|last5=Binger|first5=Tabea|last6=Kuehne|first6=Ana I|last7=Jangra|first7=Rohit K|last8=Hawkins|first8=John A|last9=Gifford|first9=Robert J|date=23 December 2015|title=Filovirus receptor NPC1 contributes to species-specific patterns of ebolavirus susceptibility in bats|journal=eLife|volume=4|page=e11785|doi=10.7554/eLife.11785|pmid=26698106|pmc=4709267}}</ref>\nBats drop partially eaten fruit and pulp, then land mammals such as [[gorilla]]s and [[duiker]]s feed on this fallen fruit. This chain of events forms a possible indirect means of transmission from the natural host to animal populations.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Gonzalez |first1=J. P.|last2= Pourrut|first2= X.|last3= Leroy|first3= E. |volume=315 |pages=363\u2013387 |year=2007 |pmid=17848072 |doi=10.1007/978-3-540-70962-6_15 |isbn=978-3-540-70961-9 |series=Current Topics in Microbiology and Immunology |title=Wildlife and Emerging Zoonotic Diseases: The Biology, Circumstances and Consequences of Cross-Species Transmission |chapter=Ebolavirus and Other Filoviruses|editor1-last=Childs|editor1-first=J. E.|editor2-last=Mackenzie|editor2-first=J. S.|editor3-last=Richt|editor3-first=J. A. }}</ref> As primates in the area were not found to be infected and [[fruit bats]] do not live near the location of the initial [[Zoonosis|zoonotic transmission]] event in Meliandou, Guinea, it is suspected that the index case occurred after a child had contact with an [[Microbat|insectivorous bat]] from a colony of [[Angolan free-tailed bat]]s near the village.<ref name=EMBOMM123014>{{cite journal |last1=Mari Saez |first1=A. |last2=Weiss |first2=S. |last3=Nowak |first3=K. |last4=Lapeyre |first4=V. |last5=Zimmermann |first5=F. |last6=Dux |first6=A. |last7=Kuhl |first7=H. S. |last8=Kaba |first8=M. |last9=Regnaut |first9=S. |last10=Merkel |first10=K. |last11=Sachse |first11=A. |last12=Thiesen |first12=U. |last13=Villanyi |first13=L. |last14=Boesch |first14=C. |last15=Dabrowski |first15=P. W. |last16=Radonic |first16=A. |last17=Nitsche |first17=A. |last18=Leendertz |first18=S. A. J. |last19=Petterson |first19=S. |last20=Becker |first20=S. |last21=Krahling |first21=V. |last22=Couacy-Hymann |first22=E. |last23=Akoua-Koffi |first23=C. |last24=Weber |first24=N. |last25=Schaade |first25=L. |last26=Fahr |first26=J. |last27=Borchert |first27=M. |last28=Gogarten |first28=J. F. |last29=Calvignac-Spencer |first29=S. |last30=Leendertz |first30=F. H. |title=Investigating the zoonotic origin of the West African Ebola epidemic |journal=EMBO Molecular Medicine |date=30 December 2014 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=17\u201323 |doi=10.15252/emmm.201404792|pmid=25550396|pmc=4309665|quote=The severe Ebola virus disease epidemic occurring in West Africa likely stems from a single zoonotic transmission event involving a 2\u2010year\u2010old boy in Meliandou, Guinea, who might have been infected by hunting or playing with insectivorous free\u2010tailed bats living in a nearby hollow tree}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 January, the journal ''Nature'' reported that the virus emergence could be found by studying how bush-meat hunters interacted with the ecosystem.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Hunt for Ebola's wild hideout takes off as epidemic wanes|journal=Nature|volume=529|issue=7585|pages=138\u2013139|publisher=Nature News & Comment|doi=10.1038/529138a|pmid=26762436|year=2016|last1=Callaway|first1=Ewen|bibcode=2016Natur.529..138C}}</ref> The continent of Africa has experienced deforestation in several areas or regions; this may contribute to recent outbreaks, including this EVD epidemic, as initial cases have been in the proximity of deforested lands where fruit-eating bats natural habitat may be affected, though 100% evidence does not as yet exist.<ref name=defor/><ref name=defor2/>\n\n=== Human to human transmission ===\n\nPrior to this outbreak, it was believed that human-to-human transmission occurred only via direct contact with blood or bodily fluids from an infected person who is showing symptoms of infection, by contact with the body of a person who had died of Ebola, or by contact with objects recently contaminated with the body fluids of an actively ill infected person.<ref name=CDCPress2014>{{cite report|title=CDC Telebriefing on Ebola outbreak in West Africa|url=https://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2014/t0728-ebola.html|publisher=CDC|accessdate=3 August 2014|date=28 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=Ost2015>{{cite journal|last1=Osterholm|first1=MT|last2=Moore|first2=KA|last3=Kelley|first3=NS|last4=Brosseau|first4=LM|last5=Wong|first5=G|last6=Murphy|first6=FA|last7=Peters|first7=CJ|last8=LeDuc|first8=JW|last9=Russell|first9=PK|last10=Van Herp|first10=M|last11=Kapetshi|first11=J|last12=Muyembe|first12=JJ|last13=Ilunga|first13=BK|last14=Strong|first14=JE|last15=Grolla|first15=A|last16=Wolz|first16=A|last17=Kargbo|first17=B|last18=Kargbo|first18=DK|last19=Formenty|first19=P|last20=Sanders|first20=DA|last21=Kobinger|first21=GP|title=Transmission of Ebola viruses: what we know and what we do not know|journal=mBio|date=19 February 2015|volume=6|issue=2|page=e00137|pmid=25698835|doi=10.1128/mBio.00137-15|pmc=4358015}}</ref>\nIt is now known that the Ebola virus can be transmitted sexually. Over time, studies have suggested that the virus can persist in [[seminal fluid]], with a study released in September 2016 suggesting that the virus may survive more than 530&nbsp;days after infection.<ref name=BDiallo/> EBOV RNA in semen is not the same situation as perseverance of EBOV in semen, however the \"clinical significance of low levels of virus RNA in convalescent\" individuals who are healthy is unknown.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Broadhurst |first1=M. Jana |last2=Brooks |first2=Tim J. G. |last3=Pollock |first3=Nira R. |title=Diagnosis of Ebola Virus Disease: Past, Present, and Future |journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews |date=October 2016 |volume=29 |issue=4 |pages=773\u2013793 |doi=10.1128/CMR.00003-16 |pmid=27413095 |pmc=5010747}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=M\u00fchlberger |editor1-first=Elke |editor2-last=Hensley |editor2-first=Lisa L. |editor3-last=Towner |editor3-first=Jonathan S. |title=Marburg- and Ebolaviruses: From Ecosystems to Molecules |volume=411 |date=2017 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-3-319-68948-7 |page=79|chapter=West Africa 2013 Ebola: From Virus Outbreak to Humanitarian Crisis|last1=Bausch|first1=Daniel G.|doi=10.1007/82_2017_69 |pmid=29071473 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=gkFEDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA79&dq=EBOV+RNA+in+semen#v=onepage&q=EBOV%20RNA%20in%20semen&f=false |accessdate=14 January 2019 |series=Current Topics in Microbiology and Immunology }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, the WHO had reported: \"No formal evidence exists of sexual transmission, but sexual transmission from convalescent patients cannot be ruled out. There is evidence that live Ebola virus can be isolated in seminal fluids of convalescent men for 82 days after onset of symptoms. Evidence is not available yet beyond 82 days.\"<ref name=\"Ebola media centre fact sheets\">{{cite report |url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs103/en/ |title=Ebola media centre fact sheets |publisher=WHO |accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref>  In April 2015, following a report that the RNA virus had been detected in a semen sample six months after a man's recovery, the WHO issued a statement: \"For greater security and prevention of other sexually transmitted infections, Ebola survivors should consider correct and consistent use of condoms for all sexual acts beyond three months until more information is available.\"<ref>{{cite report|title=Interim advice on the sexual transmission of the Ebola virus disease|url=http://www.who.int/reproductivehealth/topics/rtis/ebola-virus-semen/en/|publisher=WHO |accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Deen|first1=Gibrilla F.|last2=Knust|first2=Barbara|last3=Broutet|first3=Nathalie|last4=Sesay|first4=Foday R.|last5=Formenty|first5=Pierre|last6=Ross|first6=Christine|last7=Thorson|first7=Anna E.|last8=Massaquoi|first8=Thomas A.|last9=Marrinan|first9=Jaclyn E.|last10=Ervin|first10=Elizabeth|last11=Jambai|first11=Amara|last12=McDonald|first12=Suzanna L.R.|last13=Bernstein|first13=Kyle|last14=Wurie|first14=Alie H.|last15=Dumbuya|first15=Marion S.|last16=Abad|first16=Neetu|last17=Idriss|first17=Baimba|last18=Wi|first18=Teodora|last19=Bennett|first19=Sarah D.|last20=Davies|first20=Tina|last21=Ebrahim|first21=Faiqa K.|last22=Meites|first22=Elissa|last23=Naidoo|first23=Dhamari|last24=Smith|first24=Samuel|last25=Banerjee|first25=Anshu|last26=Erickson|first26=Bobbie Rae|last27=Brault|first27=Aaron|last28=Durski|first28=Kara N.|last29=Winter|first29=Jorn|last30=Sealy|first30=Tara|last31=Nichol|first31=Stuart T.|last32=Lamunu|first32=Margaret|last33=Str\u00f6her|first33=Ute|last34=Morgan|first34=Oliver|last35=Sahr|first35=Foday|title=Ebola RNA Persistence in Semen of Ebola Virus Disease Survivors \u2014 Preliminary Report|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|date=14 October 2015|volume=377|issue=15|pages=1428\u20131437|doi=10.1056/NEJMoa1511410|pmid=26465681|pmc=5798881}}</ref>\n\nThe WHO based their new recommendations on a March 2015 case, in which a Liberian woman who had no contact with the disease other than having had unprotected sex with a man who had had the disease in October 2014, was diagnosed with Ebola. While no evidence of the virus was found in his blood, his semen revealed Ebola virus RNA closely matching the variant that infected the woman. However, \"doctors don't know if there was any fully formed (and therefore infectious) virus in the guy's semen.\"  It is known that testes are protected from the body's immune system to protect the developing [[sperm]], and it is thought that this same protection may allow the virus to survive in the testes for an unknown time.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.popsci.com/why-ebola-lives-so-long-survivors-testicles|title=Why Testicles Are The Perfect Hiding Spot For Ebola|magazine=Popular Science|accessdate=7 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 September 2015, the body of a girl who had died in Sierra Leone tested positive for Ebola<ref name=\"auto6\" />\t and it was suspected that she may have contracted the disease from the semen of an Ebola survivor who was discharged in March 2015.<ref name=\"auto7\" /> According to some news reports, a new study to be published in the ''New England Journal of Medicine'' indicated that the RNA virus could remain in the semen of survivors for up to six months,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2015/09/09/us-health-ebola-semen-idUKKCN0R922G20150909|title=Sex and masturbation may hamper Ebola eradication efforts|work=Reuters|accessdate=14 September 2015|date=9 September 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Deen |first1=Gibrilla F. |last2=Broutet |first2=Nathalie |last3=Xu |first3=Wenbo |last4=Knust |first4=Barbara |last5=Sesay |first5=Foday R. |last6=McDonald |first6=Suzanna L.R. |last7=Ervin |first7=Elizabeth |last8=Marrinan |first8=Jaclyn E. |last9=Gaillard |first9=Philippe |last10=Habib |first10=Ndema |last11=Liu |first11=Hongtu |last12=Liu |first12=William |last13=Thorson |first13=Anna E. |last14=Yamba |first14=Francis |last15=Massaquoi |first15=Thomas A. |last16=James |first16=Faustin |last17=Ariyarajah |first17=Archchun |last18=Ross |first18=Christine |last19=Bernstein |first19=Kyle |last20=Coursier |first20=Antoine |last21=Klena |first21=John |last22=Carino |first22=Marylin |last23=Wurie |first23=Alie H. |last24=Zhang |first24=Yong |last25=Dumbuya |first25=Marion S. |last26=Abad |first26=Neetu |last27=Idriss |first27=Baimba |last28=Wi |first28=Teodora |last29=Bennett |first29=Sarah D. |last30=Davies |first30=Tina |last31=Ebrahim |first31=Faiqa K. |last32=Meites |first32=Elissa |last33=Naidoo |first33=Dhamari |last34=Smith |first34=Samuel J. |last35=Ongpin |first35=Patricia |last36=Malik |first36=Tasneem |last37=Banerjee |first37=Anshu |last38=Erickson |first38=Bobbie R. |last39=Liu |first39=Yongjian |last40=Liu |first40=Yang |last41=Xu |first41=Ke |last42=Brault |first42=Aaron |last43=Durski |first43=Kara N. |last44=Winter |first44=J\u00f6rn |last45=Sealy |first45=Tara |last46=Nichol |first46=Stuart T. |last47=Lamunu |first47=Margaret |last48=Bangura |first48=James |last49=Landoulsi |first49=Sihem |last50=Jambai |first50=Amara |last51=Morgan |first51=Oliver |last52=Wu |first52=Guizhen |last53=Liang |first53=Mifang |last54=Su |first54=Qiudong |last55=Lan |first55=Yu |last56=Hao |first56=Yanzhe |last57=Formenty |first57=Pierre |last58=Str\u00f6her |first58=Ute |last59=Sahr |first59=Foday |title=Ebola RNA Persistence in Semen of Ebola Virus Disease Survivors \u2014 Final Report |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |date=12 October 2017 |volume=377 |issue=15 |pages=1428\u20131437 |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa1511410 |pmid=26465681 |pmc=5798881 }}</ref> and according to other researchers, the RNA virus could continue in semen for 82 days and maybe longer. Furthermore, Ebola RNA had been found up to 284 days post-onset of viral symptoms.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Broutet|first=Nathalie|last2=Lofthouse|first2=Clare|last3=Formenty|first3=Pierre|last4=Thorson|first4=Anna|date=2016|title=Systematic review of the literature on viral persistence and sexual transmission from recovered Ebola survivors: evidence and recommendations|url=https://bmjopen.bmj.com/content/6/1/e008859|journal=BMJ Open|volume=6|issue=1|page=e008859|doi=10.1136/bmjopen-2015-008859|pmid=26743699|pmc=4716240}}</ref>\n\n=== Containment difficulties ===\n\nOne of the primary reasons for the spread of the disease is the low-quality, functioning health systems in the parts of Africa where the disease occurs.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Tiaji|last1=Salaam-Blyther|title=The 2014 Ebola Outbreak: International and U.S. Responses|url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/row/R43697.pdf|accessdate=9 September 2014|date=26 August 2014}}</ref> The risk of transmission is increased among those caring for people infected. Recommended measures when caring for those who are infected include [[Isolation (health care)|medical isolation]] via the proper use of boots, gowns, gloves, masks and goggles, and [[disinfection|sterilizing all equipment and surfaces]].<ref>{{cite report|title=Prevention of Ebola Hemorrhagic Fever |publisher=CDC|url=https://www.cdc.gov/vhf/ebola/prevention/index.html |accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOne of the biggest dangers of infection faced by medical staff requires their learning how to properly suit up and remove personal protective equipment.\nFull training for wearing protective body clothing can take 10 to 14 days.<ref name=\"www.telegraph.co.uk Ebola-medics-better-trained-in-Sierra-Leone-than-Spain\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/ebola/11155840/Ebola-medics-better-trained-in-Sierra-Leone-than-Spain.html Ebola medics 'better trained in Sierra Leone than Spain'] ''The Telegraph'', by Fiona Govan, 11 October 2014</ref>  Even with proper isolation equipment available, working conditions such as lack of running water, climate control, and flooring have made direct care difficult. Two American health workers who contracted the disease and later recovered said that to the best of their knowledge, their team of workers had been following \"to the letter all of the protocols for safety that were developed by the [CDC] and WHO\", including a full body coverall, several layers of gloves, and face protection including goggles. One of the two, a physician, had worked with patients, but the other was assisting workers to get in and out of their protective gear while wearing protective gear herself.<ref name=\"nbcnews.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ebola-virus-outbreak/two-americans-stricken-deadly-ebola-virus-liberia-n166281 |title=Two Americans Stricken With Deadly Ebola Virus in Liberia |publisher=NBC News |date=28 July 2014 |accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nDifficulties in attempting to halt transmission have also included the multiple disease outbreaks across country borders.<ref name=\"Control\" /> [[Peter Piot|Dr Peter Piot]], the scientist who co-discovered the Ebola virus, stated that the outbreak was not following its usual linear patterns as mapped out in earlier outbreaks\u2014this time the virus was \"hopping\" all over the Western African epidemic region.<ref name=Guinea_Ebola_Sep_Update /> Furthermore, most past epidemics had occurred in remote regions, but this outbreak spread to large urban areas, which had increased the number of contacts an infected person might have and made transmission harder to track and break.<ref name=\"WHO20140825\">{{cite report |url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/ebola/25-august-2014/en/ |title=Unprecedented number of medical staff infected with Ebola |publisher=WHO |date=25 August 2014 |accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> On 9 December, a study indicated that a single individual introduced the virus into Liberia, causing the most cases of the disease in that country.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.cell.com/cell-host-microbe/fulltext/S1931-3128(15)00462-X|title=Evolution and Spread of Ebola Virus in Liberia, 2014\u20132015|journal=Cell Host & Microbe|doi=10.1016/j.chom.2015.11.008|pmid=26651942|pmc=4711363|volume=18|issue=6|pages=659\u2013669|year=2015|last1=Ladner|first1=Jason T|last2=Wiley|first2=Michael R|last3=Mate|first3=Suzanne|last4=Dudas|first4=Gytis|last5=Prieto|first5=Karla|last6=Lovett|first6=Sean|last7=Nagle|first7=Elyse R|last8=Beitzel|first8=Brett|last9=Gilbert|first9=Merle L|last10=Fakoli|first10=Lawrence|last11=Diclaro|first11=Joseph W|last12=Schoepp|first12=Randal J|last13=Fair|first13=Joseph|last14=Kuhn|first14=Jens H|last15=Hensley|first15=Lisa E|last16=Park|first16=Daniel J|last17=Sabeti|first17=Pardis C|last18=Rambaut|first18=Andrew|last19=Sanchez-Lockhart|first19=Mariano|last20=Bolay|first20=Fatorma K|last21=Kugelman|first21=Jeffrey R|last22=Palacios|first22=Gustavo}}</ref>\n\n== Containment and control ==\n{{Main|Prevention of viral hemorrhagic fever}}\n{{See also|Ebola virus disease#Prevention}}\n[[File:PPE Training (2).jpg|thumb|Nigerian doctors training on PPE by WHO]]\nIn August 2014, the WHO published a road map of the steps required to bring the epidemic under control and to prevent further transmission of the disease within Western Africa; the coordinated [[Responses to the Ebola virus epidemic in West Africa#WHO|international response]] worked towards realising this plan.<ref name=\"res\">{{cite report|title=Ebola response Roadmap|url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/131596/1/EbolaResponseRoadmap.pdf| publisher=WHO|accessdate=21 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Surveillance and contact tracing ===\n[[Contact tracing]] is an essential method of preventing the spread of the disease, this requires effective [[Epidemiological surveillance|community surveillance]] so that a possible case of Ebola can be registered and accurately diagnosed as soon as possible, and subsequently finding everyone who has had close contact with the case and tracking them for 21 days. However, this requires careful record-keeping by properly trained and equipped staff.<ref>{{cite report |title=Contact tracing |url=https://www.who.int/features/qa/contact-tracing/en/ |publisher=WHO |accessdate=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The reason Ebola isn't being stopped|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/09/11/health/ebola-contact-tracing/|publisher=CNN|accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> WHO Assistant Director-General for Global Health Security, Keiji Fukuda, said on 3 September 2014, \"We don't have enough health workers, doctors, nurses, drivers, and contact tracers to handle the increasing number of cases.\"<ref name=\"WHO 2014-9-3 Ebola response needs\">{{cite report|title=UN senior leaders outline needs for global Ebola response|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2014/ebola-response-needs/en/|publisher=WHO|accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> There was a massive effort to train volunteers and health workers, sponsored by [[United States Agency for International Development]] (USAID).<ref>{{cite report|title=Fact sheet: U.S. Response to the Ebola Epidemic in West Africa|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/09/16/fact-sheet-us-response-ebola-epidemic-west-africa|publisher=The White House|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref> According to WHO reports, 25,926 contacts from Guinea, 35,183 from Liberia and 104,454 from Sierra Leone were listed and traced as of 23 November 2014.<ref name=WHO2014_11_23 /> According to one study, it is important to have a public awareness campaign to inform the affected community about the importance of contact tracing, so that true information can be obtained from the community.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Learning from the challenges of Ebola Virus Disease contact tracers in Sierra Leone, February, 2015|pmc=4695526|pmid=26740849|doi=10.11694/pamj.supp.2015.22.1.6537|volume=22|issue=Suppl 1|year=2015|page=21| last1 = Ilesanmi | first1 = OS | journal=Pan Afr Med J|doi-broken-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Community awareness ===\n{{See also|Cultural effects of the Ebola crisis}}\nTo reduce the spread, the WHO recommended raising community awareness of the risk factors for Ebola infection and the protective measures individuals can take.<ref name=WHOFS103>{{cite report|title= Ebola virus disease Fact sheet N\u00b0103 |url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs103/en/|publisher=WHO|accessdate=6 September 2014 }}</ref> These include avoiding contact with infected people and regular [[hand washing]] using soap and water.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://plan-international.org/about-plan/resources/news/ebola-outbreak-5-tips-to-avoid-the-deadly-disease/|title=Ebola \u2013 5 tips to avoid the deadly disease |publisher= Plan International|date=6 September 2014 |accessdate= 11 April 2015}}</ref> A condition of extreme poverty exists in many of the areas that experienced a high incidence of infections. According to the director of the NGO [[Plan (aid organisation)|Plan International]] in Guinea, \"The poor [[living conditions]] and lack of [[water supply|water]] and [[sanitation]] in most districts of Conakry pose a serious risk that the epidemic escalates into a crisis. People do not think to wash their hands when they do not have enough [[drinking water|water to drink]].\"<ref name=\"Diallo\">{{cite news|title=Ebola en Guin\u00e9e : l'ONG Plan Guin\u00e9e craint une aggravation de l'\u00e9pidemie|url=http://www.africaguinee.com/articles/2014/03/30/ebola-en-guinee-l-ong-plan-guinee-craint-une-aggravation-de-l-epidemie |language=fr |trans-title=Ebola in Guinea: the NGO Plan Guinea fears a worsening of the epidemic |publisher=Africa guin\u00e9e |date=29 March 2014 |accessdate=31 March 2014|first=Boubacar |last=Diallo}}</ref> One study showed that once people had heard of the Ebola virus disease, hand washing with soap and water improved, though socio-demographic factors influenced hygiene.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The effect of Ebola Virus Disease outbreak on hand washing among secondary school students in Ondo State Nigeria, October, 2014|pmc=4695531|pmid=26740852|doi=10.11694/pamj.supp.2015.22.1.6614|volume=22|issue=Suppl 1|year=2015|page=24| last1 = Ilesanmi | first1 = OS | last2 = Alele | first2 = FO | journal=Pan Afr Med J|doi-broken-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nA number of organisations enrolled local people to conduct public awareness campaigns among the communities in Western Africa.<ref>{{cite web|title=Encounters during the Ebola awareness campaign|url=http://plan-international.org/about-plan/resources/blogs/encounters-during-the-ebola-awareness-campaign/|publisher=PLAN International|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref> \"...&nbsp;what we mean by social mobilization is to try to convey the right messages, in terms of prevention measures, adapted to the local context\u2014adapted to the cultural practices in a specific area,\" said Vincent Martin, [[FAO]]'s representative in Senegal.<ref>{{cite web|title=FAO Launches Ebola Awareness Campaign in West Africa|url=http://www.voanews.com/content/ebola-fao-17oct14/2487282.html|publisher=FAO|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nDenial in some affected countries also made containment efforts difficult.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ofeibea Quist-Arcton|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/goatsandsoda/2014/08/06/338234063/skeptics-in-sierra-leone-doubt-ebola-virus-exists|title=Skeptics In Sierra Leone Doubt Ebola Virus Exists|publisher=NPR|date=6 August 2014}}</ref> Language barriers and the appearance of medical teams in protective suits sometimes increased fears of the virus.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Anja Wolz|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg22329774.600-fighting-fear-denial-and-death-on-ebola-frontline.html|title=Fighting fear, denial and death on Ebola frontline|magazine=New Scientist |date=15 July 2014 |accessdate= 11 April 2015}}</ref> In Liberia, a mob attacked an Ebola isolation centre, stealing equipment and \"freeing\" patients while shouting \"There's no Ebola.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theage.com.au/world/patients-reported-missing-after-ebola-clinic-attacked-in-liberia-20140818-10573f.html |title=Patients reported missing after Ebola clinic attacked in Liberia|newspaper=The Age |date=18 August 2014 |accessdate=18 August 2014 |location=Melbourne}}</ref> Red Cross staff were forced to suspend operations in southeast Guinea after they were threatened by a group of men armed with knives.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/02/health-ebola-westafrica-redcross-idUSL6N0PD2GH20140702 |title=Red Cross suspends Ebola operations in southeast Guinea after threats |work=Reuters |date=2 July 2014 |accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref> In September, in the town of [[Womey]] in Guinea, suspicious inhabitants wielding machetes murdered at least eight aid workers and dumped their bodies in a [[latrine]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2014/09/19/at-least-8-ebola-aid-workers-reportedly-killed-in-cold-blood-by-villagers-in/ |title=At least 8 Ebola aid workers reportedly killed 'in cold blood' by villagers in Guinea |publisher=Fox News |accessdate=19 September 2014 |date=19 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nAn August 2014 study found that nearly two-thirds of Ebola cases in Guinea were believed to be due to burial practices including [[bathing the dead|washing of the body of one who had died]].<ref name=\"WHO 2014-07-03\" /><ref name=\"Global Post\" /><ref name=\"Today Health\" /><ref name=\"NYT122914\" /><ref name=BBC_Freetown /><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Chan|first1=M|title=Ebola Virus Disease in West Africa \u2013 No Early End to the Outbreak|journal=The New England Journal of Medicine|date=20 August 2014|pmid=25140856|doi=10.1056/NEJMp1409859|volume=371|issue=13|pages=1183\u20135|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/d2c4abe309ec979536a57913cb8e5fbb188b5cbf}}</ref>\nIn November, WHO released a protocol for the safe and dignified burial of people who die from Ebola virus disease. It encouraged the inclusion of family and clergy, and gave specific instructions for Muslim and Christian burials.<ref>{{cite report | title=How to conduct safe and dignified burial of a patient who has died from suspected or confirmed Ebola virus disease | work= Global Alert and Response | url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/137379/1/WHO_EVD_GUIDANCE_Burials_14.2_eng.pdf | format=PDF | publisher=WHO | accessdate=14 December 2014 }}</ref>  In the 21 January 2015 WHO road map update, it was reported that 100% of districts in Sierra Leone and 71% of districts in Guinea had a list of key religious leaders who promoted safe and dignified burials.<ref name=\"Ebola situation report\">{{cite report | url=http://who.int/csr/disease/ebola/situation-reports/en/ | title=Ebola situation report | publisher=WHO | date=21 January 2015 | accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref>  Speaking on 27 January 2015, Guinea's Grand Imam, the country's highest cleric, gave a very strong message saying, \"There is nothing in the [[Koran]] that says you must wash, kiss or hold your dead loved ones,\" and he called on citizens to do more to stop the virus by practising safer burying rituals that do not compromise tradition.<ref name=\"npr.org1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/goatsandsoda/2015/01/26/381529285/guineas-grand-imam-pulls-no-punches-in-his-ebola-message|title=Guinea's Grand Imam Pulls No Punches In His Ebola Message|date=26 January 2015|publisher=NPR|accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the height of the epidemic, most schools in the three most affected countries were shut down and remained closed for several months. During the period of closure [[UNICEF]] and its partners established strict hygiene protocols to be used when the schools were reopened in January 2015.  They met with thousands of teachers and administrators to work out hygiene guidelines.  Their efforts included installing hand-washing stations and distributing millions of bars of soap and chlorine and plans for taking the temperature of children and staff at the school gate.  Their efforts were complicated by the fact that less than 50% of the schools in these three countries had access to running water. In August 2015, UNICEF released a report that stated, \"Across the three countries, there have been no reported cases of a student or teacher being infected at a school since strict hygiene protocols were introduced when classes resumed at the beginning of the year after a months-long delay caused by the virus.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unicef.org/media/media_82875.html|title=Hygiene practices have helped keep Ebola out of the classroom|date=12 August 2015|publisher=UNICEF|accessdate=14 August 2015}}</ref> Researchers presented evidence indicating that infected people that lived in low socioeconomic areas were more likely to transmit the virus to other socioeconomic status (SES) communities, in contrast to individuals in higher SES areas who were infected as well.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Mosoka P. Fallah |author2=Laura A. Skrip |author3=Shai Gertler |author4=Dan Yamin |author5=Alison P. Galvani |date=31 December 2015 |title=Quantifying Poverty as a Driver of Ebola Transmission |doi=10.1371/journal.pntd.0004260|pmid=26720278 |pmc=4697799 |volume=9|issue=12 |journal=PLOS Neglected Tropical Diseases|pages=e0004260 }}</ref> Another study showed that, in Guinea, a satisfactory knowledge had not altered the level of comprehensive knowledge about the virus. As a consequence, the high level of misinterpretation was responsible for a low comprehensive knowledge about the virus; 82% of individuals believed that Ebola was the result of a virus (36.2% thought that a higher power had caused it).<ref>{{cite journal|title=Misconceptions about Ebola seriously affect the prevention efforts: KAP related to Ebola prevention and treatment in Kouroussa Prefecture, Guinea|pmc=4695529|pmid=26740839|doi=10.11694/pamj.supp.2015.22.1.6269|volume=22|issue=Suppl 1|year=2015|page=11| last1 = Buli | first1 = BG | last2 = Mayigane | first2 = LN | last3 = Oketta | first3 = JF | last4 = Soumouk | first4 = A | last5 = Sandouno | first5 = TE | last6 = Camara | first6 = B | last7 = Toure | first7 = MS | last8 = Conde | first8 = A | journal=Pan Afr Med J|doi-broken-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> A study on Nigeria's success story stated that, in this case, a prompt response by the government and proactive public health measures had resulted in the quick control of the outbreak.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Ebola epidemic \u2013 the Nigerian experience|pmc=4695530|pmid=26740845|doi=10.11694/pamj.supp.2015.22.1.6625|volume=22|issue=Suppl 1|year=2015|page=17| last1 = Onyeonoro | first1 = UU | last2 = Ekpemiro | first2 = UC | last3 = Abali | first3 = C | last4 = Nwokeukwu | first4 = HI | journal=Pan Afr Med J|doi-broken-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nDuring the height of the crisis, Wikipedia's Ebola page received 2.5 million page views per day, making Wikipedia one of the world's most highly used sources of trusted medical information regarding the disease.<ref>[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/the-conversation-global/wikipedia-is-already-the_b_12538740.html Wikipedia is already the world\u2019s \u2018Dr Google\u2019 - it\u2019s time for doctors and researchers to make it better] ''Huffington Post''. Conversation Global Editorial Group. Oct. 18, 2016.  Downloaded Oct. 22, 2017.</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/27/business/media/wikipedia-is-emerging-as-trusted-internet-source-for-information-on-ebola-.html Wikipedia Emerges as Trusted Internet Source for Ebola Information] By Noam Cohen.  Oct. 26. 2014.  Downloaded Oct. 22, 2017.</ref>\n\n=== Travel restrictions and quarantines ===\n[[File:Quarantine travel pass sierra leone.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Quarantine travel pass for individuals providing assistance]]\nThere was serious concern that the disease would spread further within Western Africa or elsewhere in the world, such as:\n* '''Western Africa''' On 8 August 2014, a ''[[cordon sanitaire]]'', a disease-fighting practice that forcibly isolates affected regions, was established in the triangular area where Guinea, Liberia, and Sierra Leone are separated only by porous borders and where 70 per cent of the known cases had been found.<ref name=cordon>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/13/science/using-a-tactic-unseen-in-a-century-countries-cordon-off-ebola-racked-areas.html |last=McNeil |first=Donald G., Jr. |title=Using a Tactic Unseen in a Century, Countries Cordon Off Ebola-Racked Areas |newspaper=The New York Times |date=13 August 2014 |accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref> This was subsequently replaced by a series of simple checkpoints for hand-washing and measuring body temperature on major roads throughout the region, manned either by local volunteers or by the military.<ref>{{cite web|title=In Sierra Leone's Ebola hot zone: A series of reports|url=http://www.irinnews.org/report/100706/in-sierra-leone-s-ebola-hot-zone-a-series-of-reports|publisher=UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs|accessdate=2 November 2014|date=2014-10-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rally around West African communities to fight Ebola|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/opinion/2024924352_maxweihecolumnebola02xml.html|newspaper=The Seattle Times|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref>\n* '''International''' Many countries considered imposing travel restrictions to or from the region. On 2 September 2014, WHO Director-General [[Margaret Chan]] advised against this, saying that they were not justified and that they would prevent medical experts from entering the affected areas. She also stated that they were \"marginalizing the affected population and potentially worsening the crisis\". UN officials working on the ground also criticised the travel restrictions, saying the solution was \"not in travel restrictions but in ensuring that effective preventive and curative health measures are put in place\".<ref name=\"As Ebola Outbreak Surges, Health Officials Slam International 'Coalition of Inaction'\">{{cite news|url=http://www.commondreams.org/news/2014/09/03/ebola-outbreak-surges-health-officials-slam-international-coalition-inaction |title=As Ebola Outbreak Surges, Health Officials Slam International 'Coalition of Inaction' |publisher=Common Dreams |date=3 September 2014 |accessdate=7 September 2014 |author=McCauley, Lauren}}</ref> MSF also spoke out against the closure of international borders, calling them \"another layer of collective irresponsibility\" and added: \"The international community must ensure that those who try to contain the outbreak can enter and leave the affected countries if need be.\"<ref name=\"Ebola: the failures of the international outbreak response\" />\n\n:In December 2015, during the 8th meeting of WHO's \"[[International Health Regulations|IHR]] Emergency Committee regarding Ebola\", it spoke out against further travel restrictions saying: \"The Committee remains deeply concerned that 34 countries still enact inappropriate travel and transport measures and highlights the need to immediately terminate any such measures due to their negative impact, particularly on recovery efforts.\"<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2015/ihr-ebola-8th-meeting/en/|title=Statement on the 8th meeting of the IHR Emergency Committee regarding the Ebola outbreak in West Africa|author=|date=|publisher=WHO |accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref> In December 2015, the CDC indicated that it would no longer make the recommendation for US citizens going to Sierra Leone to be extra careful. However, the CDC did further indicate that individuals travelling to the country should take precaution with sick people and body fluids. Additionally, individuals travelling to the country should avoid contact with animals.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/watch/ebola-sierra-leone|title=Removed: Ebola in Sierra Leone \u2013 Watch \u2013  Level 1, Practice Usual Precautions \u2013 Travel Health Notices \u2013 Travelers|author=|date=|publisher=CDC |accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Returning health workers''' There was concern that people returning from affected countries, such as health workers and reporters, may have been incubating the disease and become infectious after arriving.  Guidelines for returning workers were issued by a number of agencies, including the CDC,<ref>{{cite report |title=Interim U.S. Guidance for Monitoring and Movement of Persons with Potential Ebola Virus Exposure |url=https://www.cdc.gov/vhf/ebola/exposure/monitoring-and-movement-of-persons-with-exposure.html|publisher=CDC|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref> MSF,<ref>{{cite news|title=MSF Protocols for Staff Returning from Ebola-Affected Countries |url=http://www.doctorswithoutborders.org/article/msf-protocols-staff-returning-ebola-affected-countries |publisher=Doctors without Borders |accessdate=2 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102033712/http://www.doctorswithoutborders.org/article/msf-protocols-staff-returning-ebola-affected-countries |archive-date=2 November 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Public Health England,<ref>{{cite report |title=Public health recommendations for returning workers who are asymptomatic contacts of Ebola virus disease |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/385769/Ebola_recommendations_for_workers_who_are_asymptomatic_contacts.pdf |publisher=Public Health England|date=10 December 2014  |accessdate= 11 April 2015|format=PDF}}</ref> and Public Health Ontario.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ebola virus disease (EVD): Advice for returning travellers from countries/areas affected by EVD |url=http://www.publichealthontario.ca/en/eRepository/EVD_advice_returning_traveller_temp_recording.pdf |publisher=Public Health Ontario|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Treatment ==\n{{See also|Ebola virus disease treatment research|Ebola vaccine}}\n[[File:Practising taking blood in Ebola saftey suits (15649429018).jpg|thumb|Practising taking blood in PPE]]\nNo proven Ebola virus-specific treatment presently exists;<ref name=addref/><ref name=Choi-2013>{{cite journal |vauthors=Choi JH, Croyle MA |title=Emerging targets and novel approaches to Ebola virus prophylaxis and treatment |journal=BioDrugs |volume=27 |issue=6 |pages=565\u201383 |date=December 2013 |pmid=23813435 |doi=10.1007/s40259-013-0046-1 |pmc=3833964}}</ref> however, measures can be taken to improve a patient's chances of survival.<ref>{{cite news|author= Makiko Kitamura |title=Sierra Leone Is Epicenter of Ebola as Guinea Clinic Shut |date=8 June 2014 |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2014-07-29/sierra-leone-is-epicenter-of-ebola-as-guinea-clinic-shut |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141024234244/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2014-07-29/sierra-leone-is-epicenter-of-ebola-as-guinea-clinic-shut |archivedate=24 October 2014 |accessdate=30 July 2014}}</ref>  Ebola symptoms may begin as early as two days or as long as 21 days after one is exposed to the virus. Symptoms usually begin with a sudden [[influenza]]-like illness characterised by [[fatigue (medical)|feeling tired]], and pain in the [[myalgia|muscles]] and [[arthralgia|joints]].  Later symptoms may include headache, [[nausea]], and abdominal pain; this is often followed by severe vomiting and [[diarrhoea]].<ref>{{cite report |title=Signs and Symptoms of Ebola Hemorrhagic Fever |url=https://www.cdc.gov/vhf/ebola/symptoms/index.html |publisher= CDC|accessdate=27 January 2019 |language=en-us |date=30 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=Hun2012>{{cite book|last1=Magill|first1=Alan|author1-link=Alan Magill|title=Hunter's tropical medicine and emerging infectious diseases|date=2013|publisher=Saunders|location=New York|isbn=978-1-4160-4390-4|page=332|edition=9th|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UgvdM8WRld4C&pg=PA332}}</ref>  In past outbreaks, it has been noted that some patients bleed internally and/or externally; however data published in October 2014 showed that this had been a rare symptom in the Western African outbreak.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite journal | title=Clinical Illness and Outcomes in Patients with Ebola in Sierra Leone | journal=The New England Journal of Medicine | date=29 October 2014 | doi=10.1056/NEJMoa1411680 | pmid=25353969 | pmc=4318555 | volume=371 | issue=22 | pages=2092\u20132100 | display-authors=3 |last1=Schieffelin|first1=John S|last2=Shaffer|first2=Jeffrey G|last3=Goba|first3=Augustine|last4=Gbakie|first4=Michael|last5=Gire|first5=Stephen K|last6=Colubri|first6=Andres|last7=Sealfon|first7=Rachel SG|last8=Kanneh|first8=Lansana|last9=Moigboi|first9=Alex|last10=Momoh|first10=Mambu|last11=Fullah|first11=Mohammed|last12=Moses|first12=Lina M|last13=Brown|first13=Bethany L|last14=Andersen|first14=Kristian G|last15=Winnicki|first15=Sarah|last16=Schaffner|first16=Stephen F|last17=Park|first17=Daniel J|last18=Yozwiak|first18=Nathan L|last19=Jiang|first19=Pan-Pan|last20=Kargbo|first20=David|last21=Jalloh|first21=Simbirie|last22=Fonnie|first22=Mbalu|last23=Sinnah|first23=Vandi|last24=French|first24=Issa|last25=Kovoma|first25=Alice|last26=Kamara|first26=Fatima K|last27=Tucker|first27=Veronica|last28=Konuwa|first28=Edwin|last29=Sellu|first29=Josephine|last30=Mustapha|first30=Ibrahim|last31=Foday|first31=Momoh|last32=Yillah|first32=Mohamed|last33=Kanneh|first33=Franklyn|last34=Saffa|first34=Sidiki|last35=Massally|first35=James LB|last36=Boisen|first36=Matt L|last37=Branco|first37=Luis M|last38=Vandi|first38=Mohamed A|last39=Grant|first39=Donald S|last40=Happi|first40=Christian Tientcha|last41=Gevao|first41=Sahr M|last42=Fletcher|first42=Thomas E|last43=Fowler|first43=Robert A|last44=Bausch|first44=Daniel G|last45=Sabeti|first45=Pardis Christine|last46=Khan|first46=S. Humarr|last47=Garry|first47=Robert F|url=http://nrs.harvard.edu/urn-3:HUL.InstRepos:14412251 }}</ref>  Another study published in October 2014 suggested that a person's genetic makeup may play a major role in determining how an infected person's body reacts to the disease, with some infected people experiencing mild or no symptoms while others progress to a very severe stage that includes bleeding.<ref>{{Cite journal | title=Host genetic diversity enables Ebola hemorrhagic fever pathogenesis and resistance | journal=Science | volume=346 | issue=6212 | pages=987\u2013991 | date=30 October 2014 | authors=Angela L. Rasmussen, Atsushi Okumura, Martin T. Ferris, Richard Green, Friederike Feldmann, Sara M. Kelly, Dana P. Scott, David Safronetz, Elaine Haddock, Rachel LaCasse, Matthew J. Thomas1, Pavel Sova1, Victoria S. Carter, Jeffrey M. Weiss, Darla R. Miller, Ginger D. Shaw, Marcus J. Korth, Mark T. Heise, Ralph S. Baric, Fernando Pardo-Manuel de Villena, Heinz Feldmann, Michael G. Katze,\u2020| bibcode=2014Sci...346..987R | doi=10.1126/science.1259595 | pmid=25359852 | pmc=4241145 }}</ref>\n\nWithout fluid replacement, such an extreme loss of fluids leads to [[dehydration]], which in turn may lead to [[hypovolaemic shock]]\u2014a condition in which there isn't enough blood for the heart to pump through the body. If a patient is alert and is not vomiting, [[oral rehydration therapy]] may be instituted, but patients who are vomiting or are [[delirium|delirious]] must be hydrated with [[intravenous therapy|intravenous (IV) therapy]].<ref name=\"addref\">{{cite report|publisher=CDC |title=Treatment of Ebola |url=https://www.cdc.gov/vhf/ebola/treatment/index.html |accessdate=23 January 2019 |language=en-us |date=22 May 2018}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite journal|last=West|first=T. Eoin|last2=von Saint Andr\u00e9-von Arnim|first2=Am\u00e9lie|date=1 November 2014|title=Clinical Presentation and Management of Severe Ebola Virus Disease|journal=Annals of the American Thoracic Society|volume=11|issue=9|pages=1341\u20131350|doi=10.1513/AnnalsATS.201410-481PS|pmid=25369317|issn=2329-6933}}</ref> However, administration of IV fluids is difficult in the African environment. Inserting an IV needle while wearing three pairs of gloves and goggles that may be fogged is difficult, and once in place, the IV site and line must be constantly monitored.   Without sufficient staff to care for patients, needles may become dislodged or pulled out by a delirious patient. A patient's [[electrolyte]]s must be closely monitored to determine correct fluid administration, for which many areas did not have access to the required laboratory services.<ref name=\"NYT010115\">{{cite news|author1=Donald G. McNeil Jr.|title=Ebola Doctors Are Divided on IV Therapy in Africa|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/02/health/ebola-doctors-are-divided-on-iv-therapy-in-africa.html|accessdate=3 January 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|date=1 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nTreatment centres were overflowing with patients while others waited to be admitted; dead patients were so numerous that it was difficult to arrange for safe burials.  Based on many years of experience in Africa\u2014and several months working in the present epidemic\u2014MSF took a conservative approach.  While using IV treatment for as many patients as they could manage, they argued that improperly managed IV treatment was not helpful and may even kill a patient when not properly managed. They also said that they were concerned about further risk to already overworked staff.<ref name=NYT010115 />  While experts have studied the mortality rates of different treatment settings, and given the wide differences in variables that affected outcomes, adequate information had not yet been gathered to make a definitive statement about what constituted optimal care in the Western African setting.<ref name=\"GHD online\">{{cite news| url=http://www.ghdonline.org/ebola/discussion/iv-therapy-for-ebola/ | title=IV Therapy for Ebola | publisher=Communities/Ebola Response | date=January 2015 | accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref> [[Paul Farmer]] of [[Partners in Health]], an NGO that only as of January 2015 had begun to treat Ebola patients, strongly supported IV therapy for all Ebola patients stating: \"What if the fatality rate isn't the virulence of disease but the mediocrity of the medical delivery?\"  Farmer suggested that every treatment facility should have a team that specialises in inserting IVs, or better yet, [[peripherally inserted central catheter]] lines.<ref name=NYT010115 />\n\n=== Prognosis ===\n\nEbola virus disease has a high case fatality rate (CFR), which in past outbreaks varied between 25% and 90%, with an average of about 50%.<ref name=\"Ebola Virus Disease\">{{cite report | url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs103/en/  | publisher=WHO | title=Ebola Virus Factsheet | date=September 2014 | accessdate=28 October 2014}}</ref>  The epidemic caused significant mortality, with reported CFRs of up to 70%.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"cfrebolavirus\" /><ref name=\"WHO2014_12_28\" /><ref name=\"WHOreport\" />\nCare settings that have access to medical expertise may increase survival by providing good maintenance of hydration, circulatory volume, and blood pressure.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThe disease affects males and females equally and the majority of those that contract Ebola disease are between 15 and 45 years of age.<ref name=\":1\" /> For those over 45 years, a fatal outcome was more likely in the Western African epidemic, as was also noted in preceding outbreaks.<ref name=\":7\" />\nOnly rarely do pregnant women survive\u2014a midwife who worked with MSF in a Sierra Leone treatment centre stated that she knew of \"no reported cases of pregnant mothers and unborn babies surviving Ebola in Sierra Leone.\"<ref name=\"/Voice of America\">{{cite news| url=http://www.voanews.com/content/ebola-increases-threat-to-sierra-leone-pregnancies/2492783.html | title=Ebola Increases Threat to Sierra Leone Pregnancies | publisher=Voice of America | date=22 October 2014 | accessdate=26 October 2014 | author=Bailes, Adam}}</ref>  In September 2015, the WHO issued pregnancy guidance information entitled,  \"Interim Guidance on Ebola Virus Disease in Pregnancy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infectioncontroltoday.com/news/2015/09/who-issues-guidance-on-ebola-virus-disease-in-pregnancy.aspx|title=WHO Issues Guidance on Ebola Virus Disease in Pregnancy|publisher=Infection Control Today |accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIt has been suggested that the loss of human life was not limited to Ebola victims alone.  Many hospitals had to shut down, leaving people with other medical needs without care. A spokesperson for the UK-based health foundation, the [[Wellcome Trust]], said in October 2014 that \"the additional death toll from malaria and other diseases [is] likely to exceed that of the outbreak itself\".<ref name=\":2\" /> Dr Paul Farmer stated: \"Most of Ebola's victims may well be dying from other causes: women in childbirth, children from diarrhoea, people in road accidents or from trauma of other sorts.\"<ref name=\"Diary\" />\nAs the epidemic drew to a close in 2015, a report from Sierra Leone showed that the fear and mistrust of hospitals generated by the epidemic had resulted in an 11% decline in facility-based births, and that those receiving care before or after birth fell by about a fifth.  Consequently, between May 2014 and April 2015, the deaths of women during or just after childbirth rose by almost a third and those of newborns by a quarter, compared to the previous year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/07/baby-and-maternal-deaths-soar-in-sierra-leone-amid-ebola-fears-researchers|title=Baby and maternal deaths soar in Sierra Leone amid Ebola fears \u2013 researchers|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=8 October 2015|date=2015-10-07}}</ref>\n\nResearch suggests that many Ebola infections are asymptomatic, meaning that some infected people show no symptoms of the disease. For example, two studies done on previous outbreaks showed that 71% of [[seropositive]] individuals did not have the clinical disease in one outbreak and another study reported that 46% of asymptomatic close contacts of patients with Ebola were seropositive.<ref name=\"The Lancet\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(14)61839-0/fulltext | title=Ebola control: effect of asymptomatic infection and acquired immunity | journal=The Lancet | volume=384 | issue=9953 | pages=1499\u20131500 | date=15 October 2015 | accessdate=26 December 2015 |author1=Steve E Bellanemail |author2=Juliet R C Pulliam |author3=Jonathan Dushoff |author4=Lauren Ancel Meyers | doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(14)61839-0| pmid=25390569 |pmc=4829342 }}</ref> On 22 January, the WHO issued ''Clinical Care for survivors of Ebola Virus Disease: interim guidance''. The guidance covers specific issues like musculoskeletal pain, which is reported in up to 75% of survivors. The pain is symmetrical and more pronounced in the morning, with the larger joints most affected. There is also possible periarticular [[tenosynovitis]] affecting the shoulders. The WHO guidelines advise to distinguish non-inflammatory [[arthralgia]] from inflammatory [[arthritis]]. With regard to ocular problems, sensitivity to light and blurry vision have been indicated among survivors. Among the aftereffects of Ebola virus disease, uveitis and optic nerve disease could appear after an individual is discharged. Ocular problems could threaten sight in survivors, thus the need for prompt treatment. In treating such individuals, the WHO recommends urgent intervention if uveitis is suspected; this consists mainly of prednisone (a [[corticosteroid]]). Hearing loss has been reported in Ebola survivors 25% of the time. Treatment, in the case of acute [[labyrinthitis]] (inner ear disorder), should be given within 10 days of the onset of symptoms and prochlorperazine, a vestibular sedative, may be administered for [[vertigo]].<ref>{{cite report|url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/204235/1/WHO_EVD_OHE_PED_16.1_eng.pdf?ua=1 |format= PDF|title=Clinical care for survivors of Ebola virus disease|publisher=WHO |date=11 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Post-Ebola virus syndrome ===\n{{See also|Post-Ebola virus syndrome}}\nThere are at least 17,000 people who have survived infection from the Ebola virus in Western Africa; some of them have reported lingering health effects.<ref name=\"Carod-Artal\">{{cite journal|title=Post-Ebolavirus disease syndrome: what do we know?|vauthors=Carod-Artal FJ|pmid=26293407|doi=10.1586/14787210.2015.1079128|volume=13|issue=10|year=2015|journal=Expert Rev Anti Infect Ther|pages=1185\u20137}}</ref> In early November, a WHO consultant reported:  \"Many of the survivors are discharged with the so-called Post-Ebola Syndrome. We want to ascertain whether these medical conditions are due to the disease itself, the treatment given or chlorine used during disinfection of the patients. This is a new area for research; little is known about the post-Ebola symptoms.\"<ref name=\"TDR\">{{cite report | url=http://www.who.int/tdr/news/2014/ebola-survival-return/en/ | title=A story of Ebola survival and return | publisher=WHO | date=14 November 2014 | accessdate=5 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/05/03/world/science-health-world/mystery-post-ebola-syndrome-emerges-in-west-africa/#.VVxhJDfbJph|title=Mystery 'post-Ebola syndrome' emerges in West Africa |newspaper=The Japan Times|accessdate=21 May 2015|date=2013-05-10 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, a Sierra Leone physician said about half of the recovered patients she saw reported declining health and that she had seen survivors go blind.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-02-05/doctors-concerned-by-reports-of-post-ebola-syndrome/6073610|title=Ebola outbreak: Doctors warn of 'post-Ebola syndrome' among survivors in West Africa|publisher=ABC News (Australia)|accessdate=5 February 2015|date=2015-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/thousands-ebola-survivors-face-severe-pain-possible-blindness-085148730.html|title=Thousands of Ebola survivors face severe pain, possible blindness|date=8 August 2015|publisher=Yahoo! News|accessdate=9 August 2015}}</ref> In May 2015,  a senior consultant to the WHO said that the reports of eye problems were especially worrying because \"there are hardly any ophthalmologists in Western Africa, and only they have the skills and equipment to diagnose conditions like [[uveitis]] that affect the inner chambers of the eye.\"<ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news|last1=Grady |first1=Denise |title=After Nearly Claiming His Life, Ebola Lurked in a Doctor's Eye |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/08/health/weeks-after-his-recovery-ebola-lurked-in-a-doctors-eye.html?_r=0#story-continues-2 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=6 March 2019 |date=7 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe medical director of a hospital in Liberia reported that he was seeing health problems in patients who had been in recovery for as long as nine months. Problems he was seeing included chronic pain, sometimes so severe that walking was difficult; eye problems, including uveitis; and headaches as the most common physical symptoms. \"They're still very severe and impacting their life every day. These patients will need medical care for months and maybe years.\"  A physician from the Kenema hospital in Sierra Leone reported similar health difficulties.<ref name=\"New York Times\" />\n\nIn December 2014, a British aid worker who had just returned from Sierra Leone was diagnosed with Ebola.  She was treated with survivors' blood plasma and experimental drugs and declared free of disease in January 2015.  However, in October 2015, she again became critically ill and was diagnosed with meningitis.  In this unprecedented case it is thought that the virus remained in her brain replicating at a very low level until it had replicated to a degree capable of causing clinical meningitis. The woman was treated and in November 2015 it was reported that she had recovered.<ref name=\"auto8\" /><ref name=\"davidwilcock\" />\n\nIn terms of medical literature that are reviews, few articles have been published, such as Shantha, et al. which discusses management of panuveitis and iris heterochromia.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shantha |first1=Jessica G. |last2=Crozier |first2=Ian |last3=Yeh |first3=Steven |title=An update on ocular complications of Ebola virus disease |journal=Current Opinion in Ophthalmology |date=November 2017 |volume=28 |issue=6 |pages=600\u2013606 |doi=10.1097/ICU.0000000000000426 |pmid=28872492 |pmc=5988239 |issn=1531-7021}}</ref>\n\n==== Ebola survivor studies ====\n\nAn observational study, done roughly 29 months after the 2007 [[Bundibugyo virus|Bundibugyo]] outbreak in [[Uganda]], found that long-term [[sequelae]] (i.e. consequences) persisted among survivors.  Symptoms included eye pain, blurred vision, hearing loss, difficulty swallowing, difficulty sleeping, arthralgias, memory loss or confusion, and \"various constitutional symptoms controlling for age and sex\".<ref name=\"The Lancet\" />\n\nFrom August through December 2014, a total of 10 patients with Ebola were treated in US hospitals; of these patients, 8 survived.  In March 2015, the CDC interviewed the survivors; they all reported having had at least one adverse symptom during their recovery period. The symptoms ranged from mild (e.g. hair loss) to more severe complications requiring re-hospitalisation or treatment. The most frequently reported symptoms were lethargy or fatigue, joint pain, and hair loss. Sixty-three per cent reported having eye problems including two who were diagnosed with uveitis, 75% reported psychological or cognitive symptoms, and 38% reported neural difficulties. Although most symptoms resolved or improved over time, only one survivor reported complete resolution of all symptoms.<ref name=\"New England Journal of Medicine\">{{cite journal| title=Post-Ebola Signs and Symptoms in U.S. Survivors | journal=New England Journal of Medicine | date=17 December 2015 | doi=10.1056/NEJMc1506576 | pmid=26672870 | volume=373 | issue=25 | pages=2484\u20132486|last1 = Epstein|first1 = Lauren| last2=Wong | first2=Karen K | last3=Kallen | first3=Alexander J | last4=Uyeki | first4=Timothy M }}</ref>\n\nA study published in May 2015 discussed the case of Ian Crozier, a Zimbabwe-born physician and American citizen who became infected with Ebola while he was working at an Ebola treatment centre in Sierra Leone. He was transported to the US and successfully treated at Emory University Hospital. However, after discharge Crozier began to experience symptoms including low back pain, bilateral [[enthesitis]] of the [[Achilles tendon]], [[paresthesias]] involving his lower legs, and eye pain, which was diagnosed as uveitis.  His eye condition worsened and a specimen of [[aqueous humor]] obtained from his eye tested positive for Ebola.  The authors of the study concluded that \"further studies to investigate the mechanisms responsible for the ocular persistence of Ebola and the possible presence of the virus in other [[immune-privileged]] sites (e.g., in the [[central nervous system]], [[gonads]], and [[articular cartilage]]) are warranted.\"  The authors also noted that 40% of participants in a survey of 85 Ebola survivors in Sierra Leone reported having \"eye problems\", though the incidence of actual uveitis was unknown.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Persistence of Ebola Virus in Ocular Fluid during Convalescence |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa1500306|volume=372|issue = 25|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|pages=2423\u20132427|pmid=25950269|date=Jun 2015|pmc=4547451 | last1 = Varkey | first1 = JB | last2 = Shantha | first2 = JG | last3 = Crozier | first3 = I | last4 = Kraft | first4 = CS | last5 = Lyon | first5 = GM | last6 = Mehta | first6 = AK | last7 = Kumar | first7 = G | last8 = Smith | first8 = JR | last9 = Kainulainen | first9 = MH | last10 = Whitmer | first10 = S | last11 = Str\u00f6her | first11 = U | last12 = Uyeki | first12 = TM | last13 = Ribner | first13 = BS | last14 = Yeh | first14 = S|hdl=2328/35704}}</ref>\n\nAnother study, which was released in August 2015 looked at the health difficulties reported by survivors.  Calling the set of symptoms \"post-Ebolavirus disease syndrome\", the research found symptoms that included \"chronic joint and muscle pain, fatigue, anorexia, hearing loss, blurred vision, headache, sleep disturbances, low mood and short-term memory problems\", and suggested the \"implementation of specialised health services to treat and follow-up survivors\".<ref name=\"Carod-Artal\"/>\n\n=== Level of care ===\n[[File:WHO in PPE.jpg|thumb|WHO workers gear up to go to Ebola ward Nigeria, 2014]]\nIn June 2014, it was reported that local authorities did not have the resources to contain the disease, with health centres closing and hospitals becoming overwhelmed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ebola outbreak in West Africa 'out of control,' says MSF |newspaper=Toronto Star|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/2014/06/20/ebola_outbreak_out_of_control_says_msf.html|accessdate=28 October 2016 |date=2014}}</ref> There were also reports that adequate personal protection equipment was not being provided for medical personnel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201406190779.html|title=Liberia: Unheralded Fear \u2013 Ebola Pose Risks for Liberia Health Workers |publisher=FrontPage Africa |via=AllAfrica.com |date=19 June 2014 |accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref> The Director-General of MSF said: \"Countries affected to date simply do not have the capacity to manage an outbreak of this size and complexity on their own. I urge the international community to provide this support on the most urgent basis possible.\"<ref name=\"Control\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/health/west-africa-s-ebola-outbreak-is-totally-out-of-control-1.1878133 |title=Doctors Without Borders: West Africa's Ebola Outbreak is Totally Out of Control |publisher=CTVNews |date=20 June 2014 |accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn late August, MSF called the situation \"chaotic\" and the medical response \"inadequate.\" They reported that they had expanded their operations, but couldn't keep up with the rapidly increasing need for assistance, which had forced them to reduce the level of care: \"It is not currently possible, for example, to administer intravenous treatments.\" Calling the situation \"an emergency within the emergency\", MSF reported that many hospitals had shut down due to lack of staff or fears of the virus among patients and staff, which had left people with other health problems without any care at all. Speaking from a remote region, an MSF worker said that a shortage of protective equipment was making the medical management of the disease difficult and that they had limited capacity to safely bury bodies.<ref name=\"doctorswithoutborders.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorswithoutborders.org/news-stories/field-news/liberia-msfs-new-ebola-management-centers-already-overwhelmed|title=MSF's new Ebola management centers already overwhelmed|publisher=M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|accessdate= 11 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nBy September, treatment for Ebola patients had become unavailable in some areas. Speaking on 12 September, WHO Director-General, Margaret Chan, said: \"In the three hardest hit countries, Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone, the number of new cases is moving far faster than the capacity to manage them in the Ebola-specific treatment centres. Today, there is not one single bed available for the treatment of an Ebola patient in the entire country of Liberia.\"<ref name=\"West African health centres can't keep up with Ebola outbreak, WHO says\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/09/12/health/ebola-outbreak/index.html |title=West African health centers can't keep up with Ebola outbreak, WHO says |publisher=CNN Health |date=12 September 2014 |accessdate=15 September 2014 |author=Payne, Ed}}</ref> According to a WHO report released on 19 September, Sierra Leone was meeting only 35% of its need for patient beds, while for Liberia it was just 20%.<ref name=\"roadmapsitrep4_eng\">{{cite report|url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/133833/1/roadmapsitrep4_eng.pdf?ua=1 |format= PDF|title=Ebola Response Roadmap Situation Report 18 September 2014|publisher=WHO |date=18 September 2014 |accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn early December, the WHO reported that at a national level there were enough beds in treatment facilities to treat and isolate all reported Ebola cases, although their uneven distribution was resulting in serious shortfalls in some areas. Similarly, all affected countries had sufficient and widespread capacity to bury reported deaths; however, because not all deaths were reported, it was possible that the reverse could have been the case in some areas. WHO also reported that every district had access to a laboratory to confirm cases of Ebola within 24 hours of sample collection, and that all three countries had reported that more than 80% of registered contacts associated with known cases of Ebola virus disease were being traced, although contact tracing was still a challenge in areas of intense transmission and those with community resistance.<ref name=WHO2014_12_10 />\n\n=== Healthcare settings ===\n{{fig\n |17\n |Kerry Town Ebola Treatment Centre in Sierra Leone MOD 45158320.jpg\n |Ebola treatment centre built by the UK in Kerry Town, Sierra Leone, in 2014\n |attribution = Carl Osmond/Open Government Licence\n}}\n\nA number of [[Aspen Medical|Ebola Treatment Centres]] were set up in the area, supported by international aid organisations and staffed by a combination of local and international staff. Each treatment centre is divided into a number of distinct and rigorously separate areas. For patients, there is a [[triage]] area, and low- and high-risk care wards. For staff, there are areas for preparation and decontamination. An important part of each centre is an arrangement for safe burial or cremation of bodies, required to prevent further infection.<ref>{{cite news|title=An Ebola treatment center|url=https://apps.washingtonpost.com/g/page/national/an-ebola-treatment-center/1333/|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=1 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|title=Guidance for Safe Handling of Human Remains of Ebola Patients in U. S. Hospitals and Mortuaries|url=https://www.cdc.gov/vhf/ebola/hcp/guidance-safe-handling-human-remains-ebola-patients-us-hospitals-mortuaries.html|publisher=Centers for Disease Control|accessdate=1 October 2014}}</ref>  In January 2015, a new treatment and research centre was built by [[Rusal]] and [[Russia]] in the city of [[Kindia]] in Guinea.  It is one of the most modern medical centres in Guinea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sdelanounas.ru/blogs/57424/#cut|title=\u0412 \u0413\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0435 \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0420\u0423\u0421\u0410\u041b\u043e\u043c \u043c\u0435\u0434\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u043f\u043e \u0431\u043e\u0440\u044c\u0431\u0435 \u0441 \u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u043e\u043c \u042d\u0431\u043e\u043b\u0430 |publisher=Sdelanounas|date=17 January 2015|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rbth.com/news/2015/01/17/russia_opens_ebola_center_in_guinea_42952.html|title=Russia opens Ebola center in Guinea |publisher=Russia Beyond The Headlines|date=17 January 2015|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref>  Also in January, MSF admitted its first patients to a new treatment centre in [[Kissy, Sierra Leone|Kissy]], an Ebola hotspot on the outskirts of Freetown, Sierra Leone. The centre has a maternity unit for pregnant women with the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msf.org/article/sierra-leone-msf-opens-maternity-unit-pregnant-women-ebola|title=Sierra Leone: MSF opens maternity unit for pregnant women with Ebola|publisher=M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|accessdate=30 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ebola: MSF opens new treatment centre in Kissy, Sierra Leone|url=http://www.msf.org.uk/article/ebola-msf-opens-new-treatment-centre-in-kissy-sierra-leone|publisher=M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|accessdate= 11 April 2015|date=2015-01-08}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the WHO does not advise caring for Ebola patients at home, in some cases it became a necessity when no hospital treatment beds were available. For those being treated at home, the WHO advised informing the local public health authority and acquiring appropriate training and equipment.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/faq-ebola/en/|title=Frequently asked questions on Ebola virus disease|publisher=WHO|date=8 August 2014|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/09/25/health/ebola-fatu-family/|title=Woman saves three relatives from Ebola |publisher=CNN | date=26 September 2014 |accessdate=14 October 2014}}</ref> UNICEF, USAID and [[Samaritan's Purse]] began to take measures to provide support for families that were forced to care for patients at home by supplying caregiver kits intended for interim home-based interventions. The kits included protective clothing, hydration items, medicines, and disinfectant, among other items.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samaritanspurse.org/article/hope-takes-flight-across-the-atlantic/|title=Ebola Supplies Arrive in Liberia|publisher=Samaritan's Purse|date=2 October 2014|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberianobserver.com/news/order-contain-ebola-9000-household-kits-arrive/|title=In Order To Contain Ebola 9,000 Household Kits Arrive|publisher=Daily Observer|date=25 September 2014|accessdate=4 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006080427/http://www.liberianobserver.com/news/order-contain-ebola-9000-household-kits-arrive/|archivedate=6 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Even where hospital beds were available, it was debated whether conventional hospitals are the best place to care for Ebola patients, as the risk of spreading the infection is high.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ebola-virus-outbreak/are-hospitals-part-ebola-problem-charity-wants-new-strategy-n202486|title=Are Hospitals Part of the Ebola Problem? Charity Wants New Strategy|publisher=NBC News|date=15 September 2013|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref>  In October, the WHO and non-profit partners launched a program in Liberia to move infected people out of their homes into ad hoc centres that could provide rudimentary care.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/new-effort-to-fight-ebola-in-liberia-would-move-infected-patients-out-of-their-homes/2014/09/22/f869dc08-4281-11e4-b47c-f5889e061e5f_story.html|title=New effort to fight Ebola in Liberia would move infected patients out of their homes|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=22 September 2014|accessdate=2 October 2014|first=Lenny|last=Bernstein}}</ref> Health facilities with low-quality systems for preventing infection were involved as sites of amplification during viral outbreaks.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Youkee|first1=Daniel|last2=Brown|first2=Colin S.|last3=Lilburn|first3=Paul|last4=Shetty|first4=Nandini|last5=Brooks|first5=Tim|last6=Simpson|first6=Andrew|last7=Bentley|first7=Neil|last8=Lado|first8=Marta|last9=Kamara|first9=Thaim B.|last10=Walker|first10=Naomi F.|last11=Johnson|first11=Oliver|title=Assessment of Environmental Contamination and Environmental Decontamination Practices within an Ebola Holding Unit, Freetown, Sierra Leone|journal=PLOS One|date=21 December 2015|volume=10|issue=12|pages=e0145167|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0145167|issn=1932-6203|pmid=26692018|pmc=4687095|bibcode=2015PLoSO..1045167Y}}</ref>\n\n==== Protective clothing ====\n[[File:Donning PPE- Inspect PPE Prior to Donning CDC04.webm|thumb|Examining equipment]]\nThe Ebola epidemic caused an increasing demand for protective clothing. A full set of protective clothing includes a suit, goggles, a mask, socks and boots, and an apron. Boots and aprons can be disinfected and reused, but everything else must be destroyed after use. Health workers change garments frequently, discarding gear that has barely been used. This not only takes a great deal of time but also exposes them to the virus because, for those wearing protective clothing, one of the most dangerous moments for contracting Ebola is while suits are being removed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-29518703|title=How not to catch Ebola |work=BBC News | date=7 October 2014 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe protective clothing sets that MSF uses cost about $75 apiece. Staff who have returned from deployments to Western Africa say the clothing is so heavy that it can be worn for only about 40 minutes at a stretch. A physician working in Sierra Leone has said: \"After about 30 or 40 minutes, your goggles have fogged up; your socks are completely drenched in sweat. You're just walking in water in your boots. And at that point, you have to exit for your own safety&nbsp;... Here it takes 20\u201325 minutes to take off a protective suit and must be done with two trained supervisors who watch every step in a military manner to ensure no mistakes are made, because a slip up can easily occur and of course can be fatal.\"<ref name=\"www.telegraph.co.uk Ebola-medics-better-trained-in-Sierra-Leone-than-Spain\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/10/07/354230895/ebola-protective-suits-are-in-short-supply|title=Ebola Protective Suits Are In Short Supply |publisher=NPR | date=7 October 2014 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref>  By October, there were reports that protective outfits were beginning to be in short supply and manufacturers began to increase their production,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/ebola-enterovirus-flu-fuel-demand-protective-gear/story?id=26070092|title=Ebola Suit Maker Triples Output |publisher=ABC-News | date=9 October 2014 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> but the need to find better types of suits has also been raised.<ref>{{cite news|last1=K|first1=Jayalakshmi|title=Ebola: Usaid Offers More Than Half a Million Pounds for Best Design for Protective Suit|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/ebola-usaid-offers-more-half-million-pounds-best-design-protective-suit-1469594|accessdate=28 October 2016|publisher=International Business Times UK|date=12 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nUSAID published an open competitive bidding for proposals that address the challenge of developing \"...&nbsp;new practical and cost-effective solutions to improve infection treatment and control that can be rapidly deployed; 1) to help health care workers provide better care and 2) transform our ability to combat Ebola\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2014/10/29/innovating-fight-ebola|title=Innovating to Fight Ebola|publisher=The White House \u2013 Office of Science and Technology Policy|date=29 October 2014|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/10/31/obama-ebola-strategy_n_6082454.html|title=Obama Tries A 'Throw Everything Against The Wall' Approach To Ebola|work=The Huffington Post|date=31 October 2014|accessdate=10 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/on-it/usaid-seeks-help-from-maker-movement-in-ebola-outbreak/2014/11/23/1c8d9a4a-6611-11e4-bb14-4cfea1e742d5_story.html|title=USAID seeks help from 'maker movement' in Ebola outbreak|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=24 November 2014|accessdate=26 November 2014|first=Mohana|last=Ravindranath}}</ref> On 12 December 2014, USAID announced the result of the first selection in a press release.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.usaid.gov/news-information/press-releases/dec-12-2014-united-states-announces-results-grand-challenge-fight-ebola|title=United States Announces Results of Grand Challenge to Fight Ebola|publisher=USAID|date=12 December 2014|accessdate=12 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109170809/http://www.usaid.gov/news-information/press-releases/dec-12-2014-united-states-announces-results-grand-challenge-fight-ebola|archivedate=9 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 December 2014, a team at [[Johns Hopkins University]] developed a prototype breakaway hazmat suit, and was awarded a grant from the USAID to develop it. The prototype has a small, battery-powered cooling pack on the worker's belt. \"You'll have air blowing out that is room temperature but it's 0% humidity&nbsp;... the Ebola worker is going to feel cold and will be able to function inside the suit without having to change the suit so frequently\", said one source.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/12/17/371413804/dreaming-up-a-safer-cooler-ppe-for-ebola-fighters |title=Dreaming Up A Safer, Cooler PPE For Ebola Fighters |date=17 December 2014 |publisher=NPR|accessdate=18 December 2014}}</ref> In March, Google developed a tablet that could be cleaned with chlorine; it is charged wirelessly and can transmit information to servers outside the working area.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-31970731|title='Ebola-proof' tablet device developed|work=BBC News|accessdate=21 March 2015|date=2015-03-20|last1=Mundasad|first1=Smitha}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/google-develops-ebolaproof-tablet-for-use-by-workers-in-sierra-leone/535450-11.html|title=Google develops Ebola-proof tablet for use by workers in Sierra Leone|publisher=IBNLive|accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe WHO recommends the use of 2 pairs of gloves, with the outer pair worn over the gown. Using 2 pairs may reduce the risk of sharp injuries; however, there is no evidence that using more than the recommended will give additional protection. WHO also recommends the use of a coverall, which is generally appraised in terms of its resistance to non-enveloped DNA virus. When a gown (or coverall) is worn, it should continue beyond the shoe covers.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=William A. Fischer II |author2=David J. Weber |author3=David A. Wohl  |url=http://www.clinicaltherapeutics.com/article/S0149-2918(15)00935-2/fulltext |title=Personal Protective Equipment: Protecting Health Care Providers in an Ebola Outbreak |journal=Clinical Therapeutics |date=November 1, 2015 |volume=37 |issue=11 |pages=2402\u201310 |doi=10.1016/j.clinthera.2015.07.007 |pmid=26452427 |pmc=4661082 |accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref> According to guidelines released by the CDC in August 2015, updates were put in place to improve the [[Powered air-purifying respirator|PAPR]] doffing method to make the steps easier, and affirm the importance of cleaning the floor where doffing has been done. Additionally, a designated doffing assistant was recommended to help in this process. The order in which boot covers are removed, by these guidelines, indicates their removal ''after'' the coverall or gown. Finally, a trained observer is to read to the healthcare worker each step in donning and doffing, but must ''not'' physically assist therein.<ref>{{cite report|url=https://www.cdc.gov/vhf/ebola/healthcare-us/ppe/guidance.html|title=Guidance on Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) To Be Used By Healthcare Workers during Management of Patients with Confirmed Ebola or Persons under Investigation (PUIs) for Ebola who are Clinically Unstable or Have Bleeding, Vomiting, or Diarrhea in U.S. Hospitals, Including Procedures for Donning and Doffing PPE|publisher=CDC |accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Preparing to enter Ebola treatment unit (3).jpg|thumb|CDC staff preparing to enter ETU in Liberia]]\n\n==== Healthcare workers ====\n\nIn the hardest hit areas there have historically been only one or two doctors available to treat 100,000&nbsp;people, and these doctors are heavily concentrated in urban areas.<ref name=\"WHO20140825\" />  Ebola patients' healthcare providers, as well as family and friends, are at highest risk of getting infected because they are more likely to come in direct contact with their blood or body fluids. In some places affected by the outbreak, care may have been provided in clinics with limited resources, and workers could be in these areas for several hours with a number of Ebola infected patients.<ref name=\"CDC\">{{cite report | url=https://www.cdc.gov/vhf/ebola/hcp/clinician-information-us-healthcare-settings.html | title=Ebola (Ebola Virus Disease) | publisher=CDC | accessdate=28 October 2014}}</ref> According to the WHO, the high proportion of infected medical staff could be explained by a lack of adequate manpower to manage such a large outbreak, shortages of protective equipment or improper use of what was available, and \"the compassion that causes medical staff to work in isolation wards far beyond the number of hours recommended as safe\".<ref name=\"WHO20140825\" />\nIn August 2014, healthcare workers represented nearly 10 per cent of cases and fatalities\u2014significantly impairing the capacity to respond to an outbreak in an area already facing severe shortages.<ref>{{cite report |url=http://www.who.int/dg/speeches/2014/ebola-briefing/en/ |title=WHO Director-General briefs Geneva UN missions on the Ebola outbreak |last=Chan |first=Margaret |publisher=WHO |date=12 August 2014 |accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref> By 1 July 2015, the WHO reported that a total of 874 health workers had been infected, of which 509 had died.<ref name=\"WHO2015_06_27\">{{cite news|url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/177990/1/roadmapsitrep_1Jul2015_eng.pdf?ua=1&ua=1|format= PDF|title=Ebola Situation Report|date=1 July 2015|accessdate =4 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nAmong the fatalities was Samuel Brisbane, a former adviser to the Liberian Ministry of Health and Social Welfare, described as \"one of Liberia's most high-profile doctors\".<ref name=guardian_27_July_2014>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/27/liberia-ebola-first-doctor-dies-brisbane-virus-outbreak |title=Liberia: top doctor becomes latest Ebola victim |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 July 2014 |accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref> In July 2014, leading Ebola doctor [[Sheik Umar Khan]] from Sierra Leone also died in the outbreak.<ref name=\"Fox News\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.africareview.com/News/Another-Sierra-Leone-doctor-contracts-Ebola/-/979180/2414158/-/kfkk7cz/-/index.html |title=Another Sierra Leone doctor contracts Ebola |last=Cham |first=Kemo |publisher=Africa Review |date=10 August 2014 |accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC News\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/health/ebola-infected-doctor-in-sierra-leone-sahr-rogers-dies-1.2748090 |title=Ebola-infected doctor in Sierra Leone, Sahr Rogers, dies |publisher=CBC News |date=27 August 2014 |accessdate=28 August 2014}}</ref> In August, a well-known Nigerian physician, [[Ameyo Adadevoh]], died.<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/08/04/us-health-ebola-nigeria-idUSKBN0G413H20140804|work=Reuters|title=Lagos records second Ebola case in doctor who treated victim: Nigerian health minister|date=4 August 2014 |accessdate= 11 April 2015}}</ref>  Mbalu Fonnie, a licensed nurse-midwife and nursing supervisor at the Kenema hospital in Sierra Leone, with over 30 years of experience, died after contracting Ebola while caring for a fellow nurse who was pregnant and had the disease.  Fonnie was also a co-author of a study that analysed the genetics of the Ebola virus;  five others contracted Ebola and died while working on the same study.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.sciencemag.org/health/2014/08/ebolas-heavy-toll-study-authors | title=Ebola's heavy toll on study authors | publisher=AAAS | date=28 August 2014 | accessdate=12 January 2015 | author=Vogel, Gretchen}}</ref>\n\nBasing their choice on \"the person or persons who most affected the news and our lives, for good or ill, and embodied what was important about the year\", the editors of ''[[Time magazine|Time]]'' magazine in December 2014 named the Ebola health workers as [[Time Person of the Year|Person of the Year]]. Editor Nancy Gibbs said: \"The rest of the world can sleep at night because a group of men and women are willing to stand and fight. For tireless acts of courage and mercy, for buying the world time to boost its defences, for risking, for persisting, for sacrificing and saving, the Ebola fighters are Time's 2014 Person of the Year.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/12/10/world/time-person-of-the-year/ | title=Ebola fighters are Time's 'Person of the Year' | publisher=CNN World | date=10 December 2014 | accessdate=10 December 2014 | author=McLaughlin, Eliott C.}}</ref> According to an October 2015 report by the CDC, Guinean healthcare workers had 42.2 times higher Ebola infection rates than non-healthcare workers, and male healthcare workers were more affected than their female counterparts. The report indicated that 27% of Ebola infections among healthcare workers in Guinea occurred among doctors. The CDC report also stated that the Guinea Ministry of Health recorded males as representing 46% of the health workforce, and that 67% of Ebola infections among non-doctor healthcare workers occurred among males. The CDC further indicated that healthcare workers in Guinea were less likely to report contact with an infected individual than non-healthcare workers.<ref>{{cite report|url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6438a6.htm|title=Ebola Virus Disease in Health Care Workers \u2014 Guinea, 2014|publisher=CDC|accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Experimental treatments and testing ==\n[[File:Biosafety level 4 hazmat suit.jpg|thumb|Researcher working on Ebola virus]]\n{{Further|Ebola virus disease treatment research}}\nThere is as yet no known confirmed medication or treatment for Ebola virus disease.  The director of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases|US National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]] has stated that the scientific community is still in the early stages of understanding how infection with the Ebola virus can be treated and prevented.<ref name=\"Choi2013\">{{cite journal | author = Choi JH, Croyle MA | title = Emerging targets and novel approaches to Ebola virus prophylaxis and treatment | journal = BioDrugs | volume = 27 | issue = 6 | pages = 565\u201383 |date=December 2013 | pmid = 23813435|pmc=3833964| doi = 10.1007/s40259-013-0046-1| last2 = Croyle }}</ref><ref name=Clark_2012>{{cite journal | author = Clark DV, Jahrling PB, Lawler JV | title = Clinical management of filovirus-infected patients | journal = Viruses | volume = 4 | issue = 9 | pages = 1668\u201386 |date=September 2012 | pmid = 23170178 | pmc = 3499825 | doi = 10.3390/v4091668 | last2 = Jahrling | last3 = Lawler }}</ref>\nA number of experimental treatments are undergoing [[clinical trial]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-28663217|publisher=BBC|title=Ebola: The race for drugs and vaccines|date=2015-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ebola virus: Clinical trials of three new treatments for disease to start in West Africa|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/ebola-virus-clinical-trials-of-three-new-treatments-for-disease-to-start-in-west-africa-9857729.html|accessdate=13 November 2014 | location=London|newspaper=The Independent|first=James|last=Rush|date=13 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news-medical.net/news/20150914/Genetic-mutations-in-deadly-Ebola-virus-appear-to-block-antibody-based-treatments.aspx|title=Genetic mutations in deadly Ebola virus appear to block antibody-based treatments|date=14 September 2015|publisher=News-Medical.net|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref>  During the epidemic some patients received experimental [[blood transfusions]] from Ebola survivors, but a later study found that the treatment did not provide significant benefit.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=van Griensven|first1=Johan|last2=Edwards|first2=Tansy|last3=de Lamballerie|first3=Xavier|last4=Semple|first4=Malcolm G.|last5=Gallian|first5=Pierre|last6=Baize|first6=Sylvain|last7=Horby|first7=Peter W.|last8=Raoul|first8=Herv\u00e9|last9=Magassouba|first9=N\u2019Faly|last10=Antierens|first10=Annick|last11=Lomas|first11=Carolyn|last12=Faye|first12=Ousmane|last13=Sall|first13=Amadou A.|last14=Fransen|first14=Katrien|last15=Buyze|first15=Jozefien|last16=Ravinetto|first16=Raffaella|last17=Tiberghien|first17=Pierre|last18=Claeys|first18=Yves|last19=De Crop|first19=Maaike|last20=Lynen|first20=Lutgarde|last21=Bah|first21=Elhadj Ibrahima|last22=Smith|first22=Peter G.|last23=Delamou|first23=Alexandre|last24=De Weggheleire|first24=Anja|last25=Haba|first25=Nyankoye|title=Evaluation of Convalescent Plasma for Ebola Virus Disease in Guinea|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|date=7 January 2016|volume=374|issue=1|pages=33\u201342|doi=10.1056/NEJMoa1511812|pmid=26735992|pmc=5856332|issn=0028-4793}}</ref>\n\nThe effectiveness of potential treatments for any disease is usually assessed in a [[randomised controlled trial]], which compares the outcome of those who received treatment to those who received a [[placebo]] (i.e. dummy treatment).  However, randomised controlled trials are considered unethical when a disease is frequently fatal, as is the case with Ebola. In December 2015, a study was released that found that the viral load found in a patient's blood in the week after the onset of symptoms is a strong indication of the patient's likelihood to die or survive the disease.  The researchers suggested that this information could help to assess the efficacy of proposed treatments more accurately in non-randomised clinical trials.<ref name=\"PLOS Medicine\">{{cite journal| title=Use of Viremia to Evaluate the Baseline Case Fatality Ratio of Ebola Virus Disease and Inform Treatment Studies: A Retrospective Cohort Study | date=1 December 2015 |author1=Oumar Faye |author2=Alessio Andronico |author3=Ousmane Faye |author4=Henrik Salje |author5=Pierre-Yves Bo\u00eblle |author6=N'Faly Magassouba |author7=Elhadj Ibrahima Bah |author8=Lamine Koivogui |author9=Boubacar Diallo |author10=Alpha Amadou Diallo |author11=Sakoba Keita |author12=Mandy Kader Konde |author13=Robert Fowler |author14=Amadou Alpha Sall | doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1001908 | pmid=26625118 | pmc=4666644 | volume=12 |issue = 12| journal=PLOS Medicine | pages=e1001908}}</ref>\n\nEbola control is hindered by the fact that current diagnostic tests require specialised equipment and highly trained personnel. Since there are few suitable testing centres in Western Africa, this delays diagnosis. {{As of | 2015 | 02}} a number of rapid diagnostic tests were under trial.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Ebola Experts Seek to Expand Testing|journal=Nature|volume=516|issue=7530|pages=154\u2013155|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/ebola-experts-seek-to-expand-testing/|accessdate=11 December 2014|bibcode=2014Natur.516..154B|last1=Butler|first1=Declan|year=2014|doi=10.1038/516154a|pmid=25503213}}</ref>  In September 2015, a new chip-based testing method that can detect Ebola accurately was reported.  This new device allows for the use of portable instruments that can provide immediate diagnosis.<ref name=\"Nature Publishing Group\">{{Cite journal | title=Optofluidic analysis system for amplification-free, direct detection of Ebola infection | journal=Scientific Reports | volume=5 | pages=14494 | date=25 September 2015 |author1=H. Cai |author2=J. W. Parks |author3=T. A. Wall |author4=M. A. Stott |author5=A. Stambaugh |author6=K. Alfson |author7=A. Griffiths |author8=R. A. Mathies |author9=R. Carrion |author10=J. L. Patterson |author11=A. R. Hawkins |author12=H. Schmidt | bibcode=2015NatSR...514494C | doi=10.1038/srep14494 | pmid=26404403 | pmc=4585921 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Health_News/2015/09/25/Chip-based-technology-allows-fast-accurate-Ebola-detection/6941443187046/|title=Chip-based technology allows fast, accurate Ebola detection|publisher=UPI|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Vaccines ==\n{{Further|Ebola vaccine}} \nSeveral Ebola [[vaccine]] candidates had been developed in the decade prior to 2014 and had been shown to protect nonhuman primates against infection, but none had yet been approved for clinical use in humans.<ref name=\"Hugues2012\">{{cite journal|date=June 2012|title=Ebolavirus vaccines for humans and apes|journal=Curr Opin Virol|volume=2|issue=3|pages=324\u201329|doi=10.1016/j.coviro.2012.04.003|pmc=3397659|pmid=22560007|vauthors=Fausther-Bovendo H, Mulangu S, Sullivan NJ}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/23/science/ebola-drug-works-against-west-african-strain-in-study-of-monkeys.html?_r=0|title=Ebola Drug Works Against West African Strain in Study of Monkeys|last=Grady|first=Denise|date=22 April 2015|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last2=Davey|first2=Richard|last3=Beck|first3=Allison|last4=Xu|first4=Yongxian|last5=Suffredini|first5=Anthony F.|last6=Palmore|first6=Tara|last7=Kabbani|first7=Sarah|last8=Rogers|first8=Susan|last9=Kobinger|first9=Gary|date=5 March 2015|title=Emergency Postexposure Vaccination With Vesicular Stomatitis Virus\u2013Vectored Ebola Vaccine After Needlestick|journal=JAMA|volume=313|issue=12|pages=1249\u201355|doi=10.1001/jama.2015.1995|last1=Lai|first1=Lilin|last10=Alimonti|first10=Judie|last11=Link|first11=Charles J.|last12=Rubinson|first12=Lewis|last13=Str\u00f6her|first13=Ute|last14=Wolcott|first14=Mark|last15=Dorman|first15=William|last16=Uyeki|first16=Timothy M.|last17=Feldmann|first17=Heinz|last18=Lane|first18=H. Clifford|last19=Mulligan|first19=Mark J.|pmid=25742465|pmc=4874522}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/07/17/health/results-are-in-ebola-vaccine-lyme-disease-als/|title=Results are in: Inhalable Ebola vaccine, Lyme disease|date=17 July 2015|publisher=CNN|first1=Ben |last1=Smart|first2=Liza |last2=Lucas}}</ref> According to a 2015 review article, about 15 different vaccines were in preclinical stages of development, including DNA vaccines, virus-like particles and viral vectors.<ref name=dev/>  and another seven as yet unheard-of vaccines were being developed. Additionally, there were two [[Phases of clinical research|phase III]] studies being conducted with two different vaccines.  .<ref name=dev>{{cite journal | pmc = 4667768 | pmid=26668751 | doi=10.1177/2051013615611017 | volume=3 | issue=5\u20136 | title=Clinical development of Ebola vaccines | year=2015 | journal=Ther Adv Vaccines | pages=125\u201338 | last1 = Sridhar | first1 = S}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, researchers announced that a vaccine trial in Guinea had been completed that appeared to give protection from the virus. The vaccine, [[rVSV-ZEBOV]],<ref name=\"The Journal of Infectious Diseases\">{{cite news| url=http://jid.oxfordjournals.org/content/204/suppl_3/S1066.full | title=Vesicular Stomatitis Virus\u2013Based Ebola Vaccines With Improved Cross-Protective Efficacy | publisher=The Oxford Press | accessdate=1 August 2015}}</ref> had shown high efficacy in individuals, but more conclusive evidence was needed regarding its capacity to protect populations through \"herd immunity\"  .  The vaccine trial employed \"ring vaccination\", a technique that was also used in the 1970s to eradicate [[smallpox]], in which health workers control an outbreak by vaccinating all suspected infected individuals within the surrounding area.<ref name=\"auto4\" /><ref name=\"auto5\" /><ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2015/07/31/428018501/new-ebola-vaccine-has-100-percent-effectiveness-in-early-results|title = New Ebola Vaccine Has '100 Percent' Effectiveness In Early Results|publisher= NPR|date = 31 July 2015|accessdate = 31 July 2015|author = Chappell, Bill}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-vaccine-idUSKCN0UY0OT|title=Vaccines alliance signs $5 million advance deal for Merck's Ebola shot|author1=Ben Hirschler |author2=Kate Kelland |date=20 January 2016|work=Reuters|accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, the results of the two-year Guinea trial were published announcing that rVSV-ZEBOV had been found to protect people who had been exposed to cases of Ebola.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\nOf the nearly 6,000 people vaccinated, none had contracted Ebola after a ten-day period while in the group not vaccinated 23 cases developed. In addition to showing high efficacy among those vaccinated, the trial also showed that unvaccinated people were indirectly protected from Ebola virus through the ring vaccination approach, termed \"herd immunity\". The vaccine has not yet had regulatory approval, but it is considered to be so effective that 300,000 doses have already been stockpiled.  Researchers have found the results \"quite encouraging [but] there is still a lot more work to be done on vaccines for Ebola.\"  Not yet known is the length of time that a vaccination will be effective and whether it will prove effective for the Sudan virus rather than only EBOV, which is responsible for the Western Africa outbreak.<ref name=\"PBS NewsHour\"/><ref name=\"WHO press release\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2016/ebola-vaccine-results/en/ |title=Final trial results confirm Ebola vaccine provides high protection against disease |date=December 23, 2006}}</ref> In April 2018 rVSV-ZEBOV Ebola vaccine was used to stop an outbreak for the first time, the 2018 \u00c9quateur province Democratic Republic of the Congo Ebola virus outbreak, with 3,481 people vaccinated.<ref name=\"who17\">{{Cite news|url=https://reliefweb.int/report/democratic-republic-congo/democratic-republic-congo-ebola-virus-disease-external-situation-14|title=Democratic Republic of Congo: Ebola Virus Disease - External Situation Report 17: Declaration of End of Ebola Virus Disease Outbreak|publisher=ReliefWeb|access-date=26 July 2018|language=en}}</ref> rVSV-ZEBOV received regulatory approval in 2019.<ref name=EMA_ZEBOV /><ref name=FDA_ZEBOV />\n\n== Outlook ==\n\nFrom the beginning of the outbreak, there existed considerable difficulty in getting reliable estimates\u2014both of the number of people affected and of its geographical extent.<ref name=WHO22August>{{cite report|title=Why the Ebola outbreak has been underestimated|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/ebola/22-august-2014/en/|publisher=WHO|accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref> The three most affected countries\u2014Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone\u2014are among the poorest in the world, with extremely low levels of literacy, few hospitals or doctors, low-quality physical infrastructure, and weakly functioning government institutions.<ref>{{cite web|title=West & Central Africa \u2013 Information by Country|url=http://www.unicef.org/infobycountry/centralafrica.html|publisher=UNICEF|accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref> One study yielded results of the spatio-temporal evolution of the viral outbreak. With the use of [[heat maps]], it was determined that the outbreak did not uniformly unfold over the affected community areas. Growth in the regions of Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone was very different over time, indicating that monitoring the outbreak at district level was important. Visual inspection of incidence curves alone could not render the needed results or data; growth rates with a two-dimensional heat map were used. Finally, the study showed that accurate predictions of growth were improbable, coupled with knowledge about the disease that was not fully adequate at the time (as there were now cases of sexual transmission).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Santermans|first1=Eva|last2=Robesyn|first2=Emmanuel|last3=Ganyani|first3=Tapiwa|last4=Sudre|first4=Bertrand|last5=Faes|first5=Christel|last6=Quinten|first6=Chantal|last7=Bortel|first7=Wim Van|last8=Haber|first8=Tom|last9=Kovac|first9=Thomas|last10=Reeth|first10=Frank Van|last11=Testa|first11=Marco|last12=Hens|first12=Niel|last13=Plachouras|first13=Diamantis|title=Spatiotemporal Evolution of Ebola Virus Disease at Sub-National Level during the 2014 West Africa Epidemic: Model Scrutiny and Data Meagreness|journal=PLOS One|date=15 January 2016|volume=11|issue=1|pages=e0147172|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147172|issn=1932-6203|pmid=26771513|pmc=4714854|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147172S}}</ref>\n\n=== Statistical measures ===\nCalculating the ''[[case fatality rate]]'' (CFR) accurately is difficult in an ongoing epidemic due to differences in testing policies, the inclusion of probable and suspected cases, and the inclusion of new cases that have not run their course. In August 2014, the WHO made an initial CFR estimate of 53%, though this included suspected cases.<ref name=epi-fatal-rate>{{cite news|author=Rambaut, Andrew |title=Case Fatality Rate for ebolavirus |url=http://epidemic.bio.ed.ac.uk/ebolavirus_fatality_rate |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140829075833/http://epidemic.bio.ed.ac.uk/ebolavirus_fatality_rate |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 August 2014 |date=7 August 2014 |publisher=Epidemic |accessdate=16 September 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"WHO_31Aug\">{{cite report|url=http://who.int/csr/don/2014_09_04_ebola/en/|title=Ebola Response Roadmap Situation Report 2, 5 September 2014|publisher=WHO|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> In September and December 2014, the WHO released revised and more accurate CFR figures of 70.8% and 71% respectively, using data from patients with definitive clinical outcomes.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"cfrebolavirus\" /><ref name=WHO2014_12_28 /> The CFR among hospitalised patients, based on the three intense-transmission countries, was between 57% and 59% in January 2015.<ref name=\"WHOreport\" />\n\n''Mortality'' is measured by number of deaths in a population per the proportion of the population per unit of time.<ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Porta|editor-first=M|title=A Dictionary of Epidemiology| chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=okf1AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA69|year=2014|edition=5th|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford| isbn=978-0-19-939005-2|page=69|chapter=Death rate}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[basic reproduction number]]'', ''R''<sub>0</sub>, is a statistical measure of the average number of people expected to be infected by one person who has a disease. If the rate is less than 1, the infection dies out; if it is greater than 1, the infection continues to spread\u2014with exponential growth in the number of cases.<ref>{{cite web|title=Basic Reproductive Rate (Ro)|url=http://practice.sph.umich.edu/micphp/epicentral/basic_reproduc_rate.php|publisher=University of Michigan|accessdate=16 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104222957/http://practice.sph.umich.edu/micphp/epicentral/basic_reproduc_rate.php|archive-date=4 November 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In September 2014, the estimated ''R''<sub>0</sub> were 1.71 (95%&nbsp;[[confidence interval|CI]], 1.44 to 2.01) for Guinea, 1.83 (95%&nbsp;CI, 1.72 to 1.94) for Liberia, and 2.02 (95%&nbsp;CI, 1.79 to 2.26) for Sierra Leone.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Althaus|first1=Christian L.|title=Estimating the Reproduction Number of Ebola Virus (EBOV) During the 2014 Outbreak in West Africa|journal=PLOS Currents|date=2014|doi=10.1371/currents.outbreaks.91afb5e0f279e7f29e7056095255b288|pmid=25642364|volume=6|pmc=4169395|bibcode=2014arXiv1408.3505A|arxiv=1408.3505}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hunt|first1=Allen G.|title=Exponential growth in Ebola outbreak since May 14, 2014|journal=Complexity|date=11 October 2014|volume=20|issue=2|pages=8\u201311|doi=10.1002/cplx.21615|bibcode=2014Cmplx..20b...8H}}</ref>\nIn October 2014, the WHO noted that exponential increase of cases continued in the three countries with the most intense transmission.<ref name=WHOvirtualpress>{{cite report|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/multimedia/vpc-23-october-2014.pdf?ua=1 |format= PDF|title=WHO Virtual Press Conference on the third meeting of the International Health Regulations Emergency Committee regarding the 2014 Ebola outbreak in West Africa|publisher=WHO|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Projections of future cases ===\n\nOn 28 August 2014, the WHO released its first estimate of the possible total cases from the outbreak as part of its road map for stopping the transmission of the virus. It stated that \"this Roadmap assumes that in many areas of intense transmission the actual number of cases may be two- to fourfold higher than that currently reported. It acknowledges that the aggregate case load of Ebola could exceed 20,000 over the course of this emergency. The Roadmap assumes that a rapid escalation of the complementary strategies in intense transmission, resource-constrained areas will allow the comprehensive application of more standard containment strategies within three months.\" The report included an assumption that some country or countries would pay the required cost of their plan, estimated at half a billion US dollars.<ref name=res/>\n\nWhen the WHO released these estimates, a number of epidemiologists presented data to show that the WHO projection of a total of 20,000 cases was likely an underestimate.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kupferschmidt|first1=Kai|title=Disease modelers project a rapidly rising toll from Ebola|url=http://news.sciencemag.org/health/2014/08/disease-modelers-project-rapidly-rising-toll-ebola|publisher=Science (news)|accessdate= 11 April 2015|date=2014-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Early Transmission Dynamics of Ebola Virus Disease (EVD), West Africa, March to August 2014 |journal=Eurosurveillance | date=11 September 2014 | author=Nishiura, H | author2=Chowell, G | volume=19 | issue=36 |pages=20894 |doi=10.2807/1560-7917.ES2014.19.36.20894 |pmid=25232919 }}</ref> On 9 September, Jonas Schmidt-Chanasit of the [[Bernhard Nocht Institute for Tropical Medicine]] in Germany, controversially announced that the containment fight in Sierra Leone and Liberia had already been \"lost\" and that the disease would \"burn itself out\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Virologist: Fight against Ebola in Sierra Leone and Liberia is lost|url=http://www.dw.de/virologist-fight-against-ebola-in-sierra-leone-and-liberia-is-lost/a-17915090|date=11 September 2014|accessdate=11 September 2014|publisher=Deutsche Welle}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 September 2014, the WHO revised their previous projection, stating that they expected the number of Ebola cases in Western Africa to be in excess of 20,000 by 2 November 2014.<ref name=\":1\" /> They further stated, that if the disease was not adequately contained it could become native in Guinea, Sierra Leone and Liberia, \"spreading as routinely as malaria or the flu\",<ref>{{cite news|last1=Szabo|first1=Liz|title=Could the Ebola outbreak last forever?|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/09/22/ebola-last-forever/16072019/|newspaper=USA Today|accessdate=22 September 2014|date=22 September 2014}}</ref> and according to an editorial in the [[New England Journal of Medicine]], eventually to other parts of Africa and beyond.<ref name=\"The Ebola Emergency \u2014 Immediate Action, Ongoing Strategy\">{{cite journal|title=The Ebola Emergency \u2014 Immediate Action, Ongoing Strategy |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |author=Farrar, Jeremy J. |date=23 September 2014 |doi=10.1056/NEJMe1411471 |pmid=25244185 |volume=371 |issue = 16|pages=1545\u20131546|url=https://researchonline.lshtm.ac.uk/1947014/1/nejme1411471.pdf }}</ref>\n\nIn a report released on 23 September 2014, the CDC analysed the impact of under-reporting, which required correction of case numbers by a factor of up to 2.5. With this correction factor, approximately 21,000 total cases were estimated for the end of September 2014 in Liberia and Sierra Leone alone. The same report predicted that total cases, including unreported cases, could reach 1.4 million in Liberia and Sierra Leone by the end of January 2015 if no improvement in intervention or community behaviour occurred.<ref name=\"CDC Estimating future number of cases\" /> However, at a congressional hearing on 19 November, the Director of the CDC said that the number of Ebola cases was no longer expected to exceed 1 million, moving away from the [[worst-case scenario]] that had been previously predicted.<ref>{{cite news|title=Overnight Health: Congress begs for attention on Ebola|url=http://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/overnights/224766-overnight-health-congress-begs-for-attention-on-ebola|newspaper=The Hill|accessdate=20 November 2014|date=2014-11-19}}</ref>\n\nA study published in December 2014 found that transmission of the Ebola virus occurs principally within families, in hospitals and at funerals. The data, gathered during three weeks of contact tracing in August, showed that the third person in any transmission chain often knew both the first and second person. The authors estimated that between 17% and 70% of cases in Western Africa were unreported\u2014far fewer than had been estimated in prior projections. The study concluded that the epidemic would not be as difficult to control as feared, if rapid, vigorous contact tracing and quarantines were employed.<ref name=NYT_fewer_unreported>{{cite news|title=Fewer Ebola Cases Go Unreported Than Thought, Study Finds|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/16/science/fewer-ebola-cases-go-unreported-than-thought-study-finds-.html?_r=0|date=16 December 2014 |accessdate= 11 April 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|first=Donald G.|last=McNeil Jr}}</ref>\n\nProjections of future cases should also reflect the possibility that [[deforestation]] might have a hand in terms of the more recent Ebola outbreaks. It has been suggested that due to the clearing of forest for commercial use, various types of bats namely '' fruit bats'' may be taken out of their natural habitat and therefore into closer and potential contact with civilisation.<ref name=\"defor2\">{{cite journal |last1=Nasi |first1=Robert |last2=Sheil |first2=Douglas |last3=Leendertz |first3=Siv Aina |last4=King |first4=Shona |last5=Suter |first5=Jamison |last6=Park |first6=Douglas |last7=Salim |first7=Mohammad A. |last8=Gaveau |first8=David |last9=Vargas |first9=J. Mario |last10=Farf\u00e1n |first10=Miguel A. |last11=M\u00e1rquez |first11=Ana L. |last12=Real |first12=Raimundo |last13=Fa |first13=John E. |last14=Olivero |first14=Jes\u00fas |title=Recent loss of closed forests is associated with Ebola virus disease outbreaks |journal=Scientific Reports |date=30 October 2017 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=14291 |doi=10.1038/s41598-017-14727-9 |pmid=29085050 |pmc=5662765 |language=en |issn=2045-2322|bibcode=2017NatSR...714291O }}</ref><ref name=\"defor\">{{cite journal |last1=D\u2019Odorico |first1=Paolo |last2=Hayman |first2=David T. S. |last3=Santini |first3=Monia |last4=Rulli |first4=Maria Cristina |title=The nexus between forest fragmentation in Africa and Ebola virus disease outbreaks |journal=Scientific Reports |date=14 February 2017 |volume=7 |pages=41613 |doi=10.1038/srep41613 |pmid=28195145 |pmc=5307336 |language=en |issn=2045-2322|bibcode=2017NatSR...741613R }}</ref>\n\n== Economic effects ==\n[[File:UNDG.gif|thumb|UNDG, improves efficiency in needing countries]]\nIn addition to the loss of life, the outbreak had a number of significant economic impacts.  In March 2015, the United Nations Development Group reported that due to a decrease in trade, closing of borders, flight cancellations, and drop in foreign investment and tourism activity fuelled by stigma, the epidemic resulted in vast economic consequences both in the affected areas and throughout Africa.<ref name=\"auto2\" />  A September 2014 report in the ''[[Financial Times]]'' suggested that the economic impact of the Ebola outbreak could kill more people than the disease itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australiannews.net/index.php/sid/225466201|publisher=Australian News.Net|title=IMF says Ebola impacted West African nations may need economic assistance}}</ref>\n\nWith regard to Ebola and economic activity in the country of Liberia, a study found that 8% of automotive firms, 8% of construction firms, 15% of food businesses and 30% of restaurants had closed due to the Ebola outbreak. Montserrado county experienced up to 20% firm closure. This indicated a decline in the Liberian national economy during the outbreak, as well as an indication that the county of Montserrado was hardest hit economically. The capital city Monrovia suffered construction and restaurant unemployment the most, while outside the capital, the food and beverage sectors suffered economically. A recuperation in the economy, at the end of the outbreak, was expected to be more rapid in some sectors than in others. Also, if the massive decline in economic activity persisted, the authors suggested a focus on economic recovery in addition to support for the healthcare system. The [[World Bank]] had projected an estimated loss of $1.6 billion in productivity for all three affected Western African countries combined for 2015. In Liberian counties that were less affected by the outbreak, the number of individuals employed fell by 24%. Montserrado saw a 47% decline in employment per firm in contrast to what was obtained prior to the Ebola outbreak.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://jech.bmj.com/content/early/2015/10/05/jech-2015-205959.full|title=Ebola, jobs and economic activity in Liberia|journal=Journal of Epidemiology and Community Health|volume=70|issue=3|pages=271\u2013277|author=Jeremy Bowles|accessdate=27 January 2016|doi=10.1136/jech-2015-205959|pmid=26438188|pmc=4789821|year=2016}}</ref>\n\nAnother study showed that the economic effect of the Ebola outbreak would be felt for years due to preexisting [[social vulnerability]]. The economic effects were being felt nationwide in Liberia, such as the termination of expansions in the mining business. Initial scenarios had placed expected economic losses at $25 billion; however subsequent World Bank estimates were much lower, at about 12% of the combined [[GDP]] of the 3 worst hit countries.<ref name=\"stanturf\">{{cite journal|last1=Stanturf|first1=John A.|last2=Goodrick|first2=Scott L.|last3=Jr|first3=Melvin L. Warren|last4=Charnley|first4=Susan|last5=Stegall|first5=Christie M.|title=Social Vulnerability and Ebola Virus Disease in Rural Liberia|journal=PLOS One|date=1 September 2015|volume=10|issue=9|pages=e0137208|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0137208|issn=1932-6203|pmid=26325519|pmc=4556488|bibcode=2015PLoSO..1037208S}}</ref> The authors went on to state that social vulnerability has multiple factors and proposed a classification based on multiple variables instead of single indicators such as food insecurity or lack of hospitals, which were problems faced by rural Liberians. In spite of the end of civil violence since 2003 and inflows from international donors, the reconstruction of Liberia had been very slow and non-productive\u2014water delivery systems, sanitation facilities and centralised electricity were practically non-existent, even in Monrovia. Even before the outbreak, medical facilities did not have potable water, lighting or refrigeration. The authors indicated that lack of food and other economic effects would probably continue in the rural population long after the Ebola outbreak had ended.<ref name=\"stanturf\" />\n\nOther economic impacts were as follows:\n* In August 2014 it was reported that many airlines had suspended flights to the area.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mark Anderson|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/aug/22/ebola-airlines-cancel-flights-guinea-liberia-sierra-leone|title=Ebola: airlines cancel more flights to affected countries|newspaper=The Guardian |date=22 August 2014|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>  Markets and shops had closed due to travel restrictions, a ''cordon sanitaire'', or fear of human contact, which led to loss of income for producers and traders.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/07/17/332351578/ebola-wreaks-economic-woe-in-west-africa |title=Ebola Wreaks Economic Woe In West Africa |publisher=NPR |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n* Movement of people away from affected areas disturbed agricultural activities.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lomax |first=Selma |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201408200742.html |title=Liberia: Ebola Outbreak Affects Agriculture in Lofa County |publisher=allAfrica.com |date=20 August 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"rappler1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rappler.com/world/regions/africa/67128-who-un-first-staff-ebola-infection |title=First WHO worker infected by Ebola, DR Congo reports cases |work=Rappler.com |date=15 August 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> The FAO warned that the outbreak could endanger harvests and food security in Western Africa,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/09/02/us-health-ebola-food-idUKKBN0GX0HB20140902 |title=Ebola threatens food security in West Africa: FAO |accessdate=3 September 2014 | work=Reuters |date=2 September 2014}}</ref> and that with all the quarantines and movement limitations placed on them, more than 1 million people could be food insecure by March 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voanews.com/content/ebola-food-security-17dec14/2562832.html|title=Ebola Threatens Millions With Food Insecurity|publisher=VOA|accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref> By 29 July, the World Bank had given 10,500 tons of maize and rice seed to the 3 hardest-hit countries to help them to rebuild their agricultural systems.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Business/The-Bite/2015/0729/How-West-Africa-is-ramping-up-food-security-after-Ebola-outbreak|title=How West Africa is ramping up food security after Ebola outbreak|journal=Christian Science Monitor|author=The Christian Science Monitor|publisher=The Christian Science Monitor|accessdate=10 August 2015|date=2015-07-29}}</ref>\n* Tourism was directly impacted in the affected countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://afkinsider.com/69855/ebola-virus-eats-west-africas-economic-growth/ |title=Ebola Virus Eats Into West Africa's Economic Growth |publisher=AFKInsider |date=21 August 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> In April 2014, Nigeria reported that 75% of hotel business had been lost due to fears of the outbreak;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnbcafrica.com/video/?bctid=3807923516001 |title= Impact of Ebola on e-commerce in Nigeria|publisher=CNBC Africa}}</ref>  the limited Ebola outbreak had cost that country [[naira|\u20a6]]8 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201504230728.html|title=Nigeria: Lagos Hotels Lose N8 Billion Over Ebola Outbreak|publisher=allAfrica.com|accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref>  Other African countries that were not directly affected by the virus also reported adverse effects on tourism.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brock |first=Joe |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/08/20/us-health-ebola-africatourism-idUKKBN0GK1GG20140820 |title=Ebola fears slowing tourist flow to Africa |work=Reuters |date=20 August 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnbcafrica.com/video/?bctid=3807923516001|title=Video: Impact of Ebola on e-commerce in Nigeria|publisher=CNBC Africa|accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2014/09/mixed-grill-businesses-ebola-impacts-economy/|title=Mixed grill for businesses as Ebola impacts economy|publisher=Vanguard News|accessdate=16 December 2014|date=2014-09-15}}</ref> For example, in 2015, it was reported that Gambia's tourism had fallen below 50 per cent of its normal business during the same period the prior year,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-30495101|title=The Gambia's tourist industry reels from Ebola fallout|work=BBC News|accessdate=13 January 2015|date=2015-01-07|last1=Williams|first1=Briohny}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spyghana.com/ebola-scares-tourist-from-cape-coast-castle-in-2014/|title=Ebola scares tourist from Cape Coast Castle in 2014|author=Ghana News Agency|publisher=spyghana.com|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> Elmina Bay in Ghana had an 80% decrease in US tourism,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanosphere.org/social-business/2015/05/tourists-abandon-ghana-despite-its-successes-against-ebola/|title=Tourists abandon Ghana despite its successes against Ebola|author=Tom Murphy|publisher=Humanosphere|accessdate=10 May 2015|date=May 2015}}</ref> and Kenya,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/business/article/2000154024/ktb-releases-sh140-million-for-tourism-campaigns|title=Kenya Tourism Board releases Sh140 million for tourism campaigns|date=8 March 2015|publisher=Standard Digital News|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> Zimbabwe,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestandard.co.zw/2015/03/29/tourism-receipts-down-3/|title=Tourism receipts down 3%|newspaper=The Standard|accessdate=10 April 2015|date=2015-03-29}}</ref>  Senegal, Zambia, and Tanzania also reported a drop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2015-04-15-africa-travel-week-focuses-on-sustainable-tourism|title=Africa Travel Week focuses on sustainable tourism|author=Sharon Gilbert-Rivett|publisher=The M&G Online|accessdate=16 April 2015|date=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n* Some foreign mining companies withdrew all non-essential personnel, deferred new investment, and cut back operations.<ref name=\"rappler1\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-27675747 |title=UK employees leave Sierra Leone over Ebola threat |work=BBC News |date=3 June 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mining.com/west-africa-ebola-outbreak-forces-miners-to-lock-down-operations-delay-projects-69246/ |title=West Africa Ebola outbreak forces miners to lock down operations, delay projects |publisher=MINING.com |date=10 August 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> In December 2014, it was reported that the iron ore mining company, African Minerals, had started the shutdown of its Sierra Leone operations because it was running low on income.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theafricareport.com/West-Africa/mining-african-minerals-begins-shutdown-of-sierra-leone-assets-as-ebola-effect-hits.html|title=Mining: African Minerals begins shutdown of Sierra Leone assets as Ebola effect hits|author=Jun Feng|publisher=The Africa Report |accessdate=21 December 2014|date=December 2014}}</ref> In March 2015, it was reported that Sierra Leone had begun to diversify away from mining, due to the country's recent problems.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2015/mar/10/ebola-crisis-sierra-leone-diversify-mining-economy|title=Ebola crisis could force Sierra Leone to diversify economy away from mining \u2013 Cl\u00e1r N\u00ed Chonghaile|author=Cl\u00e1r N\u00ed Chonghaile|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=27 March 2015|date=2015-03-10}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, [[Oxfam]], a UK-based disaster relief organisation, indicated that a \"[[Marshall Plan]]\" (a reference to the massive plan to rebuild Europe after [[World War&nbsp;II]]) was needed so that countries could begin to financially assist those that had been worst hit by the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-30995631|title=Ebola crisis: Oxfam calls for recovery Marshall Plan|work=BBC News|accessdate=27 January 2015|date=2015-01-27}}</ref>  The call was repeated in April 2015 when the most-affected Western African countries asked for an $8 billion \"Marshall Plan\" to rebuild their economies.  Speaking at the World Bank and the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF), Liberian president Ellen Johnson Sirleaf said the amount was needed because \"[o]ur health systems collapsed, investors left our countries, revenues declined and spending increased.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/news/667165-ebola-hit-countries-call-for-8-bn-aid-plan.html|title=Ebola-hit countries call for $8 bn aid plan|publisher=newvision.co.ug|accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe IMF has been criticised for its lack of assistance in the efforts to combat the epidemic.  In December 2014, a [[Cambridge University]] study linked IMF policies with the financial difficulties that prevented a strong Ebola response in the three most heavily affected countries,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/ebola/11307252/IMF-policies-blamed-for-weak-Ebola-response.html|title=IMF policies blamed for weak Ebola response|date=22 December 2014|newspaper=The Telegraph |accessdate=23 December 2014|location=London}}</ref> and they were urged by both the UN and NGOs who had worked in the affected countries to grant debt relief rather than low-interest loans. According to one advocacy group, \"...&nbsp;yet the IMF, which has made a $9 billion surplus from its lending over the last three years, is considering offering loans, not debt relief and grants, in response\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessghana.com/portal/news/index.php?op=getNews&id=202154|title=Ghana, Business Advice, Jobs, News, Business Directory, Real Estate, Finance, Forms, Auto|publisher=Business Ghana |accessdate=20 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/africa/2014/12/31/imf-under-pressure-to-cancel-ebola-hit-countries-debts|title=IMF under pressure to cancel Ebola-hit countries' debts|author=AFP|publisher=Times LIVE|accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref> On 30 January 2015, the IMF reported it was close to reaching a deal on debt forgiveness.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/topNews/idAFKBN0L31AL20150130|title=IMF hopes for deal soon on debt forgiveness for Ebola countries|work=Reuters |accessdate=3 February 2015|date=30 January 2015}}</ref> On 22 December, it was reported that the IMF had given Liberia an additional $10 million due to the economic impact of the Ebola virus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicfinanceinternational.org/news/2015/12/imf-increases-support-liberian-economy-following-ebola-outbreak|title=IMF increases support to Liberian economy following Ebola outbreak|publisher=Public Finance International |accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, a World Bank report estimated overall economic impacts of between $3.8 billion and $32.6 billion, depending on the extent of the outbreak and speed of containment. It expected the most severe losses in the three affected countries, with a wider impact across the broader Western African region.<ref>{{cite news|title=World Bank rings alarm over \u00a320bn worst-case Ebola scenario|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/economics/11149117/World-Bank-rings-alarm-over-20bn-worst-case-Ebola-scenario.html|newspaper=The Telegraph|accessdate=8 October 2014|location=London|first=James|last=Titcomb|date=8 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=New World Bank Group Study Forecasts Billions in Economic Loss|url=http://www.worldbank.org/en/news/press-release/2014/10/08/ebola-new-world-bank-group-study-forecasts-billions-in-economic-loss-if-epidemic-lasts-longer-spreads-in-west-africa|publisher=World Bank|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>  On 13 April 2015, the World Bank said that they would soon announce a major new effort to rebuild the economies of the three hardest-hit countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201504131122.html|title=Liberia: Rebuilding Ebola-Hit Economy \u2013 Focus of World Bank Spring Event|publisher=allAfrica.com|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref> On 23 July, a World Bank poll warned that \"we are not ready for another Ebola outbreak\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/3967662/world-bank-ebola-epidemics/|title='We Are Not Prepared For Another Epidemic': World Bank Survey|author=Alexandra Sifferlin|magazine=Time|accessdate=3 August 2015|date=23 July 2015}}</ref> On 15 December, the World Bank indicated that by 1 December 2015, it had marshalled $1.62 billion in financing for the Ebola outbreak response.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.worldbank.org/en/topic/health/brief/world-bank-group-ebola-fact-sheet | title=World Bank Group Ebola Response Fact Sheet | date=15 December 2015 | publisher=World Bank | accessdate=20 December 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn 6 July 2015, UN Secretary-General [[Ban Ki-moon]] announced that he would host an Ebola recovery conference to raise funds for reconstruction, stating that the three countries hardest hit by Ebola needed about $700 million to rebuild their health services over a two-year period.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/07/06/us-health-ebola-funding-idUSKCN0PG29E20150706|title=Ebola-stricken nations need $700 million to rebuild healthcare|work=Reuters|accessdate=8 July 2015|first=Daniel|last=Flynn|date=6 July 2015}}</ref> On 10 July, it was announced that the countries most affected by the Ebola epidemic would receive $3.4 billion to rebuild their economies.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ebola-Hit Countries Get Pledges of $3.4 Billion to Rebuild - ABC News |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/ebola-hit-countries-appeal-32-billion-rebuild-32360498 |accessdate=27 March 2019 |work=web.archive.org |date=11 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711224812/http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/ebola-hit-countries-appeal-32-billion-rebuild-32360498 |archive-date=11 July 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/donors-pledge-3-4-billion-for-ebola-recovery-plan-1436642289|title=Donors Pledge $3.4 Billion for Ebola Recovery Plan|author=Betsy McKay|date=11 July 2015|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> On 29 September, the leaders of both Sierra Leone and Liberia indicated at the [[UN General Assembly]] the launch of a \"Post-Ebola Economic Stabilization and Recovery Plan\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=52049#.VhED7jZdFpj|title=United Nations News Centre|date=29 September 2015|publisher=UN News Service Section|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> On 24 November, it was reported that due to the decrease in commodity prices and the Western African Ebola epidemic, [[Africa\u2013China relations|China's investment]] in the continent had declined 43% in the first 6&nbsp;months of 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/business/economy/china-s-investment-in-africa-down-43-1.2440899|title=China's investment in Africa down 43%|date=24 November 2015|newspaper=The Irish Times|accessdate=7 December 2015}}</ref> On 25 January, the IMF projected a GDP growth of 0.3% for Liberia, that country indicating it would cut spending by 11 per cent due to a stagnation in the mining sector, which would cause a domestic revenues drop of $57 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/liberia-budget-idUSL8N1594SV|title=Update 1 \u2013 Liberia to slash spending 11 pct amid mining slowdown|date=25 January 2016|work=Reuters |accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Responses ==\n\n{{Further|Responses to the Ebola virus epidemic in West Africa}}\n\nIn July 2014, the WHO convened an emergency meeting of health ministers from eleven countries and announced collaboration on a strategy to co-ordinate technical support to combat the epidemic. In August they published a road map to guide and coordinate the international response to the outbreak, aiming to stop ongoing Ebola transmission worldwide within 6\u20139 months, and formally designated the outbreak as a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]].<ref name=WHO_PHEIC_8Aug2014 /> This is a legal designation used only twice before (for the [[2009 flu pandemic|2009 H1N1 (swine flu) pandemic]] and the 2014 resurgence of poliomyelitis) that invokes legal measures on disease prevention, surveillance, control, and response, by 194 signatory countries.<ref name=\"Reuters20k\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/08/28/us-health-ebola-who-plan-idUSKBN0GS0XC20140828|title=WHO says Ebola outbreak could strike 20,000 people|work=Reuters|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=28 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"urlInside Justice-WHO-PHEIC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.insidejustice.com/intl/2009/04/30/swine_flu_who_pheic/ |publisher=Inside Justice |title=Swine Flu: Legal Obligations and Consequences When the WHO Declares a \"Public Health Emergency of International Concern\" |first=Ren\u00e9e |last=Dopplick |date=29 April 2009 |accessdate=6 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, the [[United Nations Security Council]] declared the Ebola virus outbreak in Western Africa \"a threat to international peace and security\" and unanimously adopted a resolution urging UN member states to provide more resources to fight the outbreak.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-29262968|title=Ebola 'threat to world security'- UN Security Council|date=18 September 2014|work=BBC News|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/217853-who-warns-ebola-to-cost-to-1-billion |title=WHO warns Ebola response could cost $1B|newspaper=The Hill |date=16 September 2014 |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>  In October, WHO and the UN Mission for Ebola Emergency Response announced a comprehensive 90-day plan to control and reverse the Ebola epidemic. The ultimate goal was to have capacity in place for the isolation of 100% of Ebola cases and the safe burial of 100% of casualties by 1 January 2015 (the 90-day target).<ref>{{cite report|title=Ebola Response Roadmap Situation Report 15 October 2014|url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/136508/1/roadmapsitrep15Oct2014.pdf?ua=1 |format= PDF|publisher=WHO|accessdate=29 October 2014|page=5}}</ref> Many nations and charitable organisations cooperated to realise the plan,<ref>{{cite web|title=Global Response|url=https://www.un.org/ebolaresponse/response.shtml|publisher=United Nations Mission for Ebola Emergency Response|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> and a WHO situation report published mid-December indicated that the international community was on track to meet the 90-day target.<ref>{{cite report|title=Ebola response roadmap situation report 17 December 2014|url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/situation-reports/en/?m=20141217|publisher=WHO|accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, Dr Margaret Chan indicated, \"demands on WHO were more than ten times greater than ever experienced in the almost 70-year history of this Organization\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.internationalsos.com/ebola/index.cfm?content_id=407&language_id=ENG|title=Ebola|publisher=internationalsos.com|accessdate=22 May 2015}}</ref><ref>Bruce-Cunning, Nick. (18 May 2015). [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/19/world/africa/who-leader-outlines-changes-response-ebola-epidemic.html?_r=0 WHO Leader Outlines Changes in Response to Ebola Epidemic]. ''The New York Times''.</ref> and on 23 March, she stated that \"the world remains woefully ill-prepared to respond to outbreaks that are both severe and sustained.\"<ref>{{cite report|title=WHO Director-General addresses high-level conference on global health security|url=http://www.who.int/dg/speeches/2016/global-health-security/en/|publisher=WHO|accessdate=28 October 2016|ref=WHO}}</ref>\n\n=== Criticism of WHO ===\n[[File:Flag of WHO.svg|thumb|WHO flag]]\nThere was significant criticism of the [[WHO]] from some aid agencies because its response was perceived as slow and insufficient, especially during the early stages of the outbreak.<ref name=\"AP News\" /><ref name=\"uk.reuters.com\">{{cite news|title=Aid workers ask where was WHO in Ebola outbreak|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/10/05/us-health-ebola-who-idUKKCN0HU03Q20141005|work=Reuters|accessdate=5 October 2014|date=5 October 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, the [[Associated Press]] reported in an internal draft document that the WHO admitted  \"nearly everyone\" involved in the Ebola response failed to notice factors that turned the outbreak into the largest on record, and that they had missed chances to stop the spread of Ebola due to \"incompetent staff, bureaucracy and a lack of reliable information\".<ref>{{cite news|title=WHO chief promises transparency on Ebola failures|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/98181b6515da4baa94e6ac53ce880c07/who-chief-promises-transparency-ebola-failures|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=31 December 2014}}</ref> Peter Piot, co-discoverer of the Ebola virus, called the WHO regional office in Africa \"really not competent.\"<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/18/oxfam-call-for-troops-ebola--west-africa-world-health-organisation-accused | title=Oxfam calls for troops in Africa as criticism of 'inadequate' Ebola response mounts | newspaper=The Guardian | date=18 October 2014 | accessdate=24 October 2014 | author=McVeigh, Tracy}}</ref> In April 2015, the WHO admitted very serious failings in handling the crisis and indicated reforms for any future crises; \"we did not work effectively in coordination with other partners, there were shortcomings in risk communications and there was confusion of roles and responsibilities\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-who-idUSKBN0NA12J20150419|title=WHO leadership admits failings over Ebola, promises reform|work=Reuters|accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> The Ebola crisis was discussed at the June 2015 [[G7 (major advanced economies)|G7 meeting]].  The leaders pledged to assist in carrying out WHO regulations. Critics criticised the G7 leaders, saying they were not committed enough in the fight against the possibility of future pandemics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/may/18/angela-merkel-plan-restructure-world-health-organisation|title=Plan to reform WHO after Ebola to be unveiled by Angela Merkel|author=Sarah Boseley|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=19 May 2015|date=2015-05-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.eu/article/g7-ebola-fight-response-ngo-leaders-reactions/|title=G7 underwhelms with Ebola response|publisher=Politico|accessdate=17 June 2015|date=2015-06-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 a panel of experts looked at the ways of preventing small outbreaks from becoming large epidemics. Their recommendations were published in the November issue of ''[[The Lancet]]''.  According to the panel, the epidemic had exposed problems in the national (and international) institutions responsible for protecting the public from the human consequences of infectious disease outbreaks such as the Ebola epidemic.  The panel was highly critical of the WHO's management of the Ebola crisis noting that it took them months to respond and when they did they were slow to act, poorly co-ordinated and inadequately informed.  The report pointed out that the committee responsible for checking the WHO's actions during the outbreak (i.e. the WHO Ebola Interim Assessment Panel) had delayed responses due to worries about political resistance from the Western African leaders, economic consequences, and a system within the WHO that discouraged open debate about issues such as emergency declarations. The WHO may also have hesitated because it was criticised for creating panic by declaring a public health emergency during the relatively mild [[2009 H1N1 pandemic]]. This, the report states, showed the risks in having such consequential decision-making power in one individual\u2014a risk made worse when there was no mechanism of responsibility for such leadership failure.<ref name=\"lancet\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(15)00946-0/abstract|title=Will Ebola change the game? Ten essential reforms before the next pandemic. The report of the Harvard-LSHTM Independent Panel on the Global Response to Ebola|journal=The Lancet|accessdate=27 January 2016|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(15)00946-0|pmid=26615326|volume=386|issue=10009|pages=2204\u20132221|year=2015|last1=Moon|first1=Suerie|last2=Sridhar|first2=Devi|last3=Pate|first3=Muhammad A|last4=Jha|first4=Ashish K|last5=Clinton|first5=Chelsea|last6=Delaunay|first6=Sophie|last7=Edwin|first7=Valnora|last8=Fallah|first8=Mosoka|last9=Fidler|first9=David P|last10=Garrett|first10=Laurie|last11=Goosby|first11=Eric|last12=Gostin|first12=Lawrence O|last13=Heymann|first13=David L|last14=Lee|first14=Kelley|last15=Leung|first15=Gabriel M|last16=Morrison|first16=J Stephen|last17=Saavedra|first17=Jorge|last18=Tanner|first18=Marcel|last19=Leigh|first19=Jennifer A|last20=Hawkins|first20=Benjamin|last21=Woskie|first21=Liana R|last22=Piot|first22=Peter}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/11/23/africa/ebola-lancet-report/|title=Ebola crisis: WHO slammed by Harvard-convened panel over slow response|publisher=CNN|date=23 November 2015|accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ebola global response was 'too slow', say health experts|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-34877787|accessdate=23 November 2015|work=BBC News |date=23 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe panel outlined 10 recommendations for the prevention and handling of future infectious disease outbreaks.  Included in the recommendations of the changes needed to fight future outbreaks is the creation of a U.N. Security Council health committee to expedite political attention to health issues and the establishment of a global fund to finance and accelerate the development of outbreak-relevant drugs and treatment.  The report also noted that competent governance of the global system demanded political leadership and a WHO that is more focused and appropriately financed and whose integrity is restored through the application of adequate reforms and leadership.<ref name=\"lancet\"/>\n\nThe WHO also came under fire for refusing to send Dr. Olivet Buck to Germany for experimental treatment after she contracted Ebola per the government of Sierra Leone's request. WHO claimed they could only evacuate medical professionals they had deployed to the region, not locals. Dr. Olivet Buck was the Medical Superintendent at Lumley Government Hospital in Freetown, Sierra Leone. It's believed that she contracted the virus while continuing to treat patients even during a shortage of personal protective equipment. Her loyalty and dedication to her community never wavered.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Green |first1=Andrew |title=Remembering health workers who died from Ebola in 2014 |journal=The Lancet |date=20 December 2014 |volume=384 |issue=9961 |pages=2201\u20132206 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(14)62417-X |pmid=25625389 |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(14)62417-X/fulltext |accessdate=29 February 2020 |language=English |issn=0140-6736}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline of reported cases and deaths ==\n\n{{Main|West African Ebola virus epidemic timeline of reported cases and deaths}}\n{{See also|Ebola virus epidemic in West Africa timeline}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right; width:100%;\"\n|+Major Ebola virus outbreaks by country and by date \u2013 to most recent WHO / Gov update- 14 January 2016<br />\n! rowspan=2 |Date ||colspan=2 | Total || colspan=2 | Guinea || colspan=2 | Liberia || colspan=2 | Sierra Leone || rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:120px;\"| Sources\n|-\n! style=\"color: red;\" | Cases || Deaths || style=\"color: red;\" | Cases || Deaths || style=\"color: red;\" | Cases || Deaths || style=\"color: red;\" | Cases||Deaths\n|-\n| 14 January 2016 || 28,542 || 11,299 || 3,806 || 2,535 || 10,675 || 4,809 || 14,061 || 3,955 || {{efn|group=note|25 Oct: All governments as per WHO.}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Latest Ebola outbreak over in Liberia; West Africa is at zero, but new flare-ups are likely to occur|url=http://who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2016/ebola-zero-liberia/en/|publisher=World Health Organization |accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|  23 December 2015  || 28,542 || 11,299 || 3,806 || 2,535 || 10,676 || 4,809 || 14,061 || 3,955 ||<ref>{{cite web|title=Ebola Situation Report |date= 23 September 2015 |url=http://apps.who.int/ebola/current-situation/ebola-situation-report-23-september-2015 |publisher=WHO|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|  9 December 2015  || 28,542 || 11,299||3,806|| 2,535 || 10,675 || 4,809 || 14,061  || 3,955 ||<ref>{{cite web|title=Ebola Situation Report |date= 9 December 2015 |url=http://apps.who.int/ebola/current-situation/ebola-situation-report-9-december-2015|publisher=WHO|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 25 November 2015 || 28,539 || 11,298 || 3,806 || 2,535 || 10,672 || 4,808 || 14,061 || 3,955 ||<ref>{{cite web|title=Ebola Situation Report \u2013 25 November 2015 {{!}} Ebola|url=http://apps.who.int/ebola/current-situation/ebola-situation-report-25-november-2015|publisher=WHO|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1