{"title_page": "Desmond Swayne", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Major (United Kingdom)|Major]]\n| name = Sir Desmond Swayne\n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|TD|VR|}} [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Sir Desmond Swayne crop 2.jpg\n| office = [[Secretary of State for International Development|Minister of State for International Development]]\n| term_start = 14 July 2014\n| term_end = 17 July 2016\n| primeminister = [[David Cameron]]\n| predecessor = [[Alan Duncan]]\n| successor = [[Rory Stewart]]\n| office1 = [[Vice-Chamberlain of the Household]]\n| term_start1 = 7 October 2013\n| term_end1 = 14 July 2014\n| predecessor1 = [[Greg Knight]]\n| successor1 = [[Anne Milton]]\n| primeminister1 = [[David Cameron]]\n| office2 = [[Lord of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| primeminister2 = [[David Cameron]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Michael Fabricant]]\n| successor2 = [[Sam Gyimah]]\n| term_start2 = 4 September 2012\n| term_end2 = 7 October 2013\n| office3 = [[Parliamentary Private Secretary to the Prime Minister]]\n| primeminister3 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start3 = 12 May 2010\n| term_end3 = 4 September 2012\n| predecessor3 = [[Jon Trickett]] & <br>[[Anne Snelgrove]]\n| successor3 = [[Sam Gyimah]]\n| office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br> for [[New Forest West (UK Parliament constituency)|New Forest West]]\n| parliament5 = \n| majority5 = 24,403 (48.5%)\n| predecessor5 = [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|Constituency created]]\n| successor5 = \n| term_start5 = 1 May 1997\n| term_end5 = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1956|8|20}}<ref name=BBC2122146>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2122146.stm|title=Desmond Swayne|work=BBC News|accessdate=14 July 2010 | date=17 October 2002}}</ref>\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = British\n| spouse = {{marriage|Moira Cecily Teek|August 1987}}\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| relations = \n| children = 3\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[University of St Andrews]]\n| occupation = Politician\n| profession = \n| signature = \n| website = {{URL|desmondswaynemp.com/}}\n| footnotes = <!--Military service-->\n| nickname = \n| allegiance = United Kingdom\n| branch = [[Royal Mercian and Lancastrian Yeomanry]]\n| serviceyears = 1978\u2013\n| rank = [[Major (United Kingdom)|Major]]\n| unit = \n| commands = \n| battles = \n| awards = [[Efficiency Decoration|Territorial Decoration]]<br>[[Iraq Medal (United Kingdom)|Iraq Medal]]<br>[[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]]<br>[[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]]<br>[[Volunteer Reserve Service Medal]]\n| caption = Swayne in 2017\n}}\n'''Sir Desmond Angus Swayne''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|TD|VR}} (born 20 August 1956)<ref name=BBC2122146/> is a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician,  [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for the constituency of [[New Forest West (UK Parliament constituency)|New Forest West]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/politics/15338039.Desmond_Swayne_retains_New_Forest_West_seat___but_issues_warning_to_his_party/|title=Desmond Swayne retains New Forest West seat - but issues warning to his party|work=Southern Daily Echo|publisher=Newsquest Media Group|accessdate=25 July 2017|date=9 June 2017 }}</ref> \n\nBefore going into politics, he was a schoolmaster, and then a manager at the [[Royal Bank of Scotland]]. He was [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[David Cameron]], both during his time as [[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|Leader of the Opposition]], 2005\u201310, and then for two years while Cameron was Prime Minister. In September 2012 he was appointed as [[Lord of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of HM Treasury]] and in July 2014 as [[Secretary of State for International Development|Minister for International Development]]. In June 2016, it was announced that Swayne would receive a knighthood in the Queen's Birthday Honours for political services. \n\nHe is a supporter of the Eurosceptic pressure group [[Leave Means Leave]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leavemeansleave.eu/who-we-are/ |title=Co-Chairmen - Political Advisory Board - Supporters |publisher=Leave Means Leave |access-date=14 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024153425/http://www.leavemeansleave.eu/who-we-are/ |archive-date=24 October 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nDesmond Angus Swayne was born on 20 August 1956 to George Joseph and Elizabeth McAlister Swayne (n\u00e9e Gibson).<ref name=UKWW>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-36810|publisher=A & C Black|accessdate=23 October 2019|title=Swayne, Rt Hon. Sir Desmond (Angus)}}</ref> He was privately educated at [[Drumley House School|Drumley House Preparatory School]] at [[Mossblown]] in [[South Ayrshire]] and [[Bedford School]]. He studied Theology at [[St Mary's College, St Andrews|St Mary's College]] at the [[University of St Andrews]].<ref name=TelgSwayne>{{cite news|url=http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/New+Forest+West/Desmond+Swayne|title=Desmond Swayne|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=14 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306092438/http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/New%2BForest%2BWest/Desmond%2BSwayne|archivedate=6 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe taught economics at the [[Charterhouse School]] for one year followed by seven years at [[Wrekin College]] (both independent boarding schools).<ref name=Waller>{{cite book|first1=Robert|last1=Waller|first2=Byron|last2=Criddle|title=The Almanac of British Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9mC7pEr0R6QC&pg=PA502|year=1999|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-18541-7|page=502}}</ref> From 1987 to 1997, he was a computer systems manager at [[Royal Bank of Scotland]].<ref name=Waller/><ref name=Guardian/>\n\n===Military career===\n\nOn 2 August 1987, he was commissioned into the [[Royal Armoured Corps]], Territorial Army in the rank of second lieutenant (on probation).<ref name=\"LG 9 November 1987\">{{London Gazette |issue=51115 |date=9 November 1987 |page=13839 |supp=y }}</ref> He served with the [[Queen's Own Mercian Yeomanry]].<ref name=\"LG 9 January 1989\">{{London Gazette |issue=51609 |date=9 January 1989 |page=328 |supp=y }}</ref> He was promoted to lieutenant on 2 August 1989,<ref name=\"LG 2 October 1989\">{{London Gazette |issue=51890 |date=2 October 1989 |page=11305 |supp=y }}</ref> and to [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] on 1 August 1992.<ref name=\"LG 21 September 1992\">{{London Gazette |issue=53054 |date=21 September 1992 |page=15840 |supp=y }}</ref> On 1 November 1992, he transferred to the newly formed [[Royal Mercian and Lancastrian Yeomanry]].<ref name=\"LG 1 February 1993\">{{London Gazette |issue=53192 |date=1 February 1993 |page=1866 |supp=y }}</ref> He was promoted to [[Major (United Kingdom)|major]] on 14 December 1996 with seniority from 1 January 1996.<ref name=\"LG 27 March 1997\">{{London Gazette |issue=54718 |date=27 March 1997 |page=3878 |supp=y }}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, he was called up and posted to [[Iraq]] as part of the [[Iraq War]].<ref>{{cite news|title=MP to serve in Iraq|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3004920.stm|accessdate=5 August 2014|work=BBC News|date=19 June 2003}}</ref> He served for six months before returning to the House of Commons.<ref name=Guardian/>\n\n===Blackface controversy===\n\nOn 28 September 2019, he remarked that \"blackface\" was an \"entirely acceptable bit of fun\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Swayne|first1=Desmond|title=Blackface is an 'entirely acceptable bit of fun', says Conservative MP|url=https://www.msn.com/en-nz/news/world/blackface-is-an-entirely-acceptable-bit-of-fun-says-conservative-mp/ar-AAHWScN?li=BBS2yio|accessdate=28 September 2019|work=MSN UK|date=28 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929112522/https://www.msn.com/en-nz/news/world/blackface-is-an-entirely-acceptable-bit-of-fun-says-conservative-mp/ar-AAHWScN%3Fli%3DBBS2yio|archive-date=29 September 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 30 September, it was reported that he wore blackface while attending a [[The Blues Brothers (film)|Blues Brothers]] themed party, where he was pictured posing as [[James Brown]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/09/30/tory-mp-sir-desmond-swayne-pictured-blacked-soul-singer-james/|title=Exclusive picture: Tory MP Sir Desmond Swayne 'blacked up' as soul singer James Brown|last=Ward|first=Victoria|date=2019-09-30|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-10-01|last2=Hope|first2=Christopher|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Swayne later said he \"went to some trouble to be as authentic as possible\" in creating the costume, before refusing to apologise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desmondswaynemp.com/ds-blog/trudeaus-turban/|title=Trudeau's Turban|website=www.desmondswaynemp.com|access-date=2019-10-01}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nSwayne unsuccessfully contested  the constituency of [[Pontypridd (UK Parliament constituency)|Pontypridd]] for the Conservative Party in the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 general election]], before seeking office in the constituency of [[West Bromwich West (UK Parliament constituency)|West Bromwich West]] in the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]], where he was defeated by the Labour incumbent [[Betty Boothroyd, Baroness Boothroyd of Sandwell|Betty Boothroyd]]. However, he was successfully elected to the seat of [[New Forest West (UK Parliament constituency)|New Forest West]] at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]]. In the [[1997 Conservative Party leadership election]], Swayne supported [[Michael Howard]], and later [[John Redwood]].<ref name=Waller/> He held the seat to serve his sixth consecutive term in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 General Election]].\n\nFrom 1997 to 2001, he held shadow ministerial portfolios for [[Northern Ireland]], health and defence and as a senior opposition whip. From 2001 to 2005, Swayne was [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to both [[Iain Duncan Smith]] and Michael Howard in their role as [[Leader of the Opposition]].<ref name=TelgSwayne/>\n\nFollowing the election of [[David Cameron]] as leader of the Conservative Party in December 2005, he was appointed as his PPS.<ref name=TelgSwayne/> This position involved being the eyes and ears of Cameron in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] and reporting back on observations and requests from colleagues. In 2006, a series of Swayne's e-mails to Cameron with unflattering descriptions of fellow Conservatives were leaked to the media.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article685090.ece |title=Tories lost in swirl of backbiting |author=Oakeshott, Isabel |work=The Times |date=9 July 2006 |accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe maintained his role as a PPS in [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|government]].<ref>[http://www.number10.gov.uk/news/latest-news/2010/11/government-publishes-list-of-parliamentary-private-secretaries-57099 Government publishes list of Parliamentary Private Secretaries (PPS)] Prime Minister's Office, 17 November 2010</ref> On 11 June 2011, it was announced Swayne would be appointed a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellor]] in the Queen's [[2011 Birthday Honours|2011 Birthday Honours List]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59808 |date=11 June 2011 |page=1 |supp=y}}</ref> On 13 July 2011, Swayne was duly sworn of Council.<ref name=\"O13Jul11\">[http://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/orders-13july2011.pdf Privy Council Office \u2014 Orders for 13 July 2011] Privy Council, 13 July 2011</ref> In 2014, he was appointed as a [[Department for International Development|minister for international development]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Who is Desmond Swayne? Introducing Britain's new development minister|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development-professionals-network/2014/jul/16/cabinet-reshuffle-desmond-swayne-dfid|accessdate=7 April 2015|work=The Guardian|date=16 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his salary as an MP, Swayne earns \u00a312,000 a year as a director of property development firm Lewis Charles Sofia Property Fund, which predominantly specialises in holiday developments in [[Bulgaria]]; and around \u00a35,000 in his role as a major in the [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|Army Reserve]].<ref name=TIH4463577>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisishampshire.net/news/4463577.MP_defends_right_to_have_second_job/|title=\"Politicians should rely on taxpayer\" says New Forest West MP Desmond Swayne|work=This is Hampshire|date=29 June 2009|accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] he sits on the Ecclesiastical Committee (Joint Committee). He has previously sat on the International Trade Committee, the Administration Committee, the Defence Committee, the Procedure Committee, the Social Security Committee and Scottish Affairs Committee.<ref name=parliamentbioswayne>{{cite web|title=Desmond Swayne |url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/sir-desmond-swayne/55|website=Parliament UK|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|expenses scandal]], Swayne repaid \u00a36,131 he claimed for a new kitchen in 2006 on his second-home flat in [[North Kensington]], and \u00a360.66 over claimed for a water bill.<ref name=TIH4463577/> Swayne employs his wife Moira as part-time Executive Secretary/Office Manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://parliament.telegraph.co.uk/mpsexpenses/mp-details/Desmond-Swayne/mp-10580|title=Desmond Swayne|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=15 July 2010 }}</ref> Swayne provided a full breakdown of his expenses on his website, and was found by local media in New Forest/South Dorset to be the lowest claiming of the local MP expenses' league table, after claiming \u00a394,754 expenses in 2007/08, compared with \u00a391,737 in 2006/07.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisisdorset.net/news/tidnews/4370313.What_is_the_cost_of_our_MPs_/|title=What is the cost of our MPs?|work=Dorset Echo|accessdate=15 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928061818/http://www.thisisdorset.net/news/tidnews/4370313.What_is_the_cost_of_our_MPs_/|archivedate=28 September 2011|date=15 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, the Labour Party unsuccessfully proposed an amendment in Parliament that would have required private landlords to make their homes \"fit for human habitation\". According to Parliament's register of interests, Swayne was one of 72 Conservative MPs who voted against the amendment who personally derived an income from renting out property. The Conservative Government had responded to the amendment that they believed homes should be fit for human habitation but did not want to pass the new law that would explicitly require it.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tories vote down law requiring landlords make their homes fit for human habitation|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tories-vote-down-law-requiring-landlords-make-their-homes-fit-for-human-habitation-a6809691.html|work=[[The Independent|Independent]]|accessdate=2 October 2018|date=9 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSwayne married Moira Cecily Teek in 1987. They have one son and two daughters.<ref name=UKWW/><ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development-professionals-network/2014/jul/16/cabinet-reshuffle-desmond-swayne-dfid|title=Who is Desmond Swayne? Introducing Britain's new development minister|work=The Guardian|date=16 July 2014|accessdate=23 October 2019|last1=Bax|first1=Tahmeena|last2=Anyangwe|first2=Eliza}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and decorations==\nSwayne is a recipient of the [[Queen's Golden Jubilee Medal]], the [[Iraq Medal (United Kingdom)|Iraq Medal]], and the [[Queen's Diamond Jubilee Medal]]. He has also received the [[Efficiency Decoration|Territorial Decoration]] for 12 years' service in the [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]].{{citation needed|date=September 2019}} In June 2009, he was awarded the [[Volunteer Reserves Service Medal]].<ref name=\"LG 23 June 2009\">{{London Gazette |issue=59106 |date=23 June 2009 |pages=10705\u201310706  |supp=y }}</ref>\n\nSwayne was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the [[2016 Birthday Honours]] for political and parliamentary service.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61608 |supp=y|page=B2|date=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n[[File:Knight-Bachelor.ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Iraq Medal BAR.svg|100px]]<br>\n[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Efficiency Decoration (Territorial & Volunteer Reserve).png|100px]]\n[[File:Volunteer Reserves Service Medal.png|100px]]\n</center>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:silver; text-align:center;\"\n|Ribbon || Description || Notes\n|-\n|[[File:Knight-Bachelor.ribbon.png|40px]] || [[Knight Bachelor]] (Kt) ||\n* 10 June 2016\n* For Political and Parliamentary Service \n|-\n|[[File:Iraq Medal BAR.svg|40px]] || [[Iraq Medal (United Kingdom)|Iraq Medal]] || \n|-\n|[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|40px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]] || \n* 2002\n* UK Version of this Medal\n|-\n|[[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|40px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]] || \n* 2012\n* UK Version of this Medal\n|-\n|[[File:Efficiency Decoration (Territorial & Volunteer Reserve).png|40px]] || [[Efficiency Decoration|Territorial Decoration]] (TD) ||\n* 12 Years Service in the [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]]\n|-\n|[[File:Volunteer Reserves Service Medal.png|40px]] || [[Volunteer Reserves Service Medal]] || \n* 2009\n* 10 Years Service in the [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|Army Reserves]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.desmondswaynemp.com Desmond Swayne MP] Official site\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=desmond-swayne/55 |hansardcurr=4185 |hansard=mr-desmond-swayne |publicwhip=Desmond_Swayne |theywork=desmond_swayne}}\n* [http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Swayne_Desmond.aspx Desmond Swayne MP Biography] Conservative Party\n*{{C-SPAN|Desmond Swayne}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament for [[New Forest West (UK Parliament constituency)|New Forest West]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{South East Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Swayne, Desmond}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of St Andrews]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Royal Mercian and Lancastrian Yeomanry officers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford School]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary Private Secretaries to the Prime Minister]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Major (United Kingdom)|Major]]\n| name = Sir Desmond Swayne\n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|TD|VR|}} [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Sir Desmond Swayne crop 2.jpg\n| office = [[Secretary of State for International Development|Minister of State for International Development]]\n| term_start = 14 July 2014\n| term_end = 17 July 2016\n| primeminister = [[David Cameron]]\n| predecessor = [[Alan Duncan]]\n| successor = [[Rory Stewart]]\n| office1 = [[Vice-Chamberlain of the Household]]\n| term_start1 = 7 October 2013\n| term_end1 = 14 July 2014\n| predecessor1 = [[Greg Knight]]\n| successor1 = [[Anne Milton]]\n| primeminister1 = [[David Cameron]]\n| office2 = [[Lord of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| primeminister2 = [[David Cameron]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Michael Fabricant]]\n| successor2 = [[Sam Gyimah]]\n| term_start2 = 4 September 2012\n| term_end2 = 7 October 2013\n| office3 = [[Parliamentary Private Secretary to the Prime Minister]]\n| primeminister3 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start3 = 12 May 2010\n| term_end3 = 4 September 2012\n| predecessor3 = [[Jon Trickett]] & <br>[[Anne Snelgrove]]\n| successor3 = [[Sam Gyimah]]\n| office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br> for [[New Forest West (UK Parliament constituency)|New Forest West]]\n| parliament5 = \n| majority5 = 24,403 (48.5%)\n| predecessor5 = [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|Constituency created]]\n| successor5 = \n| term_start5 = 1 May 1997\n| term_end5 = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1956|8|20}}<ref name=BBC2122146>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2122146.stm|title=Desmond Swayne|work=BBC News|accessdate=14 July 2010 | date=17 October 2002}}</ref>\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = British\n| spouse = {{marriage|Moira Cecily Teek|August 1987}}\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| relations = \n| children = 3\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[University of St Andrews]]\n| occupation = Politician\n| profession = \n| signature = \n| website = {{URL|desmondswaynemp.com/}}\n| footnotes = <!--Military service-->\n| nickname = \n| allegiance = United Kingdom\n| branch = [[Royal Mercian and Lancastrian Yeomanry]]\n| serviceyears = 1978\u2013\n| rank = [[Major (United Kingdom)|Major]]\n| unit = \n| commands = \n| battles = \n| awards = [[Efficiency Decoration|Territorial Decoration]]<br>[[Iraq Medal (United Kingdom)|Iraq Medal]]<br>[[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]]<br>[[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]]<br>[[Volunteer Reserve Service Medal]]\n| caption = Swayne in 2017\n}}\n'''Sir Desmond Angus Swayne''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|TD|VR}} (born 20 August 1956)<ref name=BBC2122146/> is a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician,  [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for the constituency of [[New Forest West (UK Parliament constituency)|New Forest West]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/politics/15338039.Desmond_Swayne_retains_New_Forest_West_seat___but_issues_warning_to_his_party/|title=Desmond Swayne retains New Forest West seat - but issues warning to his party|work=Southern Daily Echo|publisher=Newsquest Media Group|accessdate=25 July 2017|date=9 June 2017 }}</ref> \n\nBefore going into politics, he was a schoolmaster, and then a manager at the [[Royal Bank of Scotland]]. He was [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[David Cameron]], both during his time as [[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|Leader of the Opposition]], 2005\u201310, and then for two years while Cameron was Prime Minister. In September 2012 he was appointed as [[Lord of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of HM Treasury]] and in July 2014 as [[Secretary of State for International Development|Minister for International Development]]. In June 2016, it was announced that Swayne would receive a knighthood in the Queen's Birthday Honours for political services. \n\nHe is a supporter of the Eurosceptic pressure group [[Leave Means Leave]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leavemeansleave.eu/who-we-are/ |title=Co-Chairmen - Political Advisory Board - Supporters |publisher=Leave Means Leave |access-date=14 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024153425/http://www.leavemeansleave.eu/who-we-are/ |archive-date=24 October 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nDesmond Angus Swayne was born on 20 August 1956 to George Joseph and Elizabeth McAlister Swayne (n\u00e9e Gibson).<ref name=UKWW>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-36810|publisher=A & C Black|accessdate=23 October 2019|title=Swayne, Rt Hon. Sir Desmond (Angus)}}</ref> He was privately educated at [[Drumley House School|Drumley House Preparatory School]] at [[Mossblown]] in [[South Ayrshire]] and [[Bedford School]]. He studied Theology at [[St Mary's College, St Andrews|St Mary\u2019s College]] at the [[University of St Andrews]].<ref name=TelgSwayne>{{cite news|url=http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/New+Forest+West/Desmond+Swayne|title=Desmond Swayne|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=14 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306092438/http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/New%2BForest%2BWest/Desmond%2BSwayne|archivedate=6 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe taught economics at the [[Charterhouse School]] for one year followed by seven years at [[Wrekin College]] (both independent boarding schools).<ref name=Waller>{{cite book|first1=Robert|last1=Waller|first2=Byron|last2=Criddle|title=The Almanac of British Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9mC7pEr0R6QC&pg=PA502|year=1999|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-18541-7|page=502}}</ref> From 1987 to 1997, he was a computer systems manager at [[Royal Bank of Scotland]].<ref name=Waller/><ref name=Guardian/>\n\n===Military career===\n\nOn 2 August 1987, he was commissioned into the [[Royal Armoured Corps]], Territorial Army in the rank of second lieutenant (on probation).<ref name=\"LG 9 November 1987\">{{London Gazette |issue=51115 |date=9 November 1987 |page=13839 |supp=y }}</ref> He served with the [[Queen's Own Mercian Yeomanry]].<ref name=\"LG 9 January 1989\">{{London Gazette |issue=51609 |date=9 January 1989 |page=328 |supp=y }}</ref> He was promoted to lieutenant on 2 August 1989,<ref name=\"LG 2 October 1989\">{{London Gazette |issue=51890 |date=2 October 1989 |page=11305 |supp=y }}</ref> and to [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] on 1 August 1992.<ref name=\"LG 21 September 1992\">{{London Gazette |issue=53054 |date=21 September 1992 |page=15840 |supp=y }}</ref> On 1 November 1992, he transferred to the newly formed [[Royal Mercian and Lancastrian Yeomanry]].<ref name=\"LG 1 February 1993\">{{London Gazette |issue=53192 |date=1 February 1993 |page=1866 |supp=y }}</ref> He was promoted to [[Major (United Kingdom)|major]] on 14 December 1996 with seniority from 1 January 1996.<ref name=\"LG 27 March 1997\">{{London Gazette |issue=54718 |date=27 March 1997 |page=3878 |supp=y }}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, he was called up and posted to [[Iraq]] as part of the [[Iraq War]].<ref>{{cite news|title=MP to serve in Iraq|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3004920.stm|accessdate=5 August 2014|work=BBC News|date=19 June 2003}}</ref> He served for six months before returning to the House of Commons.<ref name=Guardian/>\n\n===Blackface controversy===\n\nOn 28 September 2019, he remarked that \"blackface\" was an \"entirely acceptable bit of fun\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Swayne|first1=Desmond|title=Blackface is an 'entirely acceptable bit of fun', says Conservative MP|url=https://www.msn.com/en-nz/news/world/blackface-is-an-entirely-acceptable-bit-of-fun-says-conservative-mp/ar-AAHWScN?li=BBS2yio|accessdate=28 September 2019|work=MSN UK|date=28 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929112522/https://www.msn.com/en-nz/news/world/blackface-is-an-entirely-acceptable-bit-of-fun-says-conservative-mp/ar-AAHWScN%3Fli%3DBBS2yio|archive-date=29 September 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 30 September, it was reported that he wore blackface while attending a [[The Blues Brothers (film)|Blues Brothers]] themed party, where he was pictured posing as [[James Brown]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/09/30/tory-mp-sir-desmond-swayne-pictured-blacked-soul-singer-james/|title=Exclusive picture: Tory MP Sir Desmond Swayne 'blacked up' as soul singer James Brown|last=Ward|first=Victoria|date=2019-09-30|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-10-01|last2=Hope|first2=Christopher|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Swayne later said he \"went to some trouble to be as authentic as possible\" in creating the costume, before refusing to apologise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desmondswaynemp.com/ds-blog/trudeaus-turban/|title=Trudeau's Turban|website=www.desmondswaynemp.com|access-date=2019-10-01}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nSwayne unsuccessfully contested  the constituency of [[Pontypridd (UK Parliament constituency)|Pontypridd]] for the Conservative Party in the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 general election]], before seeking office in the constituency of [[West Bromwich West (UK Parliament constituency)|West Bromwich West]] in the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]], where he was defeated by the Labour incumbent [[Betty Boothroyd, Baroness Boothroyd of Sandwell|Betty Boothroyd]]. However, he was successfully elected to the seat of [[New Forest West (UK Parliament constituency)|New Forest West]] at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]]. In the [[1997 Conservative Party leadership election]], Swayne supported [[Michael Howard]], and later [[John Redwood]].<ref name=Waller/> He held the seat to serve his sixth consecutive term in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 General Election]].\n\nFrom 1997 to 2001, he held shadow ministerial portfolios for [[Northern Ireland]], health and defence and as a senior opposition whip. From 2001 to 2005, Swayne was [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to both [[Iain Duncan Smith]] and Michael Howard in their role as [[Leader of the Opposition]].<ref name=TelgSwayne/>\n\nFollowing the election of [[David Cameron]] as leader of the Conservative Party in December 2005, he was appointed as his PPS.<ref name=TelgSwayne/> This position involved being the eyes and ears of Cameron in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] and reporting back on observations and requests from colleagues. In 2006, a series of Swayne's e-mails to Cameron with unflattering descriptions of fellow Conservatives were leaked to the media.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article685090.ece |title=Tories lost in swirl of backbiting |author=Oakeshott, Isabel |work=The Times |date=9 July 2006 |accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe maintained his role as a PPS in [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|government]].<ref>[http://www.number10.gov.uk/news/latest-news/2010/11/government-publishes-list-of-parliamentary-private-secretaries-57099 Government publishes list of Parliamentary Private Secretaries (PPS)] Prime Minister's Office, 17 November 2010</ref> On 11 June 2011, it was announced Swayne would be appointed a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellor]] in the Queen's [[2011 Birthday Honours|2011 Birthday Honours List]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59808 |date=11 June 2011 |page=1 |supp=y}}</ref> On 13 July 2011, Swayne was duly sworn of Council.<ref name=\"O13Jul11\">[http://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/orders-13july2011.pdf Privy Council Office \u2014 Orders for 13 July 2011] Privy Council, 13 July 2011</ref> In 2014, he was appointed as a [[Department for International Development|minister for international development]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Who is Desmond Swayne? Introducing Britain's new development minister|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development-professionals-network/2014/jul/16/cabinet-reshuffle-desmond-swayne-dfid|accessdate=7 April 2015|work=The Guardian|date=16 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his salary as an MP, Swayne earns \u00a312,000 a year as a director of property development firm Lewis Charles Sofia Property Fund, which predominantly specialises in holiday developments in [[Bulgaria]]; and around \u00a35,000 in his role as a major in the [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|Army Reserve]].<ref name=TIH4463577>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisishampshire.net/news/4463577.MP_defends_right_to_have_second_job/|title=\"Politicians should rely on taxpayer\" says New Forest West MP Desmond Swayne|work=This is Hampshire|date=29 June 2009|accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] he sits on the Ecclesiastical Committee (Joint Committee). He has previously sat on the International Trade Committee, the Administration Committee, the Defence Committee, the Procedure Committee, the Social Security Committee and Scottish Affairs Committee.<ref name=parliamentbioswayne>{{cite web|title=Desmond Swayne |url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/sir-desmond-swayne/55|website=Parliament UK|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|expenses scandal]], Swayne repaid \u00a36,131 he claimed for a new kitchen in 2006 on his second-home flat in [[North Kensington]], and \u00a360.66 over claimed for a water bill.<ref name=TIH4463577/> Swayne employs his wife Moira as part-time Executive Secretary/Office Manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://parliament.telegraph.co.uk/mpsexpenses/mp-details/Desmond-Swayne/mp-10580|title=Desmond Swayne|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=15 July 2010 }}</ref> Swayne provided a full breakdown of his expenses on his website, and was found by local media in New Forest/South Dorset to be the lowest claiming of the local MP expenses' league table, after claiming \u00a394,754 expenses in 2007/08, compared with \u00a391,737 in 2006/07.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisisdorset.net/news/tidnews/4370313.What_is_the_cost_of_our_MPs_/|title=What is the cost of our MPs?|work=Dorset Echo|accessdate=15 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928061818/http://www.thisisdorset.net/news/tidnews/4370313.What_is_the_cost_of_our_MPs_/|archivedate=28 September 2011|date=15 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, the Labour Party unsuccessfully proposed an amendment in Parliament that would have required private landlords to make their homes \"fit for human habitation\". According to Parliament's register of interests, Swayne was one of 72 Conservative MPs who voted against the amendment who personally derived an income from renting out property. The Conservative Government had responded to the amendment that they believed homes should be fit for human habitation but did not want to pass the new law that would explicitly require it.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tories vote down law requiring landlords make their homes fit for human habitation|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tories-vote-down-law-requiring-landlords-make-their-homes-fit-for-human-habitation-a6809691.html|work=[[The Independent|Independent]]|accessdate=2 October 2018|date=9 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSwayne married Moira Cecily Teek in 1987. They have one son and two daughters.<ref name=UKWW/><ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development-professionals-network/2014/jul/16/cabinet-reshuffle-desmond-swayne-dfid|title=Who is Desmond Swayne? Introducing Britain's new development minister|work=The Guardian|date=16 July 2014|accessdate=23 October 2019|last1=Bax|first1=Tahmeena|last2=Anyangwe|first2=Eliza}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and decorations==\nSwayne is a recipient of the [[Queen's Golden Jubilee Medal]], the [[Iraq Medal (United Kingdom)|Iraq Medal]], and the [[Queen's Diamond Jubilee Medal]]. He has also received the [[Efficiency Decoration|Territorial Decoration]] for 12 years' service in the [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]].{{citation needed|date=September 2019}} In June 2009, he was awarded the [[Volunteer Reserves Service Medal]].<ref name=\"LG 23 June 2009\">{{London Gazette |issue=59106 |date=23 June 2009 |pages=10705\u201310706  |supp=y }}</ref>\n\nSwayne was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the [[2016 Birthday Honours]] for political and parliamentary service.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61608 |supp=y|page=B2|date=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n[[File:Knight-Bachelor.ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Iraq Medal BAR.svg|100px]]<br>\n[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Efficiency Decoration (Territorial & Volunteer Reserve).png|100px]]\n[[File:Volunteer Reserves Service Medal.png|100px]]\n</center>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:silver; text-align:center;\"\n|Ribbon || Description || Notes\n|-\n|[[File:Knight-Bachelor.ribbon.png|40px]] || [[Knight Bachelor]] (Kt) ||\n* 10 June 2016\n* For Political and Parliamentary Service \n|-\n|[[File:Iraq Medal BAR.svg|40px]] || [[Iraq Medal (United Kingdom)|Iraq Medal]] || \n|-\n|[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|40px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]] || \n* 2002\n* UK Version of this Medal\n|-\n|[[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|40px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]] || \n* 2012\n* UK Version of this Medal\n|-\n|[[File:Efficiency Decoration (Territorial & Volunteer Reserve).png|40px]] || [[Efficiency Decoration|Territorial Decoration]] (TD) ||\n* 12 Years Service in the [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]]\n|-\n|[[File:Volunteer Reserves Service Medal.png|40px]] || [[Volunteer Reserves Service Medal]] || \n* 2009\n* 10 Years Service in the [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|Army Reserves]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.desmondswaynemp.com Desmond Swayne MP] Official site\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=desmond-swayne/55 |hansardcurr=4185 |hansard=mr-desmond-swayne |publicwhip=Desmond_Swayne |theywork=desmond_swayne}}\n* [http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Swayne_Desmond.aspx Desmond Swayne MP Biography] Conservative Party\n*{{C-SPAN|Desmond Swayne}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament for [[New Forest West (UK Parliament constituency)|New Forest West]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{South East Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Swayne, Desmond}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of St Andrews]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Royal Mercian and Lancastrian Yeomanry officers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford School]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary Private Secretaries to the Prime Minister]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fix