{"title_page": "Andrew Stunell", "text_new": "{{For|the Australian rower|Andrew Stunell (rower)}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix          = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name                      = The Lord Stunell\n| honorific-suffix          = [[Knight Bachelor|Kt]] [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]\n| image                     = official portrait of Lord Stunell crop 2.jpg\n| office                    = [[Department for Communities and Local Government|Parliamentary Undersecretary of State for Communities and Local Government]]\n| primeminister             = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start                = 13 May 2010\n| term_end                  = 4 September 2012\n| predecessor               = [[Barbara Follett (politician)|Barbara Follett]]\n| successor                 = [[Don Foster (politician)|Don Foster]]\n| office1                   = [[Chief Whip of the Liberal Democrats|Liberal Democrat Chief Whip]]<br /> in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]\n| leader1                   = [[Charles Kennedy]]\n| term_start1               = 7 June 2001\n| term_end1                 = 22 March 2006\n| predecessor1              = [[Paul Tyler, Baron Tyler|Paul Tyler]]\n| successor1                = [[Paul Burstow]]\n|office2 = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start2 = 26 October 2015<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n|term_end2 = \n| office3          = [[Member of the Parliament]]<br>for [[Hazel Grove (UK Parliament constituency)|Hazel Grove]]\n| term_start3               = 1 May 1997\n| term_end3                 = 30 March 2015\n| predecessor3              = [[Tom Arnold (politician)|Tom Arnold]]\n| successor3                = [[William Wragg]]\n| majority3                 = \n| birth_date                = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1942|11|24}}\n| birth_place               = [[Sutton, London|London]], UK\n| death_date                = \n| death_place               = \n| party                     = [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n| alma_mater                = [[Victoria University of Manchester]]<br />[[Liverpool John Moores University]]\n}}\n\n[[File:Knights Bachelor Insignia.png|thumb|right|80px| Insignia of a Knight Bachelor]]\n\n'''Robert Andrew Stunell, Baron Stunell''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|sep=,|OBE|PC}} (born 24 November 1942) is a [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] politician in the United Kingdom.\n\nStunell was the Member of Parliament (MP) for [[Hazel Grove (UK Parliament constituency)|Hazel Grove]], from the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] until he stood down at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]]. From 2010 to 2012 he served as the [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] at the [[Department of Communities and Local Government]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.communities.gov.uk/newsroom/articlesandspeeches/|title=Announcements - GOV.UK|website=www.communities.gov.uk}}</ref> He was nominated for a [[life peer]]age in the [[2015 Dissolution Honours]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Dissolution Peerages 2015 |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/dissolution-peerages-2015 |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom |accessdate=27 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150827131007/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/dissolution-peerages-2015 |archive-date=27 August 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and career ==\nAndrew Stunell was born in [[Sutton (Surrey)|Sutton]], Surrey and educated at [[Surbiton County Grammar School]] for Boys (moved to [[Thames Ditton]] as [[Esher County Grammar School]] with the former buildings becoming [[Hollyfield School]], then became [[Esher College]] in 1977) on St. Marks Hill in Surbiton, then studied Architecture at [[Victoria University of Manchester|University of Manchester]] and [[Liverpool John Moores University|Liverpool Polytechnic]]. He became a member of [[Royal Institute of British Architects|RIBA]] in 1969.\n\nStunell married Gillian Chorley in 1967. They have three sons and two daughters and he is a former [[Baptist]] lay preacher and an active member of his local [[Methodist]] church.\n\nAfter graduation he was an architectural assistant until 1989, working for [[The Co-operative Group|CWS Manchester]] from 1965\u20137, Runcorn New Town from 1967 to 1981, then freelance 1981\u20135. From 1989 to 1996 he worked as Political Secretary of the [[Association of Liberal Democrat Councillors]] and was appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[1995 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=53893 |date=31 December 1994 |page=14 |supp=y }}</ref>\n\nStunell was elected to [[Chester (district)|Chester City Council]] in 1979 and to [[Cheshire County Council]] in 1981. He contested the [[City of Chester (UK Parliament constituency)|City of Chester]] constituency three times, as the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] candidate in [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979]] and for the [[SDP-Liberal Alliance]] in [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]] and [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]].\n\n== Member of Parliament, 1997\u20132015 ==\n\n=== Hazel Grove ===\nStunell was elected as the member of parliament for [[Hazel Grove (UK Parliament constituency)|Hazel Grove]] in [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] having fought the seat previously in [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]] when he came second with 43.1% of the vote.  The [[1997 United Kingdom general election|general election of 1997]] resulted in a majority of 11814 and a 54.5% of the vote, taking the seat from the Conservatives.  He retained the seat at the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] (52%), [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]] (49.5%) and [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]] (48.8%) general elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics|title=Politics|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\n=== Liberal Democrat Frontbench ===\n[[File:From left to right Neil O'Brien and Andrew Stunell OBE MP.jpg|thumb|left|Stunell (right) with [[Neil O'Brien]] at Conservative Party conference in 2011]]\nOn entering parliament in 1997 Stunell was appointed the Shadow Energy minister under [[Paddy Ashdown]], a role he performed until 2005.  At the same time Stunell operated as the party's deputy chief whip, only stepping down from that position in 2001 when he was elected to the position of [[Chief Whip]], a position he was re-elected to in 2005.  He stood down from the role in March 2006 to serve as the Shadow Secretary of State for communities and local government which concluded in December 2007 when [[Nick Clegg]] asked him to become chair of the Liberal Democrat local elections team.  In January 2009 Stunell was appointed to be the Liberal Democrat representative on the International Development Select Committee and in August 2009 he was asked to take on the role of vice-chair of the General Election campaign.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.andrewstunell.org.uk/page.php?Andrew Andrew Stunell | About Andrew \u2013 Andrew in Parliament] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101025101336/http://www.andrewstunell.org.uk/page.php?Andrew |date=25 October 2010 }}</ref>\n\n=== Sustainable and Secure Buildings Act 2004 ===\nIn 2003 Stunell came top in the regular ballot of [[Private Members' Bill]]s and was successful in having his Sustainable and Secure Buildings Bill become an [[Act of Parliament]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2004/22/contents|title=Sustainable and Secure Buildings Act 2004|website=www.legislation.gov.uk}}</ref> As part of the bill Stunell wanted to see all new and existing homes either built or renovated with security and energy saving features with Stunell saying that he wanted the bill to promote \"greener and safer buildings\".<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/bbc_parliament/3399743.stm|title=MPs' lobby: Greener and safer buildings|date=18 September 2018|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n=== Coalition negotiations ===\nFollowing the general election of 2010, no one political party was able to secure a majority in the House of Commons.  As a result, the Conservatives and Liberal Democrats entered into negotiations with each other to form the United Kingdom's first coalition government since the Second World War.\n\nStunell along with [[Danny Alexander]], [[Chris Huhne]] and [[David Laws]] acted as the negotiating team for the Liberal Democrats with [[William Hague]], [[Oliver Letwin]], [[George Osborne]] and [[Edward Llewellyn, Baron Llewellyn of Steep|Edward Llewellyn]] acting for the Conservatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/11/hung-parliament-negotiators-profiles|title=Profiles: The Liberal Democrat, Conservative and Labour negotiators|first=Haroon|last=Siddique|date=11 May 2010|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\n== Coalition Government ==\nFollowing the formation of the coalition, Stunell was appointed a [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Department for Communities and Local Government]] under Secretary of State [[Eric Pickles]].  His responsibilities in the role were community cohesion, race equality, building regulations and the implementation of the [[Big Society]] particularly with regard to housing and regeneration.<ref>[http://www.communities.gov.uk/profiles/corporate/andrewstunnell Department of communities and local government | Andrews Stunell profile] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625024016/http://www.communities.gov.uk/profiles/corporate/andrewstunnell |date=25 June 2010 }}</ref>\n\nStunell was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] for public and political service in the [[2013 Birthday Honours]].<ref name=gaz31712>{{London Gazette|issue=60534 |supp=y|page=2|date=15 June 2013 }}</ref><ref name='HM Birthday Honours 2013'>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/206698/Birthday_Honours_List_2013.pdf |title=Birthday Honours List 2013 |accessdate=14 June 2013 |date=14 June 2013 |publisher=HM Government |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017051132/https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/206698/Birthday_Honours_List_2013.pdf |archive-date=17 October 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref> receiving the accolade from the [[Prince Charles|Prince of Wales]] on 24 January 2014.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60966 |date=20 August 2014 |page=16222 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 he announced that he would be stepping down at the next general election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vine |first1=Katherine |title=Hazel Grove MP Andrew Stunell to step down at next general election |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/hazel-grove-mp-andrew-stunell-6116425 |accessdate=7 April 2015 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=30 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150111180525/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/hazel-grove-mp-andrew-stunell-6116425 |archive-date=11 January 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nStunell was created a [[Life Peer]] taking the title '''Baron Stunell''', of [[Hazel Grove]] in the [[Greater Manchester|County of Greater Manchester]] on 26 October 2015.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61395 |date=30 October 2015 |page=21334 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite book |last=Laws |first=David |title=22 Days in May |year=2010 |publisher=Biteback |isbn=978-1-84954-080-3}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050516230019/http://www.andrewstunell.org.uk/ Andrew Stunell MP] ''official constituency website''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110604072315/http://www.libdems.org.uk/people/andrew-stunell Profile] at the Liberal Democrats\n* {{UK MP links | parliament = andrew-stunell/445 | hansard = mr-andrew-stunell | hansardcurr = 4170 | guardian = 5048/andrew-stunell | publicwhip = Andrew_Stunell | theywork = andrew_stunell | record = Andrew-Stunell/Hazel-Grove/1142 | bbc = 25261.stm | journalisted = }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tom Arnold (politician)|Tom Arnold]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament for [[Hazel Grove (UK Parliament constituency)|Hazel Grove]] | years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William Wragg]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Paul Tyler, Baron Tyler|Paul Tyler]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Whip of the Liberal Democrats|Liberal Democrat Chief Whip]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] | years=2001\u20132006}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Paul Burstow]]}}\n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Watts, Baron Watts|The Lord Watts]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom|Gentlemen]]'''<br />''Baron Stunell'' '''}}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Robert Mair, Baron Mair|The Lord Mair]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Current Liberal Democrat Peers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stunell, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Liverpool John Moores University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Victoria University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Nick Clegg]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People from Sutton, London]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Hazel Grove]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Australian rower|Andrew Stunell (rower)}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix          = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name                      = The Lord Stunell\n| honorific-suffix          = [[Knight Bachelor|Kt]] [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]\n| image                     = official portrait of Lord Stunell crop 2.jpg\n| office                    = [[Department for Communities and Local Government|Parliamentary Undersecretary of State for Communities and Local Government]]\n| primeminister             = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start                = 13 May 2010\n| term_end                  = 4 September 2012\n| predecessor               = [[Barbara Follett (politician)|Barbara Follett]]\n| successor                 = [[Don Foster (politician)|Don Foster]]\n| office1                   = [[Chief Whip of the Liberal Democrats|Liberal Democrat Chief Whip]]<br /> in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]\n| leader1                   = [[Charles Kennedy]]\n| term_start1               = 7 June 2001\n| term_end1                 = 22 March 2006\n| predecessor1              = [[Paul Tyler, Baron Tyler|Paul Tyler]]\n| successor1                = [[Paul Burstow]]\n|office2 = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start2 = 26 October 2015<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n|term_end2 = \n| office3          = [[Member of the Parliament]]<br>for [[Hazel Grove (UK Parliament constituency)|Hazel Grove]]\n| term_start3               = 1 May 1997\n| term_end3                 = 30 March 2015\n| predecessor3              = [[Tom Arnold (politician)|Tom Arnold]]\n| successor3                = [[William Wragg]]\n| majority3                 = \n| birth_date                = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1942|11|24}}\n| birth_place               = [[Sutton, London|London]], UK\n| death_date                = \n| death_place               = \n| party                     = [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n| alma_mater                = [[Victoria University of Manchester]]<br />[[Liverpool John Moores University]]\n}}\n\n[[File:Knights Bachelor Insignia.png|thumb|right|80px| Insignia of a Knight Bachelor]]\n\n'''Robert Andrew Stunell, Baron Stunell''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|sep=,|OBE|PC}} (born 24 November 1942) is a [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] politician in the United Kingdom.\n\nStunell was the Member of Parliament (MP) for [[Hazel Grove (UK Parliament constituency)|Hazel Grove]], from the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] until he stood down at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]]. From 2010 to 2012 he served as the [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] at the [[Department of Communities and Local Government]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.communities.gov.uk/newsroom/articlesandspeeches/|title=Announcements - GOV.UK|website=www.communities.gov.uk}}</ref> He was nominated for a [[life peer]]age in the [[2015 Dissolution Honours]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Dissolution Peerages 2015 |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/dissolution-peerages-2015 |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom |accessdate=27 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150827131007/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/dissolution-peerages-2015 |archive-date=27 August 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and career ==\nAndrew Stunell was born in [[Sutton (Surrey)|Sutton]], Surrey and educated at [[Surbiton County Grammar School]] for Boys (moved to [[Thames Ditton]] as [[Esher County Grammar School]] with the former buildings becoming [[Hollyfield School]], then became [[Esher College]] in 1977) on St. Marks Hill in Surbiton, then studied Architecture at [[Victoria University of Manchester|University of Manchester]] and [[Liverpool John Moores University|Liverpool Polytechnic]]. He became a member of [[Royal Institute of British Architects|RIBA]] in 1969.\n\nStunell married Gillian Chorley in 1967. They have three sons and two daughters and he is a former [[Baptist]] lay preacher and an active member of his local [[Methodist]] church.\n\nAfter graduation he was an architectural assistant until 1989, working for [[The Co-operative Group|CWS Manchester]] from 1965\u20137, Runcorn New Town from 1967 to 1981, then freelance 1981-5. From 1989 to 1996 he worked as Political Secretary of the [[Association of Liberal Democrat Councillors]] and was appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[1995 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=53893 |date=31 December 1994 |page=14 |supp=y }}</ref>\n\nStunell was elected to [[Chester (district)|Chester City Council]] in 1979 and to [[Cheshire County Council]] in 1981. He contested the [[City of Chester (UK Parliament constituency)|City of Chester]] constituency three times, as the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] candidate in [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979]] and for the [[SDP-Liberal Alliance]] in [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]] and [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]].\n\n== Member of Parliament, 1997\u20132015 ==\n\n=== Hazel Grove ===\nStunell was elected as the member of parliament for [[Hazel Grove (UK Parliament constituency)|Hazel Grove]] in [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] having fought the seat previously in [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]] when he came second with 43.1% of the vote.  The [[1997 United Kingdom general election|general election of 1997]] resulted in a majority of 11814 and a 54.5% of the vote, taking the seat from the Conservatives.  He retained the seat at the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] (52%), [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]] (49.5%) and [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]] (48.8%) general elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics|title=Politics|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\n=== Liberal Democrat Frontbench ===\n[[File:From left to right Neil O'Brien and Andrew Stunell OBE MP.jpg|thumb|left|Stunell (right) with [[Neil O'Brien]] at Conservative Party conference in 2011]]\nOn entering parliament in 1997 Stunell was appointed the Shadow Energy minister under [[Paddy Ashdown]], a role he performed until 2005.  At the same time Stunell operated as the party's deputy chief whip, only stepping down from that position in 2001 when he was elected to the position of [[Chief Whip]], a position he was re-elected to in 2005.  He stood down from the role in March 2006 to serve as the Shadow Secretary of State for communities and local government which concluded in December 2007 when [[Nick Clegg]] asked him to become chair of the Liberal Democrat local elections team.  In January 2009 Stunell was appointed to be the Liberal Democrat representative on the International Development Select Committee and in August 2009 he was asked to take on the role of vice-chair of the General Election campaign.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.andrewstunell.org.uk/page.php?Andrew Andrew Stunell | About Andrew \u2013 Andrew in Parliament] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101025101336/http://www.andrewstunell.org.uk/page.php?Andrew |date=25 October 2010 }}</ref>\n\n=== Sustainable and Secure Buildings Act 2004 ===\nIn 2003 Stunell came top in the regular ballot of [[Private Members' Bill]]s and was successful in having his Sustainable and Secure Buildings Bill become an [[Act of Parliament]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2004/22/contents|title=Sustainable and Secure Buildings Act 2004|website=www.legislation.gov.uk}}</ref> As part of the bill Stunell wanted to see all new and existing homes either built or renovated with security and energy saving features with Stunell saying that he wanted the bill to promote \"greener and safer buildings\".<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/bbc_parliament/3399743.stm|title=MPs' lobby: Greener and safer buildings|date=18 September 2018|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n=== Coalition negotiations ===\nFollowing the general election of 2010, no one political party was able to secure a majority in the House of Commons.  As a result, the Conservatives and Liberal Democrats entered into negotiations with each other to form the United Kingdom's first coalition government since the Second World War.\n\nStunell along with [[Danny Alexander]], [[Chris Huhne]] and [[David Laws]] acted as the negotiating team for the Liberal Democrats with [[William Hague]], [[Oliver Letwin]], [[George Osborne]] and [[Edward Llewellyn, Baron Llewellyn of Steep|Edward Llewellyn]] acting for the Conservatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/11/hung-parliament-negotiators-profiles|title=Profiles: The Liberal Democrat, Conservative and Labour negotiators|first=Haroon|last=Siddique|date=11 May 2010|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\n== Coalition Government ==\nFollowing the formation of the coalition, Stunell was appointed a [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Department for Communities and Local Government]] under Secretary of State [[Eric Pickles]].  His responsibilities in the role were community cohesion, race equality, building regulations and the implementation of the [[Big Society]] particularly with regard to housing and regeneration.<ref>[http://www.communities.gov.uk/profiles/corporate/andrewstunnell Department of communities and local government | Andrews Stunell profile] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625024016/http://www.communities.gov.uk/profiles/corporate/andrewstunnell |date=25 June 2010 }}</ref>\n\nStunell was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] for public and political service in the [[2013 Birthday Honours]].<ref name=gaz31712>{{London Gazette|issue=60534 |supp=y|page=2|date=15 June 2013 }}</ref><ref name='HM Birthday Honours 2013'>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/206698/Birthday_Honours_List_2013.pdf |title=Birthday Honours List 2013 |accessdate=14 June 2013 |date=14 June 2013 |publisher=HM Government |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017051132/https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/206698/Birthday_Honours_List_2013.pdf |archive-date=17 October 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref> receiving the accolade from the [[Prince Charles|Prince of Wales]] on 24 January 2014.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60966 |date=20 August 2014 |page=16222 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 he announced that he would be stepping down at the next general election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vine |first1=Katherine |title=Hazel Grove MP Andrew Stunell to step down at next general election |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/hazel-grove-mp-andrew-stunell-6116425 |accessdate=7 April 2015 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=30 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150111180525/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/hazel-grove-mp-andrew-stunell-6116425 |archive-date=11 January 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nStunell was created a [[Life Peer]] taking the title '''Baron Stunell''', of [[Hazel Grove]] in the [[Greater Manchester|County of Greater Manchester]] on 26 October 2015.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61395 |date=30 October 2015 |page=21334 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite book |last=Laws |first=David |title=22 Days in May |year=2010 |publisher=Biteback |isbn=978-1-84954-080-3}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050516230019/http://www.andrewstunell.org.uk/ Andrew Stunell MP] ''official constituency website''\n* [htt