{"title_page": "Mariposa Folk Festival", "text_new": "{{short description|Folk music festival}}\n{{other uses|Mariposa (disambiguation)}}\n{{infobox music festival \n | music_festival_name = Mariposa Folk Festival\n | image               = Mariposa 1975 Album Cover.jpg\n | caption             = Mariposa 1975 album cover\n | location            = [[Tudhope Park]],<br />[[Orillia, Ontario]], Canada\n | founders            = Ruth Jones (nee McVeigh),<ref name=\"atom.library.yorku.ca\">{{cite web|url=https://atom.library.yorku.ca/index.php/mariposa-folk-foundation-fonds|title= Mariposa Folk Foundation fonds - York University Libraries' Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections|website=Atom.library.yorju.ca|accessdate=January 18, 2020}}</ref> Dr. Crawford (Casey) Jones<ref name=\"atom.library.yorku.ca\" />\n | years_active        = 1961-present\n | dates               = July 3\u20135 (2020 dates)\n | genre               = [[Music festival]], [[arts festival]]\n | website             = {{url|https://www.mariposafolk.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Mariposa Folk Festival''' is a Canadian [[music festival]] founded in 1961 in [[Orillia, Ontario]]. It was held in Orillia for three years before being banned because of disturbances by festival-goers.<ref name=\"CdnEncy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/mariposa-folk-festival-emc/ |title=Mariposa Folk Festival |publisher=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |date= |accessdate=2016-02-10}}</ref> After being held in various places in [[Ontario]] for a few decades, it returned to Orillia in 2000. Ruth Jones, her husband Dr. Crawford Jones, brother David Major and Pete McGarvey organized the first Mariposa Folk Festival in August 1961. The inaugural event, covered by the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]], featured all Canadian performers. The festival grew in popularity, size and rowdiness until the popularity of the 1963 festival (with over 8,000 advance tickets sold), and the lack of sufficient security, led to a backlash from town locals.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Guitars, Goatees and Girls -- Famous Folk and Folksong Fans Flock for Festival Fun and Frolic for Third Time TO Mariposa|last=Marshall|first=Bill|date=1963-08-10|work=Toronto Daily Star|last2=Taylor|first2=Gil|page=19|id = {{ProQuest|1427335494}}}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=17,000 Paid To Enjoy Mariposa Show|last=Marshall|first=Bill|date=1963-08-12|last2=Taylor|first2=Gil|page=16|id = {{ProQuest|1427336416}}}}</ref> The city of Orillia secured a court injunction to prevent the festival from continuing in the town limits.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Curious Ethics [letter to the editor]|last=Pape|first=P. Jeffrey|date=1963-12-12|work=Toronto Daily Star|page=6|id = {{ProQuest|1430676791}}}}</ref> The first festival held in the [[Toronto]] area, in 1964, was at Maple Leaf Stadium. The subsequent three festivals were held at Innis Lake in [[Caledon, Ontario|Caledon]], northwest of the city. In the 1970s it was held on the [[Toronto Islands]] before shifting to [[Harbourfront (Toronto)]] and Bathurst Street and later [[Molson Park]] in [[Barrie]]. In 2000, the Mariposa Folk Festival was invited back to Orillia by city councilors Tim Lauer and Don Evans. The festival continues to be held in Orillia. As well as folk music, the festival highlights other aspects of folk culture including dance, crafts, storytelling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n==Festival timeline==\nThe Mariposa Folk Festival has been held in these Ontario locations with these artistic directors:<ref name=\"CdnEncy\" />\n* 1961 &ndash; 64, Oval Park, Orillia\n* 1964, [[Maple Leaf Stadium]], Toronto\n* 1965 &ndash; 67, Innis Lake, [[Caledon, Ontario|Caledon]]\n* 1968 &ndash; 79, [[Toronto Island|Centre Island]], Toronto\n* 1980 &ndash; 81, ''no festival''\n* 1982, [[Harbourfront Centre|Harbourfront]], Toronto\n*1983, small event at Cristie Pits park, Toronto<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Hill, Michael, 1952-|title=Mariposa Folk Festival : a history|date=30 May 2017|publisher=|isbn=978-1-4597-3773-0|location=Toronto|pages=151, 170|oclc=953981707}}</ref>\n* 1984 &ndash; 91, [[Molson Park]], [[Barrie, Ontario|Barrie]]\n* 1992 &ndash; [[Ontario Place (theme park)|Ontario Place]], Toronto\n* 1993 &ndash; 1995, Olympic Island & Downtown, Toronto\n* 1996, Annie Williams Park, Bracebridge, and Victoria Park, Cobourg<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.orilliapacket.com/2009/07/11/digest |title=DIGEST &#124; Orillia Packet and Times |website=Orilliapacket.com |date=2009-07-11 |accessdate=2016-02-10}}</ref>\n* 1997, Annie Williams Park, Bracebridge\n*1998 - Bracebridge<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hill, Michael, 1952-|title=Mariposa Folk Festival : a history|date=30 May 2017|publisher=|isbn=978-1-4597-3773-0|location=Toronto|pages=140|oclc=953981707}}</ref> \n* 1999, Parkdale, Toronto\n* 2000 &ndash; present, Tudhope Park, Orillia\n\nArtistic directors:\n* 1961 - 64, Ted Schaefer\n* 1964 &ndash; 77, [[Estelle Klein]]\n* 1978, [[Ken Whiteley]]\n* 1979, [[Estelle Klein]]\n* 1982, Tim Harrison\n* 1984, [[Michael Cooney]]\n* 1985, [[Ian Bell (musician)|Ian Bell]]\n* 1986, Rick Bauer\n* 1987 &ndash; 88, Drago Maleiner\n* 1989 - 92, Richard Flohil <ref name=\":0\" />\n*1993 - 94, David Warren <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mariposafolk.com/archives/|title=Mariposa Folk Foundation {{!}} Archives|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n*1995, Jeff Cohen <ref name=\":1\" />\n*1996, Artistic Committee: David Warren, Dianne Myers, Karen Carlson-Oriotis, Randi Fratkin <ref name=\":1\" />\n*1997, Neil Hutchinson <ref name=\":1\" />\n*2000 - 2006, Randi Fratkin <ref name=\":0\" />\n* 2006 - 2017, Mike Hill\n* 2017 - Present, Liz Scott<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mariposafolk.com/mariposa-folk-foundation-appoints-new-artistic-director/|title=Mariposa Folk Foundation {{!}} Mariposa Folk Foundation Appoints a New Artistic Director|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, over the years there have been some alternative concerts and festivals, splinter groups, sub-festivals, and spin-offs,<ref name=\"CdnEncy\" /> such as Mariposa-in-the-City in Toronto in 2000.<ref>\"Tonight in T.O.\", ''The Toronto Star'', 22 June 2000</ref>\n\n== Early years ==\nThe idea for the Mariposa Folk Festival was created by Ruth McVeigh and her husband Dr. Casey Jones, after hearing a presentation by John Fisher.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atom.library.yorku.ca/index.php/ruth-mcveigh-fonds|title=Ruth McVeigh fonds - York University Libraries' Clara Thomas Archives &amp; Special Collections|website=atom.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> The name for the festival was borrowed from [[Stephen Leacock]]'s Book ''[[Sunshine Sketches of a Little Town]]'', which was inspired by the town of Orillia.<ref name=\"archives.library.yorku.ca\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1961|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nMariposa Folk Festival was held for the first time in 1961.\n\nIn 1964 the festival moved unexpectedly to Toronto. Backlash from Orillia and Medonte township community members prevented the festival from continuing in its original location. Due to these circumstances as well as inclement weather, many people who had bought tickets to the festival did not attend.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1964|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966 the festival's format changed, under the direction of Estelle Klein. It became more workshop-based and featured multiple stages so that different performances could occur simultaneously.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1966|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n1968 was the first year that the festival started on a Friday night. It was advertised with a focus on workshops rather than on headlining acts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1968|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 1969 CBC filmed throughout the weekend of the festival, and created a documentary entitled \u201cMariposa: A Folk Festival\u201d, which aired on September 28, 1969.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1969|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n== 1970s ==\nIn 1970 the \"Native People area\" at the festival was expanded, and was a success with festival visitors. This year also featured workshops investigating instrumental styles, music of specific regions and song exchanges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1970|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971 there were no evening concerts or main stage performances. The festival was fully focused on workshops and small stage performances in order to promote smaller acts as well as already well known performers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1971|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nThe 1972 festival experienced heavy rainfall, but that did not affect festival attendance. Some well known musicians came to watch the festival including Joni Mitchell, Neil Young, Gordon Lightfoot, Bob Dylan and Jackson Browne and some of them were interested in performing. The festival organizers were unsure if they should include these performers because the festival was no longer focused on big name acts. Ultimately, Murry McLauchlan offered Joni Mitchell part of his performance time. Bruce Cockburn did the same for Neil Young.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1972|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\nThe 1973 festival featured musicians from around the world including Bai Konte from West Africa, Martin Carthy from England, Ardoin Family from Louisiana in the United States and the Boys of the Lough from Ulster and North England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1973|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\n1975 was [[International Women's Year|International Women's year]], so the festival added many more female performers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1975|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976 the festival received a government grant so that they could include a special group of Indigenous performers from the prairies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1976|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 1977 the festival focused on the origins of North American folk music. The large variety of music was represented under four themes: black, Spanish, francophone and English.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1977|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\nThe 1979 festival featured a special pavilion of Labrador craftspeople, musicians and storytellers. It also increased its folk music activities for children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1979|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\n==50th anniversary==\nIn 2010, Mariposa celebrated its 50th festival by fielding a lineup of classic Mariposa artists and young developing talent. [[Gordon Lightfoot]], [[Murray McLauchlan]], [[Ian and Sylvia]], and [[The Whiteley Brothers]] took the main stage on the festival's final day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/music/story/2010/07/05/mariposa-online-archive.html |title=Mariposa Looks Back at 50 Years of Folk Fest |date=2010-07-06|accessdate=July 26, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709173722/http://www.cbc.ca/arts/music/story/2010/07/05/mariposa-online-archive.html |archivedate=July 9, 2010 }}</ref> Three new performers passed an audition to perform via the \"up and coming showcase\" program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mariposafolk.com/index.php?show=showcase |title=Mariposa Folk Foundation &#124; The Grande Dame of Folk Festivals |website=Mariposafolk.com |date=2014-06-20 |accessdate=2016-02-10}}</ref> The 2010 edition also featured [[Jason Collett]] and [[Serena Ryder]], who headlined the mainstage on Friday and Saturday respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.simcoe.com/what's%20on/article/843816--mariposa-folk-festival-rocks-orillia-this-weekend |title=Mariposa Folk Festival rocks Orillia this weekend |website=Simcoe.com |date=2010-07-08 |accessdate=2016-02-10}}</ref>\n\nTo mark the 50th anniversary of the festival, [[York University|York University's]] [[Clara Thomas Archives and Special Collections]] launched an online exhibit highlighting a selection of archival material from the 1960s and 1970s.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://news.yorku.ca/2010/07/05/mariposa-archives-at-york-u-reveal-folk-festival%E2%80%99s-small-details-and-big-performances/| title = Mariposa archives at York U reveal folk festival's small details and big performances| last = Walls | first = Janice| date = July 5, 2010 | website = News.yorku.ca| publisher  = [[York University]] | accessdate = January 2, 2015}}</ref> York acquired the Mariposa Folk Fest archives, which includes sound recordings and publicity documents, in 2007.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://news.yorku.ca/2007/06/06/york-university-acquires-mariposa-folk-fest-archives/| title = York University acquires Mariposa Folk Fest archives| last = Marnoch | first = Keith| date = June 6, 2007 | website = News.yorku.ca|publisher  = [[York University]] | accessdate = January 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Notable performers ==\n*[[Jackson Browne]]<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1972|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n*[[Bruce Cockburn]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1974|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n*[[Leonard Cohen]]<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1967|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n*[[Bob Dylan]]<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n*[[Edith Fowke]]<ref name=\"archives.library.yorku.ca\"/>\n*[[Gordon Lightfoot]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1962|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n*[[Joni Mitchell]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1965|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n*[[Alanis Obomsawin]]<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/>\n*[[Buffy Sainte-Marie|Buffy Saint-Marie]]<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n*[[Neil Young]]<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n*[[John Prine]]<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n== Mariposa in the Schools ==\nIn the mid-1970s the Mariposa Folk Festival began featuring children's concerts and musical workshops. In addition to this, the year round program \"Mariposa in the Schools\" was created in order to bring folk musicians to local Ontario schools for musical programming.<ref name=\"archives.library.yorku.ca\"/> The Mariposa in the Schools program ended in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mariposaintheschools.ca/|title=Mariposa in the Schools \u2013 Ontario young people to world oral cultural traditions|website=mariposaintheschools.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> However, the Festival continues to have children's programming on the festival weekend in their Folkplay area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mariposafolk.com/the-festival/folkplay/|title=Mariposa Folk Foundation {{!}} Folkplay|website=Mariposafolk.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\nIn 1977, editors Bill Usher and Linda Page-Harpa published an anthology in celebration of the festival titled ''\"For what time I am in this world\" : stories from Mariposa''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\"For what time I am in this world\" : stories from Mariposa.|last=Usher|first=Bill|last2=Page-Harpa|first2=Linda|publisher=P. Martin Associates|year=1977|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn  2013, Sija Tsai published a doctoral thesis on the history of the festival, titled ''Mariposa Folk Festival: The Sounds, Sights, and Costs of a Fifty-Year Road Trip.''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://yorkspace.library.yorku.ca/xmlui/bitstream/10315/31317/1/Tsai_Sija_M_2013_PhD.pdf|title=Mariposa Folk Festival: The Sounds, Sights, and Costs of a Fifty-Year Road Trip|last=Tsai|first=Sija|publisher=York University|year=2013|isbn=|location=Toronto|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Michael Hill, the artistic director and the vice-president of Mariposa, and an organizer with the festival since 2000, published a book on the festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dundurn.com/books/Mariposa-Folk-Festival|title=The Mariposa Folk Festival: A History|last=|first=|date=|website=Dundurn.com|access-date=January 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.efootage.com/view_clip.php?clip_id=25942 Mariposa '75] moving images\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050418113847/http://www.jmdl.com/library/print.cfm?id=1085 ''Toronto Star''] article, 1987\n* [https://atom.library.yorku.ca/index.php/mariposa-folk-foundation-fonds Mariposa Folk Foundation archives], [[Clara Thomas Archives and Special Collections]], [[York University Libraries]], [[Toronto, Ontario]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{coord|44.6071|N|79.3872|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Folk festivals in Canada]]\n[[Category:Music festivals in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Orillia]]\n[[Category:Recurring events disestablished in 1980]]\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 1982]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Simcoe County]]\n[[Category:Music festivals established in 1961]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Folk music festival}}\n{{other uses|Mariposa (disambiguation)}}\n{{infobox music festival \n | music_festival_name = Mariposa Folk Festival\n | image               = Mariposa 1975 Album Cover.jpg\n | caption             = Mariposa 1975 album cover\n | location            = [[Tudhope Park]],<br />[[Orillia, Ontario]], Canada\n | founders            = Ruth Jones (nee McVeigh),<ref name=\"atom.library.yorku.ca\">{{cite web|url=https://atom.library.yorku.ca/index.php/mariposa-folk-foundation-fonds|title= Mariposa Folk Foundation fonds - York University Libraries' Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections|website=Atom.library.yorju.ca|accessdate=January 18, 2020}}</ref> Dr. Crawford (Casey) Jones<ref name=\"atom.library.yorku.ca\" />\n | years_active        = 1961-present\n | dates               = July 3\u20135 (2020 dates)\n | genre               = [[Music festival]], [[arts festival]]\n | website             = {{url|https://www.mariposafolk.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Mariposa Folk Festival''' is a Canadian [[music festival]] founded in 1961 in [[Orillia, Ontario]]. It was held in Orillia for three years before being banned because of disturbances by festival-goers.<ref name=\"CdnEncy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/mariposa-folk-festival-emc/ |title=Mariposa Folk Festival |publisher=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |date= |accessdate=2016-02-10}}</ref> After being held in various places in [[Ontario]] for a few decades, it returned to Orillia in 2000. Ruth Jones, her husband Dr. Crawford Jones, brother David Major and Pete McGarvey organized the first Mariposa Folk Festival in August 1961. The inaugural event, covered by the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]], featured all Canadian performers. The festival grew in popularity, size and rowdiness until the popularity of the 1963 festival (with over 8,000 advance tickets sold), and the lack of sufficient security, led to a backlash from town locals.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Guitars, Goatees and Girls -- Famous Folk and Folksong Fans Flock for Festival Fun and Frolic for Third Time TO Mariposa|last=Marshall|first=Bill|date=1963-08-10|work=Toronto Daily Star|last2=Taylor|first2=Gil|page=19|id = {{ProQuest|1427335494}}}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=17,000 Paid To Enjoy Mariposa Show|last=Marshall|first=Bill|date=1963-08-12|last2=Taylor|first2=Gil|page=16|id = {{ProQuest|1427336416}}}}</ref> The city of Orillia secured a court injunction to prevent the festival from continuing in the town limits.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Curious Ethics [letter to the editor]|last=Pape|first=P. Jeffrey|date=1963-12-12|work=Toronto Daily Star|page=6|id = {{ProQuest|1430676791}}}}</ref> The first festival held in the [[Toronto]] area, in 1964, was at Maple Leaf Stadium. The subsequent three festivals were held at Innis Lake in [[Caledon, Ontario|Caledon]], northwest of the city. In the 1970s it was held on the [[Toronto Islands]] before shifting to [[Harbourfront (Toronto)]] and Bathurst Street and later [[Molson Park]] in [[Barrie]]. In 2000, the Mariposa Folk Festival was invited back to Orillia by city councilors Tim Lauer and Don Evans. The festival continues to be held in Orillia. As well as folk music, the festival highlights other aspects of folk culture including dance, crafts, storytelling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n==Festival timeline==\nThe Mariposa Folk Festival has been held in these Ontario locations with these artistic directors:<ref name=\"CdnEncy\" />\n* 1961 &ndash; 64, Oval Park, Orillia\n* 1964, [[Maple Leaf Stadium]], Toronto\n* 1965 &ndash; 67, Innis Lake, [[Caledon, Ontario|Caledon]]\n* 1968 &ndash; 79, [[Toronto Island|Centre Island]], Toronto\n* 1980 &ndash; 81, ''no festival''\n* 1982, [[Harbourfront Centre|Harbourfront]], Toronto\n*1983, small event at Cristie Pits park, Toronto<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Hill, Michael, 1952-|title=Mariposa Folk Festival : a history|date=30 May 2017|publisher=|isbn=978-1-4597-3773-0|location=Toronto|pages=151, 170|oclc=953981707}}</ref>\n* 1984 &ndash; 91, [[Molson Park]], [[Barrie, Ontario|Barrie]]\n* 1992 &ndash; [[Ontario Place (theme park)|Ontario Place]], Toronto\n* 1993 &ndash; 1995, Olympic Island & Downtown, Toronto\n* 1996, Annie Williams Park, Bracebridge, and Victoria Park, Cobourg<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.orilliapacket.com/2009/07/11/digest |title=DIGEST &#124; Orillia Packet and Times |website=Orilliapacket.com |date=2009-07-11 |accessdate=2016-02-10}}</ref>\n* 1997, Annie Williams Park, Bracebridge\n*1998 - Bracebridge<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hill, Michael, 1952-|title=Mariposa Folk Festival : a history|date=30 May 2017|publisher=|isbn=978-1-4597-3773-0|location=Toronto|pages=140|oclc=953981707}}</ref> \n* 1999, Parkdale, Toronto\n* 2000 &ndash; present, Tudhope Park, Orillia\n\nArtistic directors:\n* 1961 - 64, Ted Schaefer\n* 1964 &ndash; 77, [[Estelle Klein]]\n* 1978, [[Ken Whiteley]]\n* 1979, [[Estelle Klein]]\n* 1982, Tim Harrison\n* 1984, [[Michael Cooney]]\n* 1985, [[Ian Bell (musician)|Ian Bell]]\n* 1986, Rick Bauer\n* 1987 &ndash; 88, Drago Maleiner\n* 1989 - 92, Richard Flohil <ref name=\":0\" />\n*1993 - 94, David Warren <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mariposafolk.com/archives/|title=Mariposa Folk Foundation {{!}} Archives|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n*1995, Jeff Cohen <ref name=\":1\" />\n*1996, Artistic Committee: David Warren, Dianne Myers, Karen Carlson-Oriotis, Randi Fratkin <ref name=\":1\" />\n*1997, Neil Hutchinson <ref name=\":1\" />\n*2000 - 2006, Randi Fratkin <ref name=\":0\" />\n* 2006 - 2017, Mike Hill\n* 2017 - Present, Liz Scott<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mariposafolk.com/mariposa-folk-foundation-appoints-new-artistic-director/|title=Mariposa Folk Foundation {{!}} Mariposa Folk Foundation Appoints a New Artistic Director|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, over the years there have been some alternative concerts and festivals, splinter groups, sub-festivals, and spin-offs,<ref name=\"CdnEncy\" /> such as Mariposa-in-the-City in Toronto in 2000.<ref>\"Tonight in T.O.\", ''The Toronto Star'', 22 June 2000</ref>\n\n== Early years ==\nThe idea for the Mariposa Folk Festival was created by Ruth McVeigh and her husband Dr. Casey Jones, after hearing a presentation by John Fisher.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atom.library.yorku.ca/index.php/ruth-mcveigh-fonds|title=Ruth McVeigh fonds - York University Libraries' Clara Thomas Archives &amp; Special Collections|website=atom.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> The name for the festival was borrowed from [[Stephen Leacock]]'s Book ''[[Sunshine Sketches of a Little Town]]'', which was inspired by the town of Orillia.<ref name=\"archives.library.yorku.ca\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1961|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nMariposa Folk Festival was held for the first time in 1961.\n\nIn 1964 the festival moved unexpectedly to Toronto. Backlash from Orillia and Medonte township community members prevented the festival from continuing in its original location. Due to these circumstances as well as inclement weather, many people who had bought tickets to the festival did not attend.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1964|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966 the festival's format changed, under the direction of Estelle Klein. It became more workshop-based and featured multiple stages so that different performances could occur simultaneously.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1966|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n1968 was the first year that the festival started on a Friday night. It was advertised with a focus on workshops rather than on headlining acts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1968|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 1969 CBC filmed throughout the weekend of the festival, and created a documentary entitled \u201cMariposa: A Folk Festival\u201d, which aired on September 28, 1969.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1969|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n== 1970s ==\nIn 1970 the \"Native People area\" at the festival was expanded, and was a success with festival visitors. This year also featured workshops investigating instrumental styles, music of specific regions and song exchanges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1970|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971 there were no evening concerts or main stage performances. The festival was fully focused on workshops and small stage performances in order to promote smaller acts as well as already well known performers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1971|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nThe 1972 festival experienced heavy rainfall, but that did not affect festival attendance. Some well known musicians came to watch the festival including Joni Mitchell, Neil Young, Gordon Lightfoot, Bob Dylan and Jackson Browne and some of them were interested in performing. The festival organizers were unsure if they should include these performers because the festival was no longer focused on big name acts. Ultimately, Murry McLauchlan offered Joni Mitchell part of his performance time. Bruce Cockburn did the same for Neil Young.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1972|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\nThe 1973 festival featured musicians from around the world including Bai Konte from West Africa, Martin Carthy from England, Ardoin Family from Louisiana in the United States and the Boys of the Lough from Ulster and North England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1973|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\n1975 was [[International Women's Year|International Women's year]], so the festival added many more female performers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1975|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976 the festival received a government grant so that they could include a special group of Indigenous performers from the prairies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1976|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 1977 the festival focused on the origins of North American folk music. The large variety of music was represented under four themes: black, Spanish, francophone and English.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1977|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\nThe 1979 festival featured a special pavilion of Labrador craftspeople, musicians and storytellers. It also increased its folk music activities for children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1979|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\n==50th anniversary==\nIn 2010, Mariposa celebrated its 50th festival by fielding a lineup of classic Mariposa artists and young developing talent. [[Gordon Lightfoot]], [[Murray McLauchlan]], [[Ian and Sylvia]], and [[The Whiteley Brothers]] took the main stage on the festival's final day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/music/story/2010/07/05/mariposa-online-archive.html |title=Mariposa Looks Back at 50 Years of Folk Fest |date=2010-07-06|accessdate=July 26, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709173722/http://www.cbc.ca/arts/music/story/2010/07/05/mariposa-online-archive.html |archivedate=July 9, 2010 }}</ref> Three new performers passed an audition to perform via the \"up and coming showcase\" program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mariposafolk.com/index.php?show=showcase |title=Mariposa Folk Foundation &#124; The Grande Dame of Folk Festivals |website=Mariposafolk.com |date=2014-06-20 |accessdate=2016-02-10}}</ref> The 2010 edition also featured [[Jason Collett]] and [[Serena Ryder]], who headlined the mainstage on Friday and Saturday respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.simcoe.com/what's%20on/article/843816--mariposa-folk-festival-rocks-orillia-this-weekend |title=Mariposa Folk Festival rocks Orillia this weekend |website=Simcoe.com |date=2010-07-08 |accessdate=2016-02-10}}</ref>\n\nTo mark the 50th anniversary of the festival, [[York University|York University's]] [[Clara Thomas Archives and Special Collections]] launched an online exhibit highlighting a selection of archival material from the 1960s and 1970s.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://news.yorku.ca/2010/07/05/mariposa-archives-at-york-u-reveal-folk-festival%E2%80%99s-small-details-and-big-performances/| title = Mariposa archives at York U reveal folk festival's small details and big performances| last = Walls | first = Janice| date = July 5, 2010 | website = News.yorku.ca| publisher  = [[York University]] | accessdate = January 2, 2015}}</ref> York acquired the Mariposa Folk Fest archives, which includes sound recordings and publicity documents, in 2007.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://news.yorku.ca/2007/06/06/york-university-acquires-mariposa-folk-fest-archives/| title = York University acquires Mariposa Folk Fest archives| last = Marnoch | first = Keith| date = June 6, 2007 | website = News.yorku.ca|publisher  = [[York University]] | accessdate = January 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Notable performers ==\n*[[Jackson Browne]]<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1972|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n*[[Bruce Cockburn]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1974|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n*[[Leonard Cohen]]<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1967|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n*[[Bob Dylan]]<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n*[[Edith Fowke]]<ref name=\"archives.library.yorku.ca\"/>\n*[[Gordon Lightfoot]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1962|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n*[[Joni Mitchell]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.library.yorku.ca/exhibits/show/mariposa/1965|title=Mariposa : celebrating Canadian folk music \u00b7 York University Libraries {{!}} Clara Thomas Archives & Special Collections online exhibits|website=archives.library.yorku.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n*[[Alanis Obomsawin]]<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/>\n*[[Buffy Sainte-Marie|Buffy Saint-Marie]]<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n*[[Neil Young]]<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n== Mariposa in the Schools ==\nIn the mid-1970s the Mariposa Folk Festival began featuring children's concerts and musical workshops. In addition to this, the year round program \"Mariposa in the Schools\" was created in order to bring folk musicians to local Ontario schools for musical programming.<ref name=\"archives.library.yorku.ca\"/> The Mariposa in the Schools program ended in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mariposaintheschools.ca/|title=Mariposa in the Schools \u2013 Ontario young people to world oral cultural traditions|website=mariposaintheschools.ca|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> However, the Festival continues to have children's programming on the festival weekend in their Folkplay area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mariposafolk.com/the-festival/folkplay/|title=Mariposa Folk Foundation {{!}} Folkplay|website=Mariposafolk.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\nIn 1977, editors Bill Usher and Linda Page-Harpa published an anthology in celebration of the festival titled ''\"For what time I am in this world\" : stories from Mariposa''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\"For what time I am in this world\" : stories from Mariposa.|last=Usher|first=Bill|last2=Page-Harpa|first2=Linda|publisher=P. Martin Associates|year=1977|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn  2013, Sija Tsai published a doctoral thesis on the history of the festival, titled ''Mariposa Folk Festival: The Sounds, Sights, and Costs of a Fifty-Year Road Trip.''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://yorkspace.library.yorku.ca/xmlui/bitstream/10315/31317/1/Tsai_Sija_M_2013_PhD.pdf|title=Mariposa Folk Festival: The Sounds, Sights, and Costs of a Fifty-Year Road Trip|last=Tsai|first=Sija|publisher=York University|year=2013|isbn=|location=Toronto|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Michael Hill, the artistic director and the vice-president of Mariposa, and an organizer with the festival since 2000, published a book on the festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dundurn.com/books/Mariposa-Folk-Festival|title=The Mariposa Folk Festival: A History|last=|first=|date=|website=Dundurn.com|access-date=January 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.efootage.com/view_clip.php?clip_id=25942 Mariposa '75] moving images\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050418113847/http://www.jmdl.com/library/print.cfm?id=1085 ''Toronto Star''] article, 1987\n* [https://atom.library.yorku.ca/index.php/mariposa-folk-foundation-fonds Mariposa Folk Foundation archives], [[Clara Thomas Archives and Special Collections]], [[York University Libraries]], [[Toronto, Ontario]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{coord|44.6071|N|79.3872|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Folk festivals in Canada]]\n[[Category:Music festivals in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Orillia]]\n[[Category:Recurring events disestablished in 1980]]\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 1982]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Simcoe County]]\n[[Category:Music festivals established in 1961]]\n", "name_user": "Tonymnace", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added performer John Prine", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mariposa_Folk_Festival"}
{"title_page": "Gisela Stuart", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = GiselaStuartOct2008.jpg\n| caption = Stuart in 2008\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Gisela Stuart\n| honorific-suffix = \n| office = [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] [[Department of Health and Social Care|for Health]]\n| parliament = \n| predecessor = [[Helene Hayman, Baroness Hayman|The Baroness Hayman]]\n| successor = [[Ann Keen]] {{small|(2007)}}\n| term_start = 29 July 1999\n| term_end = 7 June 2001\n| birth_name = Gisela Gschaider\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1955|11|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Velden (Vils)|Velden]], [[Bavaria]], [[West Germany]]\n| citizenship = British\n| spouse = {{ubl|{{marriage|Robert Stuart<br />|1980|2000|end=div}}|{{marriage|Derek Scott<br />|2010|2012|end=d.}}}}\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (Until 2019)\n| relations = \n| children = 2\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = {{ubl|[[University of London]]|[[University of Birmingham]]<ref name=\"Jones\">C. K. Jones, ''The People's University'' (London, 2008), p. 33</ref>}}\n| occupation = Chair, [[Change Britain]]\n| profession = \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br /> for [[Birmingham Edgbaston (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Edgbaston]]\n| term_end1 = 3 May 2017\n| term_start1 = 1 May 1997\n| predecessor1 = [[Jill Knight]]\n| successor1 = [[Preet Gill]]\n| primeminister = [[Tony Blair]]\n}}\n'''Gisela Stuart''' (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' '''Gschaider'''; born 26 November 1955) is a former British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician, who served as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Birmingham Edgbaston (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Edgbaston]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] until stepping down at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]]. Born and raised in [[West Germany]], she has lived in the UK since 1974.\n\nStuart was Chair of the [[Vote Leave]] Campaign Committee and was one of its most high-profile figures, along with the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MPs [[Boris Johnson]] and [[Michael Gove]]. The Vote Leave campaign was successful in achieving its goal at the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]] of winning a majority of votes for Leave.\n\nSince September 2016, Stuart has served as Chair of Vote Leave's successor organisation, [[Change Britain]].\n\nAfter she left Parliament, Stuart was appointed by the Conservative government as Chair of [[Wilton Park]], an executive agency of the UK Foreign Office dedicated to conflict resolution in international relations, in October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/fco-announce-new-chair-of-wilton-park|title=Foreign & Commonwealth Office announce new Chair of Wilton Park|website=GOV.UK|access-date=25 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125073909/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/fco-announce-new-chair-of-wilton-park|archive-date=25 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nStuart is a member of the Steering Committee of the Constitution Reform Group (CRG)<ref>https://www.constitutionreformgroup.co.uk/</ref>, a cross-party organisation chaired by [[Robert Gascoyne-Cecil, 7th Marquess of Salisbury]], which seeks a new constitutional settlement in the [[UK]] by way of a new Act of Union<ref>https://services.parliament.uk/Bills/2017-19/actofunion.html</ref>. The Constitution Reform Group's new Act of Union Bill<ref>https://services.parliament.uk/Bills/2017-19/actofunion.html</ref> was introduced as a Private Member's Bill by [[Lord Lisvane]] in the [[House of Lords]] on 9 October 2018, when it received a formal first reading. The Bill has been described by the BBC as \"one to watch\"<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50786212</ref> in the current Parliament.\n\n==Early life==\nGisela Gschaider was born in [[Velden (Vils)|Velden]], [[Bavaria]], [[West Germany]] on 26 November 1955 to Martin and Liane Gschaider.<ref name=UKWW>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-36583/version/2|title=Stuart, Rt Hon. Gisela (Gschaider)|accessdate=29 November 2019|publisher=A & C Black}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/02/standing-parliament-gisela-stuart-mp-birmingham-edgbaston/|title=Why I'm standing down from Parliament: Gisela Stuart, MP for Birmingham, Edgbaston|last=Prince|first=Rosa|date=2 June 2017|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=29 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306143648/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/02/standing-parliament-gisela-stuart-mp-birmingham-edgbaston/|archive-date=6 March 2019|url-status=live}}{{subscription}}</ref> She attended the Staatliche Realschule Vilsbiburg in [[Vilsbiburg]].<ref name=UKWW/>\n\nAfter doing an apprenticeship in bookselling, she moved to the UK in 1974 in order to improve her English and to do a Business Studies course at [[Manchester Metropolitan University|Manchester Polytechnic]].<ref>{{cite news|date=30 November 2016|title=\"There is more to write about\": Labour eurosceptic Gisela Stuart accuses journalists of hamming up Brexit hate crime|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/brexit/2016/11/there-more-write-about-labour-eurosceptic-gisela-stuart-accuses-journalists|newspaper=[[New Statesman]]|first=Anoosh|last=Chakelian|access-date=18 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031530/https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/brexit/2016/11/there-more-write-about-labour-eurosceptic-gisela-stuart-accuses-journalists|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She was deputy director of the 1983 [[London Book Fair]].<ref name=vote2001>{{cite web|accessdate=18 November 2017|title=Vote2001: Candidates \u2013 Gisela Stuart|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/candidates/candidates/0/05305.stm|website=news.bbc.co.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040523014857/http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/candidates/candidates/0/05305.stm|archive-date=23 May 2004|url-status=live}}</ref> Stuart subsequently relocated to the [[The Midlands|Midlands]].\n\nShe graduated from the [[University of London]] with an [[LLB]] in 1993, having studied through the [[University of London External System]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.londoninternational.ac.uk/people/gisela-stuart-graduated-1993|title=Gisela Stuart - graduated 1993 {{!}} University of London International Programmes|date=27 September 2011|website=www.londoninternational.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=6 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407055511/http://www.londoninternational.ac.uk/people/gisela-stuart-graduated-1993|archive-date=7 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> She began researching for a PhD in trust law (ownership of pension funds) at the [[University of Birmingham]] while she also lectured Law to [[Association of Accounting Technicians|AAT]] students at Worcestershire College, but did not complete her PhD and instead went into politics full-time.<ref name=\"Jones\" />\n\nIn 1994, as Gisela Gschaider, Stuart contested the [[Worcestershire and South Warwickshire (European Parliament constituency)|Worcester and South Warwickshire]] seat at the [[European elections]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europeaninstitute.bg/page.php?category=117&id=228&page=2 |title=European Institute |publisher=Europeaninstitute.bg |date=28 August 2007 |accessdate=2 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324061112/http://www.europeaninstitute.bg/page.php?category=117&id=228&page=2 |archive-date=24 March 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> for Labour. She lost by 1,000 votes.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nIn 1995, Stuart was selected as Labour's parliamentary candidate for the [[Birmingham Edgbaston (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Edgbaston]] constituency. The constituency, which had once been held by former Conservative [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Neville Chamberlain]] (1937\u201340), had returned only [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MPs for 99 years. The sitting Conservative MP at the time, Dame [[Jill Knight]], was retiring after 31 years. On [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1 May 1997]], Stuart was elected as the first-ever Labour MP for the constituency, making it one of a succession of traditional Conservative seats to fall to Labour control in a landslide victory for the party. Stuart's victory was the first televised Labour gain of the evening.\n\nDuring the first [[Tony Blair]] ministry, Stuart served on the Social Security Select Committee and in 1998 as PPS to [[Home Office]] Minister of State [[Paul Boateng]], before joining the government in 1999 as Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Health. Stuart left this post in the reshuffle that followed after the [[2001 United Kingdom general election]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.giselastuartmp.co.uk/biography/ |title=Gisela Stuart Biography |accessdate=1 April 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915010850/http://www.giselastuartmp.co.uk/biography/ |archivedate=15 September 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Her [[election agent]] in that election was [[John Clancy (Labour politician)|John Clancy]], who became leader of [[Birmingham City Council]] in 2015.<ref name=\"Elkes-1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/find-out-new-leader-birmingham-10489560|title=Find out all about the new leader of Birmingham City Council John Clancy|last=Elkes|first=Neil|date=23 November 2015|work=[[Birmingham Mail]]|accessdate=1 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125033020/http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/find-out-new-leader-birmingham-10489560|archive-date=25 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn Blair's second ministry, Stuart was appointed as one of the UK Parliamentary Representatives to the [[Convention on the Future of Europe|European Convention]], which was tasked with drawing up a new constitution for the European Union. In this capacity, Stuart also served as one of the thirteen members of the Convention's Presidium - the steering group responsible for managing the business of the Convention.\n\nWhen the draft Constitution emerged, Stuart was one of the most trenchant critics of the proposal, stating that it had been drawn up by a \"self-selected group of the European political elite\" determined to deepen European integration. She subsequently expounded these views in a 2004 [[Fabian Society]] pamphlet, ''The Making of Europe's Constitution''. Consequently, she has argued in favour of British withdrawal from the European Union, becoming one of the leading [[Euroscepticism in the United Kingdom|Eurosceptic]] figures in the Labour Party.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Labour MP Gisela Stuart: UK should leave European Union|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20124699|website = BBC News|access-date = 14 February 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160111201703/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20124699|archive-date = 11 January 2016|url-status = live}}</ref> In the BBC's two-hour televised debate on the EU referendum, Stuart appeared on the \"Leave\" panel, along with the Conservative MPs [[Andrea Leadsom]] and [[Boris Johnson]].<ref>{{cite news|title=EU referendum: Leave and Remain clash in BBC Great Debate|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36582567|accessdate=1 April 2018|publisher=BBC News|date=22 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204034134/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36582567|archive-date=4 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2004, she became the only Labour MP who openly supported the re-election of [[George W. Bush]] at [[2004 US presidential election|that year's U.S. presidential election]], arguing \"you know where you stand with George and, in today's world, that's much better than rudderless leaders who drift with the prevailing wind\". She wrote that a victory for [[Democratic Party (US)|Democratic Party]] challenger, [[John Kerry]], would prompt \"victory celebrations among those who want to destroy liberal democracies. More terrorists and suicide bombers would step forward to become martyrs in their quest to destroy the West\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Hennessy |first=Patrick |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/1475512/Anti-Kerry-remarks-by-Labour-MP-put-Blair-on-the-spot.html |title=Anti-Kerry remarks by Labour MP put Blair on the spot |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=31 October 2004 |accessdate=2 December 2011 |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110417071438/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/1475512/Anti-Kerry-remarks-by-Labour-MP-put-Blair-on-the-spot.html |archive-date=17 April 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBetween 2001 and 2010, Stuart also served as a member of the House of Commons Select Committee on Foreign Affairs.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nShe retained her seat at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election]] but her majority was halved in both percentage and numerical terms. Despite the predictions of the pundits, Stuart went on to retain the seat at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], against a national tide of Labour defeat. The election resulted in the first hung parliament in 36 years, with the Conservatives having the most seats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.birmingham.gov.uk/general-election-2010 |title=Birmingham City Council: General Election 2010 |location=GB-BIR |publisher=Birmingham.gov.uk |date=6 May 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100508033256/http://www.birmingham.gov.uk/general-election-2010 |archive-date=8 May 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> It earned her the title of Survivor of the Year at ''The Spectator'' magazine's 2010 Parliamentarian of the Year awards, which was presented to her by the new Conservative Prime Minister, [[David Cameron]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giselastuartmp.co.uk/2010/12/survivor-of-the-year/ |title=Gisela Stuart Survivor of the Year Award |accessdate=20 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020202116/http://www.giselastuartmp.co.uk/2010/12/survivor-of-the-year/ |archivedate=20 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> She retained her seat at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election]] with a majority of 2,706 votes, more than double her majority from 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ms Gisela Stuart MP|url = http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/ms-gisela-stuart/296|website = UK Parliament|accessdate = 3 June 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150608180124/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/ms-gisela-stuart/296|archive-date = 8 June 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> She joined the Commons Select Committee on Defence.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nStuart is a signatory of the [[Henry Jackson Society]] principles, which promote the spread of [[liberal democracy]] across the world and the maintenance of a strong military with global expeditionary reach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.henryjacksonsociety.org/signatories.asp?pageid=36 |title=Signatories to the Statement of Principles |publisher=The Henry Jackson Society |date=28 November 2011 |accessdate=2 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808045304/http://www.henryjacksonsociety.org/signatories.asp?pageid=36 |archivedate=8 August 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She is the editor of the weekly political magazine ''[[The House (magazine)|The House]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/MP%27s+pounds+63,000+profit+home%3B+New+expenses+controversy+hits+Brum+MP...-a0215264008 |title=MP's pounds 63,000 profit home; New expenses controversy hits Brum MP Gisela |publisher=Thefreelibrary.com |accessdate=2 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006174515/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/MP%27s+pounds+63,000+profit+home%3B+New+expenses+controversy+hits+Brum+MP...-a0215264008 |archive-date=6 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nShe was sworn in as a member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]] in 2015, giving her the [[Honorific|honorific title]] \"[[The Right Honourable]]\" for life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/privy-council/privy-council-members/privy-counsellors/#s1|title=Privy Counsellors - Privy Council|website=privycouncil.independent.gov.uk|access-date=26 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713132409/https://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/privy-council/privy-council-members/privy-counsellors/#s1|archive-date=13 July 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSince 2015, she has been a Steering Committee member of the Constitution Reform Group (CRG), a cross-party pressure group of current and former politicians, academics, constitutional law experts, former officials in Parliament and government and ordinary citizens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.constitutionreformgroup.co.uk/|title=Home|website=Constitution Reform Group|access-date=15 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008092906/http://www.constitutionreformgroup.co.uk/|archive-date=8 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The CRG seeks a new constitutional settlement in the [[UK]] by way of a new Act of Union.<ref name=\"parliament.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://services.parliament.uk/bills/2017-19/actofunion.html|title=Act of Union Bill [HL] 2017-19 \u2014 UK Parliament|website=services.parliament.uk}}</ref>\n\nShe announced on 19 April 2017 that she would not seek re-election at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 snap general election]]. She was succeeded by [[Preet Gill]], a [[Labour and Co-operative]] politician, and the first female British [[Sikh]] MP.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kirkham|first=David|title=Preet Gill Confirmed As Labour Candidate For Edgbaston|url=http://www.redbrick.me/news/slider-news/preet-gill-confirmed-labour-candidate-edgbaston/|work=[[Redbrick (newspaper)|Redbrick]] (student newspaper)|publisher=[[University of Birmingham]]|date=29 April 2017|accessdate=18 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170512145343/http://www.redbrick.me/news/slider-news/preet-gill-confirmed-labour-candidate-edgbaston/|archive-date=12 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Stuart announced she would vote for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/exlabour-mp-gisela-stuart-urges-voters-to-back-boris-johnson-to-deliver-brexit-a4300506.html|title=Ex-Labour MP urges voters to back Boris Johnson to deliver Brexit|date=2019-11-29|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211111116/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/exlabour-mp-gisela-stuart-urges-voters-to-back-boris-johnson-to-deliver-brexit-a4300506.html|archive-date=11 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She remained a member of the Labour Party after the election.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2019/dec/30/labour-leadership-long-bailey-clive-lewis-corbyn-should-have-kept-fighting-for-remain-says-clive-lewis-live-news?page=with:block-5e09f1d48f08c397226423ab#block-5e09f1d48f08c397226423ab</ref>\n\n==Vote Leave==\nStuart served as Chair of the [[Vote Leave]], the body which was designated by the Electoral Commission as the official campaign in favour of [[Brexit|leaving the European Union]] in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum on European Union membership]]. Other spokespersons for Vote Leave included Conservative MPs [[Boris Johnson]] and [[Michael Gove]]. There were various other groups advocating for Leave, officially working independently of Vote Leave, including UKIP and the Labour Leave.\n\nStuart was the only{{according to whom|date=June 2019}} Labour MP in the official Vote Leave Campaign. Most of the other ten Labour MPs who went against the official Labour Party policy of supporting Remain, joined [[Labour Leave]], which had a less prominent role in the referendum.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.labourleave.org/board/ |title=Labour Leave Members |last=Labour |first=Leave |date=4 August 2016 |website=Labour Leave |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151216160434/http://labourleave.org/board/ |archive-date=16 December 2015 |url-status=dead |access-date=1 April 2018 }}</ref> Stuart was the only Labour MP to take part in the official events, such as the televised debates, on behalf of the Leave side.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/02/eu-referendum-tv-debates-when-where-watch-them|title=EU referendum debates: when and where to watch them|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=9 June 2016|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=28 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180329121701/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/02/eu-referendum-tv-debates-when-where-watch-them|archive-date=29 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> During the campaign she posed in front of a controversial campaign bus<ref>{{cite news|date=31 March 2019|title=Gobby Gisela|url=http://thesteepletimes.com/the-fog/gobby-gisela/|newspaper=The Steeple Times|access-date=22 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815072705/http://thesteepletimes.com/the-fog/gobby-gisela/|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> which was subsequently the object of legal disputes.<ref>{{cite news|date=14 May 2019|title=Boris Johnson is facing a legal challenge|url=https://www.indy100.com/article/boris-johnson-court-brexit-nhs-bus-vote-leave-westminster-magistrates-8912701|newspaper=The Independent|access-date=22 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822175051/https://www.indy100.com/article/boris-johnson-court-brexit-nhs-bus-vote-leave-westminster-magistrates-8912701|archive-date=22 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nStuart's own constituency of Birmingham Edgbaston voted to Remain in the EU.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/eu-referendum-results-birmingham-leave-11537284|title=Birmingham Leave MPs' constituencies voted Remain|last=Brown|first=Graeme|date=28 June 2016|work=birminghammail|access-date=28 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180329120850/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/eu-referendum-results-birmingham-leave-11537284|archive-date=29 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nVote Leave was criticised after the Referendum and their activities were reviewed by the Electoral Commission and the organisation was fined for minor rule breaches.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/17/vote-leave-fined-and-reported-to-police-by-electoral-commission-brexit|title=Vote Leave fined and reported to police by Electoral Commission|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=2018-07-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-07-19|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730051132/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/17/vote-leave-fined-and-reported-to-police-by-electoral-commission-brexit|archive-date=30 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter stepping down at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]], Stuart revealed that she had pushed for an exit clause in the [[Treaty establishing a Constitution for Europe|European Constitution]], which later became Article 50 of the [[Treaty on the European Union]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/02/revealed-former-labour-mp-inadvertently-laid-groundwork-brexit/ | title=Revealed: How a former Labour MP inadvertently laid the groundwork for Brexit | publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | date=2 June 2017 | accessdate=8 June 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607142213/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/02/revealed-former-labour-mp-inadvertently-laid-groundwork-brexit/ | archive-date=7 June 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> Article 50 allows for [[withdrawal from the European Union]] by any member state and was [[United Kingdom invocation of Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union|invoked]] for the first and only time by Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] on 29 March 2017.<ref>{{cite web | title=Article 50: May signs letter that will trigger Brexit | publisher=[[BBC News]] | date=28 March 2017 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39422353 | accessdate=8 June 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727021653/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39422353 | archive-date=27 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a book entitled ''How to Lose a Referendum'' published on its first anniversary in June 2017, Stuart is quoted as having described the EU referendum as an \u201cabuse of democratic process\u201d and as having said she would rather it had never been called. On the eve of Brexit Gisela Stuart wrote in <i>The Guardian</i> \"The strange thing is not that Britain is leaving the EU \u2013 it\u2019s that we ever joined.\"<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jan/31/britain-eu-economic-political-maastricht</ref>\n\n==Voting record==\nHow Stuart voted on key matters since 2001:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/gisela_stuart/birmingham%2C_edgbaston |title=They Work For You |publisher=They Work For You |accessdate=20 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130628130944/http://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/gisela_stuart/birmingham,_edgbaston |archive-date=28 June 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n* Voted for introducing a [[Health Act 2006|smoking ban]]\n* Voted for introducing [[Identity Cards Act 2006|ID cards]]\n* Voted for introducing foundation hospitals\n* Voted for introducing student top-up fees\n* Voted for Labour's anti-terrorism laws\n* Voted for the [[Iraq War]]\n* Voted against investigating the Iraq War\n* Voted for replacing the [[Trident nuclear programme]]\n* Voted for ban on [[fox hunting]]\n* Voted for equal gay rights\n* Voted for leaving the [[European Union]]\n\n==Outside of politics==\nIn 2016, Stuart became the sixth President of the [[Birmingham Bach Choir]].<ref>Arts Professional, Arts People, published 11 Nov 2016, https://www.artsprofessional.co.uk/magazine/faces/birmingham-mp-gisela-stuart-lead-chamber-choir {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501224643/https://www.artsprofessional.co.uk/magazine/faces/birmingham-mp-gisela-stuart-lead-chamber-choir |date=1 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nStuart became the Chair of Wilton Park on 1 October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/fco-announce-new-chair-of-wilton-park|title=Foreign & Commonwealth Office announce new Chair of Wilton Park|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125073909/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/fco-announce-new-chair-of-wilton-park|archive-date=25 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe is a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetablet.co.uk/news/2380/fall-in-number-of-catholic-mps-in-the-house-of-commons-ahead-of-landmark-debate-on-assisted-dying|title=Fall in number of Catholic MPs in the House of Commons ahead of landmark debate on assisted dying|publisher=The Tablet|date=27 August 2015|last=Lee|first=Ceridwen|access-date=29 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191208225911/https://www.thetablet.co.uk/news/2380/fall-in-number-of-catholic-mps-in-the-house-of-commons-ahead-of-landmark-debate-on-assisted-dying|archive-date=8 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She has two sons. She married Robert Stuart in 1980, they divorced in 2000. Gisela married Derek Scott in 2010. He died in 2012.<ref name=UKWW/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122092749/http://giselastuartmp.co.uk/ |date=22 January 2017 |title=Gisela Stuart MP official site}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060206020327/http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-5044,00.html |date=6 February 2006 |title=Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: Gisela Stuart MP}}\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/gisela_stuart/birmingham,_edgbaston TheyWorkForYou.com - Gisela Stuart MP]\n* {{cite web |title=Ms Gisela Stuart \u2013 Contributions |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/search/MemberContributions?house=Commons&memberId=296 |website=Hansard Online |accessdate=1 April 2018}}\n* {{cite news |title=Spiegel Interview with UK Parliamentarian Gisela Stuart |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel-interview-with-uk-parliamentarian-gisela-stuart-blair-wants-a-radical-reform-of-the-european-union-a-361698.html |accessdate=1 April 2018 |publisher=Spiegel Online |date=22 June 2005}}\n* {{cite news |title=The health minister answers your questions |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/462038.stm |accessdate=1 April 2018 |publisher=BBC News |date=30 September 1999}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090412120934/http://news.bbc.co.uk:80/1/shared/mpdb/html/53.stm |date=12 April 2009 |title=Gisela Stuart page, BBC Politics}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jill Knight]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Birmingham Edgbaston (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Edgbaston]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Preet Gill]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stuart, Gisela}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century German women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century German women politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Manchester Metropolitan University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University of London Worldwide]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:Critics of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:German expatriates in England]]\n[[Category:People from Landshut (district)]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = GiselaStuartOct2008.jpg\n| caption = Stuart in 2008\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Gisela Stuart\n| honorific-suffix = \n| office = [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] [[Department of Health and Social Care|for Health]]\n| parliament = \n| predecessor = [[Helene Hayman, Baroness Hayman|The Baroness Hayman]]\n| successor = [[Ann Keen]] {{small|(2007)}}\n| term_start = 29 July 1999\n| term_end = 7 June 2001\n| birth_name = Gisela Gschaider\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1955|11|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Velden (Vils)|Velden]], [[Bavaria]], [[West Germany]]\n| citizenship = British\n| spouse = {{ubl|{{marriage|Robert Stuart<br />|1980|2000|end=div}}|{{marriage|Derek Scott<br />|2010|2012|end=d.}}}}\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (Until 2019)\n| relations = \n| children = 2\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = {{ubl|[[University of London]]|[[University of Birmingham]]<ref name=\"Jones\">C. K. Jones, ''The People's University'' (London, 2008), p. 33</ref>}}\n| occupation = Chair, [[Change Britain]]\n| profession = \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br /> for [[Birmingham Edgbaston (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Edgbaston]]\n| term_end1 = 3 May 2017\n| term_start1 = 1 May 1997\n| predecessor1 = [[Jill Knight]]\n| successor1 = [[Preet Gill]]\n| primeminister = [[Tony Blair]]\n}}\n'''Gisela Stuart''' (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' '''Gschaider'''; born 26 November 1955) is a former British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician, who served as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Birmingham Edgbaston (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Edgbaston]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] until stepping down at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]]. Born and raised in [[West Germany]], she has lived in the UK since 1974.\n\nStuart was Chair of the [[Vote Leave]] Campaign Committee and was one of its most high-profile figures, along with the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MPs [[Boris Johnson]] and [[Michael Gove]]. The Vote Leave campaign was successful in achieving its goal at the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]] of winning a majority of votes for Leave.\n\nSince September 2016, Stuart has served as Chair of Vote Leave's successor organisation, [[Change Britain]].\n\nAfter she left Parliament, Stuart was appointed by the Conservative government as Chair of [[Wilton Park]], an executive agency of the UK Foreign Office dedicated to conflict resolution in international relations, in October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/fco-announce-new-chair-of-wilton-park|title=Foreign & Commonwealth Office announce new Chair of Wilton Park|website=GOV.UK|access-date=25 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125073909/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/fco-announce-new-chair-of-wilton-park|archive-date=25 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nStuart is a member of the Steering Committee of the Constitution Reform Group (CRG)<ref>https://www.constitutionreformgroup.co.uk/</ref>, a cross-party organisation chaired by [[Robert Gascoyne-Cecil, 7th Marquess of Salisbury]], which seeks a new constitutional settlement in the [[UK]] by way of a new Act of Union<ref>https://services.parliament.uk/Bills/2017-19/actofunion.html</ref>. The Constitution Reform Group\u2019s new Act of Union Bill<ref>https://services.parliament.uk/Bills/2017-19/actofunion.html</ref> was introduced as a Private Member's Bill by [[Lord Lisvane]] in the [[House of Lords]] on 9 October 2018, when it received a formal first reading. The Bill has been described by the BBC as \"one to watch\"<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50786212</ref> in the current Parliament.\n\n==Early life==\nGisela Gschaider was born in [[Velden (Vils)|Velden]], [[Bavaria]], [[West Germany]] on 26 November 1955 to Martin and Liane Gschaider.<ref name=UKWW>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-36583/version/2|title=Stuart, Rt Hon. Gisela (Gschaider)|accessdate=29 November 2019|publisher=A & C Black}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/02/standing-parliament-gisela-stuart-mp-birmingham-edgbaston/|title=Why I'm standing down from Parliament: Gisela Stuart, MP for Birmingham, Edgbaston|last=Prince|first=Rosa|date=2 June 2017|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=29 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306143648/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/02/standing-parliament-gisela-stuart-mp-birmingham-edgbaston/|archive-date=6 March 2019|url-status=live}}{{subscription}}</ref> She attended the Staatliche Realschule Vilsbiburg in [[Vilsbiburg]].<ref name=UKWW/>\n\nAfter doing an apprenticeship in bookselling, she moved to the UK in 1974 in order to improve her English and to do a Business Studies course at [[Manchester Metropolitan University|Manchester Polytechnic]].<ref>{{cite news|date=30 November 2016|title=\"There is more to write about\": Labour eurosceptic Gisela Stuart accuses journalists of hamming up Brexit hate crime|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/brexit/2016/11/there-more-write-about-labour-eurosceptic-gisela-stuart-accuses-journalists|newspaper=[[New Statesman]]|first=Anoosh|last=Chakelian|access-date=18 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031530/https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/brexit/2016/11/there-more-write-about-labour-eurosceptic-gisela-stuart-accuses-journalists|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She was deputy director of the 1983 [[London Book Fair]].<ref name=vote2001>{{cite web|accessdate=18 November 2017|title=Vote2001: Candidates \u2013 Gisela Stuart|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/candidates/candidates/0/05305.stm|website=news.bbc.co.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040523014857/http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/candidates/candidates/0/05305.stm|archive-date=23 May 2004|url-status=live}}</ref> Stuart subsequently relocated to the [[The Midlands|Midlands]].\n\nShe graduated from the [[University of London]] with an [[LLB]] in 1993, having studied through the [[University of London External System]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.londoninternational.ac.uk/people/gisela-stuart-graduated-1993|title=Gisela Stuart - graduated 1993 {{!}} University of London International Programmes|date=27 September 2011|website=www.londoninternational.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=6 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407055511/http://www.londoninternational.ac.uk/people/gisela-stuart-graduated-1993|archive-date=7 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> She began researching for a PhD in trust law (ownership of pension funds) at the [[University of Birmingham]] while she also lectured Law to [[Association of Accounting Technicians|AAT]] students at Worcestershire College, but did not complete her PhD and instead went into politics full-time.<ref name=\"Jones\" />\n\nIn 1994, as Gisela Gschaider, Stuart contested the [[Worcestershire and South Warwickshire (European Parliament constituency)|Worcester and South Warwickshire]] seat at the [[European elections]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europeaninstitute.bg/page.php?category=117&id=228&page=2 |title=European Institute |publisher=Europeaninstitute.bg |date=28 August 2007 |accessdate=2 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324061112/http://www.europeaninstitute.bg/page.php?category=117&id=228&page=2 |archive-date=24 March 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> for Labour. She lost by 1,000 votes.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nIn 1995, Stuart was selected as Labour's parliamentary candidate for the [[Birmingham Edgbaston (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Edgbaston]] constituency. The constituency, which had once been held by former Conservative [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Neville Chamberlain]] (1937\u201340), had returned only [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MPs for 99 years. The sitting Conservative MP at the time, Dame [[Jill Knight]], was retiring after 31 years. On [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1 May 1997]], Stuart was elected as the first-ever Labour MP for the constituency, making it one of a succession of traditional Conservative seats to fall to Labour control in a landslide victory for the party. Stuart's victory was the first televised Labour gain of the evening.\n\nDuring the first [[Tony Blair]] ministry, Stuart served on the Social Security Select Committee and in 1998 as PPS to [[Home Office]] Minister of State [[Paul Boateng]], before joining the government in 1999 as Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Health. Stuart left this post in the reshuffle that followed after the [[2001 United Kingdom general election]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.giselastuartmp.co.uk/biography/ |title=Gisela Stuart Biography |accessdate=1 April 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915010850/http://www.giselastuartmp.co.uk/biography/ |archivedate=15 September 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Her [[election agent]] in that election was [[John Clancy (Labour politician)|John Clancy]], who became leader of [[Birmingham City Council]] in 2015.<ref name=\"Elkes-1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/find-out-new-leader-birmingham-10489560|title=Find out all about the new leader of Birmingham City Council John Clancy|last=Elkes|first=Neil|date=23 November 2015|work=[[Birmingham Mail]]|accessdate=1 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125033020/http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/find-out-new-leader-birmingham-10489560|archive-date=25 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn Blair's second ministry, Stuart was appointed as one of the UK Parliamentary Representatives to the [[Convention on the Future of Europe|European Convention]], which was tasked with drawing up a new constitution for the European Union. In this capacity, Stuart also served as one of the thirteen members of the Convention's Presidium - the steering group responsible for managing the business of the Convention.\n\nWhen the draft Constitution emerged, Stuart was one of the most trenchant critics of the proposal, stating that it had been drawn up by a \"self-selected group of the European political elite\" determined to deepen European integration. She subsequently expounded these views in a 2004 [[Fabian Society]] pamphlet, ''The Making of Europe's Constitution''. Consequently, she has argued in favour of British withdrawal from the European Union, becoming one of the leading [[Euroscepticism in the United Kingdom|Eurosceptic]] figures in the Labour Party.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Labour MP Gisela Stuart: UK should leave European Union|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20124699|website = BBC News|access-date = 14 February 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160111201703/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20124699|archive-date = 11 January 2016|url-status = live}}</ref> In the BBC's two-hour televised debate on the EU referendum, Stuart appeared on the \"Leave\" panel, along with the Conservative MPs [[Andrea Leadsom]] and [[Boris Johnson]].<ref>{{cite news|title=EU referendum: Leave and Remain clash in BBC Great Debate|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36582567|accessdate=1 April 2018|publisher=BBC News|date=22 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204034134/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36582567|archive-date=4 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2004, she became the only Labour MP who openly supported the re-election of [[George W. Bush]] at [[2004 US presidential election|that year's U.S. presidential election]], arguing \"you know where you stand with George and, in today's world, that's much better than rudderless leaders who drift with the prevailing wind\". She wrote that a victory for [[Democratic Party (US)|Democratic Party]] challenger, [[John Kerry]], would prompt \"victory celebrations among those who want to destroy liberal democracies. More terrorists and suicide bombers would step forward to become martyrs in their quest to destroy the West\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Hennessy |first=Patrick |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/1475512/Anti-Kerry-remarks-by-Labour-MP-put-Blair-on-the-spot.html |title=Anti-Kerry remarks by Labour MP put Blair on the spot |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=31 October 2004 |accessdate=2 December 2011 |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110417071438/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/1475512/Anti-Kerry-remarks-by-Labour-MP-put-Blair-on-the-spot.html |archive-date=17 April 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBetween 2001 and 2010, Stuart also served as a member of the House of Commons Select Committee on Foreign Affairs.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nShe retained her seat at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election]] but her majority was halved in both percentage and numerical terms. Despite the predictions of the pundits, Stuart went on to retain the seat at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], against a national tide of Labour defeat. The election resulted in the first hung parliament in 36 years, with the Conservatives having the most seats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.birmingham.gov.uk/general-election-2010 |title=Birmingham City Council: General Election 2010 |location=GB-BIR |publisher=Birmingham.gov.uk |date=6 May 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100508033256/http://www.birmingham.gov.uk/general-election-2010 |archive-date=8 May 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> It earned her the title of Survivor of the Year at ''The Spectator'' magazine's 2010 Parliamentarian of the Year awards, which was presented to her by the new Conservative Prime Minister, [[David Cameron]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giselastuartmp.co.uk/2010/12/survivor-of-the-year/ |title=Gisela Stuart Survivor of the Year Award |accessdate=20 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020202116/http://www.giselastuartmp.co.uk/2010/12/survivor-of-the-year/ |archivedate=20 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> She retained her seat at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election]] with a majority of 2,706 votes, more than double her majority from 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ms Gisela Stuart MP|url = http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/ms-gisela-stuart/296|website = UK Parliament|accessdate = 3 June 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150608180124/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/ms-gisela-stuart/296|archive-date = 8 June 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> She joined the Commons Select Committee on Defence.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nStuart is a signatory of the [[Henry Jackson Society]] principles, which promote the spread of [[liberal democracy]] across the world and the maintenance of a strong military with global expeditionary reach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.henryjacksonsociety.org/signatories.asp?pageid=36 |title=Signatories to the Statement of Principles |publisher=The Henry Jackson Society |date=28 November 2011 |accessdate=2 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808045304/http://www.henryjacksonsociety.org/signatories.asp?pageid=36 |archivedate=8 August 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She is the editor of the weekly political magazine ''[[The House (magazine)|The House]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/MP%27s+pounds+63,000+profit+home%3B+New+expenses+controversy+hits+Brum+MP...-a0215264008 |title=MP's pounds 63,000 profit home; New expenses controversy hits Brum MP Gisela |publisher=Thefreelibrary.com |accessdate=2 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006174515/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/MP%27s+pounds+63,000+profit+home%3B+New+expenses+controversy+hits+Brum+MP...-a0215264008 |archive-date=6 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nShe was sworn in as a member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]] in 2015, giving her the [[Honorific|honorific title]] \"[[The Right Honourable]]\" for life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/privy-council/privy-council-members/privy-counsellors/#s1|title=Privy Counsellors - Privy Council|website=privycouncil.independent.gov.uk|access-date=26 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713132409/https://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/privy-council/privy-council-members/privy-counsellors/#s1|archive-date=13 July 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSince 2015, she has been a Steering Committee member of the Constitution Reform Group (CRG), a cross-party pressure group of current and former politicians, academics, constitutional law experts, former officials in Parliament and government and ordinary citizens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.constitutionreformgroup.co.uk/|title=Home|website=Constitution Reform Group|access-date=15 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008092906/http://www.constitutionreformgroup.co.uk/|archive-date=8 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The CRG seeks a new constitutional settlement in the [[UK]] by way of a new Act of Union.<ref name=\"parliament.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://services.parliament.uk/bills/2017-19/actofunion.html|title=Act of Union Bill [HL] 2017-19 \u2014 UK Parliament|website=services.parliament.uk}}</ref>\n\nShe announced on 19 April 2017 that she would not seek re-election at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 snap general election]]. She was succeeded by [[Preet Gill]], a [[Labour and Co-operative]] politician, and the first female British [[Sikh]] MP.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kirkham|first=David|title=Preet Gill Confirmed As Labour Candidate For Edgbaston|url=http://www.redbrick.me/news/slider-news/preet-gill-confirmed-labour-candidate-edgbaston/|work=[[Redbrick (newspaper)|Redbrick]] (student newspaper)|publisher=[[University of Birmingham]]|date=29 April 2017|accessdate=18 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170512145343/http://www.redbrick.me/news/slider-news/preet-gill-confirmed-labour-candidate-edgbaston/|archive-date=12 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Stuart announced she would vote for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/exlabour-mp-gisela-stuart-urges-voters-to-back-boris-johnson-to-deliver-brexit-a4300506.html|title=Ex-Labour MP urges voters to back Boris Johnson to deliver Brexit|date=2019-11-29|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211111116/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/exlabour-mp-gisela-stuart-urges-voters-to-back-boris-johnson-to-deliver-brexit-a4300506.html|archive-date=11 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She remained a member of the Labour Party after the election.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2019/dec/30/labour-leadership-long-bailey-clive-lewis-corbyn-should-have-kept-fighting-for-remain-says-clive-lewis-live-news?page=with:block-5e09f1d48f08c397226423ab#block-5e09f1d48f08c397226423ab</ref>\n\n==Vote Leave==\nStuart served as Chair of the [[Vote Leave]], the body which was designated by the Electoral Commission as the official campaign in favour of [[Brexit|leaving the European Union]] in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum on European Union membership]]. Other spokespersons for Vote Leave included Conservative MPs [[Boris Johnson]] and [[Michael Gove]]. There were various other groups advocating for Leave, officially working independently of Vote Leave, including UKIP and the Labour Leave.\n\nStuart was the only{{according to whom|date=June 2019}} Labour MP in the official Vote Leave Campaign. Most of the other ten Labour MPs who went against the official Labour Party policy of supporting Remain, joined [[Labour Leave]], which had a less prominent role in the referendum.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.labourleave.org/board/ |title=Labour Leave Members |last=Labour |first=Leave |date=4 August 2016 |website=Labour Leave |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151216160434/http://labourleave.org/board/ |archive-date=16 December 2015 |url-status=dead |access-date=1 April 2018 }}</ref> Stuart was the only Labour MP to take part in the official events, such as the televised debates, on behalf of the Leave side.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/02/eu-referendum-tv-debates-when-where-watch-them|title=EU referendum debates: when and where to watch them|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=9 June 2016|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=28 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180329121701/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/02/eu-referendum-tv-debates-when-where-watch-them|archive-date=29 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> During the campaign she posed in front of a controversial campaign bus<ref>{{cite news|date=31 March 2019|title=Gobby Gisela|url=http://thesteepletimes.com/the-fog/gobby-gisela/|newspaper=The Steeple Times|access-date=22 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815072705/http://thesteepletimes.com/the-fog/gobby-gisela/|archive-date=15 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> which was subsequently the object of legal disputes.<ref>{{cite news|date=14 May 2019|title=Boris Johnson is facing a legal challenge|url=https://www.indy100.com/article/boris-johnson-court-brexit-nhs-bus-vote-leave-westminster-magistrates-8912701|newspaper=The Independent|access-date=22 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822175051/https://www.indy100.com/article/boris-johnson-court-brexit-nhs-bus-vote-leave-westminster-magistrates-8912701|archive-date=22 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nStuart's own constituency of Birmingham Edgbaston voted to Remain in the EU.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/eu-referendum-results-birmingham-leave-11537284|title=Birmingham Leave MPs' constituencies voted Remain|last=Brown|first=Graeme|date=28 June 2016|work=birminghammail|access-date=28 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180329120850/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/eu-referendum-results-birmingham-leave-11537284|archive-date=29 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nVote Leave was criticised after the Referendum and their activities were reviewed by the Electoral Commission and the organisation was fined for minor rule breaches.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/17/vote-leave-fined-and-reported-to-police-by-electoral-commission-brexit|title=Vote Leave fined and reported to police by Electoral Commission|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=2018-07-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-07-19|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730051132/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/17/vote-leave-fined-and-reported-to-police-by-electoral-commission-brexit|archive-date=30 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter stepping down at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]], Stuart revealed that she had pushed for an exit clause in the [[Treaty establishing a Constitution for Europe|European Constitution]], which later became Article 50 of the [[Treaty on the European Union]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/02/revealed-former-labour-mp-inadvertently-laid-groundwork-brexit/ | title=Revealed: How a former Labour MP inadvertently laid the groundwork for Brexit | publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | date=2 June 2017 | accessdate=8 June 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607142213/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/02/revealed-former-labour-mp-inadvertently-laid-groundwork-brexit/ | archive-date=7 June 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> Article 50 allows for [[withdrawal from the European Union]] by any member state and was [[United Kingdom invocation of Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union|invoked]] for the first and only time by Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] on 29 March 2017.<ref>{{cite web | title=Article 50: May signs letter that will trigger Brexit | publisher=[[BBC News]] | date=28 March 2017 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39422353 | accessdate=8 June 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727021653/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39422353 | archive-date=27 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a book entitled ''How to Lose a Referendum'' published on its first anniversary in June 2017, Stuart is quoted as having described the EU referendum as an \u201cabuse of democratic process\u201d and as having said she would rather it had never been called. On the eve of Brexit Gisela Stuart wrote in <i>The Guardian</i> \"The strange thing is not that Britain is leaving the EU \u2013 it\u2019s that we ever joined.\"<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jan/31/britain-eu-economic-political-maastricht</ref>\n\n==Voting record==\nHow Stuart voted on key matters since 2001:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/gisela_stuart/birmingham%2C_edgbaston |title=They Work For You |publisher=They Work For You |accessdate=20 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130628130944/http://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/gisela_stuart/birmingham,_edgbaston |archive-date=28 June 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n* Voted for introducing a [[Health Act 2006|smoking ban]]\n* Voted for introducing [[Identity Cards Act 2006|ID cards]]\n* Voted for introducing foundation hospitals\n* Voted for introducing student top-up fees\n* Voted for Labour's anti-terrorism laws\n* Voted for the [[Iraq War]]\n* Voted against investigating the Iraq War\n* Voted for replacing the [[Trident nuclear programme]]\n* Voted for ban on [[fox hunting]]\n* Voted for equal gay rights\n* Voted for leaving the [[European Union]]\n\n==Outside of politics==\nIn 2016, Stuart became the sixth President of the [[Birmingham Bach Choir]].<ref>Arts Professional, Arts People, published 11 Nov 2016, https://www.artsprofessional.co.uk/magazine/faces/birmingham-mp-gisela-stuart-lead-chamber-choir {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501224643/https://www.artsprofessional.co.uk/magazine/faces/birmingham-mp-gisela-stuart-lead-chamber-choir |date=1 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nStuart became the Chair of Wilton Park on 1 October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/fco-announce-new-chair-of-wilton-park|title=Foreign & Commonwealth Office announce new Chair of Wilton Park|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2019-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125073909/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/fco-announce-new-chair-of-wilton-park|archive-date=25 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe is a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetablet.co.uk/news/2380/fall-in-number-of-catholic-mps-in-the-house-of-commons-ahead-of-landmark-debate-on-assisted-dying|title=Fall in number of Catholic MPs in the House of Commons ahead of landmark debate on assisted dying|publisher=The Tablet|date=27 August 2015|last=Lee|first=Ceridwen|access-date=29 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191208225911/https://www.thetablet.co.uk/news/2380/fall-in-number-of-catholic-mps-in-the-house-of-commons-ahead-of-landmark-debate-on-assisted-dying|archive-date=8 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She has two sons. She married Robert Stuart in 1980, they divorced in 2000. Gisela married Derek Scott in 2010. He died in 2012.<ref name=UKWW/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170122092749/http://giselastuartmp.co.uk/ |date=22 January 2017 |title=Gisela Stuart MP official site}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060206020327/http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-5044,00.html |date=6 February 2006 |title=Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: Gisela Stuart MP}}\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/gisela_stuart/birmingham,_edgbaston TheyWorkForYou.com - Gisela Stuart MP]\n* {{cite web |title=Ms Gisela Stuart \u2013 Contributions |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/search/MemberContributions?house=Commons&memberId=296 |website=Hansard Online |accessdate=1 April 2018}}\n* {{cite news |title=Spiegel Interview with UK Parliamentarian Gisela Stuart |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel-interview-with-uk-parliamentarian-gisela-stuart-blair-wants-a-radical-reform-of-the-european-union-a-361698.html |accessdate=1 April 2018 |publisher=Spiegel Online |date=22 June 2005}}\n* {{cite news |title=The health minister answers your questions |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/462038.stm |accessdate=1 April 2018 |publisher=BBC News |date=30 September 1999}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090412120934/http://news.bbc.co.uk:80/1/shared/mpdb/html/53.stm |date=12 April 2009 |title=Gisela Stuart page, BBC Politics}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jill Knight]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Birmingham Edgbaston (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Edgbaston]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Preet Gill]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stuart, Gisela}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century German women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century German women politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Manchester Metropolitan University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University of London Worldwide]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:Critics of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:German expatriates in England]]\n[[Category:People from Landshut (district)]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]