{"title_page": "Howard Stoate", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Howard Stoate\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = Howard Stoate, September 2009 cropped.jpg\n| constituency_MP = [[Dartford (UK Parliament constituency)|Dartford]]\n| parliament = \n| majority = \n| predecessor = [[Bob Dunn (politician)|Bob Dunn]]\n| successor = [[Gareth Johnson]]\n| term_start = 2 May 1997\n| term_end = 12 April 2010\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1954|04|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Weymouth, Dorset]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = Deborah Dunkerley\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[King's College London]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Dr Howard Geoffrey Alvan Stoate''' (born 14 April 1954) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for the [[Dartford (UK Parliament constituency)|Dartford constituency]] in [[Kent]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] to [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]].\n\n==Early life==\nHe went to the independent [[Kingston Grammar School]] and at [[King's College London]], gaining an [[Master of Science|MSc]] and Diploma of the [[Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists|RCOG]] ([[DObst RCOG|DRCOG]]). Stoate was a junior hospital doctor from 1977\u201381, then a [[general practitioner]] in [[Bexleyheath]] from 1982, and a GP tutor at Queen Mary's Hospital in [[Sidcup]] from 1989. He was a [[Dartford Borough Council]]lor from 1990 to 99, Chair of Finance 1995\u201397.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nHe was elected MP for [[Dartford (UK Parliament constituency)|Dartford]] in 1997, having previously contested the seat in [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]] and [[Old Bexley and Sidcup (UK Parliament constituency)|Old Bexley and Sidcup]] in [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]]. Having won the seat, he was re-elected in [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] and [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]. He served as Parliamentary Private Secretary to [[Estelle Morris]] between 2003 and 2005.\n\nStoate announced on 28 July 2009 that he would stand down at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|next election]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8173135.stm |title=MP to quit over second job rules |publisher=[[BBC News Online]] |date=2009-07-28}}</ref>\n\nHe has also written a number of pamphlets for the [[Fabian Society]] including 'Challenging the Citadel' in 2006.<ref>http://www.fabians.org.uk/authors-mainmenu-88/authors/dr-howard-stoate-mp{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Fabian Society Website</ref>\n\n==Subsequent career==\nOn leaving Parliament he became Chair of the Bexley [[Clinical Commissioning Group]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Bexley Clinical Commissioning Group chairman Dr Howard Stoate answers key questions|url=http://www.bexleytimes.co.uk/news/bexley_clinical_commissioning_group_chairman_dr_howard_stoate_answers_key_questions_1_2168740|accessdate=6 March 2015|publisher=Bexley Times|date=25 April 2013}}</ref>  having continued to practice as a GP during his parliamentary career.<ref>{{cite news|title=Calm down, David Cameron \u2013 and get your facts right at PMQs|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/apr/28/calm-down-david-cameron-nhs|accessdate=6 March 2015|publisher=The Guardian|date=28 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married Deborah Dunkerley in 1979 in Dartford and they have two sons (born September 1984 and April 1987).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | dr-howard-stoate | Howard Stoate }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080409214427/http://www.howardstoate.com/ Dr Howard Stoate] official site\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-5015,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: Howard Stoate MP]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/howard_stoate/dartford TheyWorkForYou.com - Howard Stoate MP]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/178.stm BBC Politics page]\n\n===News items===\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/5175398.stm Tanning salons in July 2006]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/4647923.stm Having to move out of his offices in July 2005]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2683167.stm Warning about obesity in January 2003]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Bob Dunn (politician)|Bob Dunn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Dartford (UK Parliament constituency)|Dartford]]| years  = [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Gareth Johnson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stoate, Howard}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:20th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Borough of Dartford]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Kent]]\n[[Category:People educated at Kingston Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Members of the Fabian Society]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Howard Stoate\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = Howard Stoate, September 2009 cropped.jpg\n| constituency_MP = [[Dartford (UK Parliament constituency)|Dartford]]\n| parliament = \n| majority = \n| predecessor = [[Bob Dunn (politician)|Bob Dunn]]\n| successor = [[Gareth Johnson]]\n| term_start = 2 May 1997\n| term_end = 12 April 2010\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1954|04|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Weymouth, Dorset]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = Deborah Dunkerley\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[King's College London]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Dr Howard Geoffrey Alvan Stoate''' (born 14 April 1954) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for the [[Dartford (UK Parliament constituency)|Dartford constituency]] in [[Kent]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] to [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]].\n\n==Early life==\nHe went to the independent [[Kingston Grammar School]] and at [[King's College London]], gaining an [[Master of Science|MSc]] and Diploma of the [[Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists|RCOG]] ([[DObst RCOG|DRCOG]]). Stoate was a junior hospital doctor from 1977\u201381, then a [[general practitioner]] in [[Bexleyheath]] from 1982, and a GP tutor at Queen Mary's Hospital in [[Sidcup]] from 1989. He was a [[Dartford Borough Council]]lor from 1990 to 99, Chair of Finance 1995-97.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nHe was elected MP for [[Dartford (UK Parliament constituency)|Dartford]] in 1997, having previously contested the seat in [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]] and [[Old Bexley and Sidcup (UK Parliament constituency)|Old Bexley and Sidcup]] in [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]]. Having won the seat, he was re-elected in [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] and [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]. He served as Parliamentary Private Secretary to [[Estelle Morris]] between 2003 and 2005.\n\nStoate announced on 28 July 2009 that he would stand down at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|next election]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8173135.stm |title=MP to quit over second job rules |publisher=[[BBC News Online]] |date=2009-07-28}}</ref>\n\nHe has also written a number of pamphlets for the [[Fabian Society]] including 'Challenging the Citadel' in 2006.<ref>http://www.fabians.org.uk/authors-mainmenu-88/authors/dr-howard-stoate-mp{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Fabian Society Website</ref>\n\n==Subsequent career==\nOn leaving Parliament he became Chair of the Bexley [[Clinical Commissioning Group]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Bexley Clinical Commissioning Group chairman Dr Howard Stoate answers key questions|url=http://www.bexleytimes.co.uk/news/bexley_clinical_commissioning_group_chairman_dr_howard_stoate_answers_key_questions_1_2168740|accessdate=6 March 2015|publisher=Bexley Times|date=25 April 2013}}</ref>  having continued to practice as a GP during his parliamentary career.<ref>{{cite news|title=Calm down, David Cameron \u2013 and get your facts right at PMQs|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/apr/28/calm-down-david-cameron-nhs|accessdate=6 March 2015|publisher=The Guardian|date=28 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married Deborah Dunkerley in 1979 in Dartford and they have two sons (born September 1984 and April 1987).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | dr-howard-stoate | Howard Stoate }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080409214427/http://www.howardstoate.com/ Dr Howard Stoate] official site\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-5015,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: Howard Stoate MP]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/howard_stoate/dartford TheyWorkForYou.com - Howard Stoate MP]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/178.stm BBC Politics page]\n\n===News items===\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/5175398.stm Tanning salons in July 2006]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/4647923.stm Having to move out of his offices in July 2005]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2683167.stm Warning about obesity in January 2003]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Bob Dunn (politician)|Bob Dunn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Dartford (UK Parliament constituency)|Dartford]]| years  = [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Gareth Johnson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stoate, Howard}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:20th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Borough of Dartford]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Kent]]\n[[Category:People educated at Kingston Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Members of the Fabian Society]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1995-97 \u2192 1995\u201397", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howard_Stoate"}
{"title_page": "MBTA Bus", "text_new": "{{Infobox Bus transit\n| name = MBTA Bus\n| image = MBTA 1845 at Dudley Square station, March 2017.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| image_caption = A [[New Flyer]] XDE40 bus at Dudley Station in 2017\n| parent = [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]]\n| founded = 1964 ([[Boston-area streetcar lines|predecessors]] date to 1856)\n| locale = [[Greater Boston]]\n| service_area = [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]] and immediate suburbs\n| service_type = Local, limited stop, express, and [[Silver Line (MBTA)|Silver Line]] [[Bus rapid transit|BRT]]\n| alliance =\n| routes = 170<ref name=roster>{{cite web |url=http://www.transithistory.org/roster/ |title=MBTA Vehicle Inventory |publisher=NETransit |accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| destinations =\n| stops =\n| hubs =\n| stations =\n| lounge =\n| fleet = 1090 (Active) <ref name=roster />\n| ridership   = 387,815 (2013)<ref name=bluebook>{{MBTA Bluebook 2014}}</ref>\n| fuel_type = [[Diesel fuel|Diesel]], [[Compressed natural gas|CNG]], [[electric trolleybus]], [[Diesel-electric|diesel-electric hybrid]]\n| operator = MBTA; private operators\n| website = [http://www.mbta.com/ mbta.com]\n| map = [[File:MBTA Bus geographic map.svg|300px]]\n| map_state = collapsed\n}}\n\nThe [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] operates 170 [[bus]] routes ([[List of MBTA bus routes|list of routes]]) in the [[Greater Boston]] area, many of which were formerly part of a [[Boston-area streetcar lines|large streetcar system]]. Some routes are for local transport within the city; others bring passengers from surrounding areas to stops on the [[MBTA Commuter Rail]] or [[MBTA Subway|subway]] lines. The MBTA has a policy objective to provide transit service within walking distance (defined as {{convert|0.25|mi|km}}) for all residents living in areas with population densities greater than {{convert|5000|PD/sqmi|/km2}} within the MBTA's service district. Much of this service is provided by bus.\n\nThe MBTA operates a four-route [[bus rapid transit]] service branded as the [[Silver Line (MBTA)|Silver Line]], as well as [[MBTA crosstown bus routes|three crosstown routes]] that were intended to become the first part of the now-suspended [[Urban Ring Project (MBTA)|Urban Ring]] project. Fifteen routes designed as [[List of key MBTA bus routes|key routes]] run with higher frequency at all times, including extended service hours on Friday and Saturday nights over some of these routes.\n\nMost MBTA Bus service is served by [[Diesel engine|diesel]], [[compressed natural gas]], and [[Diesel-electric transmission|diesel-electric hybrid]] buses. Silver Line routes running in the Waterfront Tunnel use [[dual-mode bus|dual-mode]] buses that operate as [[trolleybuses]] in the tunnel and as diesel buses on the surface. [[Trolleybuses in Greater Boston#Harvard-based routes|Four routes]] based out of the [[Harvard Bus Tunnel]] run with trolleybuses in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] and several surrounding suburbs.\n\nAll buses and routes are wheelchair-accessible (see [[MBTA accessibility]]); most of the MBTA's bus fleet consists of [[low-floor bus]]es with wheelchair ramps, while older high-floor buses have lifts. All buses have [[LED]] exterior [[Destination sign|headsigns]] displaying route and destination, with automated audio/visual stop announcements for passengers.\n\nAfter taking over operations in August 1964 from the former Metropolitan Transit Authority, the MBTA began rebranding many elements of Boston's public transportation network. After being found unsuitable in 1965 for what is now the [[Orange Line (MBTA)|Orange Line]] because it did not show up well on maps, yellow was chosen for the color of bus operations on January 8, 1972.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/yourtown/boston/downtown/gallery/orange_line_111th_anniversary?pg=11 |title=MBTA Orange Line's 111th anniversary |newspaper=Boston Globe |last=Tran |first=Andrew Ba |date=June 2012 |page=11 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721150920/http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/downtown/gallery/orange_line_111th_anniversary?pg=11 |archivedate=July 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=chronicle>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/chronicleofbosto00mass |title=A Chronicle of the Boston Transit System |year=1981 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |via=Internet Archive |page=8}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Boston Elevated Railway]] and MTA operated overnight [[Night service (public transport)|Owl service]] until 1960. From September 2001 to June 2005, the MBTA operated bus service on 17 routes (7 normal bus routes and 10 routes replicating subway lines) until 2:30am on Friday and Saturday nights. Similar service on the [[List of key MBTA bus routes|key routes]] was operated from March 2013 to March 2014.<ref name=netransit /> In 2017, the MBTA Board considered a proposal to run all-night service on several routes with pulsed connections at a central hub.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/07/31/mbta-may-test-overnight-bus-service-commuter-rail-trips-foxborough/zLiX8p5cdoutmn1kYJqNbM/story.html |title=MBTA may test overnight buses, Foxborough commuter rail |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=August 1, 2017 |first=Adam |last=Vaccaro}}</ref>\n\n==Fleet==\n{{clear}}\n===Active fleet===\nThis is the current bus roster for the MBTA {{as of|2020|4|df=us|lc=y}}. All buses are {{convert|102|in|cm}} wide; most buses are {{convert|40|foot|adj=on}} length, while 102 are {{convert|60|foot|adj=on}} [[articulated bus]]es.<ref name=roster />\n<!-- DO NOT add updates on individual buses here. This is a high-level overview intended for a general audience, without the details of the NETransit roster. ALL information added here must be must be supported by the NETransit roster or another reliable published source (i.e, not Facebook).-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Order Year!! Manufacturer!! Model!! class=\"unsortable\" | Picture!! Fleet!