culator routes, most with partial MBTA subsidy.  [[Bedford, Massachusetts|Bedford]] and [[Beverly, Massachusetts|Beverly]] run single routes, [[Burlington, Massachusetts|Burlington]] runs five routes, and [[Lexington, Massachusetts|Lexington]] runs six.<ref name=netransit />  Most are run by private operators, except for the Beverly Shuttle, which is part of the [[Cape Ann Transportation Authority]] system.  Additionally, a nonprofit shuttle is run in Boston's [[Mission Hill, Boston|Mission Hill]] neighborhood.<ref name=netransit />  Those routes appear on MBTA system maps and connect with MBTA services at designated transfer points, but are numbered separately and do not accept MBTA passes.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat|MBTA Bus}}\n* [http://www.mbta.com/schedules_and_maps/bus/ MBTA - Bus Schedules and Maps]\n* [http://mbta.com/fares_and_passes/charlie/?id=25140 MBTA Bus Route Performance Indicators (2012)]\n* [https://mbta.com/projects/better-bus-project MBTA Better Bus Project]\n\n{{MBTA}}\n\n[[Category:Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]]\n[[Category:Bus transportation in the Boston area]]\n", "name_user": "Silver Line 3", "label": "safe", "comment": "my monthly update.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MBTA_Bus"}
{"title_page": "Ian Stewart (Labour politician)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{More footnotes|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = <!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people - see [[WP:NONFREE]] -->\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Ian Stewart\n| honorific-suffix =\n| office = [[Mayor of Salford]]\n| predecessor = Office Created\n| successor = [[Paul Dennett]]\n| term_start = 4 May 2012\n| term_end = 6 May 2016\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Eccles (UK Parliament constituency)|Eccles]]\n| parliament1 =\n| majority1 =\n| predecessor1 = [[Joan Lestor]]\n| successor1 = [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|Constituency Abolished]]\n| term_start1 = 2 May 1997\n| term_end1 = 12 April 2010\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1950|08|28|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Blantyre, South Lanarkshire]], Scotland, UK\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Merilyn Holding\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| alma_mater = [[Manchester Metropolitan University]]\n}}\n\n'''Ian Stewart''' (born 28 August 1950) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who was the Member of Parliament (MP) for [[Eccles (UK Parliament constituency)|Eccles]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] until [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]], when his seat was abolished and he was subsequently defeated in the selection process to be the Labour Parliamentary Candidate for the new parliamentary constituency of [[Salford and Eccles (UK Parliament constituency)|Salford and Eccles]] by [[Hazel Blears]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hazelblears.co.uk/salford-eccles |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120621041826/http://www.hazelblears.co.uk/salford-eccles |archive-date=21 June 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/guide/abolished-seats/ |title=UKPollingReport Election Guide 2010 \u00bb Abolished seats |website=Ukpollingreport.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n\nStanding as the Labour candidate for the new elected post of Mayor of [[City of Salford|Salford]], he was elected as Mayor in the [[2012 Salford mayoral election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ianstewart4salford.com |title=Archived copy |access-date=17 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130415210455/http://ianstewart4salford.com/ |archive-date=15 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=May 2016}}\nStewart attended Calder Street Junior Secondary School (now Auchinraith Primary School) in Blantyre and [[Irlam and Cadishead College|Alfred Turner Secondary Modern]] in [[Irlam]]. From 1966\u201369, he studied at [[Trafford College|Stretford Technical College]]. He later attended [[Manchester Metropolitan University]], where he carried out research towards a [[Master of Philosophy|M.Phil]] in Management of Change. Stewart worked as a chemical plant operator from 1973-78 before becoming the North West Regional Officer of the [[Transport and General Workers Union]].\n\n==MP for Eccles==\nStewart was first elected as Member of Parliament (MP) for Eccles in 1997. {{citation needed|date=May 2016}} He was a member of the All-Party Parliamentary Football Team.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n==Mayor of Salford==\nUpon his election as Mayor of Salford in 2012, Stewart appointed one deputy and 13 assistant mayors, including one in charge of 'humanegement', a nonsense word invented by Stewart to refer to [[human resources]].<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/new-salford-mayor-appoints-13-689102 |title=New Salford mayor appoints 13 assistants (including a spokesman for 'humanegement') |newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]] |date= |accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Stewart urged the government to rethink spending cuts claiming thousands of residents will be pushed further into poverty, saying: \"Salford has been forced to cut almost \u00a3100 million from council services since 2010. We have tried to increase our income in a number of ways, but it is an uphill battle. Without this funding I fear for the many families who are being asked to contribute more, whilst they have suffered a loss in benefits income.\"<ref name=\"Manchester Gazette1\">{{cite web|url=http://manchestergazette.co.uk/salford-city-mayor-urges-government-rethink-funding-cut|title=Salford City Mayor urges government to rethink funding cut|publisher=MG|date=17 October 2013|access-date=30 November 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013063622/http://manchestergazette.co.uk/salford-city-mayor-urges-government-rethink-funding-cut/|archive-date=13 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, Stewart launched the 'City Plan' which set the priories of [[Salford City Council]] over the following three years. Stewart said: \u201cIt is my firm hope that the City Plan will help to guide Salford through austerity and the \u00a375 million in government cuts to council services which we face over the next three years.\"<ref name=\"Manchester Gazette\">{{cite web|url=http://manchestergazette.co.uk/ian-stewart-sets-plan-tough-times-salford/|title=Ian Stewart Sets out Plan to beat Tough Times in Salford|publisher=MG|date=4 October 2013|access-date=30 November 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203025130/http://manchestergazette.co.uk/ian-stewart-sets-plan-tough-times-salford/|archive-date=3 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nStewart welcomed the convictions and praised the work of [[Salford City Council]] trading standards officers after a sex slave was discovered in an Eccles cellar. Stewart said: \u201cWe believe this girl was brought into the country illegally in 2000 and fell into the clutches of these evil men when she was just 10 years old.\"<ref name=\"Manchester Gazette2\">{{cite web|url=http://manchestergazette.co.uk/salford-mayor-welcomes-convictions/|title=Salford Mayor Welcomes Convictions|publisher=MG|date=17 October 2013|access-date=30 November 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203035520/http://manchestergazette.co.uk/salford-mayor-welcomes-convictions/|archive-date=3 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nStewart stepped down before the 2016 mayoral election.<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/salford-mayor-ian-stewart-not-8186320 |title=Salford mayor Ian Stewart will not seek second term of office |newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]] |date=2014-11-28 |accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married Merilyn Holding in 1968. They have two sons and a daughter.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://citymayor.salford.gov.uk/ Official website]\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-ian-stewart | Ian Stewart }}\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-5005,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics \u2013 Ask Aristotle: Ian Stewart MP]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/ian_stewart/eccles TheyWorkForYou.com \u2013 Ian Stewart MP]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/225.stm BBC News \u2013 Ian Stewart] profile 10 April 2006\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Joan Lestor, Baroness Lestor of Eccles|Joan Lestor]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = Member of Parliament for [[Eccles (UK Parliament constituency)|Eccles]]\n | years  = [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] \u2013 [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-new}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of Salford]]|years=[[Mayor of Salford#2012|2012]] \u2013 [[Mayor of Salford#2016|2016]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Paul Dennett]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Ian}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Blantyre, South Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:Scottish politicians]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Manchester Metropolitan University]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Salford]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) mayors]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{More footnotes|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = <!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people - see [[WP:NONFREE]] -->\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Ian Stewart\n| honorific-suffix =\n| office = [[Mayor of Salford]]\n| predecessor = Office Created\n| successor = [[Paul Dennett]]\n| term_start = 4 May 2012\n| term_end = 6 May 2016\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Eccles (UK Parliament constituency)|Eccles]]\n| parliament1 =\n| majority1 =\n| predecessor1 = [[Joan Lestor]]\n| successor1 = [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|Constituency Abolished]]\n| term_start1 = 2 May 1997\n| term_end1 = 12 April 2010\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1950|08|28|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Blantyre, South Lanarkshire]], Scotland, UK\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Merilyn Holding\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| alma_mater = [[Manchester Metropolitan University]]\n}}\n\n'''Ian Stewart''' (born 28 August 1950) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who was the Member of Parliament (MP) for [[Eccles (UK Parliament constituency)|Eccles]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] until [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]], when his seat was abolished and he was subsequently defeated in the selection process to be the Labour Parliamentary Candidate for the new parliamentary constituency of [[Salford and Eccles (UK Parliament constituency)|Salford and Eccles]] by [[Hazel Blears]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hazelblears.co.uk/salford-eccles |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120621041826/http://www.hazelblears.co.uk/salford-eccles |archive-date=21 June 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/guide/abolished-seats/ |title=UKPollingReport Election Guide 2010 \u00bb Abolished seats |website=Ukpollingreport.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n\nStanding as the Labour candidate for the new elected post of Mayor of [[City of Salford|Salford]], he was elected as Mayor in the [[2012 Salford mayoral election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ianstewart4salford.com |title=Archived copy |access-date=17 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130415210455/http://ianstewart4salford.com/ |archive-date=15 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=May 2016}}\nStewart attended Calder Street Junior Secondary School (now Auchinraith Primary School) in Blantyre and [[Irlam and Cadishead College|Alfred Turner Secondary Modern]] in [[Irlam]]. From 1966-69, he studied at [[Trafford College|Stretford Technical College]]. He later attended [[Manchester Metropolitan University]], where he carried out research towards a [[Master of Philosophy|M.Phil]] in Management of Change. Stewart worked as a chemical plant operator from 1973-78 before becoming the North West Regional Officer of the [[Transport and General Workers Union]].\n\n==MP for Eccles==\nStewart was first elected as Member of Parliament (MP) for Eccles in 1997. {{citation needed|date=May 2016}} He was a member of the All-Party Parliamentary Football Team.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n==Mayor of Salford==\nUpon his election as Mayor of Salford in 2012, Stewart appointed one deputy and 13 assistant mayors, including one in charge of 'humanegement', a nonsense word invented by Stewart to refer to [[human resources]].<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/new-salford-mayor-appoints-13-689102 |title=New Salford mayor appoints 13 assistants (including a spokesman for 'humanegement') |newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]] |date= |accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Stewart urged the government to rethink spending cuts claiming thousands of residents will be pushed further into poverty, saying: \"Salford has been forced to cut almost \u00a3100 million from council services since 2010. We have tried to increase our income in a number of ways, but it is an uphill battle. Without this funding I fear for the many families who are being asked to contribute more, whilst they have suffered a loss in benefits income.\"<ref name=\"Manchester Gazette1\">{{cite web|url=http://manchestergazette.co.uk/salford-city-mayor-urges-government-rethink-funding-cut|title=Salford City Mayor urges government to rethink funding cut|publisher=MG|date=17 October 2013|access-date=30 November 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013063622/http://manchestergazette.co.uk/salford-city-mayor-urges-government-rethink-funding-cut/|archive-date=13 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, Stewart launched the 'City Plan' which set the priories of [[Salford City Council]] over the following three years. Stewart said: \u201cIt is my firm hope that the City Plan will help to guide Salford through austerity and the \u00a375 million in government cuts to council services which we face over the next three years.\"<ref name=\"Manchester Gazette\">{{cite web|url=http://manchestergazette.co.uk/ian-stewart-sets-plan-tough-times-salford/|title=Ian Stewart Sets out Plan to beat Tough Times in Salford|publisher=MG|date=4 October 2013|access-date=30 November 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203025130/http://manchestergazette.co.uk/ian-stewart-sets-plan-tough-times-salford/|archive-date=3 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nStewart welcomed the convictions and praised the work of [[Salford City Council]] trading standards officers after a sex slave was discovered in an Eccles cellar. Stewart said: \u201cWe believe this girl was brought into the country illegally in 2000 and fell into the clutches of these evil men when she was just 10 years old.\"<ref name=\"Manchester Gazette2\">{{cite web|url=http://manchestergazette.co.uk/salford-mayor-welcomes-convictions/|title=Salford Mayor Welcomes Convictions|publisher=MG|date=17 October 2013|access-date=30 November 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203035520/http://manchestergazette.co.uk/salford-mayor-welcomes-convictions/|archive-date=3 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nStewart stepped down before the 2016 mayoral election.<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/salford-mayor-ian-stewart-not-8186320 |title=Salford mayor Ian Stewart will not seek second term of office |newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]] |date=2014-11-28 |accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married Merilyn Holding in 1968. They have two sons and a daughter.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://citymayor.salford.gov.uk/ Official website]\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-ian-stewart | Ian Stewart }}\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-5005,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics \u2013 Ask Aristotle: Ian Stewart MP]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/ian_stewart/eccles TheyWorkForYou.com \u2013 Ian Stewart MP]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/225.stm BBC News \u2013 Ian Stewart] profile 10 April 2006\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Joan Lestor, Baroness Lestor of Eccles|Joan Lestor]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = Member of Parliament for [[Eccles (UK Parliament constituency)|Eccles]]\n | years  = [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] \u2013 [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-new}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of Salford]]|years=[[Mayor of Salford#2012|2012]] \u2013 [[Mayor of Salford#2016|2016]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Paul Dennett]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Ian}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Blantyre, South Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:Scottish politicians]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Manchester Metropolitan University]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Salford]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) mayors]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1966-69 \u2192 1966\u201369", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ian_Stewart_(Labour_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Caroline Flint", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Carol Flint}}\n{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Caroline Flint\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Official portrait of Caroline Flint crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Flint in 2017\n| office = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]]\n| leader = [[Ed Miliband]]<br />[[Harriet Harman]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n| term_start = 7 October 2011\n| term_end = 14 September 2015\n| predecessor = [[Meg Hillier]]\n| successor = [[Lisa Nandy]]\n| office1 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]]\n| leader1 = [[Ed Miliband]]\n| term_start1 = 8 October 2010\n| term_end1 = 7 October 2011\n| predecessor1 = [[John Denham (politician)|John Denham]]\n| successor1 = [[Hilary Benn]]\n| office2 = [[Minister of State for Europe]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start2 = 3 October 2008\n| term_end2 = 5 June 2009\n| predecessor2 = [[Jim Murphy]]\n| successor2 = [[Glenys Kinnock, Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead|The Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead]]\n| office3 = [[Department for Communities and Local Government|Minister of State for Housing and Planning]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start3 = 24 January 2008\n| term_end3 = 3 October 2008\n| predecessor3 = [[Yvette Cooper]]\n| successor3 = [[Margaret Beckett]]\n| office4 = [[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister of State for Employment]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start4 = 28 June 2007\n| term_end4 = 24 January 2008\n| predecessor4 = [[Jim Murphy]]\n| successor4 = [[Stephen Timms]]\n| office5 = [[Regional minister|Minister for Yorkshire and the Humber]]\n| primeminister5 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start5 = 28 June 2007\n| term_end5 = 24 January 2008\n| predecessor5 = Position established\n| successor5 = [[Rosie Winterton]]\n| office6 = [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Public Health]]\n| primeminister6 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| term_start6 = 10 May 2005\n| term_end6 = 28 June 2007\n| predecessor6 = [[Melanie Johnson]]\n| successor6 = [[Dawn Primarolo]]\n| office7 = [[Home Office|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Home Affairs]]\n| primeminister7 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| term_start7 = 13 June 2003\n| term_end7 = 10 May 2005\n| predecessor7 = [[Geoffrey Filkin, Baron Filkin|The Lord Filkin]]\n| successor7 = [[Andy Burnham]]\n| office9 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Don Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Don Valley]]\n| term_start9 = 2 May 1997\n| term_end9 = 6 November 2019\n| predecessor9 = [[Martin Redmond]]\n| successor9 = [[Nick Fletcher (politician)|Nick Fletcher]]\n| majority9 = 5,169 (11.2%)\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1961|9|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Twickenham]], [[Middlesex]], England\n| residence = [[Doncaster]], [[South Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse = Phil Cole\n| alma_mater = [[University of East Anglia]]\n| website = [http://www.carolineflint.org Official website]<br />[http://www.facebook.com/CarolineFlintMP Official Facebook]\n}}\n'''Caroline Louise Flint''' (born 20 September 1961) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Don Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Don Valley]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] to [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]. She served in the [[UK Government|Governments]] of [[Tony Blair]] and [[Gordon Brown]] as [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Minister for Public Health]] from 2005 to 2007, [[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister for Employment]] from 2007 to 2008 and as [[Minister for Housing and Planning]] in 2008. Flint then served as [[Minister for Europe]] during the time of the introduction of the [[Treaty of Lisbon]] into [[UK law]] before resigning, citing disagreement with the leadership of Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]].\n\nIn 2010, she was [[2010 Labour Party (UK) Shadow Cabinet election|elected to the Shadow Cabinet]] and [[Ed Miliband]] appointed her [[Shadow Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehousing.co.uk/news/news/flint-gets-clg-role-in-shadow-cabinet-23111|title=Flint gets CLG role in shadow cabinet|website=Inside Housing|language=En|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223354/https://www.insidehousing.co.uk/news/news/flint-gets-clg-role-in-shadow-cabinet-23111|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> From 2011 to 2015, she was [[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]]. After coming third in the running for her party's [[Deputy leader of the Labour Party (UK)|deputy leader]] in [[2015 Labour Party deputy leadership election|2015]], Flint returned to the [[Backbencher|backbenches]] after not being reappointed to the [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn|Shadow Cabinet]] by [[Jeremy Corbyn]].\n\nAfter campaigning for remain in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum on membership of the European Union]], Flint was one of the few Labour [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MPs]] to accept the result of the vote in order to \"allow the voices of her constituents to be heard\".<ref name=\"editor\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/20/she-has-listened-to-us-constituents-back-labour-rebel-caroline-flint|title='She has listened to us': constituents back Labour rebel Caroline Flint|last=editor|first=Helen Pidd North of England|date=2019-10-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191210023322/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/20/she-has-listened-to-us-constituents-back-labour-rebel-caroline-flint|archive-date=10 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Flint supported [[Brexit]] as her constituents voted heavily to leave. She lost her seat to [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidate [[Nick Fletcher (politician)|Nick Fletcher]] in [[Boris Johnson|Boris Johnson's]] victory at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]]. Flint had served as the constituency's MP for 22 years.<ref name=\"news.sky.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/video/caroline-flint-loses-seat-and-asks-what-is-the-point-of-the-labour-party-11885177|title=Caroline Flint loses seat and asks: 'What is the point of the Labour Party?'|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223330/https://news.sky.com/video/caroline-flint-loses-seat-and-asks-what-is-the-point-of-the-labour-party-11885177|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Don Valley had been represented by Labour members of parliament since 1922. Flint blamed her defeat on \"[[Corbynistas]] and Uber Remainers\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/politics/caroline-flint-corbynistas-and-uber-remainers-blame-predicted-labour-losses-constituencies-including-her-don-valley-seat-1340064|title=Caroline Flint: 'Corbynistas and Uber Remainers' to blame for predicted Labour losses in constituencies including her Don Valley seat|website=www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223344/https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/politics/caroline-flint-corbynistas-and-uber-remainers-blame-predicted-labour-losses-constituencies-including-her-don-valley-seat-1340064|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nFlint was born on 20 September 1961 in [[Twickenham]], [[Middlesex]]. She was educated at [[Waldegrave School|Twickenham Girls' School]],<ref name=\"guardianprofile\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/person/1753/caroline-flint|title=Caroline Flint: Electoral history and profile|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=4 January 2011|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203060331/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/person/1753/caroline-flint|archive-date=3 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Richmond upon Thames College|Richmond Tertiary College]]<ref name=\"guardianprofile\"/> before earning a degree in [[American literature|American Literature]] and History and Film Studies from the [[University of East Anglia]].<ref name=\"guardianarticle\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/may/16/1|title=Only Tony Blair himself has purer Blairite credentials ... ambition is the word that crops up most about her work|last=Clark|first=Tom|date=16 May 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=4 January 2011|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530205059/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/may/16/1|archive-date=30 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She joined the Labour Party when she was 17. She was the Women's Officer of the [[National Organisation of Labour Students]] from 1982 to 1984.<ref name=\"dlprofile\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/25645.stm|title=Democracy Live \u2013 Caroline Flint MP|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=4 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110412025251/http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/25645.stm|archive-date=12 April 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShe began her career with the [[Inner London Education Authority]], as a management trainee from 1984 to 1985 and as a Policy Officer from 1985 to 1987.<ref name=\"debrett's\">{{cite web |url=http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/f/19479/Caroline%20Louise+FLINT.aspx |title=Debrett's: The Rt Hon Caroline Flint MP |accessdate=4 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607204413/http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/f/19479/Caroline%20Louise%2BFLINT.aspx |archivedate=7 June 2013  }}</ref> She was head of the Women's Unit at the [[National Union of Students (United Kingdom)|National Union of Students]] from 1988 to 1989, before joining [[Lambeth Council]] as an Equal Opportunities Officer from 1989 to 1991, and then Welfare and Staff Development Officer from 1991 to 1993.<ref name=\"debrett's\"/> From 1994 to 1997, she was the Senior Researcher and Political Officer for the [[GMB Union]].<ref name=\"debrett's\"/>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nFlint was first elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom]] in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]].<ref name=\"dlprofile\"/> She was re-elected at the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] and [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]]. Along with several other Labour women MPs, she was a member of a [[Tap dance|tap dancing]] troupe known as the Division Belles (a play on the term \"[[division bell]]\").<ref name=\"times 18 nov\">{{cite news|url=http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/families/article639007.ece|title=The nation's top nanny|last=Crompton|first=Simon|date=18 November 2006|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=4 January 2011|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615172906/http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/families/article639007.ece|archive-date=15 June 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> She is a member of the [[Fabian Society]] and of [[Labour Friends of Israel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/anger-grows-within-labour-over-forced-palestinian-vote-9788395.html|title=Anger grows within Labour over forced Palestinian vote|publisher=Independent|date=10 October 2014|access-date=10 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415021611/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/anger-grows-within-labour-over-forced-palestinian-vote-9788395.html|archive-date=15 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lfi.org.uk/in-parliament/|title=LFI Supporters in Parliament|accessdate=8 September 2019|work=Labour Friends of Israel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002100511/https://www.lfi.org.uk/in-parliament/|archive-date=2 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===In government===\nIn 1999, Flint became [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] (PPS) to [[Peter Hain]] while he was [[Minister of State]] at the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] and the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] before in 2002 becoming Parliamentary Private Secretary to [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|Dr John Reid]], while he was [[Leader of the House of Commons]] and [[Minister without portfolio]].<ref name=\"dlprofile\"/>\n\nInitially joining the government in June 2003 as [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Home Office]], Flint was moved in May 2005 to the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]], with responsibility for [[Public Health]] first as [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] and from May 2006 as [[Minister of State]] in the same role.<ref name=\"dlprofile\"/>\n\nAs Public Health minister she was responsible for managing government programmes concerning radiation exposure, the potential [[Avian influenza|bird flu]] epidemic, [[sex education]], and the prevention of communicable diseases such as [[tuberculosis]] and [[HIV]], and oversaw campaigns to tackle [[obesity]], [[type 2 diabetes]], [[heart disease]], and [[cancer]]. She was also due to take ministerial responsibility for implementing the smoke-free workplace [[Smoking ban in England|regulations]] in all public places resulting from the [[Health Act 2006]], but was moved just a couple of days before it came into force (on 1 July 2007).\n\nDuring her tenure at the [[Home Office]], Flint reclassified [[magic mushrooms]] as a [[Class A drug]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Drugs Bill | url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmbills/017/2005017.pdf | accessdate=12 October 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204090939/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmbills/017/2005017.pdf | archive-date=4 December 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> Flint pushed through the bill<ref>{{cite news | title=Magic mushrooms ban becomes law | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/4691899.stm | accessdate=12 October 2012 | publisher=BBC News | date=18 July 2005 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517121625/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/4691899.stm | archive-date=17 May 2014 | url-status=live }}.</ref> despite some challenges and objections from peers and MPs such as Dr [[Brian Iddon]],<ref>{{cite news | title=Peers and MPs join furore over 'rushed' ban on magic mushrooms | url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2005/apr/16/drugsandalcohol.immigrationpolicy | accessdate=12 October 2012 | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Mark | last=Honigsbaum | date=16 April 2005 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517182111/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2005/apr/16/drugsandalcohol.immigrationpolicy | archive-date=17 May 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Evidence to the Standing Committee on the Drugs Bill 2005 | url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmstand/f/st050203/pm/50203s05.htm | accessdate=12 October 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204161932/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmstand/f/st050203/pm/50203s05.htm | archive-date=4 December 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> plus disputed use of a scientific study by Swiss academic Dr Felix Hasler,<ref>{{cite web|title=Acute psychological and physiological effects of psilocybin in healthy humans |url=http://archive.beckleyfoundation.org/bib/doc/ah/2003/2003_hasler_6232_1.pdf |accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=The Evidence Base for the Classification of Drugs | url=http://www.rand.org/pubs/technical_reports/2006/RAND_TR362.pdf | accessdate=12 October 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110408223656/http://www.rand.org/pubs/technical_reports/2006/RAND_TR362.pdf | archive-date=8 April 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2007, it was announced that she would be [[Hazel Blears]]' campaign manager in Blears' campaign for the [[2007 Labour Party (UK) deputy leadership election|Deputy Leadership election of the Labour Party]] following [[John Prescott]]'s resignation. Blears did not win, coming sixth in the election.\n\nIn the [[Cabinet reshuffle]] of 29 June 2007 Caroline Flint moved to the [[Department for Work and Pensions]] where she served as the [[Minister for Employment|Minister for Employment and Welfare Reform]].<ref name=\"dlprofile\"/> Flint was also appointed to the new position of Minister for Yorkshire and the Humber.<ref name=\"dlprofile\"/>\n\nOn 24 January 2008, Flint was promoted to [[Minister of State for Housing and Planning]], and as a result would now attend [[Cabinet meetings]].<ref name=\"dlprofile\"/> She was also appointed a member of the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]] and she relinquished her role as regional minister.<ref name=\"dlprofile\"/> In February 2008, Flint suggested that unemployed council tenants should \"actively seek work\", as a condition of their occupancy.<ref>Wintour, Patrick. Wintour [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/feb/05/uk.topstories3 \"Labour: if you want a council house, find a job\",] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603013618/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/feb/05/uk.topstories3 |date=3 June 2016 }} ''[[The Guardian]]'', 5 February 2009. Retrieved 2 September 2019.</ref> In May that year, she inadvertently revealed grim forecasts for the future of house prices when she was photographed walking into Downing Street with her briefing papers visible. Close inspection revealed that her document read: \"We can't tell how bad it will get.\"<ref>.{{cite news| url  = https://www.theguardian.com/money/2008/may/14/houseprices.property| title  = Minister reveals housing fears in briefing gaffe| author  = Patrick Wintour| work  = [[The Guardian]]| date  = 14 May 2008| accessdate  = 27 March 2019| archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20190327123254/https://www.theguardian.com/money/2008/may/14/houseprices.property| archive-date  = 27 March 2019| url-status  = live}}</ref>\n\nShe was moved to the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] in the October 2008 reshuffle, to become the [[Minister for Europe]].<ref name=\"guardianprofile\"/>\nOn 31 March 2009 she admitted that she had not read the [[Lisbon Treaty]], the document which codifies the rules of the [[European Union]]. Critics described her admission as \"extraordinary\" and \"unbelievable,\" particularly given that the minister's responsibilities include overseeing the introduction of the Treaty.<ref>{{cite news\n |url          = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/5084584/Caroline-Flint-Europe-minister-hasnt-read-Lisbon-Treaty.html\n |title        = Caroline Flint, Europe minister, hasn't read Lisbon Treaty\n |author       = Rosa Prince\n |work         = Daily Telegraph\n |date         = 31 March 2009\n |location     = London\n |access-date  = 2 April 2018\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100712182633/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/5084584/Caroline-Flint-Europe-minister-hasnt-read-Lisbon-Treaty.html\n |archive-date = 12 July 2010\n |url-status   = live\n}}</ref>\n\nFlint resigned after the [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]] [[reshuffle]] of 5 June 2009 asserting that [[Gordon Brown]] was running a \"two-tier government\", and believed that she had been treated as \"female window dressing\" though she had earlier professed her loyalty to the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.scotsman.com/politics/39Just-female-window-dressing39-.5340489.jp|title='Just female window dressing' \u2013 Full text of Caroline Flint's resignation letter|publisher=The Scotsman|accessdate=5 June 2009|date=5 June 2009|location=Edinburgh|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608151647/http://news.scotsman.com/politics/39Just-female-window-dressing39-.5340489.jp|archive-date=8 June 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Flint renewed her attack on Gordon Brown in an ''[[The Observer|Observer]]'' newspaper article on 7 June 2009, saying that she was not ashamed of a glamorous photoshoot which had upset [[Downing Street]]. She launched a broadside against the Prime Minister, complaining of \"this constant pressure, this negative bullying\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jun/07/caroline-flint-gordon-brown-resignation|title=\"Angry Flint in fresh attack on Brown\" The Observer|publisher=Guardian|accessdate=7 June 2009|first=Gaby|last=Hinsliff|date=7 June 2009|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906181809/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jun/07/caroline-flint-gordon-brown-resignation|archive-date=6 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Expenses====\n{{Main|United Kingdom Parliamentary expenses scandal}}\n\nIn 2005, Flint claimed her constituency home in [[Sprotbrough]] in [[Doncaster]] as her second home, and a house in [[outer London]] as her main home. She sold her outer London home to buy a flat in [[Victoria, London]], in 2006. To buy the flat, Flint claimed \u00a31,000 in solicitor's fees and \u00a312,750 in stamp duty on allowances; the Fees Office paid \u00a37,700 of the claim. The Victoria flat became her second home and her constituency property her main residence.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5293149/Caroline-Flint-claimed-14000-for-fees-for-new-flat-MPs-expenses.html|title= Caroline Flint claimed \u00a314,000 for fees for new flat: MPs' expenses|work= The Daily Telegraph|first= Rosa|last= Prince|date= 8 May 2009|accessdate= 6 June 2009|location= London|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090511070105/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5293149/Caroline-Flint-claimed-14000-for-fees-for-new-flat-MPs-expenses.html|archive-date= 11 May 2009|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5293213/Caroline-Flints-response-over-MPs-expenses.html|title=Caroline Flint's response over MPs' expenses|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=1 June 2009|date=8 May 2009|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111193335/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5293213/Caroline-Flints-response-over-MPs-expenses.html|archive-date=11 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFlint was one of 98 MPs who voted in favour of legislation which would have kept MPs' expense details secret.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article1816072.ece | location=London | work=The Times | title=How your MP voted on the FOI Bill | date=20 May 2007 | first1=Charles | last1=Bremner | first2=David | last2=Robertson | access-date=9 October 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090508020947/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article1816072.ece | archive-date=8 May 2009 | url-status=live }}</ref> In an investigation into MPs claims she was ordered by [[Sir Thomas Legg]] to repay \u00a3572 in over-claimed expenses.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8493634.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Full list of MPs' expenses repayments | date=4 February 2010 | access-date=16 October 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150410113940/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8493634.stm | archive-date=10 April 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===In opposition===\n[[File:Redhill Holy Trinity Church Hall - Mar 2012 - Caroline Flint MP with Rhys.jpg|left|thumb|233x233px|Flint in March 2012]]\nFlint was reelected in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/election2010/results/constituency/b39.stm|title=BBC News {{!}} Election 2010 {{!}} Constituency {{!}} Don Valley|website=news.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715200146/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/election2010/results/constituency/b39.stm|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She served in the [[Shadow Cabinet of Ed Miliband]] from 2010 to 2015.\n\nFlint was reelected in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://electionresults.parliament.uk/election/2015-05-07/results/Location/Constituency/Don%20Valley|title=Don Valley \u2013 2015 Election Results \u2013 General Elections Online|website=electionresults.parliament.uk|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> On 16 May 2015, she announced her intention to seek candidacy for the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) deputy leadership election|Labour Party deputy leadership election]]. Along with [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]], she was seen as being a front runner in the contest.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bush|first=Stephen|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/05/caroline-flint-launches-bid-labours-deputy-leadership|title=Caroline Flint launches bid for Labour's deputy leadership|work=New Statesman|date=16 May 2015|accessdate=30 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909231127/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/05/caroline-flint-launches-bid-labours-deputy-leadership|archive-date=9 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> By the time nominations closed on 17 June, Flint had gained 43 MP nominees, second only to Tom Watson, and more than enough to confirm her place in the ballot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/main-topics/politics/yorkshire-mp-makes-final-five-in-fight-to-be-labour-s-deputy-leader-1-7314172|title=Yorkshire MP makes final five in fight to be Labour's deputy leader|work=Yorkshire Post|date=17 June 2015|accessdate=30 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725115217/http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/main-topics/politics/yorkshire-mp-makes-final-five-in-fight-to-be-labour-s-deputy-leader-1-7314172|archive-date=25 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\nShe came third.\n\nIn the [[List of MPs elected in the 2015 United Kingdom general election|56th Parliament]], Flint was a member of the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] and the [[Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament|Intelligence and Security Committee]], the [[Administration Committee]], the Education Sub-committee, the Education & Employment Committee and the Modernisation of the House of Commons Committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/caroline-flint/389|title=Caroline Flint MP|publisher=GOV.UK|accessdate=29 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029232433/https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/caroline-flint/389|archive-date=29 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 European Union membership referendum]], Flint campaigned for remain.<ref>{{Citation|title=Caroline Flint on Staying In the EU|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nJ9IK8BCdnE|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617044629/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nJ9IK8BCdnE|archive-date=17 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.carolineflint.org/i_love_britain_we_re_stronger_in_the_eu|title=Caroline Flint says: \"I Love Britain. I'm voting to REMAIN in the EU.\"|website=Caroline Flint|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223343/http://www.carolineflint.org/i_love_britain_we_re_stronger_in_the_eu|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She supported [[Owen Smith]] in the failed attempt to replace [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as party leader in the subsequent [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Labour leadership election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|title=Full list of MPs and MEPs backing challenger Owen Smith|date=21 July 2016|website=LabourList|accessdate=15 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715214543/https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Flint defied Labour [[Whip (politics)|whips]] on the [[European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018|EU withdrawal bill]]. She told [[BBC Radio 4]]'s [[Today (BBC Radio 4)|''Today'']], \"I believe Labour's job is to improve this bill, not kill it as it begins its passage through parliament.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/11/former-europe-minister-caroline-flint-to-defy-labour-whips-on-eu-bill|title=Former Europe minister Caroline Flint to defy Labour whips on EU bill|last=correspondent|first=Peter Walker Political|date=2017-09-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223330/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/11/former-europe-minister-caroline-flint-to-defy-labour-whips-on-eu-bill|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Flint said she would be willing to vote to help [[Boris Johnson]] pass a [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/foreign-affairs/brexit/news/104771/labour-mp-caroline-flint-says-she-would-vote-help-boris|title=Labour MP Caroline Flint says she would vote to help Boris Johnson pass a Brexit deal|last=PoliticsHome.com|date=2019-06-23|website=PoliticsHome.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624160630/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/foreign-affairs/brexit/news/104771/labour-mp-caroline-flint-says-she-would-vote-help-boris|archive-date=24 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, Flint stated her intention to vote for the Johnson government's EU Withdrawal Agreement, contrary to the Labour party's official stance, citing its alleged inclusion of a \"legally binding protection on workers' rights, environmental standards and consumer protection\",<ref>{{cite tweet |last=Flint |first=Caroline |user=CarolineFlintMP |number=1185313243159580672 |date=18 October 2019 |title=Labour MPs have secured legally binding protection on workers' rights, environmental standards & consumer protection & a parliamentary lock on deciding our future partnership. Plus improving unfair dismissal protections & tackling TUPE anomalies. |link=yes}}</ref> a claim rebutted as \"objectively false as a matter of law\" by the ''[[Financial Times]]''{{'}} legal commentator, [[David Allen Green]].<ref>{{cite tweet |last=Green |first=David Allen |user=davidallengreen |author-link=David Allen Green |number=1185332444494467076 |date=18 October 2019 |title=This is not a party-partisan point. Will happily promote Labour MPs and their valuable work. This account even praises Corbyn when he gets things right. But what @CarolineFlintMP says here is objectively false as a matter of law |link=no}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 October 2019, Flint was one of six Labour MPs, and the only one seeking reselection for the next general election, to rebel against the party line and vote against the [[Oliver Letwin|Letwin]] amendment to the government's Brexit deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/19/humiliated-boris-johnson-under-huge-pressure-to-seek-brexit-delay|title=Johnson 'faces fresh court action' after urging rejection of Brexit delay|last=Helm|first=Toby|date=19 October 2019|accessdate=20 October 2019|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020005323/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/19/humiliated-boris-johnson-under-huge-pressure-to-seek-brexit-delay|archive-date=20 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She spoke to [[Isabel Hardman]] from ''[[The Spectator]]'' regarding the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2019/10/the-labour-renegade/|title=Caroline Flint: why I'm backing this Brexit deal|date=2019-10-26|website=The Spectator|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223334/https://www.spectator.co.uk/2019/10/the-labour-renegade/|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Many of her constituents praised her for listening to her constituents.<ref name=\"editor\"/>\n\nIn the [[2019 England floods|November 2019 floods]], Flint's constituency was hit with heavy [[flood]]ing. [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] visited [[Conisbrough|Conisborough]] and [[Doncaster]] and viewed the property damage with Flint, calling on [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Boris Johnson]] to declare the floods a [[State of emergency|national emergency]] so immediate financial help could be provided to families in need.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/flood-warnings-remain-in-place-as-corbyn-visits-deluged-community-38676208.html|title=Flood warnings remain in place as Corbyn visits deluged community|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2019-12-14|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223335/https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/flood-warnings-remain-in-place-as-corbyn-visits-deluged-community-38676208.html|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/latest-news/jeremy-corbyn-calls-for-south-yorkshire-floods-to-be-declared-a-national-emergency-1-10095236|title=Jeremy Corbyn calls for South Yorkshire floods to be declared a national emergency|last=Hayes|first=Dan|date=9 November 2019|website=Yorkshire Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223341/https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/latest-news/jeremy-corbyn-calls-for-south-yorkshire-floods-to-be-declared-a-national-emergency-1-10095236|archive-date=14 December 2019|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Flint's daughter spoke out about a man subjecting her mother to malicious mailings for nine months. In 2018, she said one death threat had warned her: \"You'll be hanging from a rope\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/politics/daughter-of-don-valley-labour-candidate-caroline-flint-reveals-nine-month-malicious-mailings-campaign-against-her-mother-1-10123492|title=Daughter of Don Valley Labour candidate Caroline Flint reveals nine-month 'malicious mailings' campaign against her mother|website=www.yorkshirepost.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128203558/https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/politics/daughter-of-don-valley-labour-candidate-caroline-flint-reveals-nine-month-malicious-mailings-campaign-against-her-mother-1-10123492|archive-date=28 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], Flint stood for re-election and was one of the [[List of MPs who lost their seat in the 2019 United Kingdom general election|many Labour MPs to be defeated]]. Flint lost her seat to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] candidate [[Nick Fletcher (politician)|Nick Fletcher]] in the after serving 22 years in Parliament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/politics/don-valley-labours-caroline-flint-loses-seat-after-22-years-conservatives-1340210|title=DON VALLEY: Labour's Caroline Flint loses seat after 22 years to the Conservatives|website=www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223339/https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/politics/don-valley-labours-caroline-flint-loses-seat-after-22-years-conservatives-1340210|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She blamed Corbyn's leadership for her defeat.<ref name=\"news.sky.com\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/politics/caroline-flint-tears-into-jeremy-corbyn-after-losing-her-doncaster-seat-to-conservative-party-1-10151926|title=Caroline Flint tears into Jeremy Corbyn after losing her Doncaster seat to Conservative Party|website=www.yorkshirepost.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214010905/https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/politics/caroline-flint-tears-into-jeremy-corbyn-after-losing-her-doncaster-seat-to-conservative-party-1-10151926|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In her concession speech, Flint told voters that she was \"sorry we didn't give you a Labour party you could trust\" and attacked the \"influential Labour figures, living in [[North London]] postcodes, who have brought us to this point.\" She also declared that, \"Labour cannot simply be a party of big cities and university towns, nor just the party of the young or devoted [[remainer]]s\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/politics/im-sorry-we-didnt-give-you-labour-party-you-could-trust-caroline-flint-parting-shot-jeremy-corbyn-she-loses-don-valley-conservatives-1340247|title='I'm sorry we didn't give you a Labour party you could trust' \u2013 Caroline Flint in parting shot to Jeremy Corbyn as she loses Don Valley to Conservatives|website=www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223337/https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/politics/im-sorry-we-didnt-give-you-labour-party-you-could-trust-caroline-flint-parting-shot-jeremy-corbyn-she-loses-don-valley-conservatives-1340247|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the week after the election, Flint appeared on ''[[Sophy Ridge on Sunday]]'' and claimed that [[Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Shadow Foreign Secretary]] [[Emily Thornberry]] had said that Brexit voters in [[Northern England]] were \"stupid\".<ref name=\"yorkshirepost.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/politics/caroline-flint-stands-by-comments-about-emily-thornberry-as-shadow-foreign-secretary-threatens-her-with-court-action-1-10155887|title=Caroline Flint 'stands by' comments about Emily Thornberry as Shadow Foreign Secretary threatens her with court action|website=www.yorkshirepost.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> Thornberry appeared on ''[[ITV News]]'' and  accused Flint of \"making up s***\" about her<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-12-15/thornberry-criticises-total-and-utter-lie-shared-by-labour-colleague/|title=Emily Thornberry accuses Caroline Flint of 'making up s***' about her and says she is taking legal action|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> and threatened to take [[legal action]].<ref name=\"yorkshirepost.co.uk\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/16/emily-thornberry-threatens-to-sue-over-caroline-flint-stupid-voters-claim|title=Emily Thornberry threatens to sue over 'stupid voters' claim|last=editor|first=Rowena Mason Deputy political|date=2019-12-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFlint's first marriage was to Saief Zammel, a Tunisian stockbroker.<ref name=\"Langley\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3558457/An-all-too-revealing-peek-at-the-briefs-of-Caroline-Flint.html |title=An all-too-revealing peek at the briefs of Caroline Flint |last=Langley |first=William |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=18 May 2008 |accessdate=5 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205184918/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3558457/An-all-too-revealing-peek-at-the-briefs-of-Caroline-Flint.html |archive-date=5 February 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Fairford\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/may/10/caroline-flint-interview-europe-minister |title=Sexism, motherhood, ambition \u2013 and looking good |last=Fairford |first=Lucy |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |date=10 May 2009 |accessdate=5 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205185706/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/may/10/caroline-flint-interview-europe-minister |archive-date=5 February 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> They had a son and a daughter. They were divorced in 1990 after Zammel was arrested on charges of violent disorder. He was later deported.<ref name=\"Fairford\"/><ref name=\"Leach\">{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/7883064/MPs-scandals-covered-up-on-Wikipedia.html|title= MP's scandals covered up on Wikipedia|last= Leach|first= Ben|last2= Lefort|first2= Rebecca|date= 10 July 2010|accessdate= 5 February 2017|work= [[The Daily Telegraph]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110127054658/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/7883064/MPs-scandals-covered-up-on-Wikipedia.html|archive-date= 27 January 2011|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2001 she married Phil Cole, a former Labour Party regional officer and [[public relations]] professional, a [[councillor]] for the [[Edlington]] and [[Warmsworth]] ward of [[Doncaster Council]] since May 2012. They live outside Flint's former Don Valley constituency, in [[Sprotbrough]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://doncaster.moderngov.co.uk/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=157 |title=Sprotbrough |access-date=31 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609233644/http://doncaster.moderngov.co.uk/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=157 |archive-date=9 June 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Caroline|url=http://carolineflintdonvalley.com/about-caroline|accessdate=30 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111214084051/http://www.carolineflintdonvalley.com/about-caroline#|archivedate=14 December 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Flint employed her husband as her Senior Parliamentary Assistant on a salary up to \u00a340,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/caroline-flint/|title=IPSA|publisher=GOV.UK|accessdate=29 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926024242/http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/caroline-flint/|archive-date=26 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The practice of MPs employing family members was criticised by some sections of the media, on the grounds that it promotes [[nepotism]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/11706561/One-in-four-MPs-employs-a-family-member-the-full-list-revealed.html|title=One in five MPs employs a family member: the full list revealed|date=29 June 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=29 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402065627/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/11706561/One-in-four-MPs-employs-a-family-member-the-full-list-revealed.html|archive-date=2 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Mason|first1=Rowena|title=Keeping it in the family: new MPs continue to hire relatives as staff|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/jun/29/mps-continue-hire-relatives-as-staff|accessdate=29 October 2018|work=The Guardian|date=29 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180810142533/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/jun/29/mps-continue-hire-relatives-as-staff|archive-date=10 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Although MPs who were first elected in [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]] were banned from employing family members, the restriction was not retrospective \u2013 meaning that Flint's employment of her husband was lawful.<ref>{{cite news|title=MPs banned from employing spouses after election in expenses crackdown|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/mps-banned-from-employing-spouses-after-election-in-expenses-crackdown-a3520036.html|author= Cecil, Nicholas|work = [[Evening Standard]]|accessdate=29 October 2018|date=21 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181225210938/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/mps-banned-from-employing-spouses-after-election-in-expenses-crackdown-a3520036.html|archive-date=25 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111201204911/http://www.carolineflintdonvalley.com/ Caroline Flint and Labour in Don Valley] ''Official constituency website''\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = caroline-flint/389 | hansard = ms-caroline-flint | hansardcurr = 3261 | guardian = 1753/caroline-flint | publicwhip = Caroline_Flint | theywork = caroline_flint | record = Caroline-Flint/Don-Valley/182 | bbc = 25645.stm | journalisted = caroline-flint }}\n* {{Twitter | id= carolineflintmp | name= Caroline Flint }}\n*[https://en-gb.facebook.com/CarolineFlintMP/ Caroline Flint/] on [[Facebook]]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/caroline-flint Caroline Flint] on [[The Guardian]]\n*{{C-SPAN|Caroline Flint}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Martin Redmond]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Don Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Don Valley]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nick Fletcher (politician)|Nick Fletcher]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Melanie Johnson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Public Health]]|years=2005\u20132007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Dawn Primarolo]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Murphy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister of State for Employment]]|years=2007\u20132008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stephen Timms]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Regional minister|Minister for Yorkshire and the Humber]]|years=2007\u20132008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rosie Winterton]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Yvette Cooper]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Communities and Local Government|Minister of State for Housing and Planning]]|years=2008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Margaret Beckett]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Murphy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of State for Europe]]|years=2008\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Glenys Kinnock, Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead|The Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Denham (politician)|John Denham]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]]|years=2010\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Hilary Benn]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Meg Hillier]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]]|years=2011\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lisa Nandy]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Labour Party deputy leadership election, 2015}}\n{{Ministers for Europe}}\n{{Brown Cabinet}}\n{{Miliband Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Labour Party shadow cabinet election, 2010}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flint, Caroline}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of East Anglia]]\n[[Category:British feminists]]\n[[Category:British Eurosceptics]]\n[[Category:Politics of Doncaster]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Friends of Israel]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Twickenham]]\n[[Category:People from Doncaster]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Richmond upon Thames College]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Carol Flint}}\n{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Caroline Flint\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Official portrait of Caroline Flint crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Flint in 2017\n| office = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]]\n| leader = [[Ed Miliband]]<br />[[Harriet Harman]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n| term_start = 7 October 2011\n| term_end = 14 September 2015\n| predecessor = [[Meg Hillier]]\n| successor = [[Lisa Nandy]]\n| office1 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]]\n| leader1 = [[Ed Miliband]]\n| term_start1 = 8 October 2010\n| term_end1 = 7 October 2011\n| predecessor1 = [[John Denham (politician)|John Denham]]\n| successor1 = [[Hilary Benn]]\n| office2 = [[Minister of State for Europe]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start2 = 3 October 2008\n| term_end2 = 5 June 2009\n| predecessor2 = [[Jim Murphy]]\n| successor2 = [[Glenys Kinnock, Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead|The Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead]]\n| office3 = [[Department for Communities and Local Government|Minister of State for Housing and Planning]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start3 = 24 January 2008\n| term_end3 = 3 October 2008\n| predecessor3 = [[Yvette Cooper]]\n| successor3 = [[Margaret Beckett]]\n| office4 = [[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister of State for Employment]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start4 = 28 June 2007\n| term_end4 = 24 January 2008\n| predecessor4 = [[Jim Murphy]]\n| successor4 = [[Stephen Timms]]\n| office5 = [[Regional minister|Minister for Yorkshire and the Humber]]\n| primeminister5 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start5 = 28 June 2007\n| term_end5 = 24 January 2008\n| predecessor5 = Position established\n| successor5 = [[Rosie Winterton]]\n| office6 = [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Public Health]]\n| primeminister6 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| term_start6 = 10 May 2005\n| term_end6 = 28 June 2007\n| predecessor6 = [[Melanie Johnson]]\n| successor6 = [[Dawn Primarolo]]\n| office7 = [[Home Office|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Home Affairs]]\n| primeminister7 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| term_start7 = 13 June 2003\n| term_end7 = 10 May 2005\n| predecessor7 = [[Geoffrey Filkin, Baron Filkin|The Lord Filkin]]\n| successor7 = [[Andy Burnham]]\n| office9 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Don Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Don Valley]]\n| term_start9 = 2 May 1997\n| term_end9 = 6 November 2019\n| predecessor9 = [[Martin Redmond]]\n| successor9 = [[Nick Fletcher (politician)|Nick Fletcher]]\n| majority9 = 5,169 (11.2%)\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1961|9|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Twickenham]], [[Middlesex]], England\n| residence = [[Doncaster]], [[South Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse = Phil Cole\n| alma_mater = [[University of East Anglia]]\n| website = [http://www.carolineflint.org Official website]<br />[http://www.facebook.com/CarolineFlintMP Official Facebook]\n}}\n'''Caroline Louise Flint''' (born 20 September 1961) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Don Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Don Valley]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] to [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]. She served in the [[UK Government|Governments]] of [[Tony Blair]] and [[Gordon Brown]] as [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Minister for Public Health]] from 2005 to 2007, [[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister for Employment]] from 2007 to 2008 and as [[Minister for Housing and Planning]] in 2008. Flint then served as [[Minister for Europe]] during the time of the introduction of the [[Treaty of Lisbon]] into [[UK law]] before resigning, citing disagreement with the leadership of Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]].\n\nIn 2010, she was [[2010 Labour Party (UK) Shadow Cabinet election|elected to the Shadow Cabinet]] and [[Ed Miliband]] appointed her [[Shadow Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehousing.co.uk/news/news/flint-gets-clg-role-in-shadow-cabinet-23111|title=Flint gets CLG role in shadow cabinet|website=Inside Housing|language=En|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223354/https://www.insidehousing.co.uk/news/news/flint-gets-clg-role-in-shadow-cabinet-23111|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> From 2011 to 2015, she was [[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]]. After coming third in the running for her party's [[Deputy leader of the Labour Party (UK)|deputy leader]] in [[2015 Labour Party deputy leadership election|2015]], Flint returned to the [[Backbencher|backbenches]] after not being reppointed to the [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn|Shadow Cabinet]] by [[Jeremy Corbyn]].\n\nAfter campaigning for remain in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum on membership of the European Union]], Flint was one of the few Labour [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MPs]] to accept the result of the vote in order to \"allow the voices of her constituents to be heard\".<ref name=\"editor\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/20/she-has-listened-to-us-constituents-back-labour-rebel-caroline-flint|title='She has listened to us': constituents back Labour rebel Caroline Flint|last=editor|first=Helen Pidd North of England|date=2019-10-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191210023322/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/20/she-has-listened-to-us-constituents-back-labour-rebel-caroline-flint|archive-date=10 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Flint supported [[Brexit]] as her constituents voted heavily to leave. She lost her seat to [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidate [[Nick Fletcher (politician)|Nick Fletcher]] in [[Boris Johnson|Boris Johnson's]] victory at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]]. Flint had served as the constituency's MP for 22 years.<ref name=\"news.sky.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/video/caroline-flint-loses-seat-and-asks-what-is-the-point-of-the-labour-party-11885177|title=Caroline Flint loses seat and asks: 'What is the point of the Labour Party?'|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223330/https://news.sky.com/video/caroline-flint-loses-seat-and-asks-what-is-the-point-of-the-labour-party-11885177|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Don Valley had been represented by Labour members of parliament since 1922. Flint blamed her defeat on \"[[Corbynistas]] and Uber Remainers\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/politics/caroline-flint-corbynistas-and-uber-remainers-blame-predicted-labour-losses-constituencies-including-her-don-valley-seat-1340064|title=Caroline Flint: 'Corbynistas and Uber Remainers' to blame for predicted Labour losses in constituencies including her Don Valley seat|website=www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223344/https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/politics/caroline-flint-corbynistas-and-uber-remainers-blame-predicted-labour-losses-constituencies-including-her-don-valley-seat-1340064|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nFlint was born on 20 September 1961 in [[Twickenham]], [[Middlesex]]. She was educated at [[Waldegrave School|Twickenham Girls' School]],<ref name=\"guardianprofile\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/person/1753/caroline-flint|title=Caroline Flint: Electoral history and profile|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=4 January 2011|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203060331/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/person/1753/caroline-flint|archive-date=3 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Richmond upon Thames College|Richmond Tertiary College]]<ref name=\"guardianprofile\"/> before earning a degree in [[American literature|American Literature]] and History and Film Studies from the [[University of East Anglia]].<ref name=\"guardianarticle\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/may/16/1|title=Only Tony Blair himself has purer Blairite credentials ... ambition is the word that crops up most about her work|last=Clark|first=Tom|date=16 May 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=4 January 2011|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530205059/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/may/16/1|archive-date=30 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She joined the Labour Party when she was 17. She was the Women's Officer of the [[National Organisation of Labour Students]] from 1982 to 1984.<ref name=\"dlprofile\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/25645.stm|title=Democracy Live \u2013 Caroline Flint MP|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=4 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110412025251/http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/25645.stm|archive-date=12 April 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShe began her career with the [[Inner London Education Authority]], as a management trainee from 1984 to 1985 and as a Policy Officer from 1985 to 1987.<ref name=\"debrett's\">{{cite web |url=http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/f/19479/Caroline%20Louise+FLINT.aspx |title=Debrett's: The Rt Hon Caroline Flint MP |accessdate=4 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607204413/http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/f/19479/Caroline%20Louise%2BFLINT.aspx |archivedate=7 June 2013  }}</ref> She was head of the Women's Unit at the [[National Union of Students (United Kingdom)|National Union of Students]] from 1988 to 1989, before joining [[Lambeth Council]] as an Equal Opportunities Officer from 1989 to 1991, and then Welfare and Staff Development Officer from 1991 to 1993.<ref name=\"debrett's\"/> From 1994 to 1997, she was the Senior Researcher and Political Officer for the [[GMB Union]].<ref name=\"debrett's\"/>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nFlint was first elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom]] in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]].<ref name=\"dlprofile\"/> She was re-elected at the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] and [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]]. Along with several other Labour women MPs, she was a member of a [[Tap dance|tap dancing]] troupe known as the Division Belles (a play on the term \"[[division bell]]\").<ref name=\"times 18 nov\">{{cite news|url=http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/families/article639007.ece|title=The nation's top nanny|last=Crompton|first=Simon|date=18 November 2006|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=4 January 2011|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615172906/http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/families/article639007.ece|archive-date=15 June 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> She is a member of the [[Fabian Society]] and of [[Labour Friends of Israel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/anger-grows-within-labour-over-forced-palestinian-vote-9788395.html|title=Anger grows within Labour over forced Palestinian vote|publisher=Independent|date=10 October 2014|access-date=10 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415021611/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/anger-grows-within-labour-over-forced-palestinian-vote-9788395.html|archive-date=15 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lfi.org.uk/in-parliament/|title=LFI Supporters in Parliament|accessdate=8 September 2019|work=Labour Friends of Israel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002100511/https://www.lfi.org.uk/in-parliament/|archive-date=2 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===In government===\nIn 1999, Flint became [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] (PPS) to [[Peter Hain]] while he was [[Minister of State]] at the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] and the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] before in 2002 becoming Parliamentary Private Secretary to [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|Dr John Reid]], while he was [[Leader of the House of Commons]] and [[Minister without portfolio]].<ref name=\"dlprofile\"/>\n\nInitially joining the government in June 2003 as [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Home Office]], Flint was moved in May 2005 to the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]], with responsibility for [[Public Health]] first as [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] and from May 2006 as [[Minister of State]] in the same role.<ref name=\"dlprofile\"/>\n\nAs Public Health minister she was responsible for managing government programmes concerning radiation exposure, the potential [[Avian influenza|bird flu]] epidemic, [[sex education]], and the prevention of communicable diseases such as [[tuberculosis]] and [[HIV]], and oversaw campaigns to tackle [[obesity]], [[type 2 diabetes]], [[heart disease]], and [[cancer]]. She was also due to take ministerial responsibility for implementing the smoke-free workplace [[Smoking ban in England|regulations]] in all public places resulting from the [[Health Act 2006]], but was moved just a couple of days before it came into force (on 1 July 2007).\n\nDuring her tenure at the [[Home Office]], Flint reclassified [[magic mushrooms]] as a [[Class A drug]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Drugs Bill | url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmbills/017/2005017.pdf | accessdate=12 October 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204090939/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmbills/017/2005017.pdf | archive-date=4 December 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> Flint pushed through the bill<ref>{{cite news | title=Magic mushrooms ban becomes law | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/4691899.stm | accessdate=12 October 2012 | publisher=BBC News | date=18 July 2005 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517121625/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/4691899.stm | archive-date=17 May 2014 | url-status=live }}.</ref> despite some challenges and objections from peers and MPs such as Dr [[Brian Iddon]],<ref>{{cite news | title=Peers and MPs join furore over 'rushed' ban on magic mushrooms | url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2005/apr/16/drugsandalcohol.immigrationpolicy | accessdate=12 October 2012 | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Mark | last=Honigsbaum | date=16 April 2005 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517182111/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2005/apr/16/drugsandalcohol.immigrationpolicy | archive-date=17 May 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Evidence to the Standing Committee on the Drugs Bill 2005 | url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmstand/f/st050203/pm/50203s05.htm | accessdate=12 October 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204161932/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmstand/f/st050203/pm/50203s05.htm | archive-date=4 December 2012 | url-status=live }}</ref> plus disputed use of a scientific study by Swiss academic Dr Felix Hasler,<ref>{{cite web|title=Acute psychological and physiological effects of psilocybin in healthy humans |url=http://archive.beckleyfoundation.org/bib/doc/ah/2003/2003_hasler_6232_1.pdf |accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=The Evidence Base for the Classification of Drugs | url=http://www.rand.org/pubs/technical_reports/2006/RAND_TR362.pdf | accessdate=12 October 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110408223656/http://www.rand.org/pubs/technical_reports/2006/RAND_TR362.pdf | archive-date=8 April 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2007, it was announced that she would be [[Hazel Blears]]' campaign manager in Blears' campaign for the [[2007 Labour Party (UK) deputy leadership election|Deputy Leadership election of the Labour Party]] following [[John Prescott]]'s resignation. Blears did not win, coming sixth in the election.\n\nIn the [[Cabinet reshuffle]] of 29 June 2007 Caroline Flint moved to the [[Department for Work and Pensions]] where she served as the [[Minister for Employment|Minister for Employment and Welfare Reform]].<ref name=\"dlprofile\"/> Flint was also appointed to the new position of Minister for Yorkshire and the Humber.<ref name=\"dlprofile\"/>\n\nOn 24 January 2008, Flint was promoted to [[Minister of State for Housing and Planning]], and as a result would now attend [[Cabinet meetings]].<ref name=\"dlprofile\"/> She was also appointed a member of the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]] and she relinquished her role as regional minister.<ref name=\"dlprofile\"/> In February 2008, Flint suggested that unemployed council tenants should \"actively seek work\", as a condition of their occupancy.<ref>Wintour, Patrick. Wintour [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/feb/05/uk.topstories3 \"Labour: if you want a council house, find a job\",] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603013618/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/feb/05/uk.topstories3 |date=3 June 2016 }} ''[[The Guardian]]'', 5 February 2009. Retrieved 2 September 2019.</ref> In May that year, she inadvertently revealed grim forecasts for the future of house prices when she was photographed walking into Downing Street with her briefing papers visible. Close inspection revealed that her document read: \"We can't tell how bad it will get.\"<ref>.{{cite news| url  = https://www.theguardian.com/money/2008/may/14/houseprices.property| title  = Minister reveals housing fears in briefing gaffe| author  = Patrick Wintour| work  = [[The Guardian]]| date  = 14 May 2008| accessdate  = 27 March 2019| archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20190327123254/https://www.theguardian.com/money/2008/may/14/houseprices.property| archive-date  = 27 March 2019| url-status  = live}}</ref>\n\nShe was moved to the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] in the October 2008 reshuffle, to become the [[Minister for Europe]].<ref name=\"guardianprofile\"/>\nOn 31 March 2009 she admitted that she had not read the [[Lisbon Treaty]], the document which codifies the rules of the [[European Union]]. Critics described her admission as \"extraordinary\" and \"unbelievable,\" particularly given that the minister's responsibilities include overseeing the introduction of the Treaty.<ref>{{cite news\n |url          = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/5084584/Caroline-Flint-Europe-minister-hasnt-read-Lisbon-Treaty.html\n |title        = Caroline Flint, Europe minister, hasn't read Lisbon Treaty\n |author       = Rosa Prince\n |work         = Daily Telegraph\n |date         = 31 March 2009\n |location     = London\n |access-date  = 2 April 2018\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100712182633/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/5084584/Caroline-Flint-Europe-minister-hasnt-read-Lisbon-Treaty.html\n |archive-date = 12 July 2010\n |url-status   = live\n}}</ref>\n\nFlint resigned after the [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]] [[reshuffle]] of 5 June 2009 asserting that [[Gordon Brown]] was running a \"two-tier government\", and believed that she had been treated as \"female window dressing\" though she had earlier professed her loyalty to the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.scotsman.com/politics/39Just-female-window-dressing39-.5340489.jp|title='Just female window dressing' \u2013 Full text of Caroline Flint's resignation letter|publisher=The Scotsman|accessdate=5 June 2009|date=5 June 2009|location=Edinburgh|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608151647/http://news.scotsman.com/politics/39Just-female-window-dressing39-.5340489.jp|archive-date=8 June 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Flint renewed her attack on Gordon Brown in an ''[[The Observer|Observer]]'' newspaper article on 7 June 2009, saying that she was not ashamed of a glamorous photoshoot which had upset [[Downing Street]]. She launched a broadside against the Prime Minister, complaining of \"this constant pressure, this negative bullying\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jun/07/caroline-flint-gordon-brown-resignation|title=\"Angry Flint in fresh attack on Brown\" The Observer|publisher=Guardian|accessdate=7 June 2009|first=Gaby|last=Hinsliff|date=7 June 2009|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906181809/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jun/07/caroline-flint-gordon-brown-resignation|archive-date=6 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Expenses====\n{{Main|United Kingdom Parliamentary expenses scandal}}\n\nIn 2005, Flint claimed her constituency home in [[Sprotbrough]] in [[Doncaster]] as her second home, and a house in [[outer London]] as her main home. She sold her outer London home to buy a flat in [[Victoria, London]], in 2006. To buy the flat, Flint claimed \u00a31,000 in solicitor's fees and \u00a312,750 in stamp duty on allowances; the Fees Office paid \u00a37,700 of the claim. The Victoria flat became her second home and her constituency property her main residence.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5293149/Caroline-Flint-claimed-14000-for-fees-for-new-flat-MPs-expenses.html|title= Caroline Flint claimed \u00a314,000 for fees for new flat: MPs' expenses|work= The Daily Telegraph|first= Rosa|last= Prince|date= 8 May 2009|accessdate= 6 June 2009|location= London|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090511070105/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5293149/Caroline-Flint-claimed-14000-for-fees-for-new-flat-MPs-expenses.html|archive-date= 11 May 2009|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5293213/Caroline-Flints-response-over-MPs-expenses.html|title=Caroline Flint's response over MPs' expenses|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=1 June 2009|date=8 May 2009|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111193335/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5293213/Caroline-Flints-response-over-MPs-expenses.html|archive-date=11 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFlint was one of 98 MPs who voted in favour of legislation which would have kept MPs' expense details secret.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article1816072.ece | location=London | work=The Times | title=How your MP voted on the FOI Bill | date=20 May 2007 | first1=Charles | last1=Bremner | first2=David | last2=Robertson | access-date=9 October 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090508020947/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article1816072.ece | archive-date=8 May 2009 | url-status=live }}</ref> In an investigation into MPs claims she was ordered by [[Sir Thomas Legg]] to repay \u00a3572 in over-claimed expenses.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8493634.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Full list of MPs' expenses repayments | date=4 February 2010 | access-date=16 October 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150410113940/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8493634.stm | archive-date=10 April 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===In opposition===\n[[File:Redhill Holy Trinity Church Hall - Mar 2012 - Caroline Flint MP with Rhys.jpg|left|thumb|233x233px|Flint in March 2012]]\nFlint was reelected in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/election2010/results/constituency/b39.stm|title=BBC News {{!}} Election 2010 {{!}} Constituency {{!}} Don Valley|website=news.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715200146/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/election2010/results/constituency/b39.stm|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She served in the [[Shadow Cabinet of Ed Miliband]] from 2010 to 2015.\n\nFlint was reelected in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://electionresults.parliament.uk/election/2015-05-07/results/Location/Constituency/Don%20Valley|title=Don Valley \u2013 2015 Election Results \u2013 General Elections Online|website=electionresults.parliament.uk|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> On 16 May 2015, she announced her intention to seek candidacy for the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) deputy leadership election|Labour Party deputy leadership election]]. Along with [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]], she was seen as being a front runner in the contest.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bush|first=Stephen|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/05/caroline-flint-launches-bid-labours-deputy-leadership|title=Caroline Flint launches bid for Labour's deputy leadership|work=New Statesman|date=16 May 2015|accessdate=30 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909231127/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/05/caroline-flint-launches-bid-labours-deputy-leadership|archive-date=9 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> By the time nominations closed on 17 June, Flint had gained 43 MP nominees, second only to Tom Watson, and more than enough to confirm her place in the ballot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/main-topics/politics/yorkshire-mp-makes-final-five-in-fight-to-be-labour-s-deputy-leader-1-7314172|title=Yorkshire MP makes final five in fight to be Labour's deputy leader|work=Yorkshire Post|date=17 June 2015|accessdate=30 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725115217/http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/main-topics/politics/yorkshire-mp-makes-final-five-in-fight-to-be-labour-s-deputy-leader-1-7314172|archive-date=25 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\nShe came third.\n\nIn the [[List of MPs elected in the 2015 United Kingdom general election|56th Parliament]], Flint was a member of the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] and the [[Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament|Intelligence and Security Committee]], the [[Administration Committee]], the Education Sub-committee, the Education & Employment Committee and the Modernisation of the House of Commons Committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/caroline-flint/389|title=Caroline Flint MP|publisher=GOV.UK|accessdate=29 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029232433/https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/caroline-flint/389|archive-date=29 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 European Union membership referendum]], Flint campaigned for remain.<ref>{{Citation|title=Caroline Flint on Staying In the EU|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nJ9IK8BCdnE|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617044629/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nJ9IK8BCdnE|archive-date=17 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.carolineflint.org/i_love_britain_we_re_stronger_in_the_eu|title=Caroline Flint says: \"I Love Britain. I'm voting to REMAIN in the EU.\"|website=Caroline Flint|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223343/http://www.carolineflint.org/i_love_britain_we_re_stronger_in_the_eu|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She supported [[Owen Smith]] in the failed attempt to replace [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as party leader in the subsequent [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Labour leadership election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|title=Full list of MPs and MEPs backing challenger Owen Smith|date=21 July 2016|website=LabourList|accessdate=15 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715214543/https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Flint defied Labour [[Whip (politics)|whips]] on the [[European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018|EU withdrawal bill]]. She told [[BBC Radio 4]]'s [[Today (BBC Radio 4)|''Today'']], \"I believe Labour's job is to improve this bill, not kill it as it begins its passage through parliament.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/11/former-europe-minister-caroline-flint-to-defy-labour-whips-on-eu-bill|title=Former Europe minister Caroline Flint to defy Labour whips on EU bill|last=correspondent|first=Peter Walker Political|date=2017-09-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223330/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/11/former-europe-minister-caroline-flint-to-defy-labour-whips-on-eu-bill|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Flint said she would be willing to vote to help [[Boris Johnson]] pass a [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/foreign-affairs/brexit/news/104771/labour-mp-caroline-flint-says-she-would-vote-help-boris|title=Labour MP Caroline Flint says she would vote to help Boris Johnson pass a Brexit deal|last=PoliticsHome.com|date=2019-06-23|website=PoliticsHome.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624160630/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/foreign-affairs/brexit/news/104771/labour-mp-caroline-flint-says-she-would-vote-help-boris|archive-date=24 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, Flint stated her intention to vote for the Johnson government's EU Withdrawal Agreement, contrary to the Labour party's official stance, citing its alleged inclusion of a \"legally binding protection on workers' rights, environmental standards and consumer protection\",<ref>{{cite tweet |last=Flint |first=Caroline |user=CarolineFlintMP |number=1185313243159580672 |date=18 October 2019 |title=Labour MPs have secured legally binding protection on workers' rights, environmental standards & consumer protection & a parliamentary lock on deciding our future partnership. Plus improving unfair dismissal protections & tackling TUPE anomalies. |link=yes}}</ref> a claim rebutted as \"objectively false as a matter of law\" by the ''[[Financial Times]]''{{'}} legal commentator, [[David Allen Green]].<ref>{{cite tweet |last=Green |first=David Allen |user=davidallengreen |author-link=David Allen Green |number=1185332444494467076 |date=18 October 2019 |title=This is not a party-partisan point. Will happily promote Labour MPs and their valuable work. This account even praises Corbyn when he gets things right. But what @CarolineFlintMP says here is objectively false as a matter of law |link=no}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 October 2019, Flint was one of six Labour MPs, and the only one seeking reselection for the next general election, to rebel against the party line and vote against the [[Oliver Letwin|Letwin]] amendment to the government's Brexit deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/19/humiliated-boris-johnson-under-huge-pressure-to-seek-brexit-delay|title=Johnson 'faces fresh court action' after urging rejection of Brexit delay|last=Helm|first=Toby|date=19 October 2019|accessdate=20 October 2019|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020005323/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/19/humiliated-boris-johnson-under-huge-pressure-to-seek-brexit-delay|archive-date=20 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She spoke to [[Isabel Hardman]] from ''[[The Spectator]]'' regarding the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2019/10/the-labour-renegade/|title=Caroline Flint: why I'm backing this Brexit deal|date=2019-10-26|website=The Spectator|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223334/https://www.spectator.co.uk/2019/10/the-labour-renegade/|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Many of her constituents praised her for listening to her constituents.<ref name=\"editor\"/>\n\nIn the [[2019 England floods|November 2019 floods]], Flint's constituency was hit with heavy [[flood]]ing. [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] visited [[Conisbrough|Conisborough]] and [[Doncaster]] and viewed the property damage with Flint, calling on [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Boris Johnson]] to declare the floods a [[State of emergency|national emergency]] so immediate financial help could be provided to families in need.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/flood-warnings-remain-in-place-as-corbyn-visits-deluged-community-38676208.html|title=Flood warnings remain in place as Corbyn visits deluged community|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2019-12-14|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223335/https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/flood-warnings-remain-in-place-as-corbyn-visits-deluged-community-38676208.html|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/latest-news/jeremy-corbyn-calls-for-south-yorkshire-floods-to-be-declared-a-national-emergency-1-10095236|title=Jeremy Corbyn calls for South Yorkshire floods to be declared a national emergency|last=Hayes|first=Dan|date=9 November 2019|website=Yorkshire Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223341/https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/latest-news/jeremy-corbyn-calls-for-south-yorkshire-floods-to-be-declared-a-national-emergency-1-10095236|archive-date=14 December 2019|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Flint's daughter spoke out about a man subjecting her mother to malicious mailings for nine months. In 2018, she said one death threat had warned her: \"You'll be hanging from a rope\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/politics/daughter-of-don-valley-labour-candidate-caroline-flint-reveals-nine-month-malicious-mailings-campaign-against-her-mother-1-10123492|title=Daughter of Don Valley Labour candidate Caroline Flint reveals nine-month 'malicious mailings' campaign against her mother|website=www.yorkshirepost.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128203558/https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/politics/daughter-of-don-valley-labour-candidate-caroline-flint-reveals-nine-month-malicious-mailings-campaign-against-her-mother-1-10123492|archive-date=28 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], Flint stood for re-election and was one of the [[List of MPs who lost their seat in the 2019 United Kingdom general election|many Labour MPs to be defeated]]. Flint lost her seat to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] candidate [[Nick Fletcher (politician)|Nick Fletcher]] in the after serving 22 years in Parliament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/politics/don-valley-labours-caroline-flint-loses-seat-after-22-years-conservatives-1340210|title=DON VALLEY: Labour's Caroline Flint loses seat after 22 years to the Conservatives|website=www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223339/https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/politics/don-valley-labours-caroline-flint-loses-seat-after-22-years-conservatives-1340210|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She blamed Corbyn's leadership for her defeat.<ref name=\"news.sky.com\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/politics/caroline-flint-tears-into-jeremy-corbyn-after-losing-her-doncaster-seat-to-conservative-party-1-10151926|title=Caroline Flint tears into Jeremy Corbyn after losing her Doncaster seat to Conservative Party|website=www.yorkshirepost.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214010905/https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/politics/caroline-flint-tears-into-jeremy-corbyn-after-losing-her-doncaster-seat-to-conservative-party-1-10151926|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In her concession speech, Flint told voters that she was \"sorry we didn't give you a Labour party you could trust\" and attacked the \"influential Labour figures, living in [[North London]] postcodes, who have brought us to this point.\" She also declared that, \"Labour cannot simply be a party of big cities and university towns, nor just the party of the young or devoted [[remainer]]s\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/politics/im-sorry-we-didnt-give-you-labour-party-you-could-trust-caroline-flint-parting-shot-jeremy-corbyn-she-loses-don-valley-conservatives-1340247|title='I'm sorry we didn't give you a Labour party you could trust' \u2013 Caroline Flint in parting shot to Jeremy Corbyn as she loses Don Valley to Conservatives|website=www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214223337/https://www.doncasterfreepress.co.uk/news/politics/im-sorry-we-didnt-give-you-labour-party-you-could-trust-caroline-flint-parting-shot-jeremy-corbyn-she-loses-don-valley-conservatives-1340247|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the week after the election, Flint appeared on ''[[Sophy Ridge on Sunday]]'' and claimed that [[Shadow Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Shadow Foreign Secretary]] [[Emily Thornberry]] had said that Brexit voters in [[Northern England]] were \"stupid\".<ref name=\"yorkshirepost.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/politics/caroline-flint-stands-by-comments-about-emily-thornberry-as-shadow-foreign-secretary-threatens-her-with-court-action-1-10155887|title=Caroline Flint 'stands by' comments about Emily Thornberry as Shadow Foreign Secretary threatens her with court action|website=www.yorkshirepost.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> Thornberry appeared on ''[[ITV News]]'' and  accused Flint of \"making up s***\" about her<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-12-15/thornberry-criticises-total-and-utter-lie-shared-by-labour-colleague/|title=Emily Thornberry accuses Caroline Flint of 'making up s***' about her and says she is taking legal action|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> and threatened to take [[legal action]].<ref name=\"yorkshirepost.co.uk\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/16/emily-thornberry-threatens-to-sue-over-caroline-flint-stupid-voters-claim|title=Emily Thornberry threatens to sue over 'stupid voters' claim|last=editor|first=Rowena Mason Deputy political|date=2019-12-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFlint's first marriage was to Saief Zammel, a Tunisian stockbroker.<ref name=\"Langley\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3558457/An-all-too-revealing-peek-at-the-briefs-of-Caroline-Flint.html |title=An all-too-revealing peek at the briefs of Caroline Flint |last=Langley |first=William |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=18 May 2008 |accessdate=5 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205184918/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3558457/An-all-too-revealing-peek-at-the-briefs-of-Caroline-Flint.html |archive-date=5 February 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Fairford\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/may/10/caroline-flint-interview-europe-minister |title=Sexism, motherhood, ambition \u2013 and looking good |last=Fairford |first=Lucy |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |date=10 May 2009 |accessdate=5 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205185706/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/may/10/caroline-flint-interview-europe-minister |archive-date=5 February 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> They had a son and a daughter. They were divorced in 1990 after Zammel was arrested on charges of violent disorder. He was later deported.<ref name=\"Fairford\"/><ref name=\"Leach\">{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/7883064/MPs-scandals-covered-up-on-Wikipedia.html|title= MP's scandals covered up on Wikipedia|last= Leach|first= Ben|last2= Lefort|first2= Rebecca|date= 10 July 2010|accessdate= 5 February 2017|work= [[The Daily Telegraph]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110127054658/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/7883064/MPs-scandals-covered-up-on-Wikipedia.html|archive-date= 27 January 2011|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2001 she married Phil Cole, a former Labour Party regional officer and [[public relations]] professional, a [[councillor]] for the [[Edlington]] and [[Warmsworth]] ward of [[Doncaster Council]] since May 2012. They live outside Flint's former Don Valley constituency, in [[Sprotbrough]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://doncaster.moderngov.co.uk/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=157 |title=Sprotbrough |access-date=31 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609233644/http://doncaster.moderngov.co.uk/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=157 |archive-date=9 June 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Caroline|url=http://carolineflintdonvalley.com/about-caroline|accessdate=30 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111214084051/http://www.carolineflintdonvalley.com/about-caroline#|archivedate=14 December 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Flint employed her husband as her Senior Parliamentary Assistant on a salary up to \u00a340,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/caroline-flint/|title=IPSA|publisher=GOV.UK|accessdate=29 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926024242/http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/caroline-flint/|archive-date=26 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The practice of MPs employing family members was criticised by some sections of the media, on the grounds that it promotes [[nepotism]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/11706561/One-in-four-MPs-employs-a-family-member-the-full-list-revealed.html|title=One in five MPs employs a family member: the full list revealed|date=29 June 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=29 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402065627/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/11706561/One-in-four-MPs-employs-a-family-member-the-full-list-revealed.html|archive-date=2 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Mason|first1=Rowena|title=Keeping it in the family: new MPs continue to hire relatives as staff|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/jun/29/mps-continue-hire-relatives-as-staff|accessdate=29 October 2018|work=The Guardian|date=29 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180810142533/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/jun/29/mps-continue-hire-relatives-as-staff|archive-date=10 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Although MPs who were first elected in [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]] were banned from employing family members, the restriction was not retrospective \u2013 meaning that Flint's employment of her husband was lawful.<ref>{{cite news|title=MPs banned from employing spouses after election in expenses crackdown|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/mps-banned-from-employing-spouses-after-election-in-expenses-crackdown-a3520036.html|author= Cecil, Nicholas|work = [[Evening Standard]]|accessdate=29 October 2018|date=21 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181225210938/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/mps-banned-from-employing-spouses-after-election-in-expenses-crackdown-a3520036.html|archive-date=25 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111201204911/http://www.carolineflintdonvalley.com/ Caroline Flint and Labour in Don Valley] ''Official constituency website''\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = caroline-flint/389 | hansard = ms-caroline-flint | hansardcurr = 3261 | guardian = 1753/caroline-flint | publicwhip = Caroline_Flint | theywork = caroline_flint | record = Caroline-Flint/Don-Valley/182 | bbc = 25645.stm | journalisted = caroline-flint }}\n* {{Twitter | id= carolineflintmp | name= Caroline Flint }}\n*[https://en-gb.facebook.com/CarolineFlintMP/ Caroline Flint/] on [[Facebook]]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/caroline-flint Caroline Flint] on [[The Guardian]]\n*{{C-SPAN|Caroline Flint}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Martin Redmond]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Don Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Don Valley]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nick Fletcher (politician)|Nick Fletcher]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Melanie Johnson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Public Health]]|years=2005\u20132007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Dawn Primarolo]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Murphy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister of State for Employment]]|years=2007\u20132008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stephen Timms]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Regional minister|Minister for Yorkshire and the Humber]]|years=2007\u20132008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rosie Winterton]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Yvette Cooper]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Communities and Local Government|Minister of State for Housing and Planning]]|years=2008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Margaret Beckett]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Murphy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of State for Europe]]|years=2008\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Glenys Kinnock, Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead|The Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Denham (politician)|John Denham]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]]|years=2010\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Hilary Benn]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Meg Hillier]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]]|years=2011\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lisa Nandy]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Labour Party deputy leadership election, 2015}}\n{{Ministers for Europe}}\n{{Brown Cabinet}}\n{{Miliband Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Labour Party shadow cabinet election, 2010}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flint, Caroline}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people