{"title_page": "David Stewart (Scottish politician)", "text_new": "{{Other people|David Stewart}}\n{{short description|Scottish politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = David Stewart\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]]\n| image = DaveStewartMSPPortrait.jpg\n| office = Convener of the [[Committees of the Scottish Parliament|Scottish Parliament Public Petitions Committee]]\n| term_start = 14 June 2011\n| term_end =17 May 2016\n| predecessor = [[Rhona Brankin]]\n| successor =[[Johann Lamont]] {{collapsed infobox section begin|[[Shadow Cabinet (Scottish Parliament)|Shadow Cabinet]] positions}}\n| office2 = [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] <br /> for [[Highlands and Islands (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|Highlands and Islands]]<br /><small>(1 of 7 Regional MSPs)</small>\n| parliament2 = \n| majority2 =\n| term_start2 = 3 May 2007\n| term_end2 = \n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 = \n| office3 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber (UK Parliament constituency)|Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber]]\n| majority3 = \n| term_start3 = 1 May 1997\n| term_end3 = 11 April 2005\n| predecessor3 = [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|Constituency Created]]\n| successor3 = [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|Constituency Abolished]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1956|05|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| birthname = \n| nationality = \n| party = [[Scottish Labour Party|Scottish Labour]] and [[Labour Co-operative|Co-operative Party]]\n| spouse = Linda Stewart\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| cabinet = \n| committees = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n|office1=[[Scottish Labour]] [[Shadow Cabinet (Scottish Parliament)|Spokesperson]] for Eradication of Poverty and Inequality|predecessor1=[[Elaine Smith (Scottish politician)|Elaine Smith]] {{collapsed infobox section end}}|term_start1=2 September 2019|leader1=[[Richard Leonard (Scottish politician)|Richard Leonard]]|1blankname=Presiding Officer|1namedata=[[Tricia Marwick]]}}\n'''David John Stewart''' (born 5 May 1956) is a [[Scottish Labour Party|Scottish Labour]] and [[Labour Co-operative|Co-operative Party]]  politician. Since 2007, he has been a [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] (MSP) for the [[Highlands and Islands (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|Highlands and Islands]] region. From 1997 until his defeat in 2005, he sat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|British House of Commons]] as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber (UK Parliament constituency)|Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber]].\n\n==House of Commons==\nIn 1997 he was the first [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for the [[Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber (UK Parliament constituency)|Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber]] constituency in Scotland and was re-elected in [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]]. In [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]] the constituency was reformed to [[Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey (UK Parliament constituency)|Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey]], an election which he lost to [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] candidate [[Danny Alexander]]. During his time as an MP, he was a member of the Scottish Affairs and Work and Pensions Select Committees and from 2003 until 2005 was [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[Alistair Darling]], [[Secretary of State for Scotland]].\n\n== Out of office ==\nDuring his time out of office, Stewart was employed as Assistant Director for Rural Affairs with the [[Scottish Council for Voluntary Organisations]].\n\n== Scottish Parliament ==\nIn May 2007 he returned to parliamentary life, this time to the [[Scottish Parliament]] as a list MSP for the Highlands and Islands electoral region.<ref name=\"session3\">{{cite web |url=http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/msps/26665.aspx |title=Previous MSPs: Session 3 (2007-2011): David Stewart |publisher=Scottish Parliament |accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref> In October 2008, the Labour Leader in the Scottish Parliament, [[Iain Gray]], appointed him to the shadow cabinet as the [[Chief Whip]] of the Labour Party in [[Scottish Parliament|Holyrood]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/7618696.stm |title=Scottish Labour's front bench team |work=[[BBC News]] |date=31 December 2009 |accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref> In September 2019, he was made Shadow Cabinet Secretary for Eradication of Poverty and Inequality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/scottish-labour-reshuffle-as-sarah-boyack-returns-to-frontline-politics-1-4995872|title=Scottish Labour reshuffle as Sarah Boyack returns to frontline politics|website=www.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nPrior to his election in 1997, he had been a leading member of Labour's [[Organisation of the Scottish Labour Party#Scottish Executive Committee|Scottish Executive Committee]].\n\nHe is married to Linda, who stood in the 2007 Scottish Parliament election as Labour Party candidate for the [[Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber]] constituency but failed to be elected.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/election-shows-politics-runs-in-the-family-1.841980|title=Election shows politics runs in the family|date=1 May 2007|work=Herald (Glasgow)|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber (UK Parliament constituency)|Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber]]\n | years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n{{s-end}}\n{{HighlandsIslands MSPs}}\n{{Scottish Labour Party}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, David}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Highland constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:Labour Co-operative MSPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Scottish Parliament 2007\u20132011]]\n[[Category:Members of the Scottish Parliament 2011\u20132016]]\n[[Category:Members of the Scottish Parliament 2016\u2013]]\n[[Category:People educated at Inverness High School]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|David Stewart}}\n{{short description|Scottish politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = David Stewart\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]]\n| image = DaveStewartMSPPortrait.jpg\n| office = Convener of the [[Committees of the Scottish Parliament|Scottish Parliament Public Petitions Committee]]\n| term_start = 14 June 2011\n| term_end =17 May 2016\n| predecessor = [[Rhona Brankin]]\n| successor =[[Johann Lamont]] {{collapsed infobox section begin|[[Shadow Cabinet (Scottish Parliament)|Shadow Cabinet]] positions}}\n| office2 = [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] <br /> for [[Highlands and Islands (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|Highlands and Islands]]<br /><small>(1 of 7 Regional MSPs)</small>\n| parliament2 = \n| majority2 =\n| term_start2 = 3 May 2007\n| term_end2 = \n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 = \n| office3 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber (UK Parliament constituency)|Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber]]\n| majority3 = \n| term_start3 = 1 May 1997\n| term_end3 = 11 April 2005\n| predecessor3 = [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|Constituency Created]]\n| successor3 = [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|Constituency Abolished]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1956|05|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| birthname = \n| nationality = \n| party = [[Scottish Labour Party|Scottish Labour]] and [[Labour Co-operative|Co-operative Party]]\n| spouse = Linda Stewart\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| cabinet = \n| committees = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n|office1=[[Scottish Labour]] [[Shadow Cabinet (Scottish Parliament)|Spokesperson]] for Eradication of Poverty and Inequality|predecessor1=[[Elaine Smith (Scottish politician)|Elaine Smith]] {{collapsed infobox section end}}|term_start1=2 September 2019|leader1=[[Richard Leonard (Scottish politician)|Richard Leonard]]|1blankname=Presiding Officer|1namedata=[[Tricia Marwick]]}}\n'''David John Stewart''' (born 5 May 1956) is a [[Scottish Labour Party|Scottish Labour]] and [[Labour Co-operative|Co-operative Party]]  politician. Since 2007, he has been a [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] (MSP) for the [[Highlands and Islands (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|Highlands and Islands]] region. From 1997 until his defeat in 2005, he sat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|British House of Commons]] as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber (UK Parliament constituency)|Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber]].\n\n==House of Commons==\nIn 1997 he was the first [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for the [[Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber (UK Parliament constituency)|Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber]] constituency in Scotland and was re-elected in [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]]. In [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]] the constituency was reformed to [[Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey (UK Parliament constituency)|Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey]], an election which he lost to [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] candidate [[Danny Alexander]]. During his time as an MP, he was a member of the Scottish Affairs and Work and Pensions Select Committees and from 2003 until 2005 was [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[Alistair Darling]], [[Secretary of State for Scotland]].\n\n== Out of office ==\nDuring his time out of office, Stewart was employed as Assistant Director for Rural Affairs with the [[Scottish Council for Voluntary Organisations]].\n\n== Scottish Parliament ==\nIn May 2007 he returned to parliamentary life, this time to the [[Scottish Parliament]] as a list MSP for the Highlands and Islands electoral region.<ref name=\"session3\">{{cite web |url=http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/msps/26665.aspx |title=Previous MSPs: Session 3 (2007-2011): David Stewart |publisher=Scottish Parliament |accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref> In October 2008, the Labour Leader in the Scottish Parliament, [[Iain Gray]], appointed him to the shadow cabinet as the [[Chief Whip]] of the Labour Party in [[Scottish Parliament|Holyrood]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/7618696.stm |title=Scottish Labour's front bench team |work=[[BBC News]] |date=31 December 2009 |accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref> In September 2019, he was made Shadow Cabinet Secretary for Eradication of Poverty and Inequality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/scottish-labour-reshuffle-as-sarah-boyack-returns-to-frontline-politics-1-4995872|title=Scottish Labour reshuffle as Sarah Boyack returns to frontline politics|website=www.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nPrior to his election in 1997, he had been a leading member of Labour\u2019s [[Organisation of the Scottish Labour Party#Scottish Executive Committee|Scottish Executive Committee]].\n\nHe is married to Linda, who stood in the 2007 Scottish Parliament election as Labour Party candidate for the [[Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber]] constituency but failed to be elected.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/election-shows-politics-runs-in-the-family-1.841980|title=Election shows politics runs in the family|date=1 May 2007|work=Herald (Glasgow)|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber (UK Parliament constituency)|Inverness East, Nairn and Lochaber]]\n | years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n{{s-end}}\n{{HighlandsIslands MSPs}}\n{{Scottish Labour Party}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, David}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Highland constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:Labour Co-operative MSPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Scottish Parliament 2007\u20132011]]\n[[Category:Members of the Scottish Parliament 2011\u20132016]]\n[[Category:Members of the Scottish Parliament 2016\u2013]]\n[[Category:People educated at Inverness High School]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikip